1. d4 d5 2. c4 (2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {We will see the London and an assortment of early sidelines in the fourth and final section of the course. As White avoids playing the move [c4], we will eventually build up a good centre with ...[c5]. In all of these lines I want to fight for the advantage with Black, and I am not satisfied with boring equality.}) 2... c6 {We have the advantage of going for either the or the move order to get to the Semi-Slav. I was exclusively playing the system for several years before I moved on to the move order, as I wanted to add more systems to my repertoire. We will go with the Slav move order in this course, as it is easier to learn and more compact. The only potential drawback is that we allow the boring Exchange Slav. This is mostly played by those who are happy to make a draw. We will try to go for lines which keep more pieces on the board and give us chances to outplay our timid opponents.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 (4. Nc3 {This is the critical move, keeping the diagonal open for the dark-squared bishop. We cannot get our light-squared bishop out, as White can answer Qb3, targeting our queenside. The pure Slav variation is to take} dxc4 {and hang on to the pawn. This is pretty decent, and it has been covered in two excellent Chessable courses. The game gets concrete and there are a lot of forcing lines. However, White gets good control over the center which is something I rarely like to allow.}) (4. e3 {In the third section of the course, we move on to the various other options in the Slav apart from the main line, which is 4.Nc3. 4.e3 is the most critical move amongst them. We will also see the moves 4.Qc2, 4.g3, and the dreaded Exchange Slav. 4...Bf5 This is the common theme in these lines when White delays the move [Nc3]. We get the chance to get our bishop out of the pawn chain before going for the move ...[e6].}) (4. Nc3 {The Chebanenko Slav is another option with} a6 {but I am not a big fan of these structures after} 5. c5 {. It leads to more passive positions compared to our lines.}) 4... e6 {This is the starting position of the Semi-Slav variation. We block the diagonal of our light-squared bishop, but we plan to develop this bishop on the queenside. We can do this by either going ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], or by taking on [c4] followed by ...[b5]. The capture on [c4] is a pivotal part of our setup, but we will make that capture only when White has already moved their light-squared bishop. Keep in mind that taking on [c4] is a concession, and we have to play precisely after that to fight back against White's centre.} 5. e3 {We will start our journey into the Semi-Slav with the most played variations: the Meran and the Anti-Meran. White defends the pawn on [c4], but blocks the diagonal of their dark-squared bishop. We will see this complex in the first few chapters.} (5. Bg5 {In addition to the Meran, this is the best attempt for White to play for an advantage. It is even more principled, as the bishop gets out of the pawn chain before White goes for the move [e3]. We will see this in the second section of the course, along with some other sidelines.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines, and we will go for the trendy 10...Be7 variation.}) 5... Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for Bd3 in order to take on c4 with a tempo. White can either directly go for the move} 6. Bd3 {(, which is called the Meran or they can delay it in a few different ways the so-called Anti-Meran.)}) *

