[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Meran 6.Bd3: 8.Bd3 with 9.Na4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D47"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2136127621587095"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bd3 {This is the best square for the bishop, keeping an eye on [e4]. It is also by far the most-played move in the position. White can generally either go for the direct [e4] or he can castle first before going [e4].} (8. Bd3 {Now, the two main lines here are} a6 {and 8...Bb7 . 8...Bd6 is also possible, but it transposes into the main lines of the Anti-Meran variation which we don't enter. We go for another option here, which has not been explored much but is among the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Na4 {This is the usual way of responding to the move ...[b4] as we have seen in the previous lines. However, White had the chance to get the knight to [e4] instead, as the bishop is on [d3]. White's main idea should be to try and stop us from going for the ...[c5] break. They have not managed to achieve that here.} (9. Ne2 {is not great as we can answer} c5 {very easily.}) 9... c5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] We have managed to execute our plan on the queenside. Now, the bishop will be very strong on [b7] and I have seen so many games where Black takes over the initiative easily.} 10. O-O {[%cal Ge3e4] White maintains the tension, asking us to take on [d4], to either open the diagonal for the [c1]-bishop or to get the knight to the center with a tempo. Their idea is to play [e4] next if given the chance.} cxd4 {This is important here, to make sure that White does not get the move [e4] easily. Now White has a choice between the two recaptures.} 11. Nxd4 {I think this is better, with the intention to go [Qf3] next. The drawback of the knight on [d4] is that we can get ...[e5] with a tempo as we saw in the previous line.} (11. exd4 {can be met with} Bb7 {and we will follow up with ...[Bd6] next.}) 11... Bb7 12. b3 {Since White is unable to get the move [e4] in, they develop the bishop to the long diagonal. The position is somewhat symmetrical.} Be7 13. Bb2 O-O {We finally get our king to safety. Our plan is to go ...[Rc8] and ...[Qa5] next.} 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Qe2 Qa5 $10 {[%cal Gb7a6,Gf6e4,Ge7f6,Gd7e5] This is a better square for the queen than [e2]. We are now threatening to play ...[Ne5], followed by ...[Ba6] if the bishop moves back. Another idea in these positions is to go ...[Ne4] and ...[Bf6]. We are on the better side of equality.} *

