1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bd3 {This is the best square for the bishop, keeping an eye on [e4]. It is also by far the most-played move in the position. White can generally either go for the direct [e4] or he can castle first before going [e4].} (8. Bd3 {Now, the two main lines here are} a6 {and 8...Bb7 . 8...Bd6 is also possible, but it transposes into the main lines of the Anti-Meran variation which we don't enter. We go for another option here, which has not been explored much but is among the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Ne4 {This is an advantage of the bishop on [d3]. We are not getting the move ...[c5] easily here. It is hard to say whom the exchange of knights favours, though.} Nxe4 {We exchange the knight immediately on [e4], not allowing White to take on [f6]. The bishop is often misplaced on [e4] since it blocks White's e-pawn. We will first develop our pieces before eventually kicking the bishop back, followed by the ...[c5] break.} (9... c5 {runs into} 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Ne5 {⩲ .}) 10. Bxe4 Bb7 {The bishops on [e4] and [b7] are at an impasse. White does not retreat with the bishop because then we will go for the ...[c5] break. We need to slowly push the bishop back with ...[Nf6] at the right moment.} 11. O-O {Now there is a question of where to develop the dark-squared bishop.} Be7 {This move surprises even me, as I usually always want to put the bishop on the more active [d6]-square. However, White has the annoying plan of [Nd2]-[c4], targeting the bishop on [d6]. Objectively there is not a huge difference though, as the engine says the bishop can just come back to [e7] if it is attacked. However, the immediate ...[Be7] feels more secure, and the plans are more or less the same after both moves.} 12. Qc2 h6 {We saw the [a3] plan in the previous variation. Now, let us see what happens if White keeps the a-file closed. There should not be a big difference.} 13. b3 {This is more flexible, in my opinion, as White can always go [a3] later on and transpose if they wish to.} O-O 14. Bb2 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] We go for ...[a5] anyway. It is a useful move defending the [b4]-pawn, and we always have the plan of going ...[a4] in the future.} 15. Nd2 Qb8 $1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf8c8,Gc6c5] The same plan that we have seen several times so far. It's one of the best multi-purpose ideas in the entire variation.} 16. Nc4 c5 {We have managed to achieve our ideal pawn break pretty easily.} 17. Rfd1 a4 {We take the chance to break White's pawn structure on the queenside. The capture on [a4] will make the [a2]-pawn a long-term weakness.} 18. Rab1 a3 {I like this pawn structure on the queenside, as it can be a huge trump in the endgames. Especially if you consider knight endgames. It also restricts White's dark-squared bishop pretty badly.} 19. Ba1 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8] We will continue with ...[Rc8] and ...[Rd8] next. I prefer Black with our pawn structure on the queenside.} *

