1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bd3 {This is the best square for the bishop, keeping an eye on [e4]. It is also by far the most-played move in the position. White can generally either go for the direct [e4] or he can castle first before going [e4].} (8. Bd3 {Now, the two main lines here are} a6 {and 8...Bb7 . 8...Bd6 is also possible, but it transposes into the main lines of the Anti-Meran variation which we don't enter. We go for another option here, which has not been explored much but is among the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Ne4 {This is an advantage of the bishop on [d3]. We are not getting the move ...[c5] easily here. It is hard to say whom the exchange of knights favours, though.} Nxe4 {We exchange the knight immediately on [e4], not allowing White to take on [f6]. The bishop is often misplaced on [e4] since it blocks White's e-pawn. We will first develop our pieces before eventually kicking the bishop back, followed by the ...[c5] break.} (9... c5 {runs into} 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Ne5 {⩲ .}) 10. Bxe4 Bb7 {The bishops on [e4] and [b7] are at an impasse. White does not retreat with the bishop because then we will go for the ...[c5] break. We need to slowly push the bishop back with ...[Nf6] at the right moment.} 11. O-O {Now there is a question of where to develop the dark-squared bishop.} Be7 {This move surprises even me, as I usually always want to put the bishop on the more active [d6]-square. However, White has the annoying plan of [Nd2]-[c4], targeting the bishop on [d6]. Objectively there is not a huge difference though, as the engine says the bishop can just come back to [e7] if it is attacked. However, the immediate ...[Be7] feels more secure, and the plans are more or less the same after both moves.} 12. Nd2 {White immediately starts moving the knight to the queenside. In addition to that, this creates a square on [f3] for their bishop to go to. This has been seen in a lot of lines so far, and this should indicate that it is the most flexible option.} O-O 13. b3 Nf6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6d5,Gc6c5] We want to kick the bishop back, but another idea is to put our knight on [d5] and to go for the ...[c5] break. White cannot just give up the bishop on [e4], as we will then also go for the ...[c5] break immediately.} 14. Bf3 {White keeps the bishop alive, stopping the move ...[c5] for now.} (14. Bb2 {allows us to play} Nxe4 15. Nxe4 c5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. dxc5 Qg5 {. White is the one who has to be careful here, as they are forced to create some weaknesses on the kingside.}) 14... Nd5 {As I mentioned, we put our knight in the middle of the board to be able to play ...[c5] next. We can also get our knight to [c3] if allowed.} 15. Bb2 c5 {[%csl Gb4,Rc3][%cal Gc5d4] Everything has worked according to plan. We have equalised comfortably. We will take on [d4] given the chance, and then try to make use of the [c3]-square. The [b4]-pawn can be either a boon or a curse. It gives up control over [c4] and is slightly weak. But it does give us play on the queenside, and restricts the opponent's bishop.} 16. dxc5 Bxc5 {[%cal Gd8e7] The bishop is pretty decent on this diagonal, and we clear the [e7]-square for the queen.} 17. Qe2 ({The natural} 17. Rc1 $6 {runs into} Nxe3 $1 18. fxe3 Bxe3+ 19. Kh1 Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Bxc1 {↑ , when we get two pawns and a rook for the two pieces. But those are central pawns and we will go ...[f6] and ...[e5] next.}) 17... Nc3 {We finally manage to get the knight to [c3].} 18. Bxc3 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 bxc3 {It is not going to be easy for White to win the pawn on [c3]. I feel the logical end will be the trade of all the queenside pawns to reach an equal endgame.} 20. Qc4 Qa5 $10 {[%csl Gc3] The queen does a good job defending both [c5] and [c3]. White has to be very precise here, as otherwise the [c3]-pawn can become very dangerous.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Arjun's Semi-Slav"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anti-Meran 6.Qc2: 7.Bd3 with 10.a4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D46"]
[PlyCount "36"]
[GameId "2136127621714074"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. a4 {This is logical to stop the move ...[b5], but it does create a big weakness on [b4].} c5 $1 {We go for the same plan as in the last variation. This is more critical, though, as [a4] is more useful in preventing any ...[b5] ideas.} 11. dxc5 {White takes on [c5], not allowing the capture on [d4]. This is often better because White does not want to block the centre unnecessarily.} Bxc5 {Both the recaptures are fine, but I want to make sure that White does not get the move [b4] on the queenside. We will continue with ...[b6] and ...[Bb7] next.} 12. b3 {White starts to develop the bishop to [b2], keeping the option to move the [a1]-rook to the d-file.} b6 $1 {We saw this in the previous line as well, immediately getting our bishop to the long diagonal. Once we play ...[Bb7], we should be very comfortable.} 13. Ne4 {This is the critical way to exploit our early ...[b6]. Unlike in the previous line, here White does not have the rook on [d1].} Be7 {This is the easiest reply, planning to go ...[Bb7] next. Now, we make use of the move [b3] which has opened up the other long diagonal. We can recapture on [f6] with a tempo.} 14. Bb2 Nxe4 $1 {This looks strange at first sight, as we allow the queen to come to [e4] with a tempo, attacking the rook on [a8]. But we have a clever idea in mind. Take your time figuring out our the next move, as we need to be precise.} 15. Qxe4 Bb7 $1 {A stunning idea, giving up the bishop on [b7]. However, if White takes, their queen will run out of squares. I have never seen such an idea before, but it is a very effective way to complete our development.} 16. Qf4 (16. Qxb7 {runs into} Nc5 17. Qc6 Rc8 {⩱ . White is not losing outright, but is worse with a rook and bishop for the queen.}) 16... Bf6 {We trade the bishops and simplify the position. This makes sense as White has the more active pieces.} 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 {We offer to trade the queens and get into an endgame. I would be very happy if White declines the trade, as our bishop on [b7] is very active.} 18. Qxf6 gxf6 $10 {[%cal Gf8d8] Both recaptures are fine, but this imbalances the position. I like the [c5]-quare for our knight. We will continue with ...[Rfd8] and bring the king to the centre.} *

