1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. Rd1 {This is the most common move in the position, stopping our immediate pawn breaks in the centre. Now, White wants to play [e4] next. However, if you compare this position to the main lines after 9...[b5], you will see that White usually does not put the rook on [d1] so early. They usually focus on more energetic ideas, such as a quick [e4] or [Ng5]. [d1] may not necessarily be the best square for the rook, but White had no other flexible move here as we were planning to expand with ...[b5] and ...[c5] quickly.} b5 {Finally, we decide to kick the bishop away from [c4]. White has to make a decision now, and we play differently depending on where the bishop goes.} ({I also like the approach} 10... Qc7 {, delaying the move ...[b5], but I don't see a huge upside. Moreover, it gives White an extra independent option in} 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 {when after} e5 $1 {Black should be okay, but it would be an extra option we'd have to prepare for.}) 11. Be2 {Compared to the previous variation, White keeps the [d1] rook protected. They are ready to play [e4].} Qc7 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Rd1d8,Gc8f5] We get the queen out of the way. Compared to the 9...b5 variation, we would typically have the bishop on [b7] instead of the pawn on [a6]. I think this difference is in our favour, as we can achieve the ...[c5] break quicker. Moreover, in the lines with [e4] and ...[e5] I like having the bishop on [c8], covering the [f5]-square. Overall, ...[a6] is a more important move than ...[Bb7].} 12. Ne4 {White trades the knights in the centre in an attempt to bring the queen over to the kingside. This is not cohesive with the move 10.Rd1 and White cannot create much of an attack with the dark-squared bishop still on [c1].} Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] We have completed our development and are ready to carry out the ...[c5] break next. White has to do something quick in order to not be worse.} 14. Bd3 {White forces some weaknesses on our kingside.} g6 15. Qh4 c5 {[%csl Rf3]} 16. Ng5 {This is the principled move, forcing us to weaken our kingside again. At the same time, White commits to an all out attack on the kingside, abandoning the centre.} h5 17. g4 ({The principled continuation after White's previous moves. We have very few pieces defending the kingside and have to play accurately now. This has been played much less compared to the main move} 17. Ne4 {.}) 17... Nf6 18. gxh5 Nxh5 19. Be2 Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gf8h8,Gh8h2] We solve our problems tactically, as our rook is coming to the h-file. I would be pretty scared as White here.} 20. dxc5 Be5 {[%cal Ge5b2] We maintain control over the long diagonal, not allowing White to play [b3] and [Bb2].} 21. f4 Bf6 22. Bd2 Rh8 {We have taken over the initiative and there are a lot of threats in the position. We can play ...[e5] next and start opening up the diagonals.} *

