1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Bb2 {White keeps the option of both [Be2] and [Bd3] open, but this means that their king stays in the centre even longer. Also, ...[Bb4]+ can no longer be met with [Bd2].} e5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Be2 {This is the most played move in the position, but it is an inaccuracy. This is a good exercise: try and find our continuation.} (11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bd3 {transposes to an earlier variation.}) 11... Nxf3+ $1 12. Bxf3 d4 $1 {[%csl Re1] With the king still in the centre, it is time to exploit it. We have a huge dynamic advantage and we will use it to the maximum.} 13. exd4 $6 {This has been played in all games that reached this position, but again it is a dubious move.} Re8+ 14. Kf1 Qa5 $17 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ga8d8] We are going to move our bishop to [f5] next. Also, the other rook can decide to go to either one of the central files.} *

