[Black "Anti-Meran 6.Qc2: 7.b3 with 8.Be2, 11.Rac1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D45"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2136127621882017"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rac1 Rac8 {We are simply copying White. We will likely go for the ...[c5] plan now, with the rooks opposed on the c-file.} 12. Rfd1 Rfd8 {We continue with the same approach. Now, there are multiple plans for Black. Most of them revolve around the move ...[c5], but we can also jump with the knight to [e4] at the right moment.} 13. g3 {White restricts the bishop on [d6] and prepares to play [Bf1]-[g2].} Bb4 {[%cal Gc6c5]} ({We are ready to continue with ...c5. While we could have played the usual} 13... h6 {, this is more direct and exploits some of the weaknesses that White has created on the long diagonal. It is a general pattern to remember: we meet [g3] with the plan of ...[Bb4] and ...[c5].}) 14. a3 {This is a good option, forcing us to trade the dark-squared bishop on either [c3] or [a3].} ({If} 14. Bf1 {the move} c5 {equalizes easily.}) 14... Bxa3 {Both options are good, but I prefer not to give our opponent the bishop pair if possible. Both the a-pawns are removed from the board now.} 15. Bxa3 Qxa3 16. Ra1 Qd6 17. Rxa7 Qb8 $10 {[%cal Gc6c5] We kick the rook back and play ...[c5] next. I like our position more, as our light-squared bishop can prove to be very dangerous along the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} *

