1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This is the best square for this rook, as White is looking to open the e-file with [e4] soon. Moreover, White wants to meet a future ...[c5] break with the move [d5], and in that case the rook on [e1] is very useful against our queen on [e7].} Rfe8 {This is a pretty flexible move, as we are going to need the [f8]-square for the knight soon. That said, it is not a big difference if we start with bringing the other rook to [d8].} 12. Rad1 {The natural move, bringing the last remaining piece to the centre.} Rad8 {We do the same, completing our setup. Now there are multiple plans for both sides, and we have to understand the position well. Usually, most players just go for the ...[c5] break everywhere, as that makes it easy to remember how to play. I like the positions with the ...[e5] break a lot, but the drawback is that it is not effective against all of White's possible moves. However, I feel it is worth learning a few more variations if we can take over in the centre with [e5]-[e4] in some of the lines.} 13. Bf1 {Finally, we come to my favourite move. I am always hoping to get this on the board, because we have a very cunning trap prepared for our opponent.} e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] We go for the most ambitious pawn break in the centre. We are threatening to play ...[e4], and White has to react accordingly.} (13... c5 {is also good, but I feel that 13...e5 is more aggressive.}) 14. dxe5 {This is the critical move, trading the central pawns.} (14. g3 $2 {is seen in the model game Benjamin - Kalyan, Barcelona 2017.}) 14... Nxe5 {White has two options here: trade on [e5] or get the knight to [f5], keeping more pieces on the board.} 15. Nxe5 {This is the most-played move in the position. White does not waste a tempo and will try to force an IQP next. One thing to note is that after this trade a sacrifice on [h2] is always in the air. It does not work immediately but White has to be careful with every move.} Bxe5 16. cxd5 {This is the critical move, giving us an IQP, but it gives us a lot of options. There are two ways to recapture the pawn and we can also ignore the [d5]-pawn for now, since if White takes on [c6] it opens up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop.} Rc8 $1 {We put pressure along the c-file, planning to take on [d5] next.} 17. dxc6 Rxc6 {The rook joins the game along the 3rd rank. It is ready to shift over to the kingside when needed. Of course, the drawback is that this runs into [Bb5], which looks like it wins an exchange.} 18. Bb5 Bxh2+ $1 {It is time to go for our play on the kingside.} 19. Kxh2 {White takes up the challenge.} Ng4+ 20. Kg1 $1 {The king has a route to escape via [f1]-[e2].} (20. Kg3 Rh6 {∓}) 20... Rh6 $1 {[%cal Ge7h4] This rook is an important piece and we are not ready to give it up on [c6].} 21. Bxe8 Rh1+ {This is the more tempting option, forcing the White king to take a hike to the middle of the board.} 22. Kxh1 Qh4+ 23. Kg1 Qh2+ {The king is forced to go on the run. Even though it looks very impressive for us, the position still remains balanced. The line continues here.} *

