[Black "Botvinnik Sidelines: 9.Bg3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D44"]
[PlyCount "36"]
[GameId "2136127621963941"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e4 {This is the critical move, gaining space in the centre and creating a threat of both taking the [c4]-pawn as well as advancing [e5].} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4], which is our priority. This is a very risky strategy as our entire kingside will fall, but we are relying on the strength of our queenside pawns. Evaluating the resulting positions is often challenging because there are many imbalances. Our queenside pawns can compensate for a missing pawn or exchange in the endgames.} 7. e5 {This looks very strong at first sight, but we do not lose a piece. That being said, we are going to give up a big chunk of our kingside.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 {White voluntarily misplaces the bishop on [g3] and lets us keep our kingside intact. We should be very happy with our extra pawn.} Nd5 {We get our knight to the middle of the board and create a threat of either ...[Qa5] or ...[Bb4], pinning the knight on [c3].} 10. Nd2 {The knight blocks the diagonal and prepares to go to [e4] in the future.} Bb7 11. Be2 (11. h4 {can just be met with} Nd7 {⩱ and next we will take on [g5] with the queen.}) 11... Nd7 12. O-O Qb6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] We go after the [d4]-pawn. We also preparing the move ...[c5] next. White has to be very precise not to be worse.} 13. a4 $1 {White needs to start playing on the queenside before we get the move ...[c5] in.} O-O-O $5 {[%cal Ga7a6,Ga7a5] This has been played in only 3 games so far. We keep the option of playing either ...[a6] or ...[a5] open.} 14. Nde4 {This is the most natural move in the position and has been played twice. There are some other GM games which have reached this position via a transposition. However, 14.Nde4 is an inaccuracy.} (14. Qc2 {is the top choice of the computer, but it is so hard to see the point. After} h5 {↑ we can start playing on the kingside, and I do not expect White to be very pleased with their position.}) 14... a5 ({This is a big improvement over the move} 14... a6 {and is also a novelty! The main point is that after 14...a5 we can meet the move 15.b3 with 15...Nxc3 16.Nxc3 followed by 16...b4 and ...[c3]. White is not able to play [a5] and [Na4] as in the main lines.}) 15. axb5 cxb5 16. b3 {This is the best attempt I can see to create some play on the queenside for White, but it does open the long diagonal for our bishop.} Nxc3 17. Nxc3 Bb4 18. Rc1 Nc5 $15 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gd4c5,Gb6c6]} (18... Nc5 {A clever tactical idea, as} 19. dxc5 {can be met strongly with} Qc6 {.}) (18... Nc5 {White can simplify the position with} 19. Nxb5 {, but we reach a slightly better endgame. Our king is much better placed on the queenside in such endgames.}) *

