[PlyCount "44"]
[GameId "2136127621996710"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Be3 {This is a more serious option, defending the pawn on [d4]. White wants to get the queen to [f3] next and castle queenside.} Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c5] This is less common, but it makes a lot of sense here as it is aimed against the [Qf3] plan. We want to meet this queen move with ...[Nb4], both defending the [c6]-pawn and threatening a check on [c2].} 13. a4 {White is quickly going after our queenside before we get a chance to consolidate.} Nb4 $1 {This is the 3rd most played move in the position. We want to win the [d4]-pawn next.} 14. axb5 Bxd4 15. Bxd4 {This was played in all the games which reached this position.} Qxd4 {Now, letting the queens remain on the board is very risky for White.} 16. Qxd4 Nc2+ 17. Kd1 Nxd4 18. b6 ({This is the critical try, keeping the b-pawn on the board. Instead, after} 18. bxc6 Rb8 {all the pawns on the queenside are likely to be traded off, and we have enough counterplay to hold comfortably.}) 18... a5 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b6] We keep our a-pawn alive for now. We will soon play ...[Rb8] to win the [b6]-pawn.} 19. Bxc4 c5 {Our bishop is heading to the long diagonal, which would be trouble for White.} 20. Ne4 Rb8 $1 {Now it's time to go after the queenside pawns.} 21. Nxc5 Rxb6 22. Kd2 {[%cal Gb6b2]} (22. Kd2 {White sets a trap. We are unable to win a pawn with} Rxb2+ {due to} 23. Kc3 {and White wins a piece.}) 22... Ke7 $10 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gh8d8] We can bring our rook to [d8] next or play ...[Bb7], trading into a drawn endgame.} *

