1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. a4 {This makes sense, opening the a-file in anticipation of us castling long.} O-O-O {We oblige. Our king remains reasonably safe on the queenside and we are looking to win the battle for the centre.} 16. axb5 cxb5 17. Bxb7+ Kxb7 18. Nxb5 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6c6] We are targeting the [d4]-pawn but we also threaten to play ...[Qc6], with a double attack on White's pieces which would win on the spot.} 19. d5 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb4d3] We are threatening to give a check on [d3] now.} 20. O-O {This looks crushing for White, but what do we have prepared?} Qh6 $1 21. h4 Qxh4 $3 {This is the beauty of the Botvinnik variations. Our king may look weak, but at least we have a lot of pieces around it.} 22. Rxa7+ Kb6 $1 {Other moves are bad because they allow White to give up their rook on the a-file to get the queen into the game.} (22... Kb6 {The game may continue with} 23. Ra6+ Nxa6 24. gxh4 Rdg8+ 25. Kh2 Rxh4#) *

