1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. Ne4 {White kicks our queen away from [f6], stopping us from targeting the pawn on [d4].} Qe7 16. O-O O-O-O {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] We are ready to target the pawn on [d4] again, this time with ...[c5].} 17. a4 {White stops the move ...[c5] by attacking the pawn on [b5]. This is the most played move in the position.} f5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge7h7] We kick the knight back to a worse square. This weakens our [e5]-square, but you may have noticed that we are not playing solid positional chess here. :- The move 17...f5 also gives us a chance to swing our queen over to the kingside.} 18. axb5 {In general, White should delay this exchange as long as they can, as it opens up the long diagonal for our bishop. Here, this is their last opportunity to play [axb5], as we are ready to play ...[b4] which would keep the a-file closed.} cxb5 19. Rxa6 {White gives up an exchange to get the knight to the [c5]-square.} Bxa6 20. Nc5 Qxc5 $1 {We give the exchange right back, getting into an endgame. Our queenside pawns are more dangerous than White's pawns here.} 21. dxc5 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 b4 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4] We would be winning if we manage to trade rooks. White's main source of counterplay is their h-pawn.} 23. Ra1 {This is the most logical move, going after our [a7]-pawn. It was played by Gukesh against Erigaisi, but Black is well prepared to deal with this.} b3 $1 {[%cal Ga1a6,Gc4c3,Gb3b2] White is not able to win the piece on [a6] since our pawns are far too advanced.} 24. Bf1 {This is already the only move to survive, but Gukesh found it in his game.} Rd8 {Now we are ready to move the bishop to [b5] and start pushing our pawn. You can go deeper here.} *

