1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. Ne4 {White kicks our queen away from [f6], stopping us from targeting the pawn on [d4].} Qe7 16. O-O O-O-O {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] We are ready to target the pawn on [d4] again, this time with ...[c5].} 17. a4 {White stops the move ...[c5] by attacking the pawn on [b5]. This is the most played move in the position.} f5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge7h7] We kick the knight back to a worse square. This weakens our [e5]-square, but you may have noticed that we are not playing solid positional chess here. :- The move 17...f5 also gives us a chance to swing our queen over to the kingside.} 18. Nc3 b4 {We take the opportunity to keep the a-file closed. This move comes with the added benefit of kicking White's knight back again.} 19. Ne2 e5 {We continue targeting the [d4]-pawn.} 20. Qc2 {White gets the queen out of the way, attacking two of our pawns in the process. It looks like we have made a mistake, but this is all part of our plan.} Qf7 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gf5][%cal Gf7h5] Our queen defends both pawns and is also hinting at a future ...[Qh5].} 21. Rac1 {White wants to win the [c4]-pawn and target [c6] next.} c3 $1 {We keep the c-file closed. We are giving up the pride of our pawn structure, but we are in an opposite side castling middlegame where one tempo could decide the game.} 22. bxc3 b3 23. Qb1 {This is an important move, keeping an eye on both our pawns.} f4 {[%cal Gf4f3] Now we are threatening to win a piece with the move ...[f3].} 24. Bf3 c5 {[%cal Gf7b7,Gh8h2] It is time to exchange the light-squared bishops. This bishop is White's key defender on the kingside. Now, after the trade on [b7], we are threatening to take on [h2] and deliver mate on [h1].} *

