1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. Ne4 {White kicks our queen away from [f6], stopping us from targeting the pawn on [d4].} Qe7 16. O-O O-O-O {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] We are ready to target the pawn on [d4] again, this time with ...[c5].} 17. h4 {This has been played less often than 17.a4, but it is a more critical move. White creates a square on [g5] for the knight in case we play ...[f5].} c5 {We continue with our usual plan of winning the [d4]-pawn.} 18. a4 {White is poking holes in our queenside. They want to weaken the pawn on [c4].} Rxd4 19. Qe2 b4 {We reach a critical juncture. White has a few different ways of going after our king. White's own king is pretty safe on the kingside, and we have to be careful.} 20. Rad1 {Now White tries the same with the other rook. The advantage here for White is that their other rook is ready to come to [e1] at any time.} Qc7 $1 {Since White is unable to get the other rook to [c1], we are confident about placing our queen on [c7]. This is something we've seen in previous chapters. The question of where to place the rooks is quite tricky for White.} (20... Bd5 {is not as good due to} 21. Ng5 Re8 {This is not the best move here but I just want to illustrate the point. After} 22. Rfe1 $1 {White is clearly better. Instead of 21...Re8 you can make a case for Black's position after 21...Qd7 , but I prefer our main line of 20...[Qc7]!.}) 21. Ng5 {White immediately forces the trade of light-squared bishops before we get the chance to play ...[Qc6] and fight for the diagonal.} Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Qc6+ {With this check we defend the [e6]-pawn as we are planning to go ...[f6] next, kicking the knight away from [g5].} 23. f3 ({This has been played in more games, but it is less dangerous than} 23. Kh2 {as we will see.}) 23... f6 $1 {We don't mind giving up the [e6]-pawn if we get to trade the queens. Our king is weaker as long the queens are on the board, but it's a different story in the endgame. You can read the full analysis here.} *

