1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. a4 {White spends a tempo to stop us from going ...[b7]-[b5]. This weakens the [b4]-square, though, and is also a slow non-developing move.} Bb4 {We immediately exploit White's move and put our bishop on [b4]. We want to put our queen on [e7] and go for the ...[e5] break soon. On [d6] our bishop would have come under fire after [e4]-[e5] or after a capture on [c4] with the knight.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 ({This is better than} 9. Nd2 {, preparing the move [e4] and vacating the [d1]-square for the rook. White needs to keep an eye on the [e5]-square.}) 9... Qe7 {[%cal Ge6e5] This is important, to be able to meet the move [e4] with ...[e5], fighting back in the centre.} 10. Na2 {White kicks the bishop back to win the pawn on [c4], but the knight is misplaced on the edge after we retreat our bishop.} Bd6 11. Qxc4 a5 $1 {We have seen this move already, preventing White from gaining space on the queenside. We create a clear weakness on [b4]. There is no rush to play the move ...[e5], as White is unable to stop our central break anytime soon.} (11... e5 12. a5 {⩲}) 12. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4] White prepares to play [e4] next, but they have wasted a few moves.} e5 13. e4 Rd8 {We maintain the tension for now. We are preparing to take on [d4] at the right moment.} 14. Be3 exd4 {We are going after the [e4]-pawn now. The bishop on [e3] blocks the e-file, making it hard for White to defend [e4].} 15. Nxd4 Nc5 16. Nf5 {White forces us to trade on [f5], but this weakens their pawn structure and releases some control over the centre.} Bxf5 17. exf5 Ng4 {We kick the knight away from [e3] and it lacks a good square to go to. Ideally, White would like it back on [c1], but this would stop the [a1]-rook from getting into the game.} (17... Ng4 18. Bd4 {is a bold move as the bishop is pretty exposed on [d4]. We have some tactical ideas. You can go deeper here.}) *

