1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn, which is a target when we have developed our light-squared bishop on the kingside.} Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gb6b3,Ge4c2] We need to understand the difference in the move orders. In the main line with the inclusion of the moves [f3] and ...[Bg6], we put the queen on [c7]. Here, the main point is that we can meet [f3] with a capture on [b3] followed by ...[Bc2].} 8. c5 (8. f3 {is not good here due to} Qxb3 9. axb3 Bc2 {∓ .}) 8... Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gb7b6] We do not trade on [b3] especially after the move [c5], as it opens up the a-file for the rook and gives White the clear plan of pushing [b4]-[b5]. It is an achievement for us to have forced White to release the tension on the queenside. Now, it is much easier to go for the ...[e5] break or to open up the queenside with ...[b6].} 9. f3 Bg6 10. Bd2 b6 $15 {White was hinting at castling queenside, but we are quick to open up the position in our favour. After the trade on [b6], we can fight for the centre with the move ...[c5] next.} *

