1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. g3 {We have seen this idea in previous lines. White stops the immediate threat of ...[Ne4] and defends the [h4]-knight. It keeps the [h2]-pawn more secure.} O-O {As White is playing slowly, there is no need for us to delay castling. We will start our play on the queenside soon.} 11. Rc1 {This is the most common move, with or without including the capture on [g6]. These lines are slower than the ones we have seen so far, as White is likely to castle kingside too.} dxc4 {We have to release the tension. There was a lot of pressure along the c-file.} 12. Bxc4 Nbd7 {We have the option of going for either of the two breaks in the centre: ...[c5] and ...[e5].} 13. O-O {This is a natural move, getting the king to safety, but it allows us to achieve our central break without any problems.} e5 {We want to take on [d4] and follow up with ...[Nb6]. We will play against the weak pawn on [d4] and get our knight to [d5].} 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. dxe5 {This makes more sense, not allowing us to weaken White's structure. The drawback is that our [d7]-knight gets to [e5]. We can try to put it on [d3] soon.} Nxe5 16. Be2 Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gf8d8] The trade of queens is great for us here, as we will continue quickly with ...[Rfd8] and ...[Nd3]. Although the general principle is that we should not trade queens when the opponent has the bishop pair, the bishops are not very effective currently. They are stuck behind White's pawns in the centre. Also, the trade of queens either improves our pawn structure by opening up the a-file or weakens White's structure by creating a weakness on [b3]. The difference is our c-pawn: having the pawns b7-c6-b5 is a great structure for us.} 17. Rfd1 Qxb3 18. axb3 Rfd8 19. Be1 {This is the only way to stop our plan of getting the knight to [d3].} Ned7 $10 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gd7c5] We change our plans, as we want to get this knight to [c5], targeting the weak [b3]-pawn. We will put our pawn on [g5] on the kingside, keeping our opponent restricted.} *

