1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. Nxg6 {This trade can happen on several different moves, but we will look at those lines only via this move order.} hxg6 11. O-O-O {We already saw the plan of castling kingside in the previous lines. Instead, castling queenside is the most testing plan for White. If you recall, we saw similar lines with the queen on [c2] instead of [b3]. There we were not forced to go for the move ...[Qc7], though.} dxc4 {We trade immediately, not giving White any extra options. As I've mentioned earlier, with the queen on [b3] the plan of ...[c5]-[c4] will come with a tempo, and is what we are aiming for.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {We waste no time and immediately start preparing the move ...[c5]. Our king is safe on [e8] for now.} 14. Ne4 {This is the main move in the position, asking us to improve White's pawn structure in the centre. We do not have much of a choice, as otherwise it is harder to get the move ...[c5] in.} Nxe4 15. fxe4 {White's f-pawn has moved towards the centre. This also gives White the [f3]-square for the bishop.} c5 16. Kb1 (16. d5 {is not a good idea here due to} c4 {⩱ . We will close the centre with ...[e5] next, and then bring our knight to [c5]. The pawns on [e3] and [e4] become a weakness for White.}) 16... Nc6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd4d5] We want White to push the pawns in the centre, as that would create weaknesses for us to exploit. White's central formation is similar to hanging pawns, which we see in many [d4] middlegames. The pawns are strong when they are on the same rank in the middle of the board. But the very second that one of the pawns moves forward, a hole is created for the opponent to utilize.} 17. d5 {This is the critical move, even though it gives us the [e5]-square for the knight. The pawn on [d5] can become very dangerous, especially if it can get to [d6] soon.} exd5 18. exd5 Ne5 {This is a battle of time now. White will start play on the kingside quickly. We need some time to first consolidate our advantage in the centre.} 19. h4 Bd6 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc7e7] It is important to first blockade the [d5]-pawn.} 20. g4 Qe7 {This is clever because we are provoking the move [g5], which makes it harder for White to break through on the kingside.} 21. h5 {This looks like the most logical move, attempting to open up the h-file.} Nxg4 $1 {This was the hidden point behind our previous move. The important part is that White is forced to give up the light-squared bishop, as otherwise they are losing the pawn on [h5] too.} 22. Bxg4 (22. hxg6 {is not possible due to} Rxh1 23. Rxh1 Qe4+ {+ -+ , winning the rook.}) 22... Qe4+ 23. Qc2 Qxg4 24. hxg6 {Yes, our king is getting exposed, but White does not have enough pieces to exploit this factor. Our pieces are pretty active to compensate for it.} Rxh1 25. Rxh1 Ke7 $10 {[%cal Ge7f7,Ga8f8] We get out of trouble on the back rank. If we do manage to trade queens, White is in a lot of trouble. The position remains complex but is dynamically balanced.} *

