1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. cxd5 {White decides to release the tension on the queenside, stopping our plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[b5]. This is the reason why we have maintained our knight on [b8] until now.} cxd5 (10... exd5 $6 {is not good after} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. O-O-O {± .}) 11. Nxg6 {White will have to trade on [g6] at some point or the other. They want to tuck the king on [b1], where it is reasonably safe. This exchange does open the h-file for our rook, though.} hxg6 12. O-O-O {This is the only plan we need to check here. I got crushed comprehensively in this line back in 2017 when I was exclusively playing the Slav move order. The variation was published by Avrukh in one of his White repertoire books, and it got very popular pretty quickly. White's play is easy to understand while it is not as easy for Black. You need to examine the move order carefully.} Nc6 13. Kb1 a6 {We are preparing to play ...[b5] soon. Our king will remain on [e8] for the foreseeable future.} 14. Rc1 {[%cal Rc1c7,Rb8b5,Gc3b5] White stops our plan of ...[b5], as now there is a lot of pressure on the knight on [c6].} Rc8 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gb7b5,Gc6a5] We are again preparing to play ...[b5], this time by defending the knight on [c6]. We still need to prepare the move ...[b5] further with ...[Nd7] next, to counter the pin along the [a4]-[e8] diagonal.} ({The immediate} 14... b5 $2 {runs into} 15. Nxb5 {+- .}) 15. Bd3 {This is the most testing option, preparing to play [Ne2] next. White will then try to play [e4], having defended the [d4]-pawn.} Nd7 {We have seen this plan earlier, preparing ...[b5].} 16. Ne2 b5 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4]} 17. a4 $1 {This is an important move for White to not get a worse position. White needs to stop our play on the queenside, even though they end up opening files in front of their king. The key to the position is the [c4]-square.} bxa4 18. Qxa4 Nb6 {We attack the queen, giving White a choice - whether to go for our [a6]-pawn or let us complete our development comfortably.} 19. Qxa6 {This is the critical move, as White not only wins the pawn but also gets control over the [b5]-square.} (19. Qa2 {is harmless, as we answer} O-O {= followed by ...[Qd6] and ...[Nb4].}) 19... Ra8 20. Qb5 Kd7 {[%cal Gh8b8,Gb8b1,Ga8a1] The king is doing well on [d7], defending the [c6]-knight. We are going to bring the other rook to [b8] and the position looks pretty scary for White.} 21. Rc3 {This is a slightly improved version for White, as the king has the [c2]-square to run over to the centre if necessary. However, White's rook is more exposed on [c3], and we will exploit this.} Na4 $1 {The following line is practically forced.} 22. Rxc6 Qxc6 23. Rc1 Qxb5 24. Bxb5+ Kd8 {We are up an exchange. White has a pawn and the bishop pair in return. White has to keep up the pressure.} 25. Rc6 Nxb2 $10 {[%cal Gb1b2,Gh8h2] We give up the piece on our terms and will also grab the pawn on [h2]. All of this happened in my game Wang, S-Arjun, K Wch U18 Mumbai 2019 ½- ½. Surprisingly, White knew this line till the end, and we had to agree to a draw in a few more mores.} *

