1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Bd3 {White trades off the light-squared bishops, simplifying the position. This is usually played by those who are happy to make a draw with White. There are a few different ways in which we can react.} Bxd3 {We go for the simplest option, trading the bishops without wasting a tempo. While this does bring White's queen to [d3] in one go, I do not think White has any plan other than the [e4] break. This, in turn, weakens the [d4]-pawn, and then we are going to play against this pawn.} 6. Qxd3 e6 7. O-O Be7 {As we saw in the previous line, we are delaying the development of the [b8]-knight in order to be able to play ...[c5] and ...[Nc6].} 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. b3 {White wants to fianchetto the bishop before advancing [e4].} Nbd7 (9... c5 {is also good, but White can also play [b3] and [Bb2] without playing [Nbd2]. So it is more practical to get our knight to [d7] against both of White's setups.}) 10. Bb2 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] A very typical reaction to the plan of [b3] and [Bb2]. We want to get this pawn to [a4], which gives us quite a few options on the queenside.} 11. a3 Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gf8d8] This is a clever prophylactic move, aimed against the [e4] plan. Otherwise, we will get our rook to [d8] and slowly improve our position.} 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 b5 $10 {[%cal Rb8b2,Gb5c4,Gf6e4] This is the point behind moving the queen to [b8]. We have some pressure along the b-file and our threat is to take on [e4] and [c4] next.} *

