1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 {In this chapter, we will be focussing on a couple of early queen moves with which White can defend the [c4]-pawn. We saw this earlier with the inclusion of the moves [Nc3] and ...[e6]. Here, White has not committed the knight to [c3] yet. This gives White more flexibility, and they can instead develop the knight to [d2] in some cases.} e6 {We maintain the tension, as the queen on [b3] is not doing much at the moment. We will continue developing our pieces for now.} (4... dxc4 {is the usual reaction of many players, forcing White to recapture with the queen. This makes sense, also because we can do the same against the move 4.Qc2, cutting down the amount of theory to learn. However, I do feel we are releasing the tension too early, giving White easier play.}) 5. g3 {This is the natural continuation after the move 4.Qb3. White is looking to go for a Catalan type of position where it is natural to bring the queen out to regain the [c4]-pawn once Black captures it.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rb3] As I mentioned earlier, the queen on [b3] gives us the chance to break in the centre. We are happy to get an IQP on [d5]. White is far away from getting control over the [d4]-square, and our pieces are much more active.} 6. cxd5 {This is the most natural move, going for an IQP structure. This helps us develop our pieces better, though, by opening up the [c8]-[h3] diagonal for our light-squared bishop.} exd5 7. Bg2 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] We put more pressure on [d4], forcing White to take on [c5]. We want to develop our bishop directly to [c5].} (7... c4 {was played in the game Dubov, D - Erigaisi, A, 2024. This is also pretty interesting, but I do not think we need to release the tension so early.}) 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Re8 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge8e2] The rook belongs on the e-file, keeping an eye on the [e2]-pawn. We are ready to play ...[d4] next. The queen on [b3] is misplaced in these positions and will be kicked back soon.} 11. Bg5 {This bishop has no good square to go to, where it can do something useful. Thus, it makes sense for White to trade it on [f6], eliminating our knight which was fighting for the centre.} d4 {This is the reason why it is usually better for the white pawn to be on [e3] rather than [g3]. It will be very difficult for White to put pressure on our [d4]-pawn now.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd5 Qd8 $10 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc5b6,Ga1c1] If attacked, we will put our dark-squared bishop on [b6]. We do not mind trading it for the knight on [d5]. The [e2]-pawn is a target for us to pressurize. I expect both the central pawns to be liquidated in the future, leading to an equal endgame.} *

