1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. e3 {White keeps his bishop on [c1] behind the pawn chain, intending to develop the kingside as quickly as possible.} Bg7 {We are not going to rush with the bishop to [f5] to trade the light-squared bishops. Instead, our idea is much simpler. We want to play ...[O-O] next and go for ...[c5]. We will open up the centre, making use of our lead in development.} 6. Bd3 {This is the more active square for the bishop in general, but it is not as effective with our pawn on [g6] blocking the diagonal.} O-O 7. O-O c5 $1 {We continue with the same plan. It is very easy to play these types of positions once we know the ideas. It's a shock to me that this move is not more popular. It's the 6th most-played option in the position.} 8. dxc5 Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4] With the bishop on [d3], we are threatening to jump to [b4] now.} 9. cxd5 Nb4 10. Qb3 Nxd3 11. Qxd3 Qxd5 $10 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1] We trade the queens, which may look surprising, but we are way ahead in development and will likely win back the pawn soon. We have the advantage of the bishop pair, which is more evident in the endgame. The bishop on [c1] will find it hard to become active.} *

