1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. Bf4 {This is the most popular move, getting the bishop out of the pawn chain before playing [e3].} Bg7 {The best part of our repertoire is that we are going for the same plan as we saw in the previous lines. We will castle next and go for the ...[c5] break. It's a very effective plan to exploit the queen on [c2] and make use of our dark-squared bishop.} 6. e3 O-O 7. Nc3 {White goes for the most natural move, keeping an eye on the [d5]-pawn.} c5 {Once again, this is the 3rd most popular move in the position, but this pawn break should be obvious to you after having seen it so many times previously in this chapter.} 8. dxc5 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] This is different from the lines we have seen so far. White has not yet developed his light-squared bishop. The bishop being on [f4] means that this pin is very annoying for White, and they cannot block it with [Bd2]. We will get our bishop to [f5] next.} 9. Rd1 {We come to the most popular move in the position, bringing the rook to the centre. White wants to force us to take on [c4] after which they can develop the [f1]-bishop in one go.} Ne4 $5 {I don't like to play on our opponent's terms, even if it is objectively fine for us. We will use our lead in development to play dynamically.} (9... dxc4 {followed by ... [Qc5] is also equal.}) 10. cxd5 {This is the more combative option for White, winning another pawn in the centre. However, it gives us a plethora of good options to choose from.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc8f5] I want to bring the other knight into the game. We will get this knight to [c5] and follow up with ...[Bf5]. We can always win back the [c3]-pawn.} 12. Be2 Nxc5 {White cannot allow us to get our bishop to [f5] next. The white queen would lack a good square.} 13. Nd4 Na4 {[%csl Rc3,Rd5] Now we go after the [c3]-pawn, forcing White to defend it. The [d5]-pawn is also under fire.} 14. Rc1 Nb6 $10 {[%csl Rf4,Rc3][%cal Gb6d5] We can take on [d5] with the knight next, attacking the bishop on [f4]. White has a weakness we can target on [c3]. The position is dynamically balanced due to White's slight lead in development, but we have the edge in the long run.} *

