1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {We saw the Fianchetto system in the Semi-Slav too, but now we are seeing it a move earlier. Playing g3 on move 4 is more flexible for White, as their queenside knight does not need to go to [c3]. However, the drawback for White is that we are able to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} Bf5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5,Rg2][%cal Ge7e6] The bishop is well placed along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We will play ...[e6] next and get solid control over the centre. The lines here are very different compared to earlier variations where White played [g3], as we are not going to go after the [c4]-pawn. The bishop on [g2] is not a great piece when the centre remains closed.} 5. Bg2 {This is the most common move in this position, but it is not the most critical one. White lets us consolidate the bishop on [f5]. As I mentioned before, this means we are doing very well positionally. White should try to create something quick and play dynamically.} (5. Qb3 {is a move we will see several times in this chapter, and our reaction is consistent across the different move orders:} Qb6 {. This will transpose into one of our other lines.}) 5... e6 6. Nc3 {I think this is a better square for the knight. The [f3]-knight can head to [d2] if required.} h6 {Once again, we need to create a luft for the bishop on [h7].} 7. Qb3 Qb6 {We would be very happy if White opens the a-file for our rook. Otherwise, we will maintain the tension and wait for White to force us to make a decision.} 8. c5 Qxb3 {We trade queens after White has played the move [c5]. The key point to note is that White is unable to break through on the queenside. Their only plan is to go for the [b4]-[b5] advance, but this is not very effective in most cases.} 9. axb3 Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ga7a6,Gb8d7] We want to castle as quickly as possible and connect the rooks. The knight will remain on [b8] for the moment.} 10. b4 O-O 11. O-O a6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8a8] We are going to move the knight from [b8] next, which will stop White from playing [b5]. This does not work well with the knight on [b8], as we will see.} 12. b5 {This is the most common move in the position. White creates some play on the queenside.} cxb5 13. Nxb5 Nc6 {[%csl Gc6,Gd4] We get the knight directly to its best square.} 14. Nc3 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gb7b6] The next step of our plan is to go for the ...[b6] break before White is able to play their pawn to [b4].} 15. Na4 {White stops our ...[b6] break, but misplaces the knight on [a4].} g5 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg5g4] This is a very useful move in these positions, taking control over the kingside. Here we also create a threat of ...[g4] to win the [d4]-pawn.} *

