1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {We saw the Fianchetto system in the Semi-Slav too, but now we are seeing it a move earlier. Playing g3 on move 4 is more flexible for White, as their queenside knight does not need to go to [c3]. However, the drawback for White is that we are able to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} Bf5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5,Rg2][%cal Ge7e6] The bishop is well placed along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We will play ...[e6] next and get solid control over the centre. The lines here are very different compared to earlier variations where White played [g3], as we are not going to go after the [c4]-pawn. The bishop on [g2] is not a great piece when the centre remains closed.} 5. Nc3 {This is the critical move, preparing to play [Nh4] very early. As I have mentioned, White needs to play dynamically in these lines.} e6 6. Nh4 {We move on to White's critical try, going after the bishop on [f5]. This is similar to the lines we saw in the 4.e3 chapter, but the move 4.g3 is less useful in comparison. Still, we need to play precisely.} Be4 {[%cal Rf2f3] We go for the same plan as we saw in the 4.e3 chapter, forcing White to weaken the kingside with the move [f3]. This is a double-edged idea, however, as it helps White get control over the centre.} 7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc1f4] The major difference compared to the earlier chapter is that White can get the bishop to [f4] in one go. This makes it impossible for us to put our queen on [c7].} Qd7 {[%csl Re1] We keep the queens on the board, which is more principled as White has weakened their kingside. The advantage is also that it is much less common compared to the main line.} (8... Qb6 {is the main move by far, and one of the top choices of the engine, but I do not want to trade queens when White can win the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. c5 Qxb3 11. axb3 Na6 {You can definitely analyse this further. It should be a draw with precise play, but I think Black has no chances to play for a win.}) 9. Nxg6 {This trade has to happen at one point or another. There is no point for White to maintain the tension for too long. If they do keep the tension, we can take on [c4] at the right moment and follow up with ...[Bc2].} hxg6 10. Bg2 {White gets ready to castle kingside. One of the issues for White is the pawn on [d4].} Be7 (10... Be7 {We keep it simple and consistent with our usual approach. We give White the option to transpose back to the main lines with} 11. Be3 {, which are considered next.}) (10... dxc4 {is also an option, to go after the [d4]-pawn. After} 11. Qxc4 b5 {Black should be okay, but I do not think it's necessary for us to play like this.}) 11. O-O {White decides to castle first and strengthen the centre next.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rg1] Of course, we grab the chance to break in the centre. This is very effective with White's king on [g1].} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e4 $1 {This is the best try for White, counter-attacking in the centre. They want to get the d-pawn to [d5], from where it will restrict our knight on [b8]. We have to be precise.} cxd4 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 {White trades the queens as they have the bishop pair. Both the central pawns are weak now, but it is easier for us to go after White's [d5]-pawn.} Qxd5 16. exd5 Na6 $10 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga6b4,Ge8c8] We will continue with either ...[Nb4] or queenside castling. The weak pawn on [d5] compensates for the bishop pair.} *

