1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Be2 {White forces us to abandon the idea of getting our bishop to [g4]. However, White's bishop is also slightly more passive on [e2] than on its usual square [d3].} Bf5 {The bishop looks good on [f5], but is it doing something useful there? We have to be careful, since compared to the previous lines it is harder for us to get the ...[e5] break in. All the pieces are still on the board.} 8. Nf3 e6 9. O-O {This is a tame approach, as White is not looking to use their slight lead in development to do something quick.} Be7 {Preserving the bishops is better in this case, as the light-squared bishops are still on the board. We need the dark-squared bishop to deal with White's play on the queenside. In earlier lines we could always go for the ...[e5] break.} 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Na4 Ne4 $10 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5] The knight does a good job on [e4] covering the [c5]-square. We have a hidden threat of ...[g5] and ...[h5] on the kingside, going after the dark-squared bishop.} *

