1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Bd3 {White gets their bishop to [d3], but keeps options open regarding the [g1]-knight.} Bg4 {Of course, we develop the bishop to [g4] before going for the move ...[e6].} 8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 {[%cal Gd6f4,Gg4d1] We are threatening to take on [f4], as White cannot recapture with the knight currently.} 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 {Our queen is doing a good job, keeping an eye on the [c5]-square and also preparing the move ...[e5] when needed.} 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Na4 e5 $1 {We could have played more slowly, but I think this is the right moment to break into the centre before the knight has landed on [c5]. The pin with the bishop on [g4] is also in our favour.} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. h3 {White wants to force our bishop back to [h5], after which White will play [Qd2] and [Nf4].} d4 $1 {We can give up a piece on [g4] as it will allow us to get a knight there, creating a lot of threats on [h2]. Otherwise, we manage to liquidate our IQP.} (14... d4 {We can meet} 15. hxg4 {with} Nfxg4 $1 16. Nxd4 Qh6 {and we get a nice attack on the kingside.}) *

