1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. b3 {This has been played several times, but it is a small inaccuracy. I hope that by now you know exactly how to deal with the [b3] idea.} cxd4 {[%csl Rb3,Rd4][%cal Rc1b2] We release the tension in the centre as soon as White plays [b3]. Now the bishop on [b2] will be staring at the [d4]-pawn.} 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 (6. Bd3 {runs into} Bg4 {⩱ with an unpleasant pin.}) 6... Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] The bishop is well placed on [f5]. White has to either allow a trade on [d3] or accept a more passive square on [e2] for their own bishop.} 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 {After this trade it is clear that we have the better minor pieces. The bishop on [b2] is not doing much.} e6 9. O-O Be7 10. c4 O-O {[%csl Ge7,Rb2][%cal Gd8c7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8] We do not need to do much. Just continue with developing moves such as ...[Rc8] and ...[Qc7]. The other rook will come to [d8].} *

