[GameId "2136127622443201"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. c3 {White plays it in the style of the Semi-Slav with colours reversed. If you think logically you will know which setup we will be going for.} e6 {If you recall, we put our bishop on [f5] against the 4.e3 system. Here White is unable to do that since they have already shut the bishop on [c1] with the move 3.e3. We discussed in the 4.e3 chapters that it is a better version for White when they have not yet committed the knight to [c3]. So we'll stick to that approach here, with colours reversed.} 5. Bd3 Nbd7 {We put our knight on [d7], leaving the [a8]-[h1] diagonal open for the bishop which we will develop to [b7].} 6. Nbd2 b6 {The first priority is to get the bishop to [b7], keeping good control over the [e4]-square.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Qe2 {This is pretty similar to the previous two lines. We have the same choice here as well.} Ne4 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gf7f5] Once again, this would be my main recommendation, as I like to keep the game complex and fighting. As we saw, we would love to play ...[Bd6] next and maybe ...[f5] to consolidate our control over the centre.} 9. c4 {White's best try, attempting to open up the position before we finish our development.} Bd6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b3 {White maintains the tension in the centre, which makes sense as it keeps our light-squared bishop restricted on [b7].} (11. dxc5 {can be met with} bxc5 {, as there is no pressure along the d-file.}) 11... O-O 12. Bb2 Qe7 {[%cal Gf7f5] We are ready to play ...[f5] next.} 13. Ba6 {White should be trading pieces as they have a slight long-term edge due to our potential hanging pawns in the centre.} Bxa6 14. Qxa6 Qe6 $10 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ga8d8] The trade of the bishops is not a big deal for us as the bishop was not doing much on [b7] with the pawn on [d5]. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre and will maintain the tension with the pawns. White cannot win the [a7]-pawn as the queen will face difficulty getting out of there.} *

