[Black "London 2.Nf3 with 5.Ne5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D02"]
[PlyCount "44"]
[GameId "2136127622480067"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Ne5 {This was recommended by Srinath and Sahaj in their LTR on the London on Chessable. It is a serious attempt to play for a win for White, but it also gives us the chance to take over in the complications.} O-O 6. Nd2 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf1d3,Gd2f3] The move order does not matter too muche. White will put their bishop on [d3] next and will be ready to reinforce the knight on [e5] with [Ndf3]. They will always meet ...[c5] with [c3] in these lines.} c5 7. c3 Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6] This is the same development plan we go for in the main line too. We want to put the queen on [c7] first, as the [b8]-knight could go to either [d7] or [c6].} 8. Bd3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7] With White's knight on [e5], we want to put the [b8]-knight on [c6] as it will head to [e7] next. White will bring their other knight to [f3] and we want to slowly prepare the move ...[f6].} 9. Ndf3 (9. Nxc6 {is harmless after} Bxf4 10. exf4 bxc6 {, with ...[c4] and ...[c5] to follow.}) 9... Ne7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf6e4,Gf7f6] We should aim to get the [f6]-knight to [e4] and then play ...[f6], as the knight on [e5] lacks a good square to retreat to. White, on the other hand, will try to create something on the kingside, making use of their active pieces.} 10. h4 {This was recommended in the LTR London course that I mentioned earlier. The move 10.h4 makes sense, as White is preparing to play [Ng5] and attack on the kingside. Then we cannot answer ...[h6] and win the knight, as it would open up the h-file.} cxd4 $1 {We follow the conventional wisdom: an attack on the flank should be countered in the centre. This is especially applicable here, as the white king is still in the centre.} 11. cxd4 (11. exd4 {is also met with the move} Ne4 {↑ , with ...[f6] coming up next. White has to be very careful here.}) 11... Ne4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf7f6] We get the knight to an active square in the middle of the board, but more importantly, we are ready to play ...[f6], kicking the knight out.} 12. Rc1 Qa5+ 13. Kf1 {White is threatening to take on [e4] and follow up with [Nc4], winning the bishop on [d6]. We have a few different options to choose from now.} Qxa2 {We go for the greedy approach, grabbing the unprotected pawns on the queenside. It does remove our queen from the fork on [c4], though, and renews the threat of ...[f6].} 14. h5 $1 {This was the recommendation for White in the LTR London course. White wants to play [h6] next. We have to be careful.} Bxe5 $1 {We eliminate one of the knights first, which reduces White's attacking chances on the kingside. It also means that White cannot play [Nc4] forking the queen on [b2] and the bishop on [d6] any longer.} (14... f6 {runs into} 15. h6 {and the position gets very complex.}) ({And} 14... Qxb2 {is a huge mistake due to} 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Nc4 {± followed by [Bxd6].}) 15. Nxe5 Qxb2 16. Bxe4 {Yet another exchange, which makes our life easier. There was no other good option with [f2] hanging.} dxe4 17. h6 {We are following the line recommended in the LTR London course. I am not a big fan of White fixing the pawn structure on the kingside.} g6 18. Kg1 {In the aforementioned course the line ends here, which makes sense as none of it has been played before. We will continue a bit deeper, though.} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6d8,Ge7d5] This is the easiest response, bringing the queen back to [d8] to hold the position together. I would not want to be White here, as I feel it is not going to be easy practically to prove the compensation for two pawns.} (18... Nd5 {is also good and transposes to the previous variation, but it gives White a few extra options.}) 19. Nc4 Qd8 20. Nd6 Nd5 {The knight gets to its ideal square. We are ready to play ...[f5] next.} ({The immediate} 20... f5 {runs into} 21. d5 $1 {+- .}) 21. Nxe4 Nxf4 22. exf4 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] White is the one who has to be careful here to equalise. We are ready to play ...[Bb7] next and are up a pawn.} *

