[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2136127622500548"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. Nbd2 {The knight always belongs on [d2] in these positions as White will play [c3] next, strengthening their control over [d4].} c5 7. c3 {This is an almost automatic reaction from White. They keep good control over [d4].} Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gb7b6] This is an important moment, which we need to remember clearly. Our plan is to get the [b8]-knight to [d7] to control the [e5]-square. We can then either go for the ...[e5] break, or more frequently for ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], finishing our development. We keep the diagonal open for the bishop and keep the [c5]-pawn defended.} (7... Nc6 {is the main move in the position, but the drawback is that we cannot get control over [e5] as easily. Then our queen cannot go to [c7], as the [c5]-pawn will hang.} 8. Bd3 Qe7 9. Ne5 {White gets the knight to [e5] in time. There is a very famous trap here which you must know:} Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 {This looks like the most natural recapture by far, but it is actually a serious mistake.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 {+- and White gets the knight to [g5] on the next move.}) 8. Bd3 {This is the most played move in the position. White puts the bishop on its ideal diagonal and is hinting at the [e4] advance in the near future. The problem is that this move allows us to get control over [e5] very easily.} Nbd7 {[%csl Ge5]} 9. O-O {It is very natural for White to castle first, but this allows us to execute our plan on the queenside easily.} Bxg3 {As I've mentioned in the previous variation, I think this change in pawn structure is in our favour. It becomes easier for us to create an attack on the kingside.} 10. hxg3 b6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8b7] We want to get our bishop to [b7] to keep an eye on the [e4]-square. This move is less common, but it's the more fighting option.} (10... e5 {is also possible, but I think it simplifies the game too much.}) 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bb7 13. Qe2 Qc6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc6e4] We want White to trade on [f6]. Otherwise, we will trade all the pieces on [e4] and go to an endgame, where I believe there is still play left due to the imbalance in the pawn structure.} (13... cxd4 {is seen in the model game Navara-Bok, chess.com 2023.}) 14. Nxf6+ (14. Rfe1 {allows us to simplify with} Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Qxe4 16. Qxe4 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Rfd8 {. We can play ...[c4] next and follow up with ...[Nf6]-[d5].}) 14... Nxf6 {[%cal Gb7g2] With the queen on [c6], White is unable to move their knight from [f3].} 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. dxc5 Qxc5 $10 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gg7g6,Gg8g7] We get the typical structure for this middlegame. We will play ...[g6] and ...[Kg7] on the kingside. White has a majority on the queenside, but it is not going to be easy to mobilise it. The position is balanced with decent play left for both sides.} *

