[Black "Overview: Meran & Anti-Meran"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D46"]
[PlyCount "16"]
[GameId "2136127622586568"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 {We will see all the different options here in the next few chapters. These form the backbone of our repertoire and are very common. White has a choice whether to go for quick development but allow us to take on [c4] with a tempo, or to delay the development of the [f1]-bishop for a bit.} 6. Qc2 {This is White's antidote to the Meran variation and has taken over in popularity. White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we would take on [c4], allowing White to get their bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we do not allow this, but it means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. Since White delays the move ...[dxc4], these systems are called the Anti-Meran.} (6. Be2 {I was not well prepared against this line until Sam Shankland published his [d4] repertoire on Chessable a few years ago. It has since gotten more popular, mainly because it is much easier to learn compared to the complex main lines. There is also the surprise factor, which played a big effect back then, but not anymore. The main point is that White will not recapture on [c4] with the bishop as usual. We will take a look at this and a few other sidelines in the fourth chapter.}) (6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing the move [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This variation was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise. This is called the Meran variation.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 {This is the best square for the bishop, although other squares do have some merit.} b4 $5 {This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly kick the knight away and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. The fact that 8...[b4] has been played much less often is good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation. (8...a6 This was contested in the World Championship matches between Anand and Gelfand. Anand won a couple of important games here as Black, but with modern computers, it is not as easy to equalise here after 9.e4 . ) (8...Bb7 This is one of the main lines and is recommended by Sethuraman, but there is a whole lot of theory here which I want to avoid. I do not think it is a good investment of our time to learn all of that. White gets to build up the centre with the move [e4]. ) (8...Bd6 This is Shankland's recommendation and usually transposes to the sharp lines in the Anti-Meran. However, it is out of the discussion for us, as we do not enter those lines in the Anti-Meran. )}) 6... Bd6 ({There is the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, it goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against the centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want control over the centre.} (7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the pawn. Now, we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] and going ...[e5].} O-O {We have two different plans here. We can go ...[e5] in the centre to exploit White's slow play. This is effective against both} 8. Bd3 {and 8.Bb2 . The main line is the move 8.Be2 , after which we have to play more slowly. The lines are a bit similar to that of Shankland and Sethuraman, but I focus more on the ...[e5] plan in the main lines compared to the other authors. This leads to more double-edged play.}) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 a6 $5 {As I mention throughout the course, I love the flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4], which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The move 8...a6 has been played in a decent number of games, but it is still likely to be a small surprise.} (8... b5 {This is by far the main line, and was recommended by Shankland. It leads to very messy positions where it is important to remember the details accurately. I was always pretty uncomfortable in such lines and it was a pain to keep revising them.}) *

