{We are going to start with one of my old games, played back in 2017. My opponent is not a strong player, but it is instructive to see how we can punish slow play from White.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 Bb7 (8... b4 {is my recommendation in the theory section.}) 9. O-O a6 10. b3 $6 {This is too slow here. White has to make use of his dynamic advantage in these lines. We will take over the position if we are allowed to complete our development and go for the ...[c5] break.} (10. e4 {is the critical move.}) 10... c5 11. Bb2 Bd6 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Ne2 Qe7 14. Ng3 Rac8 {We have brought all the pieces to their best squares. Next, we can start our play in the centre.} 15. Qe2 cxd4 $1 {Every recapture is unpleasant for White. If he recaptures with the pawn he gets an IQP on [d4] and we have great control over [d5]. If he recaptures with either minor piece, ...[e5]-[e4] is an issue for him.} (15... Rfd8 {allows} 16. a4) 16. Nxd4 Ba3 $5 {I wanted to trade the dark-squared bishops to get better control over the [c3]-square. Our light-squared bishop is much better placed on [b7] compared to White's bishop.} (16... g6 $1 {was slightly better, preparing to continue with ...[e5] quickly.}) 17. Rfd1 g6 {Now I am preparing the move ...[e5] by covering the [f5]-square.} 18. Bb1 Nd5 (18... h5 $1 {A very common idea in this pawn structure is to go ...[h4]-[h3] on the kingside. The added benefit here is to kick away the knight on [g3]. Those days this plan was not as common yet.}) 19. Ne4 {White tries to cover the [c3]-square, but this is too provocative. We want to gain as much space as possible in the centre, and White is helping us.} e5 20. Nf3 Bxb2 21. Qxb2 b4 $1 {We have the [c3]-square firmly under control, and ...[f5] is coming next to kick the knight back.} 22. Ng3 Nc3 23. Re1 e4 24. Nd4 Ne5 25. Qd2 Rc5 $1 {The rook will swing over to the kingside along the 5th rank. We are also able to double on the c-file now, to keep control over the knight on [c3].} 26. Nge2 Rfc8 27. Nxc3 bxc3 28. Qe2 Qh4 29. Bc2 Nf3+ {I decided to go for it immediately on the kingside. It would also have made sense to prepare the attack a bit more slowly, as White has no counterplay.} 30. Nxf3 exf3 31. g3 Qh6 $1 {I want to go after [h2] with ...[Rh5] next. I was very proud of this game because even engines fail to evaluate it correctly initially. They underestimate Black's play on the kingside.} 32. Qf1 (32. Qd3 Rh5 33. h4 Rxh4 34. gxh4 Qxh4 35. Qd6 Rc5 {-+}) 32... Rh5 33. h4 Rxh4 $3 {My coach used to call this situation 'lack of communication'. The pawn on [f3] makes sure that the White king is boxed in on the kingside, and he is not able to bring more pieces to defend. In these situations, even a slow attack is deadly.} 34. gxh4 Qxh4 35. e4 Qg4+ 36. Kh2 Rc5 $1 {Bringing all the pieces into the game and, more importantly, clearing the [c8]-square for the bishop.} 37. e5 Qh4+ 38. Kg1 (38. Qh3 Qxf2+ 39. Kh1 Qd2 {-+}) 38... Bc8 $1 {The bishop joins the fray and White is unable to stop the move ...[Bh3]. The white queen will be kicked away, and White cannot stop a check on [g5].} 39. Re4 Qh5 40. Bd1 Qg5+ 41. Kh2 Qxc1 {This game shows how deadly the Semi-Slav can be if our opponent plays too slowly. We are better in the long run due to our more actively placed pieces.} 0-1

