[GameId "2136127622635722"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 {This is my recommendation in the course. It's a pretty clever system. We are very flexible and are waiting for White's next move.} 10. Rd1 b5 11. Bf1 {The bishop usually goes to either [e2] or [d3]. Putting the bishop on [f1] has a very specific drawback.} Qc7 {This is not bad either, preparing to go ...[c5] next. One big advantage in this line is that the bishop is still on [c8]. This is helpful in many lines to cover the [f5]-square.} (11... c5 $1 {This is easier, exploiting the rook on [d1]. It is my recommendation in the theory section.} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 {This is possible only because White moved the bishop back to [f1].}) 12. e4 e5 13. g3 Re8 14. Bg2 h6 {As I've mentioned, Black is delaying the move ...[Bb7] for a while.} 15. h3 c5 $1 {Finally, Black forces White to release the tension in the centre. White now has to make a tough decision.} 16. dxe5 {This is the more fighting option, but it is also more risky as the [e4]-pawn comes under a lot of pressure.} (16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Ra7 {and we would reach a more symmetrical structure. However, I prefer Black due to the passive bishop on [g2].}) 16... Nxe5 17. Nh4 $6 {White is preparing to go [f4] and [e5] in the centre, but he has not yet completed his development.} g5 (17... c4 $1 {was better to get the knight to [d3] immediately but the lines are extremely hard to find over the board.} 18. f4 Nd3 19. e5 g5 $3 {We give up the rook along the long diagonal, but we will break open the centre soon.} 20. Bxa8 Qa7+ 21. Kh2 Qxa8 {The control Black gets along the long diagonal is easily worth the exchange.} 22. fxg5 Rxe5 $1 23. gxf6 Rh5 {-+ This is a fascinating position where Black is down a whole rook, but the white kingside is in complete ruins.}) 18. Nf5 (18. Nf3 {is not possible due to} Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 Bxh3 {-+}) 18... Bxf5 19. exf5 Rad8 20. a4 $1 {White needs to break our structure on the queenside. This is a typical idea in this pawn structure.} (20. a3 c4 {-+}) 20... b4 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Nd7 $1 {I like this manoeuvre to get the knight to [f6]. This keeps our kingside very secure and we can push our pawns on the queenside.} 23. f6 $2 {White tries to create something on the kingside, but this is just going to backfire. As I've mentioned earlier, he has still not developed his queenside.} (23. Be3 {was better.} Nf6 24. Rd2 c4 {↑}) 23... Nxf6 24. Rf5 Re1+ 25. Kh2 Nh5 {g3 is under a lot of pressure. Moreover, Black is dominating positionally here, with ...[Rde8]-[e2] to follow next. Black is easily winning.} 26. Qb3 Ng7 27. Rf6 c4 28. Qf3 h5 $1 {We bring another attacker to the kingside.} 29. Rh6 h4 30. Qg4 hxg3+ 31. fxg3 Qc5 32. h4 Bxg3+ 33. Qxg3 Qg1+ 34. Kh3 Rd3 35. Bf3 Rxf3 36. Qxf3 g4+ 37. Qxg4 Qh1+ 38. Kg3 Rg1+ {Once again, we see how easily Black can take over the position if White is not accurate. White got over-ambitious on the kingside with his queenside still undeveloped.} 0-1

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Arjun's Semi-Slav"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Meran & Anti-Meran: Overview"]
[Black "Karthik Venkataraman vs. Arjun Kalyan, Pune 2022"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "D46"]
[PlyCount "86"]
[GameId "2136127622656203"]

{In this game I am playing against my friend and roommate Karthik, who has recently won his second Indian National Championship.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 {I had prepared this line a while ago, but had never gotten a chance to use it earlier. I was pretty confident that this would come as a surprise to Karthik, as he is not a conventional [d4] player. He probably had some very concrete prep in the main lines.} 10. Rd1 b5 11. Be2 Qc7 12. e4 e5 13. g3 {This is pretty slow here and is very similar to what we saw in the previous game.} Re8 14. a3 exd4 15. Nxd4 Be5 $1 {I was pretty happy with myself for coming up with this idea over the board. Black is preparing to go ...[c5] on the next move and kick the knight away. The bishop on [e5] is indirectly fighting for the [e4]-square as it targets the [c3]-knight.} 16. Bf3 (16. f4 {is bad due to} Bxd4+ 17. Rxd4 c5 {-+}) 16... Bxd4 {This was a bit hasty. I've always had this issue with maintaining the tension. I like clarifying the position, but in many cases you end up losing part of your advantage.} (16... Bb7 17. Bg2 c5 18. Nf5 g6 19. Nh6+ Kg7 {⩱}) 17. Rxd4 Ne5 18. Bg2 c5 19. Nd5 {White has to trade these knights and simplify the position.} (19. Rd2 c4 {⩱}) 19... Nxd5 20. Rxd5 c4 21. Bf4 Bb7 22. Rd2 Qe7 23. Bxe5 {This came accompanied by a draw offer. I might have considered taking it against another player, but I knew my opponent was a very fighting player in general. If he is offering a draw, most likely he feels pretty uncomfortable with his position.} Qxe5 24. Re1 Rad8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Rd1 Rd4 27. h3 Kf8 28. f4 Rxd1+ 29. Qxd1 Qc5+ 30. Kh2 Ke7 31. Qd2 f6 {The position has simplified quite a bit. It is very close to a draw, but I felt Black had the slight pull due to the majority on the queenside and a more active bishop.} 32. g4 h6 33. e5 Bxg2 34. exf6+ Kxf6 35. Qd8+ $2 {White wants to force the draw, and this is a significant mistake.} (35. Kxg2 Ke7) 35... Kf7 $2 (35... Ke6 $1 {This was just not on my radar and is a very unusual move. However, now we are able to force the trade of queens in most situations.} 36. Qg8+ Kd6 37. Qf8+ Kc6 38. Qa8+ Kc7 39. Qxg2 Qe3 {-+}) 36. Qd7+ $4 {He gives me another chance to go for the queen trade. It is much easier now.} (36. Kxg2 Qc6+ 37. Kf2 Qe4 38. Qc7+ Kg8 39. Qe5) 36... Qe7 $1 37. Qxe7+ (37. Qf5+ Qf6 38. Qd7+ Kg8 39. Qe8+ Kh7 40. Kxg2 Qxb2+ 41. Kg3 Qxa3+ 42. Kh4 Qd3 {-+}) 37... Kxe7 38. Kxg2 a5 39. Kf3 b4 40. axb4 c3 $1 {White probably missed this, but even with slow play it was a winning position for me.} 41. bxc3 a4 42. b5 a3 43. b6 Kd7 0-1

