{We will see another one of my games here. I promise you that the other sections will contain less of my personal games. :-} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a popular line, as it stops Black from taking on [c4] early. White gets a slow positional game.} O-O 8. Be2 {This is the best square for the bishop, otherwise we get the move ...[e5] in.} (8. Bb2 e5) 8... b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 11. Rad1 Rad8 12. Rfe1 Rfe8 13. Bf1 e5 $1 {This is the more fighting option, especially when White has played the move [Bf1]. We get an imbalance in the pawn structure and are looking to attack on the kingside.} (13... c5 {is another very common move.}) 14. g3 $2 {White allows us to close the position in the centre. The major issue with this is White's queen, which is stuck on [c2]. Now we'll get easy play on the kingside.} (14. cxd5 $2 {This a trap which I have desperately been hoping for almost 10 years now. I was so hopeful that he was going to fall for it. You can take a look at it here, in the theory section. The beauty is that even modern engines do not see it immediately.}) 14... e4 15. Nd2 a6 {I wanted to first make sure that there is no play on the queenside for White, but this move is not really required.} (15... Ng4 $1 {This is a surprising idea. We want to stop the move [f3] and we prepare to play ...[f5] next. Our point is that the move [h3] is a big weakness which we can exploit.} 16. h3 Ngf6 {∓ Even though we have wasted two full moves, now we can implement the plan of ...[h5]-[h4], which is very strong.}) 16. Bg2 (16. f3 $1 {White should look to open up the centre if possible.} exf3 17. e4 {⇆}) 16... Ng4 17. Nf1 (17. Ndxe4 $1 {I was shocked to see this suggestion of the engine. It claims that this is the only way to stop our play on the kingside. White needs to react before we go ...[f5]. Now the game is not that clear with his pieces freeing up.} dxe4 18. Nxe4 Bb4 {∓ We still maintain an edge.}) 17... f5 18. Rc1 g5 $6 {This is sloppy as it allows White to get the [f3] break in. I underestimated this idea in the game.} (18... h5 $1 19. f3 Nh6 {∓ with an almost winning advantage.}) 19. Bh3 (19. f3 $1 Ngf6 {(19...Nh6 is better. 20.Nd2 Nf6 ⩱)} 20. g4 {⇆ This is the only move, and is insanely hard to find over the board. But if White does find it, he manages to free up his position and his knight is heading to [g3] and [f5] next.}) 19... h5 {Now, we have managed to stop all the counterplay on the kingside. It is completely one-sided now.} 20. f3 Nh6 21. fxe4 fxe4 22. Bxd7 Rxd7 23. Na4 Bc7 24. b4 Qe6 25. cxd5 cxd5 26. Qe2 g4 {I want to bring the knight to [f3] next via [f7] and [g5]. My idea was to continue the attack slowly, without giving White any counterplay. I can afford this due to the domination in the centre and on the kingside.} (26... h4 {-+ is also winning for Black.}) 27. Rc2 Nf7 28. Rec1 Bd8 29. h4 gxh3 30. Qxh5 Ng5 31. Nh2 Rf8 32. Rf1 Rxf1+ 33. Kxf1 Rh7 34. Qd1 Qd6 35. Qg4 Bc6 $1 {We bring the bishop over to kick the queen back. The game is completely over now.} 36. Nc3 Bd7 37. Qe2 Qxg3 38. Nxd5 Rf7+ 39. Nf4 Bb5 {A beautiful final position with complete domination all around the board. This is my favourite game in the Semi-Slav and led to me playing it exclusively for several years.} 0-1

