[White "1) Semi-Slav Meran: 6.Bd3"]
[Black "Meran 6.Bd3: 8.Bb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D47"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2136127622688973"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bb3 {What is the bishop doing on [b3]? It is unlikely that we are going to go ...[e5] and open the diagonal for the bishop. It does not fight for the centre and it can come under fire after the ...[c5] break. The only point I see is to help meet the move ...[c5] with [d5], but this rarely works.} Bb7 ({What are the different options for us here? We can go} 8... a6 {and prepare the ...[c5] break. 8...b4 is another option. We can also play more slowly with 8...Be7 . All of these moves make sense and in such cases, we need to figure out what is the most necessary move. There are different plans on the queenside and the dark-squared bishop can go to [d6] or directly to [c5] in some lines. The light-squared bishop almost always goes to [b7], and this is the most flexible move, keeping other options open.}) 9. O-O (9. e4 {runs into the move} b4 10. e5 bxc3 11. exf6 Nxf6 {when we will continue with ...[Be7] and ...[O-O], followed by an eventual ...[c5] break.}) 9... Be7 {The bishop is usually better here when the White bishop is not on [d3]. This is because there we have to meet the move [e4] with ...[e5], and then the bishop is better on [d6]. Here, [e4] is met with the move ...[b4] and the [e4]-pawn is in trouble.} ({The main move in the position is} 9... a6 {, but I think this is not necessary yet. We often just avoid it and go for the direct ...[c5] break or go ...[b4] followed by ...[c5].}) 10. a3 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge3e4] White stops the move [b4] in order to play [e4] next. However, [e4] is not a huge threat with the bishop on [b3].} O-O 11. e4 c5 $1 {[%cal Gb7e4] We go for the typical ...[c5] break and open the diagonal for the bishop. With the bishop on [b3], we do not mind the fact that the [b5]-pawn is undefended. We have enough play in the centre.} 12. e5 Ng4 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc5d4,Gb7f3] The knight looks stuck on [g4], but we are going after the pawn on [e5]. ...[cxd4] is coming up next, and we can also eliminate the knight on [f3].} 13. h3 (13. Nxb5 {is met by} cxd4 {⩱ .}) 13... cxd4 14. Qxd4 {This is essential to keep an eye on the [e5]-pawn.} Bxf3 {[%csl Re5] We eliminate the key defender of the [e5]-pawn.} 15. hxg4 Bc6 $36 {[%cal Gd8b8,Gf8d8,Gb8b7,Gb7g2] I like the plan to go ...[Qb8] next followed by ...[Rd8]. The queen would be ideal on [b7] along the long diagonal. We would love to force the move [f3], weakening White's kingside. The bishop on [b3] is useless here and has to go to [c2] soon.} *

