1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bb3 {What is the bishop doing on [b3]? It is unlikely that we are going to go ...[e5] and open the diagonal for the bishop. It does not fight for the centre and it can come under fire after the ...[c5] break. The only point I see is to help meet the move ...[c5] with [d5], but this rarely works.} Bb7 ({What are the different options for us here? We can go} 8... a6 {and prepare the ...[c5] break. 8...b4 is another option. We can also play more slowly with 8...Be7 . All of these moves make sense and in such cases, we need to figure out what is the most necessary move. There are different plans on the queenside and the dark-squared bishop can go to [d6] or directly to [c5] in some lines. The light-squared bishop almost always goes to [b7], and this is the most flexible move, keeping other options open.}) 9. O-O (9. e4 {runs into the move} b4 10. e5 bxc3 11. exf6 Nxf6 {when we will continue with ...[Be7] and ...[O-O], followed by an eventual ...[c5] break.}) 9... Be7 {The bishop is usually better here when the White bishop is not on [d3]. This is because there we have to meet the move [e4] with ...[e5], and then the bishop is better on [d6]. Here, [e4] is met with the move ...[b4] and the [e4]-pawn is in trouble.} ({The main move in the position is} 9... a6 {, but I think this is not necessary yet. We often just avoid it and go for the direct ...[c5] break or go ...[b4] followed by ...[c5].}) 10. Qe2 {White prepares the move [e4] next, but this takes the [e2] square away from the knight.} b4 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc3e2] We immediately exploit it and force the knight to [a4]. The knight is stuck there as we have the [c5]-square firmly under control.} 11. Na4 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gb7a6,Ga6f1] We prepare to go ...[Ba6] next, winning an exchange. This shows another drawback of the move [Qe2]. We are also preparing the move ...[c5] at the right moment to open the diagonal for the bishop.} 12. Rd1 O-O {White has no direct threats and we can take a move to get our king to safety.} (12... c5 13. Bd2 {gives White some counterplay.}) 13. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] White finally gets the move [e4] in and is planning to go [e5] next. But this has been too slow, and we are in time to fight back in the center.} Qb5 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5] We force the queen away from the [e2] square and also activate our queen. The queen was defending the knight on [f3] and keeping an eye on [e4]. We exploit the knight on [a4] as White is unable to take on [b5]. We will go for the move [c5] next and we will rather have the bishop on [b7] than on [a6].} (13... c5 {is met with} 14. e5 {∞ .}) 14. Qc2 c5 15. e5 Be4 {This is another benefit for us of the white queen being on [c2]. We get the bishop to [e4] with a tempo. White is forced to trade the queens now.} 16. Qc4 Qxc4 17. Bxc4 Nd5 $10 {[%cal Re4c2] We are threatening to go ...[Bc2] here. White is forced to take on [c5], which leads to a comfortable endgame for us. The [e5]-pawn is a long-term problem for White.} *

