1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bb3 {What is the bishop doing on [b3]? It is unlikely that we are going to go ...[e5] and open the diagonal for the bishop. It does not fight for the centre and it can come under fire after the ...[c5] break. The only point I see is to help meet the move ...[c5] with [d5], but this rarely works.} Bb7 ({What are the different options for us here? We can go} 8... a6 {and prepare the ...[c5] break. 8...b4 is another option. We can also play more slowly with 8...Be7 . All of these moves make sense and in such cases, we need to figure out what is the most necessary move. There are different plans on the queenside and the dark-squared bishop can go to [d6] or directly to [c5] in some lines. The light-squared bishop almost always goes to [b7], and this is the most flexible move, keeping other options open.}) 9. O-O (9. e4 {runs into the move} b4 10. e5 bxc3 11. exf6 Nxf6 {when we will continue with ...[Be7] and ...[O-O], followed by an eventual ...[c5] break.}) 9... Be7 {The bishop is usually better here when the White bishop is not on [d3]. This is because there we have to meet the move [e4] with ...[e5], and then the bishop is better on [d6]. Here, [e4] is met with the move ...[b4] and the [e4]-pawn is in trouble.} ({The main move in the position is} 9... a6 {, but I think this is not necessary yet. We often just avoid it and go for the direct ...[c5] break or go ...[b4] followed by ...[c5].}) 10. Re1 {The is the most played move in the position, preparing to go [e4].} b4 {We kick the knight back. We are also ready to go for the move ...[c5] immediately.} 11. Na4 c5 12. e4 {White sacrifices a pawn for the initiative. They finally make use of their lead in development.} ({After} 12. dxc5 O-O {⩱ we will eventually win back the pawn on [c5]. There is no rush at all.}) 12... Bxe4 {I have a rule: take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger. I think it was Nimzowitsch who came up with it in his book 'My System'. There must be an emphasis on the not much danger part, though! :- Here, we can castle on the next move and get our king to safety.} 13. Ng5 Bg6 {[%cal Ge8g8] I like this more as it enables us to castle quicker. The drawback is clear: White can win the pawn on [e6]. However, this is only our extra pawn, and we do not mind giving it up in order to keep our king safe.} (13... Bd5 {is a good alternative, but the position gets complex after} 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 15. Qh5 g6 16. Qh6 {∞ .}) 14. Bxe6 $1 {We cannot afford to take this sacrifice with our king still in the centre. However, there is nothing too dangerous for White.} O-O 15. Bb3 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Nc5 $10 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gd4d8,Gf8d8,Rd1h1] We force the trade of queens and reach an equal endgame. Note that we can recapture on [d8] with the rook due to White's back rank issue. The pawn on [b4] can be a trump in the endgame. 16...Nc5 may not be the most ambitious response, but we have plenty of play left in the endgame. It is not necessary that the position has to be very complicated for us to outplay our opponent.} *

