1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Be2 {This is similar to 8.Bb3 in a lot of ways, and our plan remains the same. White cannot get the move [e4] as easily as in the lines with 8.Bd3. Here we do not go for the move ...[a6] early on, as we often are just able to avoid it completely.} Bb7 {This is the most flexible and necessary move here.} 9. e4 {This is pretty similar to the 10.e4 lines which we will look at next. Here, White wants to delay castling for a bit and tries to create something quick on the queenside.} b4 {[%csl Re4] White cannot defend the [e4]-pawn and instead should advance the pawn exchanging the knights.} 10. e5 bxc3 11. exf6 Nxf6 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gf8d6] I like to recapture with the knight, in order to soon follow up with the ...[c5] break. The Queen is better off on the queenside, [c7] for example. We can now get our bishop to [d6] which is a more active square compared to [e7].} (11... cxb2 {is possible, but there is no need to allow our kingside to be weakened.}) 12. bxc3 Bd6 {[%cal Rc6c5,Re2b5] We have to castle before going for the ...[c5] break, as otherwise there is a check on [b5] which is quite annoying.} 13. Rb1 ({White has to do something quick. Otherwise we get the ...c5 break very easily. We are statically better here.} 13. O-O {does not help White after} O-O {.}) 13... Qc7 14. Qb3 Rb8 15. Ba3 {[%csl Gc5] White's goal is to trade the dark-squared bishops and get control over the [c5]-square. But this will not be easy to achieve.} O-O {[%cal Gc6c5] Already ...[c5] is a big threat now. White should take the chance to trade the bishops immediately.} 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. O-O Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5f4,Gc6c5,Gb7g2] I like this move, regrouping our knight to [f4]. White's slow play on the queenside gives us the chance to take over the initiative.} (17... c5 {can be met by} 18. Qa3 {.}) 18. Qc4 Nf4 19. Rfd1 c5 $10 (19... c5 {We finally achieve the ...c5 break. White has to answer} 20. dxc5 {, and we get a great position after} Nxe2+ 21. Qxe2 Qxc5 {when our bishop is the superior minor piece and White has a clear weakness on [c3].}) *

