1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Be2 {This is similar to 8.Bb3 in a lot of ways, and our plan remains the same. White cannot get the move [e4] as easily as in the lines with 8.Bd3. Here we do not go for the move ...[a6] early on, as we often are just able to avoid it completely.} Bb7 {This is the most flexible and necessary move here.} 9. O-O {This is a more flexible move, as White at least waits for us to develop the dark-squared bishop.} Be7 {As I mentioned earlier, we keep the bishop on [e7] in these lines, as we are not planning to meet [e4] with ...[e5]. We usually go for ...[b4] followed by ...[c5] at the right moment.} (9... Bd6 {does not work well here due to} 10. e4 b4 11. e5 bxc3 12. exd6 {+- when White has managed to win the important dark-squared bishop, which gives them a huge advantage.}) 10. a3 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge3e4] White stops the move ...[b4] and gets ready to play [e4] next.} a5 {[%cal Gb5b4] Of course, we renew the threat. I think the inclusion of [a3] and ...[a5] favours us in these lines, as White will be forced to trade the rooks on [a8].} 11. b3 {This plan is pretty slow, allowing us to achieve our plans easily on the queenside. If not for the [e4] plan it is hard for White to create any problems for us.} O-O 12. Bb2 b4 {This is a typical move, kicking the knight away before playing ...[c5] next.} 13. axb4 axb4 14. Na4 c5 {[%cal Gb7f3,Gf6e4,Ga8c8] We finally activate the bishop on [b7]. We will continue with ...[Ne4] or ...[Rc8] next.} 15. Nd2 {White stops ...[Ne4] and prepares to go [Bf3].} cxd4 16. Bxd4 Qb8 $10 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gf8d8] This is a common idea in these positions, in order to bring our [f8]-rook into the game. On [c7] the queen would come under fire along the c-file. Now we will continue with ...[Rc8] or ...[Rd8] next.} *

