] in these lines, as we are not planning to meet [e4] with ...[e5]. We usually go for ...[b4] followed by ...[c5] at the right moment.} (9... Bd6 {does not work well here due to} 10. e4 b4 11. e5 bxc3 12. exd6 {+- when White has managed to win the important dark-squared bishop, which gives them a huge advantage.}) 10. a3 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge3e4] White stops the move ...[b4] and gets ready to play [e4] next.} a5 {[%cal Gb5b4] Of course, we renew the threat. I think the inclusion of [a3] and ...[a5] favours us in these lines, as White will be forced to trade the rooks on [a8].} 11. Qc2 {The queen is usually best placed here on [c2], but this works better with the bishop on [d3]. Here, White will try to either go [Rd1] next or bring the rook to [c1] after [Bd2]. The white queen might come under fire later on along the c-file.} O-O 12. Bd2 {White develops the last piece, connecting the rooks. All their options are open.} (12. Rd1 {is also met with the move} Qb8 $1 {= .}) 12... Qb8 $1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf8c8] A typical regrouping in order to bring the rook to [c8]. We defend the bishop on [b7] too. Another advantage is that we keep an eye on the [e5]-square. We can even go ...[e5] ourselves.} 13. Rfc1 Rc8 14. Qd1 h6 15. h3 e5 $10 {[%cal Gb8e5] Instead of the ...[c5] break opening up files for White's rooks, we go for this central break, making use of our queen on [b8].} *

