1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Be2 {This is similar to 8.Bb3 in a lot of ways, and our plan remains the same. White cannot get the move [e4] as easily as in the lines with 8.Bd3. Here we do not go for the move ...[a6] early on, as we often are just able to avoid it completely.} Bb7 {This is the most flexible and necessary move here.} 9. O-O {This is a more flexible move, as White at least waits for us to develop the dark-squared bishop.} Be7 {As I mentioned earlier, we keep the bishop on [e7] in these lines, as we are not planning to meet [e4] with ...[e5]. We usually go for ...[b4] followed by ...[c5] at the right moment.} (9... Bd6 {does not work well here due to} 10. e4 b4 11. e5 bxc3 12. exd6 {+- when White has managed to win the important dark-squared bishop, which gives them a huge advantage.}) 10. e4 {This is the most common move, trying to get in the [e5] advance. As usual, the drawback of [Be2] is that the [e4]-pawn is not sufficiently defended.} b4 11. e5 {This is necessary, but White trades their central pawn for our b-pawn, which is in our favour.} bxc3 12. exf6 Bxf6 {[%cal Gc6c5] We can take on [f6] here with the bishop. We do not take with the knight as our bishop is already on [e7] and cannot go to [d6] directly.} 13. bxc3 c5 {This is one advantage of taking with the bishop: we can play ...[c5] faster without worrying about the check on [b5]. The bishop is well placed along the long diagonal.} 14. Rb1 Be4 {We gain a tempo by attacking the rook on [b1].} 15. Bd3 Bxd3 {We trade the light-squared bishops, which should help us in the fight against White's centre. Even though our bishop looked very active on the long diagonal, it had no stable square.} 16. Qxd3 O-O 17. Rd1 cxd4 {We force a weakness in White's pawn structure. It can either be the pawn on [d4] or the pawn on [c3].} 18. cxd4 Nb6 $10 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb6d5] The knight is heading to the [d5] outpost. We have a clear plan to play against the weak pawn on [d4].} *

