1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bd3 {This is the best square for the bishop, keeping an eye on [e4]. It is also by far the most-played move in the position. White can generally either go for the direct [e4] or he can castle first before going [e4].} (8. Bd3 {Now, the two main lines here are} a6 {and 8...Bb7 . 8...Bd6 is also possible, but it transposes into the main lines of the Anti-Meran variation which we don't enter. We go for another option here, which has not been explored much but is among the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Na4 {This is the usual way of responding to the move ...[b4] as we have seen in the previous lines. However, White had the chance to get the knight to [e4] instead, as the bishop is on [d3]. White's main idea should be to try and stop us from going for the ...[c5] break. They have not managed to achieve that here.} (9. Ne2 {is not great as we can answer} c5 {very easily.}) 9... c5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] We have managed to execute our plan on the queenside. Now, the bishop will be very strong on [b7] and I have seen so many games where Black takes over the initiative easily.} 10. dxc5 {This is usually just helping our game, as we can get our pieces out easily. The more ambitious way for White is to allow us to take on [d4]. Even better would be to play [d5], but that is not possible here.} Nxc5 11. Bb5+ {White tries to exchange the light-squared bishops.} (11. Nxc5 Bxc5 {only helps us get our bishop out directly.}) 11... Ncd7 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7g2] I prefer keeping the bishops on the board! Our bishop is better on the long diagonal. This does mean that we are delaying our development, but we always have to pay a small price if we want to be ambitious.} 12. Ne5 {This has been played in a few games of online chess. It's quite a useful tool to check what has been played frequently on chess.com and which moves have a good score for either side.} Qa5 {[%cal Ga5e5,Gb5d7,Gf6d7] The queen is well placed here, targeting both the pieces on the 5th rank.} 13. Bc6 $1 {This is the only move for White not to be worse, which is a good sign for us. This is a key aspect of opening preparation: understanding which moves are harder to play for the opponent. There is no point in blindly following the top choices of the computer.} (13. Bxd7+ {is met by} Nxd7 $1 {∓ , after which the white knight is kicked back, as a trade on [d7] would put the [a4]-knight in trouble.}) 13... Rb8 14. Bxd7+ {[%cal Rf6d7,Re5c6] The big difference now is that we cannot take on [d7] with the knight, as it runs into a fork on [c6]. Forcing the rook to [b8] makes a huge difference.} Bxd7 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. O-O Qe5 $10 {[%cal Ge5a1] I like this move, stopping White's ideal development with [b3] and [Bb2]. We pose small problems for White on each move, giving them the chance to go wrong. That's the key to winning games, which many people don't understand: give your opponent chances to go wrong!} *

