 of [Nc6].} Qa5 14. Be2 Bb7 {Finally, the bishop gets to its ideal diagonal. White can trade the bishops on [f3], but they will be left with a passive bishop on [c1].} 15. Bd2 {[%cal Ga2a3] White creates a threat of [a3]. This is how you try to exploit a lead in development. We have to be precise here.} e5 $1 {It's time to play concrete chess. The knight is forced to go back to [f3]. Keep in mind, though, that playing ...[e5] weakens some of the squares in the centre.} 16. Nf3 Bxf3 $1 {[%cal Ge2f3,Ge5e4] This is a really surprising move for me as we give up the bishop pair voluntarily. The point is that White is forced to take with the g-pawn. We want to follw up with ...[e4] followed by ...[Bd6] and start attacking on the kingside.} 17. gxf3 (17. Bxf3 $2 {runs into} e4 18. Be2 Bd6 {∓ .}) 17... e4 $36 {[%cal Ga5f5,Gh7h5,Gh8h6,Gf6g4] We have a nice initiative on the kingside. Our queen will go to [f5] next. One potential idea is to go ...[h5] followed by activating the rook via [h6], or to play ...[Ng4].} *

