mong the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Na4 {This is the usual way of responding to the move ...[b4] as we have seen in the previous lines. However, White had the chance to get the knight to [e4] instead, as the bishop is on [d3]. White's main idea should be to try and stop us from going for the ...[c5] break. They have not managed to achieve that here.} (9. Ne2 {is not great as we can answer} c5 {very easily.}) 9... c5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] We have managed to execute our plan on the queenside. Now, the bishop will be very strong on [b7] and I have seen so many games where Black takes over the initiative easily.} 10. O-O {[%cal Ge3e4] White maintains the tension, asking us to take on [d4], to either open the diagonal for the [c1]-bishop or to get the knight to the center with a tempo. Their idea is to play [e4] next if given the chance.} cxd4 {This is important here, to make sure that White does not get the move [e4] easily. Now White has a choice between the two recaptures.} 11. Nxd4 {I think this is better, with the intention to go [Qf3] next. The drawback of the knight on [d4] is that we can get ...[e5] with a tempo as we saw in the previous line.} (11. exd4 {can be met with} Bb7 {and we will follow up with ...[Bd6] next.}) 11... Bb7 12. b3 {Since White is unable to get the move [e4] in, they develop the bishop to the long diagonal. The position is somewhat symmetrical.} Be7 13. Bb2 O-O {We finally get our king to safety. Our plan is to go ...[Rc8] and ...[Qa5] next.} 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. Qe2 Qa5 $10 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gb7a6,Gf6e4,Ge7f6] This is a better square for the queen than [e2]. We are now threatening to play ...[Ne5], followed by ...[Ba6] if the bishop moves back. Another idea in these positions is to go ...[Ne4] and ...[Bf6]. We are on the better side of equality.} *

