1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 {White defends the pawn on [c4] and wants to develop the light-squared bishop next. At the same time, the [c1]-bishop is usually not very active in these lines.} Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {An important flexible move, waiting for White's next move. This is broadly known as the Meran variation, particularly after the move} 6. Bd3 {, which we will see in this chapter. Over the last two decades the move 6.Qc2 has taken over and is called the Anti-Meran. Both sides are playing a cat-and-mouse game: we are waiting for [Bd3] to take on [c4] with a tempo.}) (5... dxc4 $6 {I see a lot of players confusing the move order and taking on [c4] immediately. This is a big inaccuracy, as White takes on [c4] directly with the bishop, without losing a tempo. We rarely allow this to happen. After} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 {± we lack the bishop on [d6] to go for the ...[e5] break.}) 6. Bd3 {The principled move, preparing to go for [e4]. This is the most active square for the bishop, but it falls right into our plan. This was fiercely contested in the early 2000s and also in the World Championship matches. With the advent of computers, there are a few good options for us to equalise.} dxc4 {We release the tension immediately after White moves his light-squared bishop.} 7. Bxc4 b5 {We gain space on the queenside and get the [b7] square for the bishop. The pawn on [b5] also helps fight for the centre with the move ...[b4]. Now the bishop has 3 different squares that it can go to.} 8. Bd3 {This is the best square for the bishop, keeping an eye on [e4]. It is also by far the most-played move in the position. White can generally either go for the direct [e4] or he can castle first before going [e4].} (8. Bd3 {Now, the two main lines here are} a6 {and 8...Bb7 . 8...Bd6 is also possible, but it transposes into the main lines of the Anti-Meran variation which we don't enter. We go for another option here, which has not been explored much but is among the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Ne4 {This is an advantage of the bishop on [d3]. We are not getting the move ...[c5] easily here. It is hard to say whom the exchange of knights favours, though.} Nxe4 {We exchange the knight immediately on [e4], not allowing White to take on [f6]. The bishop is often misplaced on [e4] since it blocks White's e-pawn. We will first develop our pieces before eventually kicking the bishop back, followed by the ...[c5] break.} (9... c5 {runs into} 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Ne5 {⩲ .}) 10. Bxe4 Bb7 {The bishops on [e4] and [b7] are at an impasse. White does not retreat with the bishop because then we will go for the ...[c5] break. We need to slowly push the bishop back with ...[Nf6] at the right moment.} 11. Qa4 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6] White is going after our [c6]-pawn. We cannot play the move ...[Rc8], as the [a7]-pawn is also under fire. White also claims that it is harder for us to play the move ...[c5], as there are some issues along the [a4]-[e8] diagonal.} Qb6 {[%csl Gb7,Gc6][%cal Gc6c5] We defend the [c6]-pawn and the bishop on [b7].} 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gc4a5] White immediately tries to exploit the queen on [b6] by getting the knight to [c4]. This is a common idea in these positions. White also creates a square on [f3] for the bishop.} a5 $1 {We stop White's plan of [Nc4]-[a5]. The knight on [c4] alone is not an issue since it blocks the c-file.The move ...[a5] also gives us an extra square on [a6] for the queen if needed.} 13. Nc4 Qc7 14. O-O Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc6c5] Our plan is simple: we want to castle and then slowly prepare ...[c5]. This can happen after getting the rook to [c8] or after ...[Nf6].} 15. Bd2 O-O 16. Rfc1 Nf6 {I like the knight more on [f6], since we can eventually head to the [e4]-square after the exchange of the light-squared bishops.} 17. Bf3 c5 {Our [f8]-rook can go to either [d8] or [c8], so we keep the option open.} 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. dxc5 Ne4 $10 {[%csl Ra4,Ga5,Gb4][%cal Ge4c5] We want to bring our knight to [c5]. I like our pawns on the queenside here. There is still play left in the position.} *

