mong the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Ne4 {This is an advantage of the bishop on [d3]. We are not getting the move ...[c5] easily here. It is hard to say whom the exchange of knights favours, though.} Nxe4 {We exchange the knight immediately on [e4], not allowing White to take on [f6]. The bishop is often misplaced on [e4] since it blocks White's e-pawn. We will first develop our pieces before eventually kicking the bishop back, followed by the ...[c5] break.} (9... c5 {runs into} 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Ne5 {⩲ .}) 10. Bxe4 Bb7 {The bishops on [e4] and [b7] are at an impasse. White does not retreat with the bishop because then we will go for the ...[c5] break. We need to slowly push the bishop back with ...[Nf6] at the right moment.} 11. O-O {Now there is a question of where to develop the dark-squared bishop.} Be7 {This move surprises even me, as I usually always want to put the bishop on the more active [d6]-square. However, White has the annoying plan of [Nd2]-[c4], targeting the bishop on [d6]. Objectively there is not a huge difference though, as the engine says the bishop can just come back to [e7] if it is attacked. However, the immediate ...[Be7] feels more secure, and the plans are more or less the same after both moves.} 12. Bd2 {This is a popular move in online games, but it is pretty tame and allows us to execute our ideas easily.} Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc6c5] We force the bishop away from the annoying diagonal. Once we get our ...[c5] break in, our bishop will be a monster on the light-squares.} 13. Bd3 O-O {We first get the king to safety, as it is extremely hard for White to stop our central break anyhow.} 14. Qe2 c5 15. dxc5 Bxf3 $10 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Rg2f3] We transform our advantage by crippling White's pawn structure on the kingside. White is not able to do much with the bishop pair. We will take on [c5] next and put our queen on [e7].} *

