le opening up at all.} 13. Qc2 h6 {We need to defend the pawn on [h7] before castling kingside. It is useful anyway to clear our back rank.} 14. Bxc6 {This is definitely a move to consider. It can happen with or without the inclusion of the move [a3]. It's pretty popular in online games, as people live to win material.} Rc8 15. Bxd7+ Qxd7 16. Qd1 (16. Qd3 {can be met with} Qc6 $1 {= , preparing to go ...[Qc2] next.}) 16... O-O {[%csl Gb7,Ge7][%cal Gb7f3] There is no rush here. We have the bishop pair and a beautiful bishop on [b7]. White is stuck with a passive dark-squared bishop and we have long-term compensation.} 17. axb4 axb4 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gb7g2]} 18. Ne5 {This is the best plan for White to try to get more control over the centre. Otherwise, we are dominating after putting our queen on [d5].} Qd5 19. f3 Rfd8 {[%cal Gf7f6,Re3e4,Rd5d4] We keep control over the [d4] pawn to stop White from getting in the move [e4]. We will go ...[f6] next, kicking the knight away. The safest for White is to give up the pawn with [e4] and get the bishop out, which leads to an equal endgame.} *

