mong the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Ne4 {This is an advantage of the bishop on [d3]. We are not getting the move ...[c5] easily here. It is hard to say whom the exchange of knights favours, though.} Nxe4 {We exchange the knight immediately on [e4], not allowing White to take on [f6]. The bishop is often misplaced on [e4] since it blocks White's e-pawn. We will first develop our pieces before eventually kicking the bishop back, followed by the ...[c5] break.} (9... c5 {runs into} 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Ne5 {⩲ .}) 10. Bxe4 Bb7 {The bishops on [e4] and [b7] are at an impasse. White does not retreat with the bishop because then we will go for the ...[c5] break. We need to slowly push the bishop back with ...[Nf6] at the right moment.} 11. O-O {Now there is a question of where to develop the dark-squared bishop.} Be7 {This move surprises even me, as I usually always want to put the bishop on the more active [d6]-square. However, White has the annoying plan of [Nd2]-[c4], targeting the bishop on [d6]. Objectively there is not a huge difference though, as the engine says the bishop can just come back to [e7] if it is attacked. However, the immediate ...[Be7] feels more secure, and the plans are more or less the same after both moves.} 12. a3 {White tries to open the queenside for their pieces. Especially an open b-file would be very useful.} a5 {[%csl Gb4] Of course, we keep the pawn on [b4]. It helps restrict White's pieces and gives us space on the queenside. We do not mind the a-file opening up at all.} 13. Qc2 h6 {We need to defend the pawn on [h7] before castling kingside. It is useful anyway to clear our back rank.} 14. b3 {With the bishop on [e4], the best square for the dark-squared bishop is [b2]. White cannot retreat the [e4]-bishop as we are ready to meet it with ...[c5].} O-O 15. axb4 axb4 16. Bb2 Qb8 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf8c8,Gc6c5] We have already seen this plan before. We defend the bishop on [b7], preparing the move ...[c5]. This also allows us to bring our [f8]-rook to the c-file.} 17. Nd2 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 c5 $10 {[%cal Gf8c8,Ge7f6] We finally achieve the ...[c5] break and equalise completely. The pawn on [b4] can be a trump in these endgames. Our rook will come to [c8] next, and we can trade the bishops with ...[Bf6] if needed in the future.} *

