mong the top choices of the computer.}) 8... b4 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a new way of playing. We want to quickly go ...[b4] and follow it up with the move ...[c5]. Why don't we go for 8...[Bb7] as we saw previously? With the bishop on [d3], it is much easier for him to go for the [e4] break.The fact that 8... [b4] has been played much less often is also good news, as it will likely come as a surprise to your opponent. In modern chess, this surprise factor has become a big deal, as everyone has access to computers for preparation.} 9. Ne4 {This is an advantage of the bishop on [d3]. We are not getting the move ...[c5] easily here. It is hard to say whom the exchange of knights favours, though.} Nxe4 {We exchange the knight immediately on [e4], not allowing White to take on [f6]. The bishop is often misplaced on [e4] since it blocks White's e-pawn. We will first develop our pieces before eventually kicking the bishop back, followed by the ...[c5] break.} (9... c5 {runs into} 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Ne5 {⩲ .}) 10. Bxe4 Bb7 {The bishops on [e4] and [b7] are at an impasse. White does not retreat with the bishop because then we will go for the ...[c5] break. We need to slowly push the bishop back with ...[Nf6] at the right moment.} 11. O-O {Now there is a question of where to develop the dark-squared bishop.} Be7 {This move surprises even me, as I usually always want to put the bishop on the more active [d6]-square. However, White has the annoying plan of [Nd2]-[c4], targeting the bishop on [d6]. Objectively there is not a huge difference though, as the engine says the bishop can just come back to [e7] if it is attacked. However, the immediate ...[Be7] feels more secure, and the plans are more or less the same after both moves.} 12. Nd2 {White immediately starts moving the knight to the queenside. In addition to that, this creates a square on [f3] for their bishop to go to. This has been seen in a lot of lines so far, and this should indicate that it is the most flexible option.} O-O 13. b3 Nf6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6d5,Gc6c5] We want to kick the bishop back, but another idea is to put our knight on [d5] and to go for the ...[c5] break. White cannot just give up the bishop on [e4], as we will then also go for the ...[c5] break immediately.} 14. Bf3 {White keeps the bishop alive, stopping the move ...[c5] for now.} (14. Bb2 {allows us to play} Nxe4 15. Nxe4 c5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. dxc5 Qg5 {. White is the one who has to be careful here, as they are forced to create some weaknesses on the kingside.}) 14... Nd5 {As I mentioned, we put our knight in the middle of the board to be able to play ...[c5] next. We can also get our knight to [c3] if allowed.} 15. Ne4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rd1c2] White stops the move [c5]. If given the chance, White will go [Qc2], clamping down on the [c6]-pawn.} f5 $1 {This is a very important move. We have to play dynamically and get our pawn break as soon as we can.} 16. Nc5 {White forces us to give up one of our bishops, but now the [c5]-pawn becomes a weakness too.} (16. Ng3 {moves the knight away from the centre, allowing us to prepare the ...[c5] break more slowly with} Qb6 {.}) 16... Bxc5 17. dxc5 Nc3 {White has to trade the queens or make a concession, moving the queen to a worse square.} 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga8a1] This is always a hard question: Which rook to bring to the open file? Here our task is easier, since we need to be able to meet the move [a3] with ...[a5]. We cannot give White an easy open file to play on.} 19. a3 a5 20. Bb2 Ba6 21. Rfc1 Ne2+ $10 {We trade the bishop by force and reach an equal endgame.} *

