[White "2) Semi-Slav Anti-Meran: 6.Qc2, 7.Bd3"]
[Black "Anti-Meran 6.Qc2: 7.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D46"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2136127623139556"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Be2 {I feel this is a slightly less precise version of main 7.Bd3 lines. This is because the ...[e5] system works much better for Black here. However, it does not make sense for us to learn those lines when the ...[dxc4] lines almost always transpose. We will only analyze some rare independent options here.} O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2c4] White delays winning the pawn back, as they do not want us to gain space on the queenside. White stops the move ...[b5]. The drawback is that this wastes a lot of time, which allows us to break White's centre.} e5 {We break in the centre, looking to activate our minor pieces.} 10. Bxc4 exd4 {White has to decide how to recapture. One way of recapturing is more ambitious, but creates a long-term weakness in the centre. The other one is less active and keeps the dark-squared bishop stuck on [c1].} 11. Nxd4 {White wants to advance the central pawns with [e4] and [f4] in the future. We need to play dynamically and make use of our active pieces.} Ne5 12. Be2 Re8 {We are going to bring all our pieces to the centre. We try to make the move [e4] very hard to achieve.} 13. Rd1 (13. e4 {can be met with} Neg4 14. Nf3 Qe7 {, when the [e4]-pawn is more of a weakness here than a strength.}) 13... Ng6 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gd8c7,Gd8a5] We have a few different square which we can develop our queen to. The usual square is [e7], but we can also go ...[Qc7] to force White to create some weaknesses on the kingside. ...[Qa5] is another option to be considered.} 14. a5 a6 {This is a standard reaction to [a5]. White cannot exploit the [b6]-square easily, while the [a5]-pawn could become a weakness.} 15. h3 Qe7 16. e4 Bc7 $10 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4,Gc8e6,Ga8d8] With the bishop out of the way, we can take on [e4] next. We can also play more slowly with ...[Be6] followed by ...[Rad8].} *

