[PlyCount "36"]
[GameId "2136127623168229"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Be2 {I feel this is a slightly less precise version of main 7.Bd3 lines. This is because the ...[e5] system works much better for Black here. However, it does not make sense for us to learn those lines when the ...[dxc4] lines almost always transpose. We will only analyze some rare independent options here.} O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2c4] White delays winning the pawn back, as they do not want us to gain space on the queenside. White stops the move ...[b5]. The drawback is that this wastes a lot of time, which allows us to break White's centre.} e5 {We break in the centre, looking to activate our minor pieces.} 10. Bxc4 exd4 {White has to decide how to recapture. One way of recapturing is more ambitious, but creates a long-term weakness in the centre. The other one is less active and keeps the dark-squared bishop stuck on [c1].} 11. exd4 {[%csl Rd4,Gd5] White opens the diagonal for the bishop, but allows an IQP Isolated queen's pawn position. The fight goes on for the [d5]-square.} Nb6 12. Bb3 {White keeps the bishop on this diagonal, from where it covers the [d5]-square.} Nbd5 13. Bg5 Qa5 {[%cal Gd5c3,Gc8f5] The queen is perfect on [a5], exploiting the weakness created by the move [a4]. It helps prepare the move ...[Bf5] after a trade on [c3].} 14. Rae1 {White brings the rook to the open file, preparing the move [Ne5].} Nxc3 15. bxc3 (15. Bxf6 {is not a big concern for us with the bishop pair.} gxf6 16. bxc3 Qh5 {↑ and we can start attacking on the kingside.}) 15... Bf5 {This is the ideal diagonal for the bishop, preparing the move ...[Ne4] next.} 16. Qc1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb3c2] White defends the bishop on [g5], planning to meet the knight jump with [Bc2], which is annoying.} Rfe8 {[%cal Gf5e4] We are in no rush as [Bxf6] is not a worry. We can also go ...[Be4] next.} 17. c4 c5 18. d5 Ne4 $10 {[%cal Gg5f4,Ge4d6] White has to trade the dark-squared bishop on [f4] and we will be able to get our knight to the ideal [d6]-square, blocking White's passed pawn.} *

