1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Be2 {I feel this is a slightly less precise version of main 7.Bd3 lines. This is because the ...[e5] system works much better for Black here. However, it does not make sense for us to learn those lines when the ...[dxc4] lines almost always transpose. We will only analyze some rare independent options here.} O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2c4] White delays winning the pawn back, as they do not want us to gain space on the queenside. White stops the move ...[b5]. The drawback is that this wastes a lot of time, which allows us to break White's centre.} e5 {We break in the centre, looking to activate our minor pieces.} 10. Bxc4 exd4 {White has to decide how to recapture. One way of recapturing is more ambitious, but creates a long-term weakness in the centre. The other one is less active and keeps the dark-squared bishop stuck on [c1].} 11. exd4 {[%csl Rd4,Gd5] White opens the diagonal for the bishop, but allows an IQP Isolated queen's pawn position. The fight goes on for the [d5]-square.} Nb6 12. Bb3 {White keeps the bishop on this diagonal, from where it covers the [d5]-square.} Nbd5 13. Bg5 Qa5 {[%cal Gd5c3,Gc8f5] The queen is perfect on [a5], exploiting the weakness created by the move [a4]. It helps prepare the move ...[Bf5] after a trade on [c3].} 14. Nxd5 {White takes on [d5], not allowing the capture on [c3].} Nxd5 15. Rfe1 Be6 {[%cal Gd5b4,Ge6b3] We are ready to play ...[Nb4] and trade the bishops. When playing against an IQP, the exchange of minor pieces is in our favour. White, on the other hand, has to create some play quickly with their minor pieces.} 16. Bd2 Nb4 17. Bxb4 Bxb4 18. Rxe6 {White decides to complicate matters by giving up an exchange to weaken our kingside. Our pieces are already developed, though, and White cannot create a mating attack so quickly.} (18. Re3 {can just be met by} Qf5 {.}) 18... fxe6 19. Bxe6+ Kh8 20. Ne5 g6 {If we get another move to bring our pieces back, we would be winning.} 21. Nxg6+ {White forces a draw.} hxg6 22. Qxg6 Qc7 23. Qh5+ Qh7 {[%cal Gh5e5,Ge5h5,Gh7g7,Gg7h7] There is no way for either side to deviate.} 24. Qe5+ $10 *

