1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. e4 {I don't think this makes much sense with the king still on [e1]. This move has not been seen in GM practice, but it has been played in many games online, and we should take a look.} (8. b3 {runs into} e5 {and we will take a look at this position in the next chapter. The move [b3] is usually combined with [Be2], after which our ...[e5] advance is not so effective.}) 8... dxc4 {This is our standard response in the Semi-Slav. It is very rare that we take on [e4] and give White control over the centre.} 9. Bxc4 e5 {[%csl Rd4,Re4] The issue for White is that both their central pawns are under fire. White is not in time to castle.} 10. Be3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ge1g1] This is best, covering the [d4]-square and preparing to castle the next move. We are going to keep harassing White, though.} (10. O-O {runs into} exd4 11. Nxd4 Nb6 12. Be2 Bxh2+ {and we win a clean extra pawn.}) 10... b5 {[%cal Rc4f7] We are going to go after the [e3]-bishop next, and we need the light-squared bishop away from the diagonal.} 11. Bd3 (11. Bb3 {will run into} a5 {and White is under pressure with the king still on [e1].}) 11... Ng4 {[%csl Re3] As promised, we keep creating threats in the position.} 12. Bg5 f6 {This was the reason why we forced White's light-squared bishop away from the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 13. Bh4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Qb6 {[%csl Rd4]} 15. Nf5 Bf4 $10 {[%csl Re1,Rh2][%cal Gd7e5] We reach a complex position. White still cannot castle as the [h2]-pawn is under fire. Moving either one of the kingside pawns creates weaknesses which we will exploit. We want to get our other knight to [e5] next.} *

