1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. a4 {This is logical to stop the move ...[b5], but it does create a big weakness on [b4].} c5 $1 {We go for the same plan as in the last variation. This is more critical, though, as [a4] is more useful in preventing any ...[b5] ideas.} 11. Rd1 {White maintains the tension in the centre. We have a couple of options here.} Qc7 {We also maintain the tension while eyeing the [c4]-bishop.} 12. dxc5 {This simplifies the position, going for a symmetrical structure.} Bxc5 13. Ne4 Be7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gc7c2] We create a pin on the c-file and are preparing to play ...[Nb6] next.} 14. b3 {White does have a lead in development, and has some pressure if they are able to play [Bb2] next.} b5 $1 {We realise the danger and go for a very forcing solution. This is usually the sign of a very good dynamic player, who knows exactly when to strike: usually right before our opponent manages to consolidate completely.} 15. axb5 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bb7 {Getting the bishop to the long diagonal was the main plan. We might give up the [b5]-pawn, but White's queenside will likely fall anyway.} 17. Qf4 Qxf4 18. exf4 Nb6 $10 {[%csl Rc4,Rf3] We want to win the bishop on [c4] or completely damage White's structure on the kingside. We have enough activity for equality.} *

