1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. a4 {This is logical to stop the move ...[b5], but it does create a big weakness on [b4].} c5 $1 {We go for the same plan as in the last variation. This is more critical, though, as [a4] is more useful in preventing any ...[b5] ideas.} 11. Rd1 {White maintains the tension in the centre. We have a couple of options here.} Qc7 {We also maintain the tension while eyeing the [c4]-bishop.} 12. Ne4 {This is a typical plan in these positions, in order to get the queen over to the kingside. However, we have a very creative solution.} Nxe4 13. Qxe4 b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] We really want to get the bishop to [b7] as quickly as possible. The pawn is a small price to pay for that.} 14. axb5 Bb7 15. Qd3 {The queen looks pretty threatening along the d-file.} (15. Qc2 {would allow us to play} cxd4 {and the pin along the c-file is very useful for us.}) 15... cxd4 {[%cal Gd7e5] We want the [e5]-square for the knight. White cannot do anything on the d-file.} 16. Ng5 {This is a computer move, but we have to find a couple of good moves now.} (16. Qxd4 {is met with} Ne5 $1 {= .}) 16... Bxh2+ 17. Kh1 Nf6 18. bxa6 h6 {[%csl Ge4] We want to kick the knight back to get the [e4]-square for our pieces.} 19. Nh3 Be4 20. Qe2 Bd6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ga8c8] We have very good activity in return for the pawn. We will bring our rook to [c8] next or go ...[Qc6] to force further weaknesses on White's kingside.} *

