o a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. a4 {This is logical to stop the move ...[b5], but it does create a big weakness on [b4].} c5 $1 {We go for the same plan as in the last variation. This is more critical, though, as [a4] is more useful in preventing any ...[b5] ideas.} 11. Rd1 {White maintains the tension in the centre. We have a couple of options here.} Qc7 {We also maintain the tension while eyeing the [c4]-bishop.} 12. Ne4 {This is a typical plan in these positions, in order to get the queen over to the kingside. However, we have a very creative solution.} Nxe4 13. Qxe4 b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] We really want to get the bishop to [b7] as quickly as possible. The pawn is a small price to pay for that.} 14. Bd3 {This keeps the initiative going for White. They can also take on [a8] now, without hanging the bishop on [c4].} f5 $1 {An important move as we fight for the initiative too! Both sides are yet to develop the queenside.} 15. Qxa8 (15. Qxe6+ {gives up the initiative completely after} Kh8 16. axb5 Nb6 {↑ .}) 15... Nb6 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Qxc8 Qxc8 $10 {We have an interesting material imbalance. White will win the [b5]-pawn next and will have a rook, bishop and pawn, which is numerically equal to the queen. The position remains complex and will favour the side creating more attacking chances.} *

