1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. a4 {This is logical to stop the move ...[b5], but it does create a big weakness on [b4].} c5 $1 {We go for the same plan as in the last variation. This is more critical, though, as [a4] is more useful in preventing any ...[b5] ideas.} 11. dxc5 {White takes on [c5], not allowing the capture on [d4]. This is often better because White does not want to block the centre unnecessarily.} Bxc5 {Both the recaptures are fine, but I want to make sure that White does not get the move [b4] on the queenside. We will continue with ...[b6] and ...[Bb7] next.} 12. b3 {White starts to develop the bishop to [b2], keeping the option to move the [a1]-rook to the d-file.} b6 $1 {We saw this in the previous line as well, immediately getting our bishop to the long diagonal. Once we play ...[Bb7], we should be very comfortable.} 13. Ne4 {This is the critical way to exploit our early ...[b6]. Unlike in the previous line, here White does not have the rook on [d1].} Be7 {This is the easiest reply, planning to go ...[Bb7] next. Now, we make use of the move [b3] which has opened up the other long diagonal. We can recapture on [f6] with a tempo.} 14. Bb2 Nxe4 $1 {This looks strange at first sight, as we allow the queen to come to [e4] with a tempo, attacking the rook on [a8]. But we have a clever idea in mind. Take your time figuring out our the next move, as we need to be precise.} 15. Qxe4 Bb7 $1 {A stunning idea, giving up the bishop on [b7]. However, if White takes, their queen will run out of squares. I have never seen such an idea before, but it is a very effective way to complete our development.} 16. Qf4 (16. Qxb7 {runs into} Nc5 17. Qc6 Rc8 {⩱ . White is not losing outright, but is worse with a rook and bishop for the queen.}) 16... Bf6 {We trade the bishops and simplify the position. This makes sense as White has the more active pieces.} 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 {We offer to trade the queens and get into an endgame. I would be very happy if White declines the trade, as our bishop on [b7] is very active.} 18. Qxf6 gxf6 $10 {[%cal Gf8d8] Both recaptures are fine, but this imbalances the position. I like the [c5]-quare for our knight. We will continue with ...[Rfd8] and bring the king to the centre.} *

