1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. a4 {This is logical to stop the move ...[b5], but it does create a big weakness on [b4].} c5 $1 {We go for the same plan as in the last variation. This is more critical, though, as [a4] is more useful in preventing any ...[b5] ideas.} 11. dxc5 {White takes on [c5], not allowing the capture on [d4]. This is often better because White does not want to block the centre unnecessarily.} Bxc5 {Both the recaptures are fine, but I want to make sure that White does not get the move [b4] on the queenside. We will continue with ...[b6] and ...[Bb7] next.} 12. b3 {White starts to develop the bishop to [b2], keeping the option to move the [a1]-rook to the d-file.} b6 $1 {We saw this in the previous line as well, immediately getting our bishop to the long diagonal. Once we play ...[Bb7], we should be very comfortable.} 13. Ne4 {This is the critical way to exploit our early ...[b6]. Unlike in the previous line, here White does not have the rook on [d1].} Be7 {This is the easiest reply, planning to go ...[Bb7] next. Now, we make use of the move [b3] which has opened up the other long diagonal. We can recapture on [f6] with a tempo.} 14. Ng3 {White declines the trade of knights, keeping more pieces on the board. I am not sure if it was worth the time to bring the knight to [g3], though. The advantage of the knight manoeuvre is that the [a1]-[h8] diagonal is open for the dark-squared bishop.} Bb7 {We are ready to play ...[b5] next if given the chance. We are also keeping an eye on the knight on [f3]. We are not going to take it immediately, but it is good to keep this possibility in reserve.} 15. Bb2 Qc7 {We threaten the move ...[b5], utilising the pin along the c-file.} 16. Qe2 Bd5 {We trade the bishop on [c4] and simplify the position. I quite like my bishop on the [a8]-[h1] diagonal, but it was not doing anything useful.} 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Rac1 Qb7 $10 {This is the other advantage of the move 16...Bd5: we get the [b7]-square for the queen. We will get our rook to the c-file next, and I do not see a great plan for White. The bigger question in general is if we can create winning chances. I am optimistic about these endgames as White has some weaknesses on the queenside. Our knight would be well placed on [c5].} *

