o a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. a4 {This is logical to stop the move ...[b5], but it does create a big weakness on [b4].} c5 $1 {We go for the same plan as in the last variation. This is more critical, though, as [a4] is more useful in preventing any ...[b5] ideas.} 11. dxc5 {White takes on [c5], not allowing the capture on [d4]. This is often better because White does not want to block the centre unnecessarily.} Bxc5 {Both the recaptures are fine, but I want to make sure that White does not get the move [b4] on the queenside. We will continue with ...[b6] and ...[Bb7] next.} 12. b3 {White starts to develop the bishop to [b2], keeping the option to move the [a1]-rook to the d-file.} b6 $1 {We saw this in the previous line as well, immediately getting our bishop to the long diagonal. Once we play ...[Bb7], we should be very comfortable.} 13. Ne4 {This is the critical way to exploit our early ...[b6]. Unlike in the previous line, here White does not have the rook on [d1].} Be7 {This is the easiest reply, planning to go ...[Bb7] next. Now, we make use of the move [b3] which has opened up the other long diagonal. We can recapture on [f6] with a tempo.} 14. Rd1 {White brings the rook to the central file, eyeing the [d6]-square.} Bb7 {Our bishop is ideal on [b7], and this also stops [Nd6] since then we can damage White's structure on the kingside by taking on [f3].} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Nd4 {The dark-squared bishop will go to [a3] next. The knight on [d4] cannot be dislodged with ...[e5], as it will then land on [f5]. We need to find a good square for our queen.} Qb8 $1 {We have seen this idea several times already. We want to bring the [f8]-rook into the game next. The d-file was pretty dangerous for our queen with White's rook on [d1].} 17. Ba3 Nc5 {The knight lands on its ideal square. White is unable to take it immediately because of the bishop on [f6].} 18. a5 {White is trying to dislodge our knight from [c5].} Rc8 19. axb6 Be4 {We will win back the pawn on [b6] next with a great position. Our bishops are very active. White has to do something concrete.} 20. Qe2 Qxb6 21. Bxc5 {White gives up the bishop pair to win our queenside pawn. It is a gamble, though, as we can now go after the initiative.} Rxc5 22. Rxa6 Rxa6 23. Bxa6 Rg5 {[%csl Rg2,Rg1] We would like to force some weaknesses on White's kingside. Our rook is not in danger as it will come back to [c5] next. The bishops give us full compensation for the pawn.} *

