1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. e4 {This is the usual plan for White in the Semi-Slav, trying to advance in the centre. We will counter immediately in the centre with a pawn break, and there will be a few pawn exchanges which open up the centre. This can favour either side, as the [e4]-pawn can become a strength or a weakness.} e5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8f5] This is the reason we put our bishop on [d6]. We can fight back in the centre immediately. If we compare this with the main theoretical line, our pawn is on [a6] instead of the bishop on [b7]. I like the bishop on [c8] for now, keeping an eye on the [f5]-square, particularly once we take on [d4].} 11. h3 {This is a typical move in these structures, but it is not the most important move. It allows us to complete our development and start our play in the centre.} b5 {It is time to advance on the queenside, since White has played the less critical move [h3].} 12. Be2 {This is the best square for the bishop. Other squares will come under fire after [c5]-[c4].} (12. Bb3 {allows us to answer} c5 {.}) 12... Re8 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge5d4] We keep an eye on the centre and are ready to take on [d4] soon. White cannot do much other than maintain the tension.} 13. Be3 exd4 {We exchange on [d4], because otherwise White gets the option of [Rad1] followed by [Rxd4]. So now is the perfect time to release the tension.} 14. Nxd4 Qc7 {This is the best square for the queen, keeping an eye on the [c6] and [e5]-squares. We are also keeping an eye on the [f4]-square.} 15. Nf5 Bh2+ $1 {This is a very typical idea, forcing the king to [h1] where it stands worse than on [g1].} 16. Kh1 {[%csl Rh1]} Bf4 {We trade the dark-squared bishops, which should favour us. We are also threatening to play ...[b4] next. The [e4]-pawn is a nice target for us.} 17. Rad1 b4 18. Na4 Nxe4 $10 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd7f6] One of my general rules is to take any central pawn if this can be done without too much danger. We will continue with ...[Ndf6], keeping control over the centre. The knight on [f5] is pretty unstable. White has some concrete ideas, though, and they need to be precise so as not to get a worse position.} *

