o a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. e4 {This is the usual plan for White in the Semi-Slav, trying to advance in the centre. We will counter immediately in the centre with a pawn break, and there will be a few pawn exchanges which open up the centre. This can favour either side, as the [e4]-pawn can become a strength or a weakness.} e5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8f5] This is the reason we put our bishop on [d6]. We can fight back in the centre immediately. If we compare this with the main theoretical line, our pawn is on [a6] instead of the bishop on [b7]. I like the bishop on [c8] for now, keeping an eye on the [f5]-square, particularly once we take on [d4].} 11. Be3 {The bishop keeps an eye on the [d4]-pawn. White is preparing to bring the queenside rook to [d1].} b5 12. Be2 Re8 {As we saw in the previous line, we play our useful moves first, maintaining the tension in the centre. The rook is very well placed on [e8], keeping an eye on the [e4]-pawn.} 13. Rad1 {White has managed to bring the rook to the centre quicker, omitting the move [h3].} Qc7 {[%cal Gf6g4] The other standard move. Now ...[Ng4] is a threat since White has not played the move [h3] yet.} 14. Kh1 {White is avoiding the move [h3], but they do not have a clear plan to utilise the centre. We have quite a few different options here to fight against White's centre.} exd4 {We finally release the tension in the centre. We want to follow up with ...[c5] and ...[Bb7], playing against the [e4]-pawn.} 15. Nxd4 g6 {[%csl Gf5] It is important to first cover the [f5]-square. We can play one more preparatory move like ...[Bf8] and then continue with ...[c5], kicking the knight back. The other immediate threat is ...[b4], winning the [e4]-pawn.} 16. f4 {The most principled move, preparing to play [e5] next. It creates some complications in the centre.} b4 $7 {The knight cannot retreat without losing the [e4]-pawn.} 17. e5 $1 {White wants to win our dark-squared bishop, even at the cost of a pawn. The game becomes very concrete.} bxc3 18. exd6 Qxd6 19. Bc1 Ne4 $10 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gd6c5,Gc8f5] We put our knight on a strong central square and will cover it with ...[Ndf6] next. It is extremely difficult for White to dislodge it. Then we will continue with ...[Qc5] followed by ...[Bf5]. In return, White has the bishop pair and can try to create play on the kingside with [f5]. The position is dynamically balanced.} *

