o a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. e4 {This is the usual plan for White in the Semi-Slav, trying to advance in the centre. We will counter immediately in the centre with a pawn break, and there will be a few pawn exchanges which open up the centre. This can favour either side, as the [e4]-pawn can become a strength or a weakness.} e5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8f5] This is the reason we put our bishop on [d6]. We can fight back in the centre immediately. If we compare this with the main theoretical line, our pawn is on [a6] instead of the bishop on [b7]. I like the bishop on [c8] for now, keeping an eye on the [f5]-square, particularly once we take on [d4].} 11. Rd1 {White does not waste time bringing the [a1]-rook to [d1], which is what we saw in previous lines. In such concrete positions, the value of a tempo is very high. This move also creates a square on [f1] for the light-squared bishop.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc7h2] We must play this move first, as White was threatening to take on [e5]. Now our threat is to take on [d4], as the [h2]-pawn is under fire. Taking with the rook on [d4] is not ideal for White here.} 12. g3 {White defends the [h2]-pawn but does create some weaknesses on the kingside, especially on the light squares. The benefit is that White can get the bishop to [g2], but this plan is not that threatening.} b5 {There is no real benefit in delaying ...[b5] any longer. If we move our [f8]-rook, White currently has some annoying ideas with [Ng5].} 13. Bf1 (13. Be2 {will transpose to a later variation.}) 13... Re8 {[%cal Ge8e4] The typical move, creating pressure along the e-file.} 14. Bg2 {White has gotten the bishop to a secure square and they can look to play [f4] and [e5] in the future.} c5 $1 {Because the bishop is on [g2] we don't take on [d4] immediately, as it would free up White's pieces. Now, White has to release the tension on our terms.} 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 $10 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Ge5c3] We have the centre under control. We will continue with ...[Bb7], putting more pressure on [e4]. White's [f4] advance is rarely a good idea, as it weakens the king. White is likely to play [Nd5] soon, and after an exchange the pawn on [d5] is more likely to be a weakness than a strength.} *

