1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. e4 {This is the usual plan for White in the Semi-Slav, trying to advance in the centre. We will counter immediately in the centre with a pawn break, and there will be a few pawn exchanges which open up the centre. This can favour either side, as the [e4]-pawn can become a strength or a weakness.} e5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8f5] This is the reason we put our bishop on [d6]. We can fight back in the centre immediately. If we compare this with the main theoretical line, our pawn is on [a6] instead of the bishop on [b7]. I like the bishop on [c8] for now, keeping an eye on the [f5]-square, particularly once we take on [d4].} 11. Rd1 {White does not waste time bringing the [a1]-rook to [d1], which is what we saw in previous lines. In such concrete positions, the value of a tempo is very high. This move also creates a square on [f1] for the light-squared bishop.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc7h2] We must play this move first, as White was threatening to take on [e5]. Now our threat is to take on [d4], as the [h2]-pawn is under fire. Taking with the rook on [d4] is not ideal for White here.} 12. h3 {This is the most natural move, not creating any weaknesses and covering the [g4]-square.} b5 {White could have gone for the move [a4] next and there was no real benefit of delaying ...[b5] any longer.} 13. Bf1 {This always feels good, tucking the bishop away, but it would be more active on [b3]. On [f1] the bishop does not help White in the fight for the centre.} Re8 {This is another drawback of the move [Bf1]. We cannot play this move if the bishop is on [b3] due to the powerful [Ng5]. Here, this is very useful in putting pressure on [e4]. Currently we are threatening ...[exd4] followed by ...[b4].} 14. Be3 exd4 15. Nxd4 g6 $1 {[%csl Gf5] We have seen similar ideas before. We stop the knight from jumping to [f5] and prepare to play ...[c5] and ...[Bb7] on the queenside.} 16. Rac1 Bb7 17. Qd2 Rad8 {[%cal Gc6c5] All our pieces are positioned well, and we are ready to play ...[c5] next. White has to try something quick and dynamic to not get outplayed.} 18. Nxc6 $1 Bh2+ 19. Kh1 Bxc6 20. Nd5 {Our queen is overloaded and cannot defend both [c6] and [h2].} Qb7 {We give up the bishop on [h2], but we are ready to take on [e4] next.} 21. Nxf6+ Nxf6 22. Qxd8 {White is forced to give up the queen, but they will get excellent compensation if they manage to win the bishop on [h2] for free.} Rxd8 23. Rxd8+ Ne8 24. Kxh2 {White gives up the rook on [d8] but gets 2 pieces in return. This results in a very interesting imbalance.} Qc7+ 25. Kg1 Qxd8 26. Rxc6 Qa8 $10 {[%cal Ge8g7,Gg7e6,Gh7h5] We will bring the knight to [e6] next. We can play ...[h5] on the kingside, and although our dark squares look weak, White cannot exploit them immediately.} *

