o a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. e4 {This is the usual plan for White in the Semi-Slav, trying to advance in the centre. We will counter immediately in the centre with a pawn break, and there will be a few pawn exchanges which open up the centre. This can favour either side, as the [e4]-pawn can become a strength or a weakness.} e5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8f5] This is the reason we put our bishop on [d6]. We can fight back in the centre immediately. If we compare this with the main theoretical line, our pawn is on [a6] instead of the bishop on [b7]. I like the bishop on [c8] for now, keeping an eye on the [f5]-square, particularly once we take on [d4].} 11. Rd1 {White does not waste time bringing the [a1]-rook to [d1], which is what we saw in previous lines. In such concrete positions, the value of a tempo is very high. This move also creates a square on [f1] for the light-squared bishop.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc7h2] We must play this move first, as White was threatening to take on [e5]. Now our threat is to take on [d4], as the [h2]-pawn is under fire. Taking with the rook on [d4] is not ideal for White here.} 12. h3 {This is the most natural move, not creating any weaknesses and covering the [g4]-square.} b5 {White could have gone for the move [a4] next and there was no real benefit of delaying ...[b5] any longer.} 13. Bb3 {The bishop is more active on [b3], keeping an eye on the [f7]-square.} Bb7 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc6c5] We are ready to take on [d4] and then play ...[c5]. This is dangerous because we threaten ...[c4] to trap the [b3]-bishop. Also, if White attacks our [d6]-bishop, we can always give a check on [h2] with a tempo.} (13... Re8 $2 {fails to} 14. Ng5 $1 Re7 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Ne2 {+- when we are in huge trouble with [f4] and [e5] coming next. White can take on [f7] at any moment.}) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd4 {This is clever because now with the knight on [e5], we cannot go for the move ...[c5]. The [d6]-bishop is a problem.} Bc5 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gc6c5,Gc5c4] A very simple solution: we want to take on [d4] first before playing [c5]-[c4].} 16. Nf5 {White gets the knight out of the way.} Bc8 $1 {[%csl Rf5] A nice move, immediately attacking the knight on [f5]. The knight does not have a good square to retreat to.} 17. Ng3 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gc8a6] We want to trap the bishop on [b3]. It is also useful to get the [a6]-square for our light-squared bishop in the future.} 18. a4 Neg4 $1 {The knight on [g3] is a big tactical motif along the diagonal. All of our pieces are looking towards the kingside while White has been very careless.} 19. hxg4 Nxg4 $19 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc7g3] The knight on [g3] is hanging and so does the pawn on [f2]. We've included the moves ...[a5] and [a4] so that we can take on [a4] and continue with ...[Ba6] quickly.} *

