1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. e4 {This is the usual plan for White in the Semi-Slav, trying to advance in the centre. We will counter immediately in the centre with a pawn break, and there will be a few pawn exchanges which open up the centre. This can favour either side, as the [e4]-pawn can become a strength or a weakness.} e5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8f5] This is the reason we put our bishop on [d6]. We can fight back in the centre immediately. If we compare this with the main theoretical line, our pawn is on [a6] instead of the bishop on [b7]. I like the bishop on [c8] for now, keeping an eye on the [f5]-square, particularly once we take on [d4].} 11. Rd1 {White does not waste time bringing the [a1]-rook to [d1], which is what we saw in previous lines. In such concrete positions, the value of a tempo is very high. This move also creates a square on [f1] for the light-squared bishop.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc7h2] We must play this move first, as White was threatening to take on [e5]. Now our threat is to take on [d4], as the [h2]-pawn is under fire. Taking with the rook on [d4] is not ideal for White here.} 12. h3 {This is the most natural move, not creating any weaknesses and covering the [g4]-square.} b5 {White could have gone for the move [a4] next and there was no real benefit of delaying ...[b5] any longer.} 13. Bb3 {The bishop is more active on [b3], keeping an eye on the [f7]-square.} Bb7 {[%cal Ge5d4,Gc6c5] We are ready to take on [d4] and then play ...[c5]. This is dangerous because we threaten ...[c4] to trap the [b3]-bishop. Also, if White attacks our [d6]-bishop, we can always give a check on [h2] with a tempo.} (13... Re8 $2 {fails to} 14. Ng5 $1 Re7 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Ne2 {+- when we are in huge trouble with [f4] and [e5] coming next. White can take on [f7] at any moment.}) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd4 {This is clever because now with the knight on [e5], we cannot go for the move ...[c5]. The [d6]-bishop is a problem.} Bc5 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gc6c5,Gc5c4] A very simple solution: we want to take on [d4] first before playing [c5]-[c4].} 16. Be3 {This is a natural move, but it allows us to simplify the position a lot.} Bxd4 17. Bxd4 c5 {White cannot afford to allow us to play the move ...[c4] next. We would love to see an exchange on [e5], as the dark-squared bishop is White's best minor piece.} 18. Nd5 $5 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Rac8 20. Bc3 {White has managed to keep the bishop alive, but simultaneously we have managed to get exactly what we want on the queenside.} Rfe8 $10 {[%cal Gc5c4,Ge5d3] We have several different plans here. We can go ...[c4] next to get the knight to [d3]. Taking on [d5] is always an option, but there is no rush.} *

