1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. Rd1 {This is the most common move in the position, stopping our immediate pawn breaks in the centre. Now, White wants to play [e4] next. However, if you compare this position to the main lines after 9...[b5], you will see that White usually does not put the rook on [d1] so early. They usually focus on more energetic ideas, such as a quick [e4] or [Ng5]. [d1] may not necessarily be the best square for the rook, but White had no other flexible move here as we were planning to expand with ...[b5] and ...[c5] quickly.} b5 {Finally, we decide to kick the bishop away from [c4]. White has to make a decision now, and we play differently depending on where the bishop goes.} ({I also like the approach} 10... Qc7 {, delaying the move ...[b5], but I don't see a huge upside. Moreover, it gives White an extra independent option in} 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 {when after} e5 $1 {Black should be okay, but it would be an extra option we'd have to prepare for.}) 11. Be2 {Compared to the previous variation, White keeps the [d1] rook protected. They are ready to play [e4].} Qc7 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Rd1d8,Gc8f5] We get the queen out of the way. Compared to the 9...b5 variation, we would typically have the bishop on [b7] instead of the pawn on [a6]. I think this difference is in our favour, as we can achieve the ...[c5] break quicker. Moreover, in the lines with [e4] and ...[e5] I like having the bishop on [c8], covering the [f5]-square. Overall, ...[a6] is a more important move than ...[Bb7].} 12. e4 {This is similar to lines we have seen already.} e5 {White has to deal with our threat of taking on [d4]. The [h2]-pawn is an issue.} 13. g3 {Not a pretty move, but White had to defend [h2]. As is usual in these positions, it becomes hard for White to make any progress.} Re8 14. a3 h6 {We could have released the tension, but let us torture White a bit more. 14...h6 is anyway a useful move, covering [g5] and removing any back rank issues.} (14... exd4 {(is what I played in my game, which you can check in the model games section. 0-1 43 Karthik,V 2480-Arjun,K 2477 Pune IND 2022)}) 15. b4 {White wants to stop the move ...[c5] at all costs.} exd4 ({This is less popular compared to} 15... Bb7 {, but I like to keep our bishop on the [c8]-[h3] diagonal. It can go to [h3] directly, making use of the weaknesses created by the move [g3].}) 16. Nxd4 Nb6 $36 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8h3,Ga8d8,Gc6c5] The bishop on [c8] keeps the [f5]-square under control. We can put the bishop on [h3] next, followed by bringing the rook to [d8]. The only plan I can see for White is [f4], but this weakens the kingside and we can break with ...[c5] afterwards.} *

