o a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. Rd1 {This is the most common move in the position, stopping our immediate pawn breaks in the centre. Now, White wants to play [e4] next. However, if you compare this position to the main lines after 9...[b5], you will see that White usually does not put the rook on [d1] so early. They usually focus on more energetic ideas, such as a quick [e4] or [Ng5]. [d1] may not necessarily be the best square for the rook, but White had no other flexible move here as we were planning to expand with ...[b5] and ...[c5] quickly.} b5 {Finally, we decide to kick the bishop away from [c4]. White has to make a decision now, and we play differently depending on where the bishop goes.} ({I also like the approach} 10... Qc7 {, delaying the move ...[b5], but I don't see a huge upside. Moreover, it gives White an extra independent option in} 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 {when after} e5 $1 {Black should be okay, but it would be an extra option we'd have to prepare for.}) 11. Be2 {Compared to the previous variation, White keeps the [d1] rook protected. They are ready to play [e4].} Qc7 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Rd1d8,Gc8f5] We get the queen out of the way. Compared to the 9...b5 variation, we would typically have the bishop on [b7] instead of the pawn on [a6]. I think this difference is in our favour, as we can achieve the ...[c5] break quicker. Moreover, in the lines with [e4] and ...[e5] I like having the bishop on [c8], covering the [f5]-square. Overall, ...[a6] is a more important move than ...[Bb7].} 12. Ne4 {White trades the knights in the centre in an attempt to bring the queen over to the kingside. This is not cohesive with the move 10.Rd1 and White cannot create much of an attack with the dark-squared bishop still on [c1].} Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] We have completed our development and are ready to carry out the ...[c5] break next. White has to do something quick in order to not be worse.} 14. Bd3 {White forces some weaknesses on our kingside.} g6 15. Qh4 c5 {[%csl Rf3]} 16. Ng5 {This is the principled move, forcing us to weaken our kingside again. At the same time, White commits to an all out attack on the kingside, abandoning the centre.} h5 17. Ne4 {White changes their mind, but this is a bit too late now and we can take over the position.} Bxe4 {We give up the bishop pair, but our piece activity more than compensates for it.} 18. Bxe4 Rac8 19. Bd2 c4 {[%cal Gb5b4] An ambitious move, gaining space on the queenside. We will continue with ...[b4] next.} 20. f4 b4 21. Rdc1 Nb6 $15 {[%cal Gb6d5] The knight is coming to [d5]. White has no clear plan in the position and is just slightly worse.} *

