ow, though.} c5 {[%cal Gc5c4] We get the desired pawn break in pretty easily. We would like to play ...[c4] if given the chance.} 13. Ne4 {[%csl Rd6] This is the most popular move, going after the bishop on [d6]. We are slightly behind in development and have to be precise now.} c4 {This is the most ambitious move, gaining space on the queenside, but it is also a necessary move in order not to be worse. The challenge for us is to make sure White is not able to play the move [e4] easily.} 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Be2 Bb7 {[%csl Ge4] We maintain a firm grip on the [e4]-square. Also, we finally finish our development.} 16. b3 Bd5 17. Qb2 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gb3c4,Gd2b4] White prepares to move the knight to [e5] next. They are also planning to take on [c4] and continue with [Bb4] at the right moment.} Ne4 {[%csl Rd2] We would love to win the dark-squared bishop.} 18. Be1 {The bishop may look safe here, but this takes away the [e1]-square from White's knight. White has to try and play [f3] and [e4] to create play in the centre.} Rfc8 19. Rdc1 f6 $10 {I like this move, covering the [e5]-square. Next, we can double rooks on the c-file. I like our chances with the pawn on [c4].} *

