1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 ({This is White's antidote to the Meran variation} 6. Bd3 dxc4 {, which we checked in the last chapter. With 6.Qc2 White keeps the bishop on [f1] for now, hoping that we will take on [c4], allowing them to get the bishop to [c4] in one go. Of course, we won't play into White's hands, but this means that we have to commit our dark-squared bishop immediately, and also that quick [b5]-[b4] ideas are not possible. The move 6.Qc2 has now taken over as the main line and has been analysed deeply.}) 6... Bd6 {We develop our bishop first, waiting for White to do the same with the [f1]-bishop. With the bishop on [d6], we always have the idea of going for the ...[e5] break. Also, in the lines after we take on [c4], we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5].} ({There is also the option of} 6... b6 {, which is a slower way of playing, recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, 6...b6 goes against all the principles of the Semi-Slav. We do not want to play a slightly passive position trying to equalise. We want to fight back against White's centre aggressively.}) 7. Bd3 {This is the main move in the position, getting the bishop to its natural square. White is okay with losing a tempo with [Bd3xc4], but they want to retain control over the centre.} O-O ({There is not much difference between this and the capture} 7... dxc4 {first. The move 7...O-O feels more flexible to me, keeping more options open.}) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 $5 ({This is our surprise idea. The main move is to go} 9... b5 {followed by ...[Bb7], but we play more slowly with 9...a6 first. What is the point? As I mention throughout the course, I love having flexibility in our move order. We keep a few plans open: the usual ...[b5] plan, the ...[c5] break and the ...[e5] break. We avoid the lines with [Ng5] and [Ne4] which are a big headache with the inclusion of the move ...[b5].}) (9... b5 {is the main line by far. White has two options, both of which lead to a lot of theory:} 10. Bd3 a6 {is similar to how we play in our main line, but here the inclusion of the move ...[b5] makes a big difference. White can play} 11. Ne4 $1 {± This would not be great if White had to recapture on [e4] with the queen. Here, it is very hard for us to preserve the dark-squared bishop and keep the [c6]-pawn alive at the same time. Instead of 10.Bd3, 10.Be2 is also a serious move. After 10...a6 , 11.Ng5 ⩲ is another plan which works well for White with the inclusion of the move ...[b5]. The knight coming to [e4] is the big issue.}) 10. Rd1 {This is the most common move in the position, stopping our immediate pawn breaks in the centre. Now, White wants to play [e4] next. However, if you compare this position to the main lines after 9...[b5], you will see that White usually does not put the rook on [d1] so early. They usually focus on more energetic ideas, such as a quick [e4] or [Ng5]. [d1] may not necessarily be the best square for the rook, but White had no other flexible move here as we were planning to expand with ...[b5] and ...[c5] quickly.} b5 {Finally, we decide to kick the bishop away from [c4]. White has to make a decision now, and we play differently depending on where the bishop goes.} ({I also like the approach} 10... Qc7 {, delaying the move ...[b5], but I don't see a huge upside. Moreover, it gives White an extra independent option in} 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 {when after} e5 $1 {Black should be okay, but it would be an extra option we'd have to prepare for.}) 11. Bd3 {White wants to continue with [Ne4], targeting both [c6] and [h7]. The bishop does block the d-file, though, making it easier for us to carry out the ...[c5] break.} Qc7 {We go for the usual move, getting the queen away from the d-file. We also defend the pawn on [c6].} (11... Bb7 {is another option here, but I do not like allowing White to play} 12. Ng5 {∞ .}) 12. Bd2 {White wants to develop the [a1]-rook to [c1] next and try to stop the move ...[c5]. This is too slow, though.} c5 {[%cal Gc5c4] We get the desired pawn break in pretty easily. We would like to play ...[c4] if given the chance.} 13. Ne4 {[%csl Rd6] This is the most popular move, going after the bishop on [d6]. We are slightly behind in development and have to be precise now.} c4 {This is the most ambitious move, gaining space on the queenside, but it is also a necessary move in order not to be worse. The challenge for us is to make sure White is not able to play the move [e4] easily.} 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Be2 Bb7 {[%csl Ge4] We maintain a firm grip on the [e4]-square. Also, we finally finish our development.} 16. b3 Bd5 17. Qb2 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gb3c4,Gd2b4] White prepares to move the knight to [e5] next. They are also planning to take on [c4] and continue with [Bb4] at the right moment.} Ne4 {[%csl Rd2] We would love to win the dark-squared bishop.} 18. Ba5 ({This is the most common move, and I think it is better than} 18. Be1 {because now White keeps the option of playing [Ne1] followed by [f3].}) 18... f5 $1 {[%csl Ge4] We anticipate an eventual [f3] from White. While the [e5]-square is a slight concern for us, [Ne5] is no longer so dangerous as we can just exchange the knight, leaving White with a weak pawn on [e5]. Playing [Ne5] makes much more sense when our f-pawn is back on [f7] and the [e4]-pawn would have been a weakness.} 19. Rdc1 Rfc8 20. Rc2 Rc6 $10 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gg7g5] We have seen this plan already. We will look to double rooks on the c-file. At some point, we can start playing on the kingside too. White will not be able to play [f3] and [e4].} *

