1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd2 {White is preparing to castle queenside.} O-O 8. O-O-O {This is extremely risky with the pawn on [c4]. We can open up the centre and the queenside much easier than White can create play on the kingside.} e5 {We quickly break in the centre. Usually, we would be worried about getting an IQP on [d5], but here that means that the c-file is opened up.} 9. cxd5 cxd5 {[%cal Gc8c1]} 10. Nb5 {White wants to get the knight to [d4].} Bb8 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 {The position has been clarified a bit. Our king is much safer than White's, but a potential endgame would be amazing for White. We are going to try to do something quick on the queenside or in the centre.} 13. Kb1 Be6 $36 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf6e4] ...[Rc8] is coming up next followed by moving the knight to [e4]. White has to be very careful.} *

