1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. e4 {This is a premature break in the centre, as our king reaches safety much faster than White's and we are in time to fight back in the centre.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 e5 $1 {[%cal Re8e1,Ge8g8] Of course, we do not miss the chance to open the centre. White has broken general opening principles by bringing the queen out so early.} 10. c5 {This was tried by Karpov once, though in 2008, way after his prime.} Bc7 {We are ready to play ...[Nf6] next, kicking the queen back. This is why we keep control over the [e5]-square with the bishop.} 11. dxe5 Nxc5 12. Qc2 Qe7 {[%csl Re5]} 13. Be2 {White is willing to give up the [e5]-pawn in return for our dark-squared bishop and some tempi.} Ba5+ {We force the trade of the dark-squares bishops. The bishop on [c1] was potentially more active compared to our bishop, ready to jump to [g5] next.} 14. Bd2 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Bg4 $36 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge8g8] We will castle and then go after the [e5]-pawn. I like the knight vs bishop positions here, especially with the queens on the board.} *

