1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. e4 {This is a premature break in the centre, as our king reaches safety much faster than White's and we are in time to fight back in the centre.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 e5 $1 {[%cal Re8e1,Ge8g8] Of course, we do not miss the chance to open the centre. White has broken general opening principles by bringing the queen out so early.} 10. dxe5 O-O {Now we are ready to take on [e5] or play ...[Re8] first.} (10... Nxe5 {I thought I was clever and blundered. My opponent's response} 11. c5 $1 {⩲ stops us from giving a check on [a5] to win back the piece on [e5]. Black is in trouble here.}) 11. exd6 {This is the main move, giving up the queen. White gets decent compensation in return, but not more than equality.} Re8 12. Qxe8+ Qxe8+ 13. Be3 Ne5 {We exchange the knights, as the queen becomes stronger when more pieces are traded off. White has to create some initiative with their pieces.} 14. O-O-O Bd7 $36 {[%csl Rc1,Rd6] The pawn on [d6] is securely blockaded and our king is safer. We can slowly try to round up the [d6]-pawn.} *

