1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. g4 $5 {This is the famous Shirov variation. White decides to go caveman style, giving up the g-pawn for the initiative. It is tried occasionally as a surprise weapon and has to be taken seriously.} Nxg4 ({Why not just take the pawn? I used to automatically go for the move} 7... h6 {, but there is no need to give so much respect for our opponent. Quite a few White moves are forced which makes our task of remembering the lines easier. 7...h6 is the usual move, and is recommended by almost everyone who creates a course for Black. It is a perfectly fine alternative.}) 8. Rg1 {White would love to win the pawn on [g7] if the knight retreats. This is a great trade for White, as they can castle queenside much faster than we can.} Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3] This is the key point behind our previous move. Of course, we did not take on [g4] just to retreat. Now the knight on [f3] has no good square as [f2] is a big headache.} 9. Rxg4 Qxf3 (9... Qxf3 {Now White has two options to choose from,} 10. Rxg7 {and 10.h3 , but the second one has been played only twice.}) 10. h3 {Even though this has been seen only twice, both of them were critical classical games. White wants to play [e4] next, and the queen on [f3] might be in trouble.} Qf6 {This is the most obvious move, bringing the queen back and targeting the [d4]-pawn in order to discourage the move [e4].} 11. e4 {This has to be played anyway.} Qxd4 {We follow our general rule: take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger.} (11... h5 {(was played in the game ½-½ Abdusattorov,N 2731-Gukesh,D 2732 Stavanger NOR 2023, but it gave White something to play for.)}) 12. Be3 Qf6 13. Bg5 Qd4 $10 {[%cal Gg5e3,Ge3g5] White is forced to go back with [Be3] and repeat moves. This is perfectly fine if you are okay with a draw. However, I will give you a more fighting alternative as the main line if you need to keep your winning chances alive.} *

