1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. g4 $5 {This is the famous Shirov variation. White decides to go caveman style, giving up the g-pawn for the initiative. It is tried occasionally as a surprise weapon and has to be taken seriously.} Nxg4 ({Why not just take the pawn? I used to automatically go for the move} 7... h6 {, but there is no need to give so much respect for our opponent. Quite a few White moves are forced which makes our task of remembering the lines easier. 7...h6 is the usual move, and is recommended by almost everyone who creates a course for Black. It is a perfectly fine alternative.}) 8. Rg1 {White would love to win the pawn on [g7] if the knight retreats. This is a great trade for White, as they can castle queenside much faster than we can.} Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3] This is the key point behind our previous move. Of course, we did not take on [g4] just to retreat. Now the knight on [f3] has no good square as [f2] is a big headache.} 9. Rxg4 Qxf3 (9... Qxf3 {Now White has two options to choose from,} 10. Rxg7 {and 10.h3 , but the second one has been played only twice.}) 10. h3 {Even though this has been seen only twice, both of them were critical classical games. White wants to play [e4] next, and the queen on [f3] might be in trouble.} h6 {[%csl Gg5] This is a strange move at first sight. The [g7]-pawn is hanging, but we play a seemingly useless move. However, covering the [g5]-square is a huge plus for us.} 11. e4 {This is the only good independent option here which doesn't transpose to our main line.} (11. Rxg7 Nf6 {will transpose to our main line. 11.Bd2 Nf6 12.Rxg7 also transposes.}) 11... e5 $1 {[%cal Gc8g4] These kinds of pawn breaks are very typical in the Semi-Slav. We want to free up the position for our pieces and open the centre.} 12. c5 {This is the best move, hoping that we will retreat after which White can win the [d5]-pawn and create pressure on the long diagonal.} exd4 {Of course, we don't retreat. We go for the critical line, opening the central files.} 13. cxd6 dxc3 14. exd5 O-O {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8e8] Our king is safe, but the same cannot be said yet about our opponent's monarch. We are ready to give a check on [e8].} 15. Bg2 Qf6 16. dxc6 Re8+ 17. Kf1 {The king gets to the kingside finally.} bxc6 $10 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd7e5] We will play ...[Ne5] next and win the pawn on [d6]. The position is dynamically balanced.} *

