1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. g4 $5 {This is the famous Shirov variation. White decides to go caveman style, giving up the g-pawn for the initiative. It is tried occasionally as a surprise weapon and has to be taken seriously.} Nxg4 ({Why not just take the pawn? I used to automatically go for the move} 7... h6 {, but there is no need to give so much respect for our opponent. Quite a few White moves are forced which makes our task of remembering the lines easier. 7...h6 is the usual move, and is recommended by almost everyone who creates a course for Black. It is a perfectly fine alternative.}) 8. Rg1 {White would love to win the pawn on [g7] if the knight retreats. This is a great trade for White, as they can castle queenside much faster than we can.} Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3] This is the key point behind our previous move. Of course, we did not take on [g4] just to retreat. Now the knight on [f3] has no good square as [f2] is a big headache.} 9. Rxg4 Qxf3 (9... Qxf3 {Now White has two options to choose from,} 10. Rxg7 {and 10.h3 , but the second one has been played only twice.}) 10. Rxg7 Nf6 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf6g4] The knight is heading to [g4]. The rook on [g7] might get trapped if White is not careful.} 11. Rg5 {This is a clever move, as White has a huge threat of [Bg2] trapping our queen on [f3]. White has taken the [h5]-square away from the queen.} Qh1 $1 {We keep the pressure on White by pinning the bishop on [f1]. Moreover, we are also attacking the [h2]-pawn.} 12. f4 {White defends the pawn on [h2] with the queen, but this will not last for long as they need to complete the development of their queenside.} Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc8d7,Ge8c8] We are threatening to play ...[Ne4] next, or we can just castle queenside depending on White's next move.} 13. Rg2 Bd7 14. Bd2 O-O-O 15. O-O-O ({The engines like the move} 15. Ne2 {more, but we can just take} Bxd2+ 16. Qxd2 {and plant our knight with} Ne4 {.}) 15... Rhg8 $15 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gh1f3] We exchange the rooks and the queen can finally either win the pawn on [h2] or come back home via [e4] or [f3].} *

