1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. g4 $5 {This is the famous Shirov variation. White decides to go caveman style, giving up the g-pawn for the initiative. It is tried occasionally as a surprise weapon and has to be taken seriously.} Nxg4 ({Why not just take the pawn? I used to automatically go for the move} 7... h6 {, but there is no need to give so much respect for our opponent. Quite a few White moves are forced which makes our task of remembering the lines easier. 7...h6 is the usual move, and is recommended by almost everyone who creates a course for Black. It is a perfectly fine alternative.}) 8. Rg1 {White would love to win the pawn on [g7] if the knight retreats. This is a great trade for White, as they can castle queenside much faster than we can.} Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3] This is the key point behind our previous move. Of course, we did not take on [g4] just to retreat. Now the knight on [f3] has no good square as [f2] is a big headache.} 9. Rxg4 Qxf3 (9... Qxf3 {Now White has two options to choose from,} 10. Rxg7 {and 10.h3 , but the second one has been played only twice.}) 10. Rxg7 Nf6 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf6g4] The knight is heading to [g4]. The rook on [g7] might get trapped if White is not careful.} 11. h3 {We have seen this idea before, preventing our move ...[Ng4].} h6 {We do the same as our opponent, covering the [g5]-square.} 12. Bd2 Bd7 {We can castle queenside next, while it is not as easy for White with our queen on [f3].} 13. Be2 {White tries to kick the queen away, but we can always repeat moves with ...[Qh1]+ if needed.} Qxh3 {This keeps the game going.} 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Rxf7 Rdf8 $10 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gf7g7,Gf6e8] We would love to trade the rooks. If the rook moves to [g7], we can kick it back with our knight. We have a passed h-pawn which can become dangerous in the endgame.} *

