[Black "Anti-Meran 6.Qc2: 7.b3 with 8.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D46"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2136127623852306"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Bd3 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Ge5e4] As I've mentioned, this central break works very well here, as the bishop on [d3] comes under fire in many of the lines. For starters ...[e4] is a threat already. If White takes on [e5], we retake with the knight, attacking the bishop on [d3].} 9. dxe5 {White maintains the tension with the c-pawn, which at least keeps the c-file closed.} Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Bb2 Re8 {[%cal Gd5d4] We are ready to play ...[d4] next.} 12. O-O {This is a serious mistake, and it is a nice chance for us to practise our tactical abilities. Please calculate accurately and don't just stop after one move. White should have taken on [d5], but we equalise very comfortably there.} d4 $1 {It is important to first close off the diagonal. I am sure a lot of you were too tempted to take on [h2] immediately.} 13. exd4 Bxh2+ $1 {Now we go for the famous Greek Gift sacrifice on [h2]. We will see what difference the inclusion of our previous 12...d4 makes.} 14. Kxh2 Ng4+ 15. Kg3 {This would be a much better version for White if they still had a pawn on [e3]. They would be able to run with [Kf3]-[e2].} Qd6+ 16. f4 Re3+ 17. Rf3 g5 $3 {[%cal Gd6f4,Gd6h6] A very important move which decides the game. In addition to threatening to take on [f4], we also have the super strong threat of ...[Qh6].} *

