1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Bd3 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Ge5e4] As I've mentioned, this central break works very well here, as the bishop on [d3] comes under fire in many of the lines. For starters ...[e4] is a threat already. If White takes on [e5], we retake with the knight, attacking the bishop on [d3].} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 {White cannot afford to give up the bishop on [d3] and is forced to exchange on [e5], which further activates our pieces.} 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bb2 d4 $1 {It is time to break in the centre with the white king still on [e1].} 13. exd4 Bxd4 14. O-O-O {This is the aggressive option, but I think it is more dangerous for White.} Qa5 15. Bxh7+ {White can win a pawn, but now their light squares become terribly weak.} Nxh7 16. Rxd4 Bf5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gh7f6,Ga8c8] We will bring our knight back with ...[Nf6]. White's king is stuck on the open c-file. White has to do damage control here.} *

