1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Bd3 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Ge5e4] As I've mentioned, this central break works very well here, as the bishop on [d3] comes under fire in many of the lines. For starters ...[e4] is a threat already. If White takes on [e5], we retake with the knight, attacking the bishop on [d3].} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 {This works very well with the bishop on [e2], but here ...[e4] is always in the air.} Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 e4 $1 {This is the more fighting option, gaining space in the centre. We will try to create play on the kingside next. On the other hand, we should be careful as we are fixing the pawns on the light squares and the endgame can be pretty dangerous for us.} 13. Be2 Ne8 $5 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8g5]} ({This is the less common move; the main line continues with} 13... a6 {. However, I don't think it is really necessary to kick the knight back. If we stop the knight from coming to [c7], it is not doing much on [b5]. Also, White can jump in with [Nc7] after the move ...[a6], which we need not allow.}) 14. Rc1 {This is the best move, stopping us from regrouping with ...[Nb8]-[c6]. That is not our only plan, though.} Qg5 {We bring the queen to the kingside. We will bring the other knight to [f6] and start our play here.} 15. O-O Ndf6 $36 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Ga7a6,Gc8h3] A typical plan in these positions is to play ...[h5]-[h4]. We can kick the knight back with ...[a6] next, as White cannot answer [Nc7] we have the intermediate move ...[Bh3] followed by ...[Rc8], pinning the knight.} *

