1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Bb2 {White keeps the option of both [Be2] and [Bd3] open, but this means that their king stays in the centre even longer. Also, ...[Bb4]+ can no longer be met with [Bd2].} e5 9. Be2 {White allows us to gain space in the centre. This is pretty dangerous.} e4 {Of course, there should be no hesitation and we even have the powerful dark-squared bishop on the board compared to earlier variations where we played ...[e4].} 10. Nd2 Nb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4] We regroup our knight to [b4] and also open the diagonal for the [c8]-bishop.} 11. h3 {White is preparing to play [g4] on the kingside. They have to justify allowing us to play ...[e4] in some way.} Na6 12. a3 Nc7 {[%csl Rb5,Gd5] Since we are unable to get the knight to [b4], we bring it to [c7] where it does a very good defensive job. It keeps an eye on the [d5]-pawn and also stops ideas of [Nb5].} 13. g4 b5 {This is another benefit of the knight on [c7]. We force White to make a decision regarding the [c4]-pawn.} 14. c5 Be7 15. g5 Nfe8 $10 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf7f6] We are ready to play ...[f6] next and open the f-file. White has to play precisely to keep the kingside under control. The queenside is likely to remain completely blocked.} *

