1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Bb2 {White keeps the option of both [Be2] and [Bd3] open, but this means that their king stays in the centre even longer. Also, ...[Bb4]+ can no longer be met with [Bd2].} e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. O-O-O {We should take such moves seriously as they can be super uncomfortable over the board, even though it is objectively equal. We just need to follow the basics.} Qe7 $1 {There should be no hesitation giving up the pawn on [d5], as it only opens up the files for us on the queenside.} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 {There are a lot of trades happening. White has to try to win the pawn on [d5] as otherwise they are worse.} 13. Nxd5 Bxb2+ 14. Kxb2 Nxd5 15. Rxd5 Qf6+ {[%cal Gc8f5,Ga8c8,Gc8e6] I like this check. It allows us to play ...[Bf5] next if White blocks the check with the rook.} (15... Be6 {is less accurate because after} 16. Rd4 {(, which happened in the game ½-½ 34 Kramnik,V 2791-Aronian,L 2801 Moscow 2010, we are unable to create something before White develops the light-squared bishop.)}) 16. Rd4 Bf5 $1 {This was the reason why we needed the queen on [f6]. Now the rook on [d4] is stuck while we will try to get our rook to [c2].} 17. Qc3 Rac8 18. Rc4 {White manages to unpin the rook.} Qg6 $15 {[%csl Rg2]} (18... Qg6 {We tie White's bishop to the g2-pawn. This is dangerous territory for White as we will play either ...Be6 or ...b5 next, forcing a trade on c8 which would be curtains. White has to give up a pawn with} 19. e4 {just to survive.}) *

