1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. e4 {White goes for an early [e4] break, but we are well placed to counter it. We have completed our development while White cannot say the same for their queenside.} dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qh4 c5 {[%cal Gb7f3] We achieve our ideal break, opening up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop. White should typically meet this break with [d5] if they want to fight for the advantage, but here White is lagging behind in development and can't achieve the [d5] advance.} 14. Bb2 Ne4 $1 {We offer the trade of queens and also get our knight to its ideal square on [e4].} 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. Rad1 cxd4 17. Bxd4 {This has been played in a few games and is very natural, but it is not accurate.} Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c3] Our threat is ...[Bc3] and trading the dark-squared bishops.} 18. Rd3 f6 $17 {[%cal Ge6e5] This is our usual plan in these positions after we get our knight to [e4]. It restricts both the knight on [f3] and the bishop on [d4].} *

