1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rfd1 Rac8 {It does not look like we are copying White here, but it is clear that their other rook will come to [c1] soon.} 12. e4 {White claims that we have wasted a tempo putting our rook on [c8], as it doesn't do much of importance in these lines. At the same time, however, White also needs to put the rook on [e1] rather than the d-file.} (12. Rac1 {will transpose to the next variation.}) 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 15. Qh4 c5 {By now you must be well aware of these types of positions. The only line we have to check here is if White can get in the move [d5].} 16. d5 exd5 17. Bxf6 {This is necessary to win the pawn back, but White is giving up their best minor piece, leaving us with the bishop pair.} Qxf6 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. cxd5 Rfd8 $10 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga7a6,Gb6b5] We will go after the [d5] pawn hard. I anticipate White putting the bishop on [c4] and going [a4] to stop us from playing ...[b5]. We will probably play it anyway, and end up trading it for the [d5]-pawn. Our bishop pair compensates for the doubled f-pawns.} *

