e restricts the bishop on [d6] and prepares to play [Bf1]-[g2].} Bb4 {[%cal Gc6c5]} ({We are ready to continue with ...c5. While we could have played the usual} 13... h6 {, this is more direct and exploits some of the weaknesses that White has created on the long diagonal. It is a general pattern to remember: we meet [g3] with the plan of ...[Bb4] and ...[c5].}) 14. a3 {This is a good option, forcing us to trade the dark-squared bishop on either [c3] or [a3].} ({If} 14. Bf1 {the move} c5 {equalizes easily.}) 14... Bxa3 {Both options are good, but I prefer not to give our opponent the bishop pair if possible. Both the a-pawns are removed from the board now.} 15. Bxa3 Qxa3 16. Ra1 Qd6 17. Rxa7 Qb8 $10 {[%cal Gc6c5] We kick the rook back and play ...[c5] next. I like our position more, as our light-squared bishop can prove to be very dangerous along the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} *

