1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] This has been played by a few strong players and is one of the favourite moves of the computer. White gains space on the queenside and is ready to continue with [a5]. It does create a hole on [b4], but our knight is pretty far away from exploiting this square.} a5 {We stop White's intended expansion, but this move does create a potential weakness on [b5] once we play the ...[c5] break. White is well placed to exploit this with the [c3]-knight.} 12. Rad1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White brings their rook to the d-file, preparing the [e4] advance. White will then be able to meet a future ...[c5] with [d5] in the centre.} Bb4 {[%csl Rc3] We stop the move [e4] by putting pressure on the [c3]-knight.} 13. Bd3 Rfd8 14. e4 {White plays their central break, but we can deal with it as usual.} dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Nf6 17. Bd3 c5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb7f3] This is even stronger here, as the bishop on [b4] prevents any tricks with [Re1]. White can easily get a worse position if they do not play accurately now.} 18. d5 {This is more or less necessary to open up White's pieces.} exd5 19. cxd5 Bxd5 $10 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ge7e6] White has a few options to prove compensation for the pawn, but can't get more than that. We are threatening to play ...[Qe6], targeting the [b3]-pawn.} *

