eate a potential weakness on [b5] once we play the ...[c5] break. White is well placed to exploit this with the [c3]-knight.} 12. Bd3 {White is preparing to play [e4] next. We have a few decent options.} Rac8 {[%cal Gc6c5] I like this move, preparing the ...[c5] break. It also allows us to put our bishop on [b8] if needed without blocking the rook.} 13. e4 {This still seems a bit premature.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bd3 Bb4 $1 {[%csl Ra4,Gb4] This is one of the drawbacks of the [a4]/[a5] inclusion. We cement our bishop on [b4], stopping the move [Re1]. We are going to play ...[c5] next.} 17. Ng5 {White is looking to trade off the knights, which is not a big deal for us.} h6 18. Nh7 Nxh7 {I like our rook on [f8] for the moment. We will bring the other rook to [d8], and the [f8]-rook can go to [e8] in the future.} 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Be4 c5 $10 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc5d4,Gb4c5] We easily get our desired break in the centre and equalise. We can take on [d4] at the right moment and follow up with ...[Bc5]. White then either has to trade bishops, opening up the b-file, or surrender the diagonal to our bishop.} *

