1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This is the best square for this rook, as White is looking to open the e-file with [e4] soon. Moreover, White wants to meet a future ...[c5] break with the move [d5], and in that case the rook on [e1] is very useful against our queen on [e7].} Rfe8 {This is a pretty flexible move, as we are going to need the [f8]-square for the knight soon. That said, it is not a big difference if we start with bringing the other rook to [d8].} 12. e4 $5 {This advance is more effective now compared to earlier variations, as here White has a rook on [e1] eyeing our queen.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Rad8 $1 {We bring the rook to the centre. Next, our plan is to put our knight on [f8] and go for the ...[c5] break. This is the second way of meeting the [e4] break. The major advantage of this approach is that we can opt for the move ...[f6], restricting White's minor pieces.} 15. Bd3 {This does not achieve much as we were hoping to get our knight to [f8] anyway, in order to defend the [h7]-pawn.} Nf8 16. Qg4 {The threat is [c5] followed by the move [d5], opening up the diagonal for the [b2]-bishop. Typically we have two ways to respond to this.} Ba3 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4] This is the easiest option, forcing the trade of the dark-squared bishops. White's bishop cannot escape as we can keep chasing it.} ({The other option was already mentioned earlier: we can also play} 16... f6 {, taking away squares from White's pieces and blocking the long diagonal.}) 17. Bxa3 Qxa3 {[%cal Gc6c5] This exchange completely changes the position, as now ...[c5] becomes a big threat.} 18. Qf4 Qe7 {We bring the queen back and prepare to play ...[c5] on the next move.} ({The immediate} 18... c5 {is careless as White can answer} 19. d5 exd5 20. Ng5 $1 {± .}) 19. Rad1 c5 20. d5 Qf6 $10 {The exchange of queens solves most of our problems, and White will be forced to release the tension in the centre.} *

