 for the knight soon. That said, it is not a big difference if we start with bringing the other rook to [d8].} 12. e4 $5 {This advance is more effective now compared to earlier variations, as here White has a rook on [e1] eyeing our queen.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Rad8 $1 {We bring the rook to the centre. Next, our plan is to put our knight on [f8] and go for the ...[c5] break. This is the second way of meeting the [e4] break. The major advantage of this approach is that we can opt for the move ...[f6], restricting White's minor pieces.} 15. Qc2 {As I've mentioned earlier, there are two good plans in these positions. I will give both of them, as it is good to know both plans well.} Ba3 {We have seen this idea before, exchanging the dark-squared bishops by force. It makes our task of playing the ...[c5] break much easier. The other option keeps more pieces on the board.} 16. Bxa3 Qxa3 17. Bd3 h6 {We keep our knight on [d7], preparing to play ...[c5] next.} 18. Rad1 c5 $10 {[%csl Ra2,Ga3][%cal Gc5d4,Gb7f3]} (18... c5 {We can leave the queen on a3 for now, as it keeps White's queenside in check. If White trades the bishops with} 19. Be4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 {, we can play} Nf6 {followed by taking on [d4] with equality.}) *

