1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This is the best square for this rook, as White is looking to open the e-file with [e4] soon. Moreover, White wants to meet a future ...[c5] break with the move [d5], and in that case the rook on [e1] is very useful against our queen on [e7].} Rfe8 {This is a pretty flexible move, as we are going to need the [f8]-square for the knight soon. That said, it is not a big difference if we start with bringing the other rook to [d8].} 12. Rad1 {The natural move, bringing the last remaining piece to the centre.} Rad8 {We do the same, completing our setup. Now there are multiple plans for both sides, and we have to understand the position well. Usually, most players just go for the ...[c5] break everywhere, as that makes it easy to remember how to play. I like the positions with the ...[e5] break a lot, but the drawback is that it is not effective against all of White's possible moves. However, I feel it is worth learning a few more variations if we can take over in the centre with [e5]-[e4] in some of the lines.} 13. Bd3 {This is the 5th most common move in the position. What is the drawback of putting the bishop on [d3]?} e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] We already saw way back on move 8 that the bishop on [d3] allows us to get the move ...[e5] in much more easily. We are creating a threat of advancing further with ...[e4] immediately. Also, our knight will attack the bishop if White exchanges on [e5].} 14. e4 {Visually this creates a big mess in the centre, but it is nothing to worry about. We have to be a bit precise, though.} dxc4 15. Bxc4 {White does not want to weaken their pawn structure, but they have just wasted a tempo moving the bishop to [d3].} exd4 16. Nxd4 g6 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gd7e5,Gc6c5] We cover the [f5]-square and are now planning to get our knight to [e5] followed by ...[c5].} 17. Bf1 {The 4th time moving the bishop, this time back to its initial square!} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g4] We are threatening to get our knight to [g4], forcing White to create weaknesses there.} 18. h3 Nh5 $10 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gd8d7,Ge8d8] This is a clever move, stopping White from going [f4]. Our knight can jump to [f4] anytime. I think Black is starting to take the initiative. We can double on the d-file and put our bishop on [b8].} *

