1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This is the best square for this rook, as White is looking to open the e-file with [e4] soon. Moreover, White wants to meet a future ...[c5] break with the move [d5], and in that case the rook on [e1] is very useful against our queen on [e7].} Rfe8 {This is a pretty flexible move, as we are going to need the [f8]-square for the knight soon. That said, it is not a big difference if we start with bringing the other rook to [d8].} 12. Rad1 {The natural move, bringing the last remaining piece to the centre.} Rad8 {We do the same, completing our setup. Now there are multiple plans for both sides, and we have to understand the position well. Usually, most players just go for the ...[c5] break everywhere, as that makes it easy to remember how to play. I like the positions with the ...[e5] break a lot, but the drawback is that it is not effective against all of White's possible moves. However, I feel it is worth learning a few more variations if we can take over in the centre with [e5]-[e4] in some of the lines.} 13. g3 {Do you remember one of the general rules I outlined earlier in the chapter? If you do, then it's much easier to understand our plan here.} Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4e1,Gc6c5] I mentioned earlier that we meet the move [g3] with ...[Bb4] followed by ...[c5]. We want to exploit the weaknesses along the long diagonal.} 14. a3 {This is White's best response, forcing us to trade on [c3]. It's not that great to take on [a3] here, as it would give White the open a-file for free.} Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Ne4 16. Qc2 c5 {[%csl Rg3] Even though we gave up our dark-squared bishop, we are happy to open up the centre. The weaknesses created by the move [g3] compensate for White's bishop pair.} 17. dxc5 dxc4 $1 {We go for White's kingside immediately.} 18. Bxc4 Nxg3 {[%csl Rf3,Rc5][%cal Gb7f3] This is the point! We want to win the knight on [f3] followed by the [c5]-pawn.} 19. e4 $1 {This is an important move for White to not be worse.} Nxe4 20. Rxe4 Bxe4 21. Qxe4 Nxc5 $10 {[%csl Rg1] We reach an interesting imbalanced position. White has two beautiful bishops, but they are missing the important g-pawn and are two pawns down. The rooks are going to be traded off, and I like our chances to outplay our opponent.} *

