1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This is the best square for this rook, as White is looking to open the e-file with [e4] soon. Moreover, White wants to meet a future ...[c5] break with the move [d5], and in that case the rook on [e1] is very useful against our queen on [e7].} Rfe8 {This is a pretty flexible move, as we are going to need the [f8]-square for the knight soon. That said, it is not a big difference if we start with bringing the other rook to [d8].} 12. Rad1 {The natural move, bringing the last remaining piece to the centre.} Rad8 {We do the same, completing our setup. Now there are multiple plans for both sides, and we have to understand the position well. Usually, most players just go for the ...[c5] break everywhere, as that makes it easy to remember how to play. I like the positions with the ...[e5] break a lot, but the drawback is that it is not effective against all of White's possible moves. However, I feel it is worth learning a few more variations if we can take over in the centre with [e5]-[e4] in some of the lines.} 13. e4 {I assure you that this is one of the final instances where we will consider White's move [e4] :-. Even I am bored of the oh so many different move orders, but this advance is a favourite of most White players. In this instance, both sides have brought all their pieces to their ideal squares already.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf8 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gf7f6] We saw this plan previously with White's rook on [e1]. There we had another option - to go ...[Ba3] to trade the bishops - but now White can retreat their bishop to [a1]. After 15...[Nf8], we are ready to play ...[c5] on the next move.} 16. Bf1 c5 17. d5 f6 {[%csl Rb2,Rf3][%cal Ge7f7] This is the point behind our move 15...Nf8, to blunt both the bishop on [b2] and the knight on [f3]. We will continue with ...[Qf7] and force White to trade on [e6]. White has to try something dynamic if they want to fight for an advantage.} 18. Qg4 $5 {White plans to go [Nh4] next and meet the capture on [d5] with [Nf5].} Bc8 $1 {A cunning move, preparing to take on [d5] next. We do not allow White to get the knight to [f5].} ({After} 18... Qf7 19. Nh4 {(White had some pressure in the game ½-½ Khusnutdinov,R 2491-Nihal,S 2620 Chess.com INT 2020.)}) 19. dxe6 Nxe6 $10 {[%cal Ge6g5,Ge7f7] We can either play ...[Ng5] next or move the queen out of the way. I think we have solved all of our issues.} *

