1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 {This is a very common move, defending the pawn on [c4] with the b-pawn. Now we cannot go for our usual plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[e5], which we've seen in the last two chapters. At the same time, White is playing pretty slowly, so we can do the same.} O-O {We go for the ...[b6] plan in the main lines, but it is important to castle first, keeping our options open for now. Now we've come to an important crossroads for White. Ideally, White would want to play [Bd3] and [Bb2] followed by [O-O] and [e4]. But we meet both those moves with the ...[e5] break in the centre. The main line is the move 8.Be2, which is less principled but which makes our ...[e5] plan less effective.} 8. Be2 {This is a clever move, aimed against the ...[e5] plan. It is less active than the alternatives, but White is not in a rush to open up the position. They first want to complete development and bring the rooks to the centre before going for the [e4] break.} b6 {We do the same, developing our bishop to [b7]. We will eventually achieve either the ...[e5] or the ...[c5] break.} (8... e5 {is possible, but a bit passive after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 {. Here, the bishop is traded off with a tempo and White brings the knight to [d2], which is its best square.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 {The queen is ideally positioned on [e7] to prepare our central breaks. Next, we will bring our rooks to the centre. Typically to [e8] and [d8], as these files are the most likely to open up in the next few moves. However, sometimes we just copy White if, for example, they put a rook on [c1].} 11. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This is the best square for this rook, as White is looking to open the e-file with [e4] soon. Moreover, White wants to meet a future ...[c5] break with the move [d5], and in that case the rook on [e1] is very useful against our queen on [e7].} Rfe8 {This is a pretty flexible move, as we are going to need the [f8]-square for the knight soon. That said, it is not a big difference if we start with bringing the other rook to [d8].} 12. Rad1 {The natural move, bringing the last remaining piece to the centre.} Rad8 {We do the same, completing our setup. Now there are multiple plans for both sides, and we have to understand the position well. Usually, most players just go for the ...[c5] break everywhere, as that makes it easy to remember how to play. I like the positions with the ...[e5] break a lot, but the drawback is that it is not effective against all of White's possible moves. However, I feel it is worth learning a few more variations if we can take over in the centre with [e5]-[e4] in some of the lines.} 13. Bf1 {Finally, we come to my favourite move. I am always hoping to get this on the board, because we have a very cunning trap prepared for our opponent.} e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] We go for the most ambitious pawn break in the centre. We are threatening to play ...[e4], and White has to react accordingly.} (13... c5 {is also good, but I feel that 13...e5 is more aggressive.}) 14. cxd5 $2 {This is a pretty common response to the move 13...e5, but it is a serious mistake. It does not look so at first sight, even for the computer! That is one of the big reasons why we can even catch a well-prepared player here, if they have not checked it deeply enough.} e4 $1 {We close the situation in the centre, and if we can recapture the pawn on [d5] we are much better. The bishop on [b2] is completely stuck.} 15. dxc6 $2 {This is the critical line and the reason why engines like White initially.} (15. Ne5 {is probably the best, but it just gives Black a big advantage after} cxd5 {∓ .}) 15... exf3 $1 {Of course, we did not go for this variation just to take back on [c6].} 16. cxb7 {This is a position I have given to several GMs and strong players. I will warn you that it is not easy to find the solution here, but you can give it a try. Black needs to do something immediately on the kingside.} Bxh2+ $1 {This is pretty obvious, but the follow up is the most difficult part.} 17. Kxh2 Qd6+ 18. Kh3 {It looks like White's king has escaped, but we have a killer blow prepared.} Re5 $3 {[%cal Ge5h5] What a stunning move! We give up a whole rook just to force the [d4]-pawn to [e5]. That gives us the [e5]-square, which is extremely important to give mate.} 19. dxe5 Qe6+ 20. Kh2 Qxe5+ {[%cal Gh2g1,Gf6g4]} 21. Kh3 {White can dally around a bit, but it is futile.} Qh5+ 22. Kg3 Qg4+ 23. Kh2 Qh4+ {Finally we force the king to [g1] and it's game over.} 24. Kg1 Ng4 $19 {All of this happened in one of my blitz games online. It's been a dream of mine to get it in classical chess as well, but fate has not been so kind. :-} *

