 3rd rank. It is ready to shift over to the kingside when needed. Of course, the drawback is that this runs into [Bb5], which looks like it wins an exchange.} 18. Bb5 Bxh2+ $1 {It is time to go for our play on the kingside.} 19. Kf1 {This is the safer move, but it becomes dangerous once White gives up the bishop for the rook on [c6].} Qc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b5] We are threatening to take on [b5] and also prepare a route for our queen towards the kingside.} 20. Qe2 Rce6 $1 {[%cal Gc5g5] Another difficult move which we need to remember. The light-squared bishop is extremely important here and worth the rook on [e8]. Moreover, ...[Qg5] is a huge threat right now.} 21. Bxe8 Bxg2+ $1 {This was the point behind our previous moves.} 22. Kxg2 Qg5+ 23. Kh1 $1 Nxe8 {[%cal Ge6h6] We finally win the bishop back and are just a rook down. White has to give up the queen to avoid mate.} 24. f4 Bxf4 25. exf4 Rh6+ 26. Qh2 Rxh2+ 27. Kxh2 Qxf4+ $10 {Once again, we reach a crazy endgame with chances for both sides. We can get our knight to [d6] next and try to bring it into the attack.} *

