1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. a3 {We will be taking a look at some of the sidelines on move 6 in this chapter. I think it makes sense to call them Anti-Meran lines, since all of them are aimed against our plan of ...[dxc4] followed by ...[b5].} ({The move} 6. a3 {is a bit different, as White is preparing to play [Bd3] next and the move [a3] will be useful if we take on [c4]. Our usual plan against [Bd3] is ...[b5] and ...[b4], which is no longer possible. But, at the same time, the move [a3] is not useful in quite a few other systems which we can play.}) 6... Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O e5 $1 {This is a decent line in the 6.Qc2 variation which we've seen in the last two chapters. Here, it is a much better version for us since White has played the non-developing move [a3] instead of [Qc2].} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 {We do get an IQP position, but we have a nice lead in development. White has to waste further time, as we are threatening to take on [f3] here.} 11. Be2 {White has to defend [f3].} (11. b3 {falls for our trick as after} Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Bg4 {-+ the queen is trapped.}) 11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Be6 13. Nb5 Be5 14. Nd4 Ne4 $10 {[%csl Rc1,Rd4][%cal Gd8f6,Gd8d6,Ga8c8] Our minor pieces are well placed in the centre. It is hard for White to develop the bishop on [c1]. If White removes the [d4]-knight , they will have issues with the pawn on [b2]. We can put our queen on either [f6] or [d6] and develop our rooks.} *

