1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. b3 {This is similar to lines we've seen in the previous chapter, but here White's queen is on [d1] instead. Another important difference is that we have not committed our bishop to [d6] yet.} Bb4 $1 {We force White to make an unpleasant decision.} 7. Bb2 {This would be ideal, but it is a serious inaccuracy. The pin is too dangerous for White.} Qa5 8. Rc1 Qxa2 {We take the free pawn on [a2] and also attack the bishop on [b2].} 9. Qc2 Ne4 $15 {[%cal Gb4c3,Ga2c2] We will take on [c3] next and trade the queens. We are just left with an extra pawn in the endgame. It may not be lost for White because of their space advantage, but White has to defend accurately to hold.} *

