1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. b3 {This is similar to lines we've seen in the previous chapter, but here White's queen is on [d1] instead. Another important difference is that we have not committed our bishop to [d6] yet.} Bb4 $1 {We force White to make an unpleasant decision.} 7. Bd2 {This is an unfortunate necessity. The bishop is misplaced here, blocking the d-file, and does not achieve much.} O-O 8. Bd3 {This is in general the more active option for White, but the bishop on [d2] poses some issues for them.} dxc4 {There were other good options, but this is the best way to exploit White's play.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {is not an ambitious option, and we can continue as usual with} a6 {followed by ...[b5] next.}) 9... e5 $1 {[%csl Rd3] This is the point. We are targeting the bishop on [d3] which is undefended.} 10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Ne4 {White has to go in damage control mode, as they are in a bit of a pickle.} Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Ngxe5 $10 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf7f5,Gf5f4] We have managed to exchange the dark-squared bishops and weaken White's pawn structure on the queenside. We can even start an initiative with ...[f5]-[f4] next on the kingside. White has to be careful.} *

