1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. b3 {This is similar to lines we've seen in the previous chapter, but here White's queen is on [d1] instead. Another important difference is that we have not committed our bishop to [d6] yet.} Bb4 $1 {We force White to make an unpleasant decision.} 7. Bd2 {This is an unfortunate necessity. The bishop is misplaced here, blocking the d-file, and does not achieve much.} O-O 8. Be2 {This is safer compared to the previous line, but also less active.} Re8 {[%cal Ge6e5] We will again try to go for the ...[e5] plan, but we have to prepare it more slowly now, as the bishop is on [e2] is more secure.} 9. O-O {There is a cunning trap here for us that we need to watch out for.} Bd6 {We bring the bishop back, which avoids White's trick with [Nd5].} (9... b6 {falls right into it, as White can play} 10. Nxd5 $1 {and White just wins a free extra pawn.}) 10. Qc2 a6 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ge6e5] This is not a usual move for us, but we want to go for the ...[e5] break next. That's why we cover the [b5]-square.} (10... e5 {would be a bit premature due to} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nb5 $1 Bb8 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bc3 {⩲ and White establishes control over the [d4]-square.}) 11. Rad1 e5 {We finally get our desired break in the centre. The main question is whether White can get full control over the [d4]-square. With the bishop on [d2], this is not an easy task for White.} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Bc1 Qc7 {We get the queen out of the d-file and also target the pawn on [h2]. Another benefit is that we indirectly pin the [c3]-knight along the c-file.} 14. h3 dxc4 15. bxc4 b5 {We allow White to liquidate their weak pawn, but this helps us gain space on the queenside. it also helps open the a-file.} 16. Bb2 Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Be6 $10 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Gc6] We force White to release the tension on the queenside. We have equalised comfortably with our pawn majority on the queenside.} *

