1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Be2 {I was not well prepared against this line until Sam Shankland published his [d4] repertoire on Chessable a few years ago. This move has since gotten more popular, mainly because it is much easier to learn compared to the complex lines we have seen so far. There is also the surprise factor, which played a big effect back then but not anymore.The main point of 6.Be2 is that White will not recapture on [c4] with the bishop as usual.} Bd6 {We will not take on [c4] anytime soon. Instead, our play is very similar to the lines we saw in the previous chapter. As we know, the bishop is less active on [e2] compared to [d3].} (6... dxc4 {is met cleverly with} 7. a4 {, and White will decide later how to win the pawn back. For example, against our usual setup of ...[Bd6], White would bring their knight to [c4].}) 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 b6 {We just copy White and fianchetto the bishop. At any moment White can play [Qc2] and transpose to the previous chapter. However, Sam's whole point is to keep the queen on [d1] and try to play [e4] with the move [Bd3] instead.} 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Bd3 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5] This is a cunning move not covered by Shankland. It is a useful waiting move, asking White how they want to continue. We will typically put our rook on [e8] next and look for an opportunity to go for the ...[e5] break. It has been played in only 16 games so far.} 11. e4 {This pawn break is premature with the queen still on [d1].} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Nf6 {We have seen this reply to the [e4] break countless times in the previous chapter. We are ready to break with ...[c5] next. Here, White has a distinctly worse version as they can only retreat with the bishop. At least when White takes with the queen on [e4], they have the option of going to [h4] or [e3], which may be better squares.} 14. Bc2 {This is not much of an improvement.} c5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Ne5 Qe7 $10 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gc5d4,Ga8c8,Gb7a8,Ge7b7] We will play ...[Rfd8] next, followed by maybe ...[Bd4] trading the dark-squared bishops. Another plan is to move the [a8]-rook and follow it up with ...[Ba8] and ...[Qb7].} *

