1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Be2 {I was not well prepared against this line until Sam Shankland published his [d4] repertoire on Chessable a few years ago. This move has since gotten more popular, mainly because it is much easier to learn compared to the complex lines we have seen so far. There is also the surprise factor, which played a big effect back then but not anymore.The main point of 6.Be2 is that White will not recapture on [c4] with the bishop as usual.} Bd6 {We will not take on [c4] anytime soon. Instead, our play is very similar to the lines we saw in the previous chapter. As we know, the bishop is less active on [e2] compared to [d3].} (6... dxc4 {is met cleverly with} 7. a4 {, and White will decide later how to win the pawn back. For example, against our usual setup of ...[Bd6], White would bring their knight to [c4].}) 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 b6 {We just copy White and fianchetto the bishop. At any moment White can play [Qc2] and transpose to the previous chapter. However, Sam's whole point is to keep the queen on [d1] and try to play [e4] with the move [Bd3] instead.} 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Bd3 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5] This is a cunning move not covered by Shankland. It is a useful waiting move, asking White how they want to continue. We will typically put our rook on [e8] next and look for an opportunity to go for the ...[e5] break. It has been played in only 16 games so far.} 11. h3 {White copies us, but I do not think this move is as useful for White.} Re8 {This is our main plan in the position. The rook is best placed on the e-file and we have the option to go for the ...[e5] break in many positions.} 12. Re1 Rc8 {Now, we hint at going for the other pawn break in the position with ...[c5] next. Both these rook moves are pretty useful when the centre eventually opens up.} 13. Rc1 {Very original play from White :-. Now both pawn breaks are possible for us.} e5 {I generally prefer this break when we have a choice, as you must have seen in the last chapter. It creates more attacking chances and forces White to open the centre.} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. cxd5 {This is the only option for White to try and create a weakness in the centre. Other moves give us a very easy life.} Nxd3 {We eliminate the light-squared bishop when we get the chance.} (15... cxd5 {was played by Erigaisi against Nihal, but I am not a fan of entering this particular pawn structure if we can avoid it.}) 16. Qxd3 Bf8 $1 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd8d5] We want to take on [d5] with the queen and trade the queens. The two bishops are generally stronger in the endgame. Moreover, the queen is an important piece to play against an IQP.} 17. Red1 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 $10 {[%csl Gb7,Gf8] The bishop pair easily compensates for the potential pawn weakness. The endgame can become pretty risky for White. Why is the bishop pair so lethal there? Because the bishops can play on both flanks and can control the opponent's king very well. The knight is a short-range piece and can be restricted.} *

