1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Be2 {I was not well prepared against this line until Sam Shankland published his [d4] repertoire on Chessable a few years ago. This move has since gotten more popular, mainly because it is much easier to learn compared to the complex lines we have seen so far. There is also the surprise factor, which played a big effect back then but not anymore.The main point of 6.Be2 is that White will not recapture on [c4] with the bishop as usual.} Bd6 {We will not take on [c4] anytime soon. Instead, our play is very similar to the lines we saw in the previous chapter. As we know, the bishop is less active on [e2] compared to [d3].} (6... dxc4 {is met cleverly with} 7. a4 {, and White will decide later how to win the pawn back. For example, against our usual setup of ...[Bd6], White would bring their knight to [c4].}) 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 b6 {We just copy White and fianchetto the bishop. At any moment White can play [Qc2] and transpose to the previous chapter. However, Sam's whole point is to keep the queen on [d1] and try to play [e4] with the move [Bd3] instead.} 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Bd3 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5] This is a cunning move not covered by Shankland. It is a useful waiting move, asking White how they want to continue. We will typically put our rook on [e8] next and look for an opportunity to go for the ...[e5] break. It has been played in only 16 games so far.} 11. Re1 {White is preparing the move [e4].} Re8 {We are not too concerned about White's idea and just improve our position.} 12. e4 dxc4 $1 {This is the idea we had in mind on the previous move.} 13. bxc4 e5 {[%csl Gc5] We force White to answer [d5] and close the centre. This gives us the [c5]-square for our knight.} 14. d5 Rc8 $10 {[%cal Gb6b5,Ga7a6] We will continue with ...[a6] followed by ...[b5] on the queenside. I cannot see a good plan for White to improve their position.} *

