1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Be2 {I was not well prepared against this line until Sam Shankland published his [d4] repertoire on Chessable a few years ago. This move has since gotten more popular, mainly because it is much easier to learn compared to the complex lines we have seen so far. There is also the surprise factor, which played a big effect back then but not anymore.The main point of 6.Be2 is that White will not recapture on [c4] with the bishop as usual.} Bd6 {We will not take on [c4] anytime soon. Instead, our play is very similar to the lines we saw in the previous chapter. As we know, the bishop is less active on [e2] compared to [d3].} (6... dxc4 {is met cleverly with} 7. a4 {, and White will decide later how to win the pawn back. For example, against our usual setup of ...[Bd6], White would bring their knight to [c4].}) 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 b6 {We just copy White and fianchetto the bishop. At any moment White can play [Qc2] and transpose to the previous chapter. However, Sam's whole point is to keep the queen on [d1] and try to play [e4] with the move [Bd3] instead.} 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Bd3 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5] This is a cunning move not covered by Shankland. It is a useful waiting move, asking White how they want to continue. We will typically put our rook on [e8] next and look for an opportunity to go for the ...[e5] break. It has been played in only 16 games so far.} 11. Qc2 {What is the drawback of the queen moving away from the d-file?} dxc4 $1 12. bxc4 c5 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3] We get the ...[c5] break without allowing White to go for the move [d5]. This is the other benefit of the move ...[h6], as [h7] does not hang with check.} 13. d5 {White has to try giving up the d-pawn for the initiative, but this does not lead to much.} exd5 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rfd1 {There are some temporary issues with the d-file which we need to solve.} Nf6 17. e4 c4 $10 {We give back the pawn but get White's light-squared bishop in return. The position is balanced.} *

