1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Be2 {I was not well prepared against this line until Sam Shankland published his [d4] repertoire on Chessable a few years ago. This move has since gotten more popular, mainly because it is much easier to learn compared to the complex lines we have seen so far. There is also the surprise factor, which played a big effect back then but not anymore.The main point of 6.Be2 is that White will not recapture on [c4] with the bishop as usual.} Bd6 {We will not take on [c4] anytime soon. Instead, our play is very similar to the lines we saw in the previous chapter. As we know, the bishop is less active on [e2] compared to [d3].} (6... dxc4 {is met cleverly with} 7. a4 {, and White will decide later how to win the pawn back. For example, against our usual setup of ...[Bd6], White would bring their knight to [c4].}) 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 b6 {We just copy White and fianchetto the bishop. At any moment White can play [Qc2] and transpose to the previous chapter. However, Sam's whole point is to keep the queen on [d1] and try to play [e4] with the move [Bd3] instead.} 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Bd3 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5] This is a cunning move not covered by Shankland. It is a useful waiting move, asking White how they want to continue. We will typically put our rook on [e8] next and look for an opportunity to go for the ...[e5] break. It has been played in only 16 games so far.} 11. Qe2 {Is the queen on [e2] better than on [c2]? I don't think so, as we can meet the move [e4] with ...[e5], opening up the e-file.} Re8 {[%cal Ge8e2] We get the added benefit of playing against the queen on [e2].} 12. Rfd1 Qe7 {We decide where to put our queen based on which white rook comes to [d1]. Now that White would lose a tempo by playing [Re1], we put it on [e7].} 13. Rac1 Rad8 {The white rooks seem misplaced, and White does not have a clear plan regarding the pawn tension in the centre.} 14. h3 Bb8 {[%cal Ge6e5] We are now ready to play ...[e5] next, as [Nb5] is no longer an issue.} 15. Bb1 {White gets the bishop away from our threat of ...[e5]-[e4].} dxc4 $1 {We change plans now that the bishop is not on [d3]. White is forced to recapture with the pawn.} 16. bxc4 c5 $10 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4] We open the diagonal for our bishop and equalize comfortably. White has to be careful not to get worse as they will have to play with hanging pawns in the centre.} *

