1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Be2 {I was not well prepared against this line until Sam Shankland published his [d4] repertoire on Chessable a few years ago. This move has since gotten more popular, mainly because it is much easier to learn compared to the complex lines we have seen so far. There is also the surprise factor, which played a big effect back then but not anymore.The main point of 6.Be2 is that White will not recapture on [c4] with the bishop as usual.} Bd6 {We will not take on [c4] anytime soon. Instead, our play is very similar to the lines we saw in the previous chapter. As we know, the bishop is less active on [e2] compared to [d3].} (6... dxc4 {is met cleverly with} 7. a4 {, and White will decide later how to win the pawn back. For example, against our usual setup of ...[Bd6], White would bring their knight to [c4].}) 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 b6 {We just copy White and fianchetto the bishop. At any moment White can play [Qc2] and transpose to the previous chapter. However, Sam's whole point is to keep the queen on [d1] and try to play [e4] with the move [Bd3] instead.} 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Bd3 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5] This is a cunning move not covered by Shankland. It is a useful waiting move, asking White how they want to continue. We will typically put our rook on [e8] next and look for an opportunity to go for the ...[e5] break. It has been played in only 16 games so far.} 11. Rc1 {This was played by Shankland from the white side. I am not sure what his plan was, though.} Re8 {Our usual move, preparing ...[e5] at the right moment.} 12. Re1 {This seems to be the natural way to play for White, keeping the queen on [d1].} dxc4 $1 {We have seen this plan before. It is an ambitious idea, forcing some weaknesses in White's centre.} 13. bxc4 c5 {We saw the ...[e5] plan in the variation with the pawn on [e4], but now we go for the queenside break, opening up the diagonal for the bishop.} 14. d5 {This is the only ambitious option which can pose us any problems after the ...[c5] break.} exd5 15. cxd5 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gc5c4,Gb5b4] We want to play ...[b5] next followed by both ...[c4] and ...[b4].} (15... Nxd5 {is tempting, but White has some initiative after} 16. Bc4 Nxc3 17. Qxd6 {↑ .}) 16. a4 {This is necessary to stop ...[b5], but it makes a big difference when we take on [d5], as the pawn on [a4] is hanging in some of the lines.} Nxd5 $1 {We follow the rule: win any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger.} 17. Bc4 Nxc3 18. Qxd6 Nxa4 {This is the major difference. The knight gets to win the pawn on [a4] with a tempo. We are up two pawns now.} 19. Ba1 Bxf3 20. Qg3 {This is White's idea, trying to force some more weaknesses on the kingside.} Bg4 $1 {We give up the bishop on [g4] to get a tempo with the knight.} 21. Qxg4 Nf6 22. Qg6 Ra7 $10 {We defend [f7] comfortably and are still up two pawns. It is high time White decides how they want to show compensation for the missing material.} *

