1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before playing [e3]. There are three systems that Black can go for here. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory.} (5. g3 {In addition to the Botvinnik, we will also cover all of White's different sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.}) (5. Qd3 {(Both the queen moves Qb3/[d3] lead to the same position. This is not principled, as White brings their queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using their centre to justify this.)}) (5. cxd5 {We will see this trade last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.}) 5... dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945 and theory has kept expanding. But, we have our modern twist in the main lines and go for the trendy 10...Be7 variation.} ({There are also the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback of the move 5...h6 is that White can choose the type of game they want to get. They can play very solidly with 6.Bxf6 or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This way of playing for Black was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) ({There is also the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. However, I do not think it fits well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation.}) 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. It was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even, as we will regain a pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {Shankland gives this as an extra option in his course. It is the traditional Botvinnik main line, and while it also equalises, it is much more complex. Most people are going to be expecting this as White.}) *

