{We start our journey into the Botvinnik with the uber-sharp mainline.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is a modern twist to the Botvinnik which has become decently popular in recent times. It is less played compared to the main line, which is in our favour.} (10... Nbd7 {is the main line.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 Bb7 14. Bg2 Na6 15. Ne4 Qe7 16. O-O O-O-O 17. h4 c5 18. a4 Rxd4 19. Qe2 b4 20. Rac1 Bd5 {I like the bishop on [d5], as it holds our position together. These lines are extremely complex, as the pawn structure is very asymmetric.} 21. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Rd8 {We need to keep an eye on the bishop on [d5]. Next, our plan is to go ...[Nb8]-[c6]-[d4], after which we are much better. White should try to create something before that.} 23. Rc1 Nb8 $1 24. Qe3 Nc6 {We are willing to give up the [c5]-pawn to get our knight to [d4].} 25. Nxc5 Qf6 {Until here the variation is covered in the theoretical chapter. Both sides have played very precisely so far, and were likely in prep for a long time. I feel this position is much easier to play as Black, as ...[Nd4] is in the air.} 26. b3 $2 {White tries to go after our king along the [f1]-[a6] diagonal, but looks are very deceptive here. Our king is often able to run away successfully in the middle of the board.} (26. Bf1 {White should go after the [c4]-pawn. We are able to defend it with our knight, but that distracts it from the [d4]-square.} Ne5 27. Be2 Qf5 {We create a cunning threat of ...[c3] followed by ...[b3]-[b2].} 28. Qf4 $1 Qxf4 29. gxf4 Nf3+ 30. Bxf3 Bxf3 {The game is likely to end in perpetual check here.} 31. Rxc4 Rd1+ 32. Kh2 Bd5) 26... c3 27. Qe2 Qd4 {The queen is centralised and all our pieces are perfectly placed. The position is already lost for White.} 28. Qb5 Kc7 29. Na6+ Kd6 30. Bxd5 exd5 (30... Qxd5 {was slightly better, as Black keeps the d-file open and can put his king on [e7].} 31. Qe2 Nd4 32. Qe3 Qe5 {-+}) 31. a5 (31. h5 {This White's the best attempt, but is still very hard to play for White.} Qb6 {We would like to trade the queens if possible.} 32. Qe2 d4 {∓ with a huge advantage still.}) 31... Re8 32. Qb7 Re7 33. Qc8 Qd2 34. Nb8 Qxc1+ 35. Kg2 Nxb8 36. Qxb8+ Kc5 37. Qc8+ Kd4 {A very nice final position with the king in the middle of the board!} 0-1

