{As is tradition, we will see one of my games in the Botvinnik. It is also going to be the final game of mine that we will see in this course.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 {This was the first and only time I have played this line, and it was a surprise to my opponent. I do not think this move was as well-known back in 2018.} 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 Bb7 14. Bg2 Na6 15. Nxb5 {This is the human reaction, as we tend to want to force matters and clarify the position. I was expecting this.} cxb5 {In the theory chapter I recommend castling long instead.} 16. Bxb7 Nb4 17. O-O Rd8 {We are winning the [d4]-pawn and the knight is getting to [d3].} 18. a4 $1 {White wants to break our pawn structure on the queenside.} (18. Qf3 $6 {is what I was hoping for, as it is tempting to trade the queens.} Qxf3 19. Bxf3 Nc2 20. Rac1 Nxd4 {⩱}) 18... Qf5 $1 {This was also part of my prep. The queen is heading to [h3].} 19. Qf3 (19. Qd2 $5 {is an option, but is extremely unpractical. When faced with such a surprise, you are usually happy to trade queens.} Nc2 20. axb5 Qh3 $1 21. Bc6+ Kf8 22. f4 Nxa1 23. Rxa1 Qf5) 19... Qxf3 20. Bxf3 Nc2 {This was the end of my home preparation. I had assessed this position as equal.} 21. axb5 {White gives up the exchange but gets a couple of pawns in return for it.} (21. Bc6+ Ke7 22. Rad1 {, trying to hold on to the exchange, is not great after} b4 {↑}) 21... Nxa1 22. Rxa1 O-O 23. Rxa7 Rxd4 24. Rc7 (24. Ra4 $1 {This was the move I was expecting, after which White gets a much improved version of the game.} Rd3 25. Bc6 Rb3 26. Rxc4 Rxb2 27. Rd4 {with an equal endgame.}) 24... Rd3 25. Be2 Rd2 26. Bxc4 Rxb2 {Here the position is still equal, but it is less comfortable to play as White since we have some ideas along the 7th rank.} 27. Rd7 Rc8 28. Bd3 (28. Rd4) 28... Kf8 29. h4 $2 {This is the decisive mistake, allowing me to pin the bishop. It is so easy for White to lose the plot of the game.} (29. Kg2 Rc1 30. b6 $1 Rxb6 31. Be2 {⩱ White will manage to get her rook to [d2] next and it is likely a fortress.}) 29... Rc1+ 30. Kg2 Rd1 31. Kf3 (31. h5 Rdd2 {-+}) 31... Ke8 32. Rd4 Ke7 $2 {This is a bit slow, but luckily for me my opponent is not able to punish it.} (32... f5 {-+}) 33. Ke3 $2 (33. h5 $1 Rh1 34. g4 {⇆}) 33... Re1+ 34. Kf3 Rb3 35. Kg2 Rd1 36. Bc4 Rxg3+ 37. fxg3 Rxd4 {Once a pair of rooks is exchanged, the endgame is easily winning for Black.} 38. Be2 f5 39. Bf3 Rb4 40. Bc6 Kf6 41. h5 Rb2+ 42. Kf3 e5 43. Ke3 Rb3+ 44. Kf2 Kg5 45. Be8 e4 46. Bd7 Kxh5 0-1

