{Let us see a game by the current or possibly former, depending on when the WC match happens and when this course is released :- World Champion.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 dxc4 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O b5 8. e4 b4 {This is a comparatively rare move, and it's my recommendation in the course. We want to immediately go after White's centre, particularly the [e4]-pawn.} 9. e5 Nd5 10. Ne4 N7b6 (10... Be7 {is my suggestion in the 5.g3 chapter, and is more flexible.} 11. Re1 a5 12. Bg5 O-O {=}) 11. Re1 a5 {Black feels that his king is pretty safe in the centre, as the position is closed.} 12. Nc5 (12. Bg5 $5 {is a good try here, as Black has not developed the dark-squared bishop yet.} Qc7 13. Nfd2 h6 14. Qh5 {∞ The position is complicated, but should be fine for Black with correct play.}) 12... Bxc5 (12... Be7 {looks easier.}) 13. dxc5 Nd7 14. Nd2 $6 (14. Qd4 $1 Ba6 15. Ng5 {White gets his knight to [e4] and [d6] next.} h6 16. Ne4 O-O 17. f4 Qc7 {Black needs to play on the queenside with ...[Rfb8] and ...[a4] next.}) 14... Ba6 15. Qg4 O-O 16. Nxc4 f5 $1 {A very important move to maintain equality. Moreover, Black is taking over the initiative now, as White cannot create anything on the kingside.} 17. Qd4 (17. exf6 Qxf6 {-+}) 17... Bxc4 $1 {This is a good trade, as the knight can be a huge issue for Black when it lands on [d6].} 18. Qxc4 Rb8 19. Bd2 Qe7 20. Rac1 Rb5 21. Qd4 Rc8 $1 {Black defends the pawn on [c6] in order to take on [c5] next. This is the mark of a strong player. Prophylactic thinking is a big part of the game.} (21... Rxc5 22. Rxc5 Qxc5 23. Qxc5 Nxc5 24. Rc1 {⩲}) 22. Be3 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 Rxc5 24. Rxc5 Qxc5 25. Qd2 {White has to preserve the queens and looks for some counterplay. The Black king is a bit more exposed.} Qe7 26. Qd4 c5 27. Qc4 Rc7 28. f4 $6 {This is a very tempting move to defend the [e5]-pawn and to get the rook to the d-file. However, it creates a hook for Black to start play on the kingside. It exposes the king on [g1].} Nf8 29. Rd1 g5 $1 {Black immediately takes his chance to open up the kingside in his favour.} 30. g4 $1 {This is the best move for White too, as he has to create some counterplay. Otherwise, we would have got one-sided play on the kingside with ...[gxf4] followed by ...[Qh4].} Kg7 (30... gxf4 {was maybe better.} 31. gxf5 Qg5 32. fxe6 Kg7 {∓}) 31. gxf5 exf5 32. Rd6 $1 {This was the only move to fight back but White has to continue playing precisely to survive.} Ng6 33. Rf6 $2 Nxf4 (33... gxf4 {was a bit better:} 34. Rxf5 Rd7 {-+ , with the rook penetrating along the d-file with devastating effect.}) 34. Rxf5 Rd7 35. Bf3 h6 36. h4 Rd4 37. Qc2 gxh4 38. Qh2 Ne6 39. Qg2+ Ng5 40. Bh5 Rd3 $2 (40... Qd7 {-+ This is a difficult move to find, as you are giving up control over the knight on [g5]. Black has to stop the queen from getting to [c6], and it also comes with a tempo.}) 41. Qc6 Rg3+ 42. Kf1 Qd8 43. Qf6+ Qxf6 44. exf6+ Kg8 45. Rxc5 Nh7 46. Rc8+ Nf8 47. Rc4 h3 48. Rh4 Nh7 49. f7+ $2 (49. Bg4 Ng5 50. Be2 {It is still a very tough position to play for White.} Kh7 {↑}) 49... Kg7 50. Kf2 Rg2+ 51. Kf1 Rxb2 52. Rxh3 Rxa2 53. Rg3+ Ng5 54. Rd3 Rh2 {It was a good fighting game from both sides, but Black was in control for most of the game. I really like Black's play on the kingside, with moves like ...[f5] and ...[g5] at the right moment.} 0-1

