1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. g3 {[%csl Rg3,Rg5] I don't think mixing [Bg5] and [g3] is a great idea. It is pretty slow, allowing us to advance on the queenside and consolidate our extra pawn. Also, if we go ...[h6] at some point, White will have to take on [f6] and give up the bishop. [Bh4] is no longer an option as White does not have the [g3]-square available after ...[g5].} b5 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 {Our extra pawn on the queenside is now secure. White still has compensation due to their centre, but nothing more.} 9. a4 a6 10. Ne5 Qc8 {[%cal Gd7e5] We keep everything under control. We can take on [e5] next, if given the chance. Our kingside is not a huge concern for now. White needs a lot of time to create something meaningful.} 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. e4 b4 {We start our play on the queenside. The [c3]-knight is kicked back and it lacks a good square to go to.} 13. Nb1 a5 14. Nd2 {This has been played in three games, but is an inaccuracy.} (14. Re1 {is better, but we have a nice sequence of moves:} c5 15. d5 c3 $1 16. bxc3 c4 {and we get very strong pawns on the queenside. It is much easier to play as Black here.}) 14... c3 $15 {[%cal Gb7a6,Gf8b4,Ge6e5] We will play ...[Ba6] next, followed by ...[Bb4]. We can even break into the centre with the move ...[e5] at the right moment. We will just be one move away from castling kingside anytime.} *

