1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e3 {This is even worse for White, as they do not get anything in return for the missing pawn. At least in the previous variation, White got good control over the centre.} b5 7. a4 {White tries to provoke us into playing ...[b4], which would weaken our [c4]-pawn.} Bb4 8. Be2 {White wants to castle first and then try to fight for the centre.} Nbd7 9. O-O Qb6 {[%csl Gb4,Gb5] We defend the pawn on [b5] with the queen, and now we do not need to give up our bishop on [c3].} 10. Qc2 O-O 11. e4 a6 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7] We will continue with ...[Bb7] and finish our development. White's best attempt is to retreat with the bishop and admit their error. White can then try to play [e5] and [Ng5] to create something on the kingside. If White plays very accurately they might end up equalising, but they are at least slightly worse for now.} *

