1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2e4] White stops us from playing ...[b5] to defend the pawn on [c4]. They give up the juicy [b4]-square, but if White does manage to win the pawn on [c4] easily, they would be better. They will play [e4] next, building up the centre.} b5 $1 {We give back the pawn on [b5] in return for activity.} 7. axb5 {Taking the pawn is the critical try.} cxb5 8. Nxb5 Qb6 {We force the knight back. White has two options to retreat here.} 9. Nc3 {The knight heads back to keep the centre under control.} Qxb2 10. Bd2 {White defends the knight, threatening to play [Rb1] followed by [Nb5] next.} Nd5 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gd5c3] We stop the move [Rb1] by attacking the knight on [c3].} 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Rb1 Qa2 {It is better to keep the queen on [a2] for now, keeping contact with the rook on [b1].} 13. e4 $1 {White has to try something like this, making use of their big lead in development.} Bd6 {We prepare to castle next, getting the king to safety.} 14. Be2 ({If White takes the pawn with} 14. exd5 {, we can go 14…O-O and get the bishop out to [f5] next. White is lagging behind in development.}) 14... O-O 15. O-O dxe4 $10 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3g5,Gc8f5]} (15... dxe4 {We win the central pawn and White has compensation in the form of piece activity, but this only leads to equality at best.} 16. Ng5 {is met with} Bf5 {, holding on to the pawn.}) *

