1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2e4] White stops us from playing ...[b5] to defend the pawn on [c4]. They give up the juicy [b4]-square, but if White does manage to win the pawn on [c4] easily, they would be better. They will play [e4] next, building up the centre.} b5 $1 {We give back the pawn on [b5] in return for activity.} 7. axb5 {Taking the pawn is the critical try.} cxb5 8. Nxb5 Qb6 {We force the knight back. White has two options to retreat here.} 9. Na3 {This is the more critical move, targeting the pawn on [c4]. We have a few different options.} Bxa3 $1 {Although it looks risky to give up the dark-squared bishop, we need to play concretely here and it helps us to gain a couple of moves to develop our pieces.} ({There were a few other options such as} 9... Ba6 {and 9...Ne4 which should also equalise with best play. However, our text continuation is the easiest and most precise.}) 10. Qa4+ {This is necessary to stop us from castling kingside and to defend the [b2]-pawn.} Nc6 11. Qxa3 Ne4 $1 {As I've mentioned already, we need to play dynamically here. Positionally White is doing very well, but we have active knights which we need to use.} 12. Bf4 {White tries to preserve the bishop.} a5 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gb6b4] This is a very useful move on the queenside, preparing the move ...[Ba6] to defend the pawn on [c4]. It also helps us play ...[Qb4]+ and recapture with the a-pawn.} 13. Rc1 (13. e3 {is met with} Ba6 {.}) 13... Qb4+ $1 {We give up a pawn, but a trade of queens on [b4] would open the a-file for our rook.} 14. Bd2 {White does not want to play into that. Instead, White gives up the dark-squared bishop to eliminate our strong knight on [e4].} Nxd2 15. Nxd2 Nxd4 $10 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gd4b3]} (15... Nxd4 {We will lose the c4-pawn, but I feel we are on the better side of equality with more active pieces.} 16. e3 {will be met with} Nb3 {, exchanging the knights.}) *

