1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2e4] White stops us from playing ...[b5] to defend the pawn on [c4]. They give up the juicy [b4]-square, but if White does manage to win the pawn on [c4] easily, they would be better. They will play [e4] next, building up the centre.} b5 $1 {We give back the pawn on [b5] in return for activity.} 7. axb5 {Taking the pawn is the critical try.} cxb5 8. Nxb5 Qb6 {We force the knight back. White has two options to retreat here.} 9. Na3 {This is the more critical move, targeting the pawn on [c4]. We have a few different options.} Bxa3 $1 {Although it looks risky to give up the dark-squared bishop, we need to play concretely here and it helps us to gain a couple of moves to develop our pieces.} ({There were a few other options such as} 9... Ba6 {and 9...Ne4 which should also equalise with best play. However, our text continuation is the easiest and most precise.}) 10. Qa4+ {This is necessary to stop us from castling kingside and to defend the [b2]-pawn.} Nc6 11. Qxa3 Ne4 $1 {As I've mentioned already, we need to play dynamically here. Positionally White is doing very well, but we have active knights which we need to use.} 12. e3 {White is attacking the pawn on [c4]. They only need two more moves to get their king to safety.} f6 $1 {We want to get our knight to [b4], and the bishop on [g5] was quite annoying, creating a potential threat of mate on [e7].} 13. Bf4 Nb4 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb4c2]} 14. Rc1 Ba6 {We keep an eye on the [c4]-pawn. We are not going to let White take it without a fight.} 15. Qa4+ {This was played by Martirosyan against Erigaisi Arjun in classical chess. It helps us bring our [h8] rook into the game faster.} Ke7 $1 {This is the natural move, connecting the rooks. The one drawback is that a capture on [b4] would come with a check but we are not too bothered about that.} 16. Bc7 Qb7 $5 {This is an improvement over the previous game which continued with the capture on [c7]. I want to maintain our knight on [b4] for the time being.} 17. Ba5 Rab8 {[%cal Gh8c8,Gb4d3] Once again the knight is not going anywhere. We want to bring our other rook to [c8] and then jump in with the knight to [d3].} 18. Ra1 Rhc8 $1 {We give up a whole piece just to maintain control over the [c4] pawn. Our lead in development is the key here. Now, we are ready to go ...[Nd3] next.} 19. Bxb4+ Qxb4+ 20. Qxb4+ Rxb4 21. Rxa6 Rxb2 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb2f2] I used to underestimate the importance of the 7th rank. It can be extremely dangerous, especially when combined with a passed pawn. The ultimate goal of an open file is to get the rook to the 7th rank.We have multiple threats here. We can take on [f2] and just keep pushing the c-pawn. The plan of ...[Rb1] followed by ...[Rcb8] is another idea.} *

