1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2e4] White stops us from playing ...[b5] to defend the pawn on [c4]. They give up the juicy [b4]-square, but if White does manage to win the pawn on [c4] easily, they would be better. They will play [e4] next, building up the centre.} b5 $1 {We give back the pawn on [b5] in return for activity.} 7. axb5 {Taking the pawn is the critical try.} cxb5 8. Nxb5 Qb6 {We force the knight back. White has two options to retreat here.} 9. Na3 {This is the more critical move, targeting the pawn on [c4]. We have a few different options.} Bxa3 $1 {Although it looks risky to give up the dark-squared bishop, we need to play concretely here and it helps us to gain a couple of moves to develop our pieces.} ({There were a few other options such as} 9... Ba6 {and 9...Ne4 which should also equalise with best play. However, our text continuation is the easiest and most precise.}) 10. Qa4+ {This is necessary to stop us from castling kingside and to defend the [b2]-pawn.} Nc6 11. Qxa3 Ne4 $1 {As I've mentioned already, we need to play dynamically here. Positionally White is doing very well, but we have active knights which we need to use.} 12. e3 {White is attacking the pawn on [c4]. They only need two more moves to get their king to safety.} f6 $1 {We want to get our knight to [b4], and the bishop on [g5] was quite annoying, creating a potential threat of mate on [e7].} 13. Bf4 Nb4 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gb4c2]} 14. Rc1 Ba6 {We keep an eye on the [c4]-pawn. We are not going to let White take it without a fight.} 15. Bc7 {White gives up the bishop to win the knight and keep control over [f8], keeping us from castling kingside.} Qxc7 (15... Qb7 {is not possible here, as after} 16. Ba5 {± both the knight and the c-pawn are hanging.}) 16. Qxb4 Rb8 {We would be doing very well if we manage to castle. White should try to prevent it.} 17. Qa4+ Bb5 18. Qa3 Qe7 {We either want to trade queens or castle kingside.} 19. Nd2 {White trades our active knight and improves their king. We are almost guaranteed to reach an endgame, and the king is an important piece.} (19. Qa5 {is met with} Qd8 {.}) 19... Nxd2 20. Kxd2 Kf7 $10 {[%cal Ge7b7] I don't want to trade on [a3], improving White's pawn structure. We connect the rooks and will keep the queens on the board if possible with the move ...[Qb7] next. It is likely to lead to an equal rook endgame.} *

