1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e4 {This is the critical move, gaining space in the centre and creating a threat of both taking the [c4]-pawn as well as advancing [e5].} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4], which is our priority. This is a very risky strategy as our entire kingside will fall, but we are relying on the strength of our queenside pawns. Evaluating the resulting positions is often challenging because there are many imbalances. Our queenside pawns can compensate for a missing pawn or exchange in the endgames.} 7. a4 {This is a lame attempt to break our structure on the queenside.} Qb6 {We keep the [b5]-pawn under control. The [f8]-bishop will likely head to [b4] soon, and the lines resemble some of the variations we have seen in this chapter already.} 8. Bxf6 {White doubles our pawns before we get the chance to play ...[Nbd7] to defend the knight on [f6]. However, this is not a great deal for White, since they are nowhere close to creating their own play.} gxf6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O a6 {We defend the pawn on [b5], as White was threatening to advance with [d5] in the centre.} 11. d5 {White does it anyway, but it is not so dangerous now.} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] We might just end up castling queenside here. This is one of the big advantages of our queenside structure. Our king is not super safe on the queenside, but it still takes a lot of time for White to create an attack. We usually have a lot of pieces to keep our king safe.} 12. Nd4 Ne5 $17 {[%cal Gd5c6,Ge5c6,Ge8c8]} (12... Ne5 {We want to recapture on c6 with the knight. Also, we now meet} 13. dxe6 {with the strong} O-O-O {, which just wins the piece on [d4]. Black is much better.}) *

