1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e4 {This is the critical move, gaining space in the centre and creating a threat of both taking the [c4]-pawn as well as advancing [e5].} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4], which is our priority. This is a very risky strategy as our entire kingside will fall, but we are relying on the strength of our queenside pawns. Evaluating the resulting positions is often challenging because there are many imbalances. Our queenside pawns can compensate for a missing pawn or exchange in the endgames.} 7. e5 {This looks very strong at first sight, but we do not lose a piece. That being said, we are going to give up a big chunk of our kingside.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. exf6 $6 {This is foolish, saying no to a free pawn. It has been played in a decent amount of games, though.} gxh4 10. Ne5 Qxf6 {White has given up two pawns and the bishop pair as well.} 11. g3 {This has been played by the very creative Georgian GM Baadur Jobava in classical chess, but it is one of his more unsound lines.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is the simplest answer. Jobava's opponent went for something else, and the Georgian grandmaster went on to win that game. We are looking to continue with ...[c5] and open up the long diagonal.} 12. Bg2 h3 $1 {One of the benefits of having extra pawns: we can always just give them back to dis-coordinate our opponent's pieces.} 13. Bxh3 Nd7 $1 {Our king is pretty safe in the middle of the board!} 14. Nxd7 Kxd7 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ga8d8,Gd7c8] We will castle artificially with ...[Rd8] followed by ...[Kc8]. Our king is safe and we are up a clean pawn with the bishop pair.} *

