eing said, we are going to give up a big chunk of our kingside.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. exf6 $6 {This is foolish, saying no to a free pawn. It has been played in a decent amount of games, though.} gxh4 10. Ne5 Qxf6 {White has given up two pawns and the bishop pair as well.} 11. a4 {With the queen on the kingside, White is going after our [b5]-pawn.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] This has never been played before! We just ignore our precious queenside and create a route for our king to the kingside.} 12. axb5 cxb5 13. Nxb5 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge7b4]} (13... Nd7 {Would you like to grab our rook too? White has to be very careful about the check on b4. For instance} 14. Nc7+ $6 Kf8 15. Nxa8 $2 Bb4+ 16. Ke2 Nxe5 {and White is toast.}) 14. Nxc4 O-O {We get our king to safety and are, in fact, ahead in development. It is usually the opposite in these lines.} 15. Be2 Bb7 {[%cal Gb7h1,Gh4h3] I love this long diagonal for the bishop. White's king is never going to be as safe on the kingside as ours, and we are missing the g-pawn!} 16. O-O h3 $36 {We force White to create some weaknesses on the light squares. We can try to get our queen to [d5] once we soften up the long diagonal.} *

