1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e4 {This is the critical move, gaining space in the centre and creating a threat of both taking the [c4]-pawn as well as advancing [e5].} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4], which is our priority. This is a very risky strategy as our entire kingside will fall, but we are relying on the strength of our queenside pawns. Evaluating the resulting positions is often challenging because there are many imbalances. Our queenside pawns can compensate for a missing pawn or exchange in the endgames.} 7. e5 {This looks very strong at first sight, but we do not lose a piece. That being said, we are going to give up a big chunk of our kingside.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. exf6 $6 {This is foolish, saying no to a free pawn. It has been played in a decent amount of games, though.} gxh4 10. Ne5 Qxf6 {White has given up two pawns and the bishop pair as well.} 11. a4 {With the queen on the kingside, White is going after our [b5]-pawn.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] This has never been played before! We just ignore our precious queenside and create a route for our king to the kingside.} 12. axb5 cxb5 13. Ng4 {The best move according to computer. It is a weird move to play, but White is trying to chase our queen away from the f-file so they can play [Qf3] and target our rook on [a8].} Qf4 14. g3 {White wins a tempo to get their bishop to [g2].} Qc7 {[%cal Gc8b7] We are forced to retreat, but we keep control over the [b7]-square.} 15. Bg2 Bb7 16. d5 {This is forced, trying to go after our king in the centre.} Nd7 {[%cal Gc7b6,Ge8c8] We can play ...[Qb6] on the next move and just castle queenside. White's king is not all that safe either on the kingside.} 17. Nxb5 {White wins the [b5]-pawn at the cost of a tempo, but at least weakens our queenside.} Qb6 18. Nc3 h5 $36 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd7e5] We will get our knight to [e5] next. We can still castle queenside and we are going to try to create play on the kingside quickly.} *

