1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e4 {This is the critical move, gaining space in the centre and creating a threat of both taking the [c4]-pawn as well as advancing [e5].} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4], which is our priority. This is a very risky strategy as our entire kingside will fall, but we are relying on the strength of our queenside pawns. Evaluating the resulting positions is often challenging because there are many imbalances. Our queenside pawns can compensate for a missing pawn or exchange in the endgames.} 7. e5 {This looks very strong at first sight, but we do not lose a piece. That being said, we are going to give up a big chunk of our kingside.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 {White voluntarily misplaces the bishop on [g3] and lets us keep our kingside intact. We should be very happy with our extra pawn.} Nd5 {We get our knight to the middle of the board and create a threat of either ...[Qa5] or ...[Bb4], pinning the knight on [c3].} 10. Be2 $2 {This is a serious mistake as White either loses the crucial b-pawn or is forced to get into an unpleasant pin with their queen.} Bb4 {[%cal Ra5e1]} 11. Rc1 Qa5 12. Qd2 {This is the only way to keep the pawn alive without giving up [a2]. However, this is only a temporary relief for White as we are going to bring in more attackers.} Nd7 13. O-O N7b6 {[%cal Gb6a4] We are ready to play either ...[Na4] next or take on [c3] with the knight to get the other one to [d5].} 14. Bd1 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Ba3 $19 {[%cal Gb5b4]} (15... Ba3 {We will play ...b4 next with a winning advantage, while} 16. Rb1 {is answered by} Nd5 {and the [c3]-pawn falls.}) *

