1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e4 {This is the critical move, gaining space in the centre and creating a threat of both taking the [c4]-pawn as well as advancing [e5].} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4], which is our priority. This is a very risky strategy as our entire kingside will fall, but we are relying on the strength of our queenside pawns. Evaluating the resulting positions is often challenging because there are many imbalances. Our queenside pawns can compensate for a missing pawn or exchange in the endgames.} 7. e5 {This looks very strong at first sight, but we do not lose a piece. That being said, we are going to give up a big chunk of our kingside.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 {White voluntarily misplaces the bishop on [g3] and lets us keep our kingside intact. We should be very happy with our extra pawn.} Nd5 {We get our knight to the middle of the board and create a threat of either ...[Qa5] or ...[Bb4], pinning the knight on [c3].} 10. h4 {At least here White is trying to do something active on the kingside. They would like to force the move ...[g4] and then answer [Nd2], gaining a tempo by attacking the pawn on [g4].} Qa5 {The queen is best placed here, keeping an eye on White's queenside.} 11. Rc1 g4 {We do play ...[g4], because we want to keep the h-file closed for the rook on [h1].} 12. Nd2 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5] Of course, our intention was never to defend the pawn on [g4]. We are looking to play ...[c5] next and create play on the queenside and the centre.} 13. Nce4 $1 {White prevents the move ...[c5] for now. The knight is better on [d2] compared to [c3], as then we could exchange on [c3] anytime.} (13. Qxg4 {can be met with} Nd7 {∓ and we will play ...[c5] next with a big edge.}) 13... Qb6 $5 {[%csl Rd4] We go after White's central pawn. The next moves are not easy to find as White, and they can easily go wrong.} 14. Be2 {This is the best option to get the king to safety. There was a possible sacrifice on [c4] with the bishop, but it is too impractical and gives us easy play.} Qxd4 15. O-O Nd7 16. Qc2 Nxe5 {We are extremely greedy, grabbing all the pawns. Practically to me it looks like we are completely winning with the knight getting to [d3], but White has some counterplay.} 17. b3 $1 {The only move to maintain equality. White is trying to open up the queenside.} c3 18. Rfd1 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] Yet another difficult move to find.} f5 19. Nf6+ $1 {White gives up the piece to remove the beautiful knight on [d5].} Nxf6 20. Nc4 Qe4 $10 {We force the queens off the board and play a risk-free position where White has to prove compensation in a practical game.} *

