1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {This is the most dangerous and principled option for White, bringing the bishop out before the move [e3]. There are three different systems conventionally here plus a new twist in one of the three lines which is what we go for. It is not easy to prepare all of them for White, as all three lead to different types of positions with a huge amount of theory. So the move 5.Bg5 is not very common at the lower levels assuming they know the theory in the first place :-.} dxc4 {We go for the principled Botvinnik variation, which is known to be one of the sharpest lines in opening theory. It was played by Botvinnik all the way back in 1945, and theory has kept expanding. However, we have our modern twist in the main lines and we'll go for the trendy 10...[Be7] variation. In this chapter, we will focus on some of the early sidelines.} ({There is the solid but passive Cambridge Springs variation with} 5... Nbd7 {, which was the main recommendation of Sam Shankland 4 years ago. I do not think it fits in well with the spirit of the Semi-Slav variation, however.}) ({Then there are the Moscow and Anti-Moscow variations which start after} 5... h6 {. The principal drawback here is that White chooses the type of game they want to get. White can play very solidly with} 6. Bxf6 {or go for the crazy complications after 6.Bh4 . This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course.}) 6. e4 {This is the critical move, gaining space in the centre and creating a threat of both taking the [c4]-pawn as well as advancing [e5].} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4], which is our priority. This is a very risky strategy as our entire kingside will fall, but we are relying on the strength of our queenside pawns. Evaluating the resulting positions is often challenging because there are many imbalances. Our queenside pawns can compensate for a missing pawn or exchange in the endgames.} 7. e5 {This looks very strong at first sight, but we do not lose a piece. That being said, we are going to give up a big chunk of our kingside.} h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 {White voluntarily misplaces the bishop on [g3] and lets us keep our kingside intact. We should be very happy with our extra pawn.} Nd5 {We get our knight to the middle of the board and create a threat of either ...[Qa5] or ...[Bb4], pinning the knight on [c3].} 10. Nd2 {The knight blocks the diagonal and prepares to go to [e4] in the future.} Bb7 11. Be2 (11. h4 {can just be met with} Nd7 {⩱ and next we will take on [g5] with the queen.}) 11... Nd7 12. O-O Qb6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] We go after the [d4]-pawn. We also preparing the move ...[c5] next. White has to be very precise not to be worse.} 13. Nde4 {This is a natural move, but it is an inaccuracy.} c5 $1 {We are opening up the position for our bishop on [b7]. We will likely castle queenside and start playing on the kingside. The bishop on [g3] is a big issue for White.} 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Nc3 {This is by far the best move, getting rid of our bishop at the cost of another pawn. This is why these lines are very difficult to play for White. They have to play very dynamically, and in many cases it is not very practical.} cxd4 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bh5 Be7 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8] We will castle next on the kingside. We are up two pawns and should be a favourite to convert this position into a win.} *

