1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bf4 {This was tried by Mamedyarov in a rapid game, and it can be an unpleasant surprise.} Bxd4 {Take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger!} 13. Qf3 {White is planning to castle queenside next.} e5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb8d7,Gf4d2] If White retreats with the bishop, we will play ...[Be6] followed by ...[Nd7], finishing our development.} 14. O-O-O exf4 15. Qe4+ Kf8 16. Rxd4 Qf6 $10 {I like this trade as our king is safer now, and White has to take on [f4] at some point, going into an endgame. White's other bishop is not that effective here due to our pawn on [c4].} *

