1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Be3 {This is a more serious option, defending the pawn on [d4]. White wants to get the queen to [f3] next and castle queenside.} Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c5] This is less common, but it makes a lot of sense here as it is aimed against the [Qf3] plan. We want to meet this queen move with ...[Nb4], both defending the [c6]-pawn and threatening a check on [c2].} 13. g3 {White is looking to exploit the long diagonal, but this is a bit slow.} c5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1] We immediately challenge White's centre. Now the big threat is ...[Bb7], and so White has to take control over the diagonal immediately. But then White is losing the pawn on [d4].} 14. Bg2 cxd4 $1 {Of course we do not bother moving the rook on [a8]. White's dark-squared bishop is a more important minor piece. Now White has two ways to win the exchange.} 15. Bxa8 dxe3 16. fxe3 {This opens up the f-file, but the pawn on [e3] is a definite weakness.} Nc5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd3] The knight is heading to the [d3]-square. You should not underestimate our [c4]-pawn. If we manage to win [b2] it will be a big headache for White.} 17. O-O Qxd1 18. Raxd1 Ke7 {This is a typical position for this variation. We do not have a single pawn for the exchange, but our bishop pair and pawn structure easily compensate for it. We will continue with ...[Bd7] followed by play on the queenside.} 19. Bg2 Bd7 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gc5d3] It may not look so at first sight but White should be careful here, since if we manage to play ...[Nd3] next they are in some trouble.} *

