1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Be3 {This is a more serious option, defending the pawn on [d4]. White wants to get the queen to [f3] next and castle queenside.} Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c5] This is less common, but it makes a lot of sense here as it is aimed against the [Qf3] plan. We want to meet this queen move with ...[Nb4], both defending the [c6]-pawn and threatening a check on [c2].} 13. g3 {White is looking to exploit the long diagonal, but this is a bit slow.} c5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1] We immediately challenge White's centre. Now the big threat is ...[Bb7], and so White has to take control over the diagonal immediately. But then White is losing the pawn on [d4].} 14. Bg2 cxd4 $1 {Of course we do not bother moving the rook on [a8]. White's dark-squared bishop is a more important minor piece. Now White has two ways to win the exchange.} 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 16. Bxa8 {White wisely does not take on [d4] but encourages us to trade on [d1].} Qxd1+ {This trade is not a bad idea actually, because the endgames are generally very promising for us with our bishops and the queenside pawn majority.} 17. Rxd1 Bd7 {This is very similar to the previous variation.} 18. O-O Nc5 19. Rd2 {The rook is needed here to defend the [b2]-pawn.} Ke7 20. Bf3 b4 $1 {We need to start our play on the queenside.} 21. Ne4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 c3 23. bxc3 Bxc3 {I was initially surprised that the engines are so happy with Black here, but then I realised that it is very hard for White to preserve the extra exchange.} 24. Rdd1 Ba4 25. Rb1 {This is very passive, but it's the only way I could see for White to maintain their extra material. Black will start taking over if White remains careless.} f5 26. Bf3 a5 $36 {[%cal Gh8d8,Gd8d2] We are going to play ...[Rd8]-[d2] and White has to suffer to defend.} *

