1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Be3 {This is a more serious option, defending the pawn on [d4]. White wants to get the queen to [f3] next and castle queenside.} Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c5] This is less common, but it makes a lot of sense here as it is aimed against the [Qf3] plan. We want to meet this queen move with ...[Nb4], both defending the [c6]-pawn and threatening a check on [c2].} 13. Be2 {White is getting ready to castle, but is the king really safe on the kingside? Moreover, this does lose valuable time.} Nb4 {[%cal Gf6d4,Rb4c2] We are threatening to win the pawn on [d4].} 14. a3 (14. O-O {is met with} e5 {and we force the queens off.}) 14... Nd5 15. Bf3 {White needs to deal with the threat of ...[Nxe3].} Bb7 16. Nxd5 {This is probably best, as giving up the dark-squared bishop is pretty dangerous for White - especially when White is castling kingside. Now, how do we recapture?} exd5 $1 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gb7c8,Gc8e6,Gc6c5] We want to bring our light-squared bishop to [e6], which is the perfect square. Our king will be safe in the centre. In the long run, our queenside pawns are looking very promising. We can play ...[c5] at some point and start advancing our pawns in the centre.} 17. O-O Bc8 18. Re1 Be6 $10 {We reach a promising middlegame with chances for both sides. Ideally, we would like to get the pawn to [a4] and close the queenside. We can then put our king on [d7] and start attacking on the kingside.} (18... Be6 {White should try to act quickly with} 19. b3 {after which we go} Kf8 {and [Kg7] next move.}) *

