1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qd2 {White decides to castle queenside early.} Na6 {The knight keeps an eye on the [c5]-square and can head to [b4] in the future. I do not want to block the d-file with the knight, as we will likely castle queenside soon.} 14. O-O-O Bb7 15. Ne4 Qe7 16. Be2 {This has been recommended in the course - Plichta’s 1. [d4] on Chessable. White develops the bishop first, keeping other options open.} O-O-O {We are ready to go for the move ...[c5] next and activate our bishop.} (16... c5 {is also an option and we equalise objectively after} 17. Qf4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Rc8 {but I feel it is more complex compared to our main line.}) 17. Qg5 {White decides that it is the right moment to trade the queens. The knight get to the [g5] square which is an improvement.} (17. Qe3 {is met with} Nb4 18. Nc5 Nxa2+ 19. Kb1 Nb4 {and it will not be easy for White to prove his compensation.}) 17... Qxg5+ 18. Nxg5 Rd7 19. a4 {The key point is to stop the move ...[c5] once again. We cannot move our b-pawn as we need to maintain the pawn on [c4].} (19. h4 {allows us to equalise easily with} c5) 19... Nb4 20. h4 Kc7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gc6c5,Gd7e7,Gf7f6] We improve the position of the king. We have two plans now - to go ...[a6] and ...[c5] on the queenside or to kick the knight away with ...[Re7] and ...[f6].} 21. h5 a6 22. h6 c5 23. dxc5 Bd5 {This is a key move to remember. In addition to the bishop being very active here, it also helps us go for the move ...[f6] next.} 24. Nf3 f6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5,Gd7h7] We are hinting at shifting our rook on [d7] over to the kingside. We can also win the [c5] pawn easily with ...[Kc6]-[c5].} *

