1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. a4 {This makes sense, opening the a-file in anticipation of us castling long.} O-O-O {We oblige. Our king remains reasonably safe on the queenside and we are looking to win the battle for the centre.} 16. axb5 cxb5 17. Bxb7+ Kxb7 18. Nxb5 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6c6] We are targeting the [d4]-pawn but we also threaten to play ...[Qc6], with a double attack on White's pieces which would win on the spot.} 19. O-O {White's king seems safe for now, but the h-file is open and we have a few tricks in the bag.} Qc6 $1 {We are threatening the knight on [b5] and also a sacrifice on [h2] to checkmate the white king.} 20. Qa4 exd4 {[%cal Gh8h2,Gd8h8] There is no rush yet. We are ready to take on [h2] now.} ({The immediate} 20... Rxh2 {could have ran into} 21. d5 $1 {This is not terrible for Black after} Qh6 {, but it leads to unnecessary complications.}) 21. Rfe1 Rxh2 22. Nd6+ $1 {This is the only move which saves White.} Rxd6 23. Qxc6+ Rxc6 24. Kxh2 Kb6 {[%csl Gb6,Gc4,Gd4] We reach another interesting endgame with a lot of imbalance. Our pawns and active king compensate for the missing exchange.} *

