1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. a4 {This makes sense, opening the a-file in anticipation of us castling long.} O-O-O {We oblige. Our king remains reasonably safe on the queenside and we are looking to win the battle for the centre.} 16. axb5 cxb5 17. Bxb7+ Kxb7 18. Nxb5 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6c6] We are targeting the [d4]-pawn but we also threaten to play ...[Qc6], with a double attack on White's pieces which would win on the spot.} 19. d5 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb4d3] We are threatening to give a check on [d3] now.} 20. Rxa7+ Kb6 21. Qa4 {Now it looks like our end is near, but we have several checks to save the day.} Nd3+ 22. Kd2 Qxf2+ 23. Kc3 Qxb2+ {White's king is forced to take a walk across the board.} 24. Kxc4 Rc8+ 25. Kxd3 e4+ {I love this! :- How often can you see such lines coming from an opening variation? All of this is forced too.} 26. Ke3 Rc3+ 27. Nxc3 Qxc3+ 28. Kxe4 f5+ 29. Kf4 Qd2+ 30. Ke5 {The king is trying to run towards our rook, but this will not save White from perpetual check.} Qe3+ 31. Kd6 Rh6+ 32. Kd7 Rh7+ {And White has nothing better than going back to [d6]. This is one of the craziest lines I have seen in my opening preparation. Essentially, all we need to remember is that after 22...Qxf2 we have at least a draw. The lines are not too hard to figure out over the board.} *

