1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. Nxb5 {White wins the pawn on [b5] but will likely be forced back, losing a tempo.} O-O-O 16. Nxa7+ {It is tempting for White to win another pawn, but the knight is almost trapped on [a7].} Kb8 {It looks like we let the knight escape, but things are not so easy for White.} 17. Nxc6+ Bxc6 18. Bxc6 Nb4 $1 {We have a huge threat of ...[Nd3]+, and the [d4]-pawn is also hanging.} 19. Qf3 {White has to give up the exchange.} Nc2+ 20. Kd2 Qxf3 21. Bxf3 Nxd4 $1 {We attack the bishop on [f3] and keep the threat of ...[Nb3]+ alive.} ({After} 21... Nxa1 22. Kc3 $1 {White keeps the [d4]-pawn defended and will win the knight on [a1] next. We can get a pawn back, but White will have a few pawns for the rook which is good enough compensation.}) 22. Be2 c3+ {We force White to weaken their pawn structure before we go after their kingside.} 23. bxc3 Nb3+ $10 {The endgame is roughly balanced as White will get enough compensation for the exchange.} *

