1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 {This is by far the main move, winning both of Black's kingside pawns and maintaining the pin along the diagonal. This way White wins back the pawn they gave up on [c4].} hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 $1 {This is the modern Botvinnik variation. This line was traditionally supposed to be great for White because of our exposed king. But we know how many lines which seem dangerous have been proven to be fine by the all-knowing computer. We have enough play left with our queenside pawns. The benefit over the mainline is that the material is already even as we regain the pawn on [f6] on the next move.} (10... Nbd7 {is the old mainline, recommended by Shankland as an alternative. There is a huge amount of theory to be checked here, and it is not as practical of a choice in my opinion.}) 11. exf6 Bxf6 {Now White has to make a choice. The natural reaction for me would be to trade the bishops and try to play along the dark squares. But White can try keeping the bishops on the board too.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. g3 {This is the most popular move in the position and the most critical move, as White gets their bishop to the long diagonal before we do.} Na6 {As we have seen before, the knight is usually heading to [b4], leaving the d-file open for our rook.} 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We are ready to castle long next, after which we can go after the [d4]-pawn.} 15. Ne4 {White kicks our queen away from [f6], stopping us from targeting the pawn on [d4].} Qe7 16. O-O O-O-O {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] We are ready to target the pawn on [d4] again, this time with ...[c5].} 17. h4 {This has been played less often than 17.a4, but it is a more critical move. White creates a square on [g5] for the knight in case we play ...[f5].} c5 {[%csl Rd4] We continue with our usual plan of winning the [d4]-pawn.} 18. a4 {White is poking holes in our queenside. They want to weaken the pawn on [c4].} Rxd4 19. Qe2 b4 {We reach a critical juncture. White has a few different ways of going after our king. White's own king is pretty safe on the kingside, and we have to be careful.} 20. Rac1 {This has been played by a couple of strong GMs.} Bd5 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5] I like this construction with the rook on [d4] and the bishop on [d5], holding our position together. Our next job will be to get the knight into the game. However, we need to be very careful to consider what our opponent is threatening on each move.} 21. Rfd1 {This transposes into a top-level game between Kramnik and Aronian in 2013. White trades our active rook on [d4].} Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Rd8 $7 {We need to keep an eye on the bishop on [d5]. Our plan is to play ...[Nb8]-[c6]-[d4] next, after which we are much better. White should try to create something before that.} 23. Rc1 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6d4]} ({We continue with our plan. Aronian went astray with} 23... Qb7 {, which was not needed.}) 24. Qe3 {White is targeting our [c5]-pawn to force our knight to a passive square to defend it.} Nc6 $1 {Our goal is to improve the knight by bringing it to [d4]. We can achieve that even without the [c5]-pawn.} 25. Nxc5 Qf6 $36 {We attack the pawn on [b2] and prepare the move ...[Nd4] at the same time. It's very hard to play this position as White, as we've seen in the model game Melkumyan-Shankland.} *

