w different ways of going after our king. White's own king is pretty safe on the kingside, and we have to be careful.} 20. Rfd1 {White offers the trade of one pair of rooks.} Bd5 {We just need to keep the pawn on [c4] defended. The trade on [d4] would only improve our pawn structure.} 21. Ng5 {White is threatening to win the bishop on [d5]. This is an important position, and we need to play accurately.} Re8 {We defend the queen on [e7]. One general guideline in these positions is that we want to maintain the tension with our pieces in the centre. We are not happy about the exchange on [g2], as then the [c4]-pawn becomes a weakness again. That being said, the most alert people will realise that we are losing a pawn by force here.} 22. Rxd4 {This is the critical move, intending to win one of our pawns.} cxd4 23. Bxd5 exd5 {We are going to replace the [d4]-pawn which we will lose with the pawn on [d5]. The number of pawns does not matter as much as the quality of pawns.} 24. Qg4+ Kb7 25. Qxd4 Nc7 {The knight is the perfect defender for our king, keeping our queenside secure.} 26. Rd1 a5 {Our work on the queenside is now done.} 27. Kg2 f6 28. Nf3 Qf7 {We want to enter with our rook on either [e2] or [e4].} 29. Re1 Rxe1 30. Nxe1 Kc6 $10 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gc7e6,Gc6d6]} (30... Kc6 {We want to play ...Ne6 next, followed by ...Kd6. The queen can then head over to b7. Our pawns will become very dangerous in the centre.} 31. Qa7 {can be met with} Qe7 {followed by ...[Qc5].}) *

