w different ways of going after our king. White's own king is pretty safe on the kingside, and we have to be careful.} 20. Rad1 {Now White tries the same with the other rook. The advantage here for White is that their other rook is ready to come to [e1] at any time.} Qc7 $1 {Since White is unable to get the other rook to [c1], we are confident about placing our queen on [c7]. This is something we've seen in previous chapters. The question of where to place the rooks is quite tricky for White.} (20... Bd5 {is not as good due to} 21. Ng5 Re8 {This is not the best move here but I just want to illustrate the point. After} 22. Rfe1 $1 {White is clearly better. Instead of 21...Re8 you can make a case for Black's position after 21...Qd7 , but I prefer our main line of 20...[Qc7]!.}) 21. Rfe1 {White activates the other rook, preparing to play [Ng5] next.} Rhd8 22. Rc1 {White should not trade the rooks here if they want to pose problems for us. Instead, White is targeting the pawn on [c4].} Qc6 {[%cal Gf7f5] We create our own threat of ...[f5] along the long diagonal.} 23. Qf1 {This is different because White wants to trade the queens on [g2] after [Ng5] on the next move. This is a much better version for White compared to the next line.} b3 $1 {We prepare to bring our knight into the game with ...[Nb4]. Now the exchange of queens is very good for us.} 24. Rxc4 $1 {White gives up a piece to start an attack against our king. On the previous move we could just have answered ...[f5] directly, but now the bishop on [g2] is protected.} Rxc4 (24... f5 $2 {is met with} 25. Nxc5 {+- .}) 25. Qxc4 f5 26. Bf3 $1 {This is White's idea, forcing us to take on [e4] immediately.} fxe4 27. Bxe4 Qd7 28. Bxb7+ Qxb7 $10 {We reach an interesting endgame with a material imbalance. White has two pawns for the piece, but a much safer king and connected passed pawns on the kingside. Objectively it is equal with precise play.} *

