1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. a4 {This goes against the logic of his previous move. White cannot play so slowly after giving up the [c4]-pawn.} c5 $1 {Yes, we lose a tempo as we have moved our c-pawn twice, but White has gone for the move [g3] which only weakens his position here. He should go [e3] and try to win the pawn on [c4].} 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. dxc5 {This has been played the most. White allows us to trade the queens. They are in for a tough time, a pawn down, as the [c5]-pawn will fall soon.} (8. e3 {is the better move, but we are very comfortable after} cxd4 9. exd4 Bb4 {.}) 8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 10. Be3 Be7 {White can win the pawn on [c4] back, but they will likely lose the dark-squared bishop. We get a very comfortable endgame.} 11. Bd2 {White wants to get the knight to [e3], and they also stop us from playing ...[Na5] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} Ne4 12. Ne3 Nxd2 13. Nxd2 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8] We will castle long next. Our king is pretty safe after we have traded off White's dark-squared bishop. On the queenside our king is better in the endgames.} *

