1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Ne5 {White immediately goes after our pawn on [c4]. This has been played by Magnus and a few other strong players. This is the only chance White will get, as we prevent any other [Ne5] ideas on the next move.} Nbd7 {We are not greedy. We make use of White's knight to develop our pieces with tempo.} 7. Nxc4 b5 {This is exactly what we want to get on the queenside. In addition to getting the [b7]-square for the bishop, we can also go ...[b4] in the future to kick the [c3]-knight away.} 8. Nd2 {This is the natural move, retreating with the knight. The knight will head to [e4] in the future.} Bb7 9. Bg2 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is a typical move in these positions in order to prepare the move ...[c5]. We defend the bishop on [b7] and the pawn on [b5].} 10. Nde4 {White has to try something quick, otherwise we take over the centre.} Nxe4 11. Nxe4 c5 12. Be3 {This is the best try to get the dark-squared bishop to the centre.} c4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb7d5] Typically, this is the most ambitious way to deal with the tension. We are giving up control over the centre to gain space on the queenside. We need to make sure that White is not able to overwhelm us in the centre, though. Our next move is going to be ...[Bd5] to blockade White's central [d4]-pawn.} 13. d5 {The only way to continue the fight for an advantage.} Bb4+ $1 {An important check, developing our bishop with a tempo and forcing White to make an uncomfortable choice.} 14. Kf1 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Gd5e6,Gf7e6,Ge8g8,Gf8f1] We are okay with the weakening of the pawn structure in the centre as it opens the f-file for our rook.} *

