1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Ne5 {White immediately goes after our pawn on [c4]. This has been played by Magnus and a few other strong players. This is the only chance White will get, as we prevent any other [Ne5] ideas on the next move.} Nbd7 {We are not greedy. We make use of White's knight to develop our pieces with tempo.} 7. Nxc4 b5 {This is exactly what we want to get on the queenside. In addition to getting the [b7]-square for the bishop, we can also go ...[b4] in the future to kick the [c3]-knight away.} 8. Ne5 {This was played in a playoff game between Magnus and Ding. White has wasted two tempi to win back the pawn on [c4]. Logically, this cannot lead to much for White.} Bb7 {We could take on [e5] directly, but I prefer to include this move as it is anyway necessary.} 9. Bg2 Nxe5 {We go for this trade in the centre as we will likely win the [e5]-pawn soon. White is relying on their extra space and active pieces to compensate for the pawn structure.} 10. dxe5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 {[%cal Gc3b5] This is more critical as the knight remains on [c3] targeting the pawn on [b5]. Also, White can now trade on [d5] with the knight which would lead to a slightly unpleasant position for us.} (11. Nxd1 {is safer but less ambitious. We are perfectly fine after the simple} Nd5 {.}) 11... Ng4 {[%csl Re5,Rf2] We attack both the [e5] and [f2]-pawns and will win at least one of them.} 12. Kc2 {White gets the king off the open d-file and prepares to take on [b5] next. White could not do so earlier as we had the option to castle long with check, defending the bishop on [b7].} b4 {We first kick the knight away before winning the pawn on [e5].} 13. Ne4 Nxe5 14. Rd1 {White will win our dark-squared bishop by giving a check on [d6] next. This gives White enough compensation with the bishop pair.} c5 $1 {We are willing to give up the light-squared bishop, especially if it helps us to develop faster.} 15. Nd6+ Bxd6 16. Bxb7 Rd8 $10 {We will play ...[Ke7] and finish our development. White will probably play [a3] and open the a-file for the rook. The best White can achieve is to win the [a7]-pawn, which is not a big deal for us.} *

