1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. a4 {White spends a tempo to stop us from going ...[b7]-[b5]. This weakens the [b4]-square, though, and is also a slow non-developing move.} Bb4 {We immediately exploit White's move and put our bishop on [b4]. We want to put our queen on [e7] and go for the ...[e5] break soon. On [d6] our bishop would have come under fire after [e4]-[e5] or after a capture on [c4] with the knight.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd2 $2 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] It looks logical to go after the [c4]-pawn, but White is ignoring the centre. We should keep an eye out for the drawbacks of our opponent's every move.} e5 $1 {Of course, we immediately pounce on the chance to break in the centre. We planned to prepare this move with ...[Qe7] first, but we are able to carry out this break immediately here.} 10. Nxc4 exd4 11. Qxd4 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5b3] The knight is heading to [b3] next. This is a nice square for the knight, especially with the bishop on [b4]. We keep the pressure on White.} 12. Qh4 Nb3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gd8d4]} 13. Rd1 {White gets a tempo with the rook, but more importantly, they stop us from playing ...[Qd4] next which was our plan if White moved the rook on [a1].} ({After} 13. Rb1 Qd4 {∓ the knight coming to [d4] is a big issue for White.}) 13... Qe7 14. Rb1 Bf5 {We are provoking White to advance in the centre as this would create a few weaknesses for us to exploit.} 15. e4 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Gg4e6,Gf2f3] Once again, we are probing White, and this time White is forced to move the rook. The rook has to leave the open d-file. We will bring our bishop back to [e6] next, attacking the knight on [c4]. The [e5] advance is never a big problem since our queen on [e7] is protected.} *

