1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. a4 {White spends a tempo to stop us from going ...[b7]-[b5]. This weakens the [b4]-square, though, and is also a slow non-developing move.} Bb4 {We immediately exploit White's move and put our bishop on [b4]. We want to put our queen on [e7] and go for the ...[e5] break soon. On [d6] our bishop would have come under fire after [e4]-[e5] or after a capture on [c4] with the knight.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 ({This is better than} 9. Nd2 {, preparing the move [e4] and vacating the [d1]-square for the rook. White needs to keep an eye on the [e5]-square.}) 9... Qe7 {[%cal Ge6e5] This is important, to be able to meet the move [e4] with ...[e5], fighting back in the centre.} 10. Ne5 {White stops us from getting our central break, but the pawn becomes a weakness on [e5].} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 {There are two logical ways to defend the pawn, but both have their issues. Moving the f-pawn always weakens the king on [g1].} 12. Bf4 {If White is able to get the knight to [e4] next, we are in a lot of trouble. We have to act quickly now.} ({In case of} 12. f4 Rb8 {we want to play ...[b5] next.}) 12... g5 $1 {Go after any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger. The [e5]-pawn restricts our pieces and creates a weakness on [d6].} 13. Be3 Nxe5 {We are up two pawns now. White has compensation with their active pieces but not for more than equality. If given the chance, I would like to play ...[f5] next.} 14. Ne4 h6 15. f4 {White is playing dynamically to make use of their lead in development and our kingside weaknesses.} Ng4 {The bishop is kicked away from the [a7]-[g1] diagonal.} 16. Bc1 gxf4 {[%cal Gf1f4,Ge6e5,Gf7f5]} 17. h3 {This is forced to try to kick our knight away.} Bc5+ {[%cal Gg1h1,Gg4e3] This is an important move, forcing White's king to [h1]. We want to play ...[Ne3] next followed by a recapture with the bishop.} 18. Nxc5 Qxc5+ 19. Kh1 Ne3 20. Bxe3 fxe3 $10 {The position has simplified a bit and we are 3 pawns up! However, this does not matter too much due to our queenside pieces. White is able to get enough compensation for the material deficit.} *

