1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. a4 {White spends a tempo to stop us from going ...[b7]-[b5]. This weakens the [b4]-square, though, and is also a slow non-developing move.} Bb4 {We immediately exploit White's move and put our bishop on [b4]. We want to put our queen on [e7] and go for the ...[e5] break soon. On [d6] our bishop would have come under fire after [e4]-[e5] or after a capture on [c4] with the knight.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qc2 ({This is better than} 9. Nd2 {, preparing the move [e4] and vacating the [d1]-square for the rook. White needs to keep an eye on the [e5]-square.}) 9... Qe7 {[%cal Ge6e5] This is important, to be able to meet the move [e4] with ...[e5], fighting back in the centre.} 10. a5 {White takes the opportunity to gain space on the queenside before we are able to play ...[a5] ourselves. This does give us time to play in the centre, though.} e5 11. Rd1 {White brings the rook into the game, but this is pretty slow.} e4 {We keep the d-file closed. Now the [f3]-knight lacks a good square to go to.} 12. Nd2 {[%csl Re4,Rc4] White attacks both of our pawns, but this comes at a big cost.} e3 $1 {We are able to damage White's pawn structure on the kingside. White's king is also forced to come out of hiding.} 13. Nxc4 exf2+ 14. Kxf2 Nc5 $1 {[%csl Re4] A nice tactical idea to get control over the [e4]-square. We are planning to play ...[Be6] next, dislodging the knight on [c4].} 15. dxc5 {This is the principled move, accepting the sacrifice, but it guarantees at least a draw for us.} Qxc5+ 16. Ne3 Ng4+ 17. Kf3 Nxh2+ {We win the pawn on [h2] with tempo.} 18. Kf2 Ng4+ 19. Kf3 Qh5 $1 {We keep the game going as White has such a weak king on [f3].} 20. Nxg4 Bc5 $1 {We cut off the retreating squares for the king. White is now forced to give up the rook on [d1] to keep the king safe.} 21. e3 Bxg4+ 22. Kf2 Bxd1 23. Qxd1 Qh6 $36 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] We maintain a strong initiative against the White king. The rooks will come to the central files next.} *

