1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O {This is the most common move, preparing to play [e4] next. White is not too bothered about the missing pawn and instead wants to advance in the centre. I think this is the more critical approach and we need to be careful.} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4] and gain space on the queenside. The added benefit is that we can kick the knight from [c3] with ...[b4] at any moment.} 8. a4 $6 {This is not a great move. It invites us to push the b-pawn, which is something we were intending to do anyway.} b4 9. Nb1 Ba6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6c5] We keep the pawn on [c4] protected. Our plan is to play ...[Rc8] and ...[c5] next. The development of the dark-squared bishop is not a priority right now.} ({I played} 9... a5 {in a training game against the WCh challenger Gukesh a few years ago. It is not necessary here, however, as it does not help our development.} 10. Nbd2 {∞}) 10. Bg5 Rc8 {Why do we make this move before developing our kingside? We can develop our bishop to either [e7]/[d6] depending on the situation. There are some cases where we are able to trade the queens, after which our king would be well placed in the centre.} 11. Nbd2 c5 12. Rc1 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Qb6 $17 {White is nowhere close to winning the pawn back and we have a great position.} *

