1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O {This is the most common move, preparing to play [e4] next. White is not too bothered about the missing pawn and instead wants to advance in the centre. I think this is the more critical approach and we need to be careful.} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4] and gain space on the queenside. The added benefit is that we can kick the knight from [c3] with ...[b4] at any moment.} 8. e4 {White's threat is [d5], opening up the position. The conventional wisdom is to put our bishop on [b7] to prevent this.} b4 $5 {Instead of the standard lines, we are looking to be more aggressive and pro-active on the queenside.} 9. Nb1 {A sad move to make, retreating back to the first rank. It is not going to be easy for White to win back the pawn on [c4].} Be7 10. a3 b3 {This is strategically a risky move, as the [b3]-pawn is likely to fall if we lose the pawn on [c4]. It does keep the queenside under control for now, however.} 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Nbd2 Ba6 {We are ready to play ...[c3] next, targeting the rook on [f1].} 13. Re1 c5 $10 {[%cal Gc5d3,Gd7c5] We have managed to achieve all that we want. Our king is safe and we have broken White's centre. It would be amazing to get the knight to [d3] via [c5] soon.} *

