1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O {This is the most common move, preparing to play [e4] next. White is not too bothered about the missing pawn and instead wants to advance in the centre. I think this is the more critical approach and we need to be careful.} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4] and gain space on the queenside. The added benefit is that we can kick the knight from [c3] with ...[b4] at any moment.} 8. e4 {White's threat is [d5], opening up the position. The conventional wisdom is to put our bishop on [b7] to prevent this.} b4 $5 {Instead of the standard lines, we are looking to be more aggressive and pro-active on the queenside.} 9. e5 {This is the only critical move here, as White needs to get the knight to [e4]. White will then try to get the knight to [d6], especially after the trade of dark-squared bishops.} Nd5 10. Ne4 Be7 {We prepare to castle. The one drawback of this move is that White can trade the dark-squared bishops, but it was very difficult to stop this anyhow. We need to prioritise our king safety.} 11. Qc2 {White is going after our [c4]-pawn. We will not give it away cheaply on [c4], though.} a5 {[%cal Gc8a6] We are preparing the move ...[Ba6] if White takes on [c4] with the queen. Even if not, the move ...[a5] is pretty useful, gaining space on the queenside.} 12. Nfd2 c3 $1 {Now we change plans after White has retreated with the knight. We want to trade our pawns on the queenside and free up our position. 10...N7b6 has been played a few times, but it is not the most flexible move.} 13. bxc3 bxc3 14. Nxc3 Ba6 {It is useful to gain a tempo to attack the rook on [f1].} 15. Rd1 O-O {We can play ...[Nb4] next followed by the ...[c5] break, sacrificing the exchange on [a8]. White's queen lacks a good retreat square.} 16. a3 {White stops our plan, but [a3] is not a very useful move otherwise.} Rb8 $10 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gb6a7,Gc6c5] Our rook is well placed along the open file. If the knight moves away from [c3] we are ready to go for the ...[c5] break. Otherwise, we can bring our queen over to [b6] and [a7], targeting the [d4]-pawn and further preparing our ...[c5] break.} *

