1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O {This is the most common move, preparing to play [e4] next. White is not too bothered about the missing pawn and instead wants to advance in the centre. I think this is the more critical approach and we need to be careful.} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4] and gain space on the queenside. The added benefit is that we can kick the knight from [c3] with ...[b4] at any moment.} 8. e4 {White's threat is [d5], opening up the position. The conventional wisdom is to put our bishop on [b7] to prevent this.} b4 $5 {Instead of the standard lines, we are looking to be more aggressive and pro-active on the queenside.} 9. e5 {This is the only critical move here, as White needs to get the knight to [e4]. White will then try to get the knight to [d6], especially after the trade of dark-squared bishops.} Nd5 10. Ne4 Be7 {We prepare to castle. The one drawback of this move is that White can trade the dark-squared bishops, but it was very difficult to stop this anyhow. We need to prioritise our king safety.} 11. Bg5 {This is a very logical move, exchanging the key defender of our dark squares.} O-O {This has never been played before. We are okay with White trading on [e7] and will look to initiate play on the queenside quickly.} (11... Bxg5 {is a significant error, as after} 12. Nfxg5 {⩲ White gets a dangerous initiative with the knights.}) 12. Bxe7 ({I do not think the inclusion of} 12. h4 h6 {helps White much. Play should be similar to what we're about to see.}) 12... Qxe7 13. Nfd2 {White goes after our [c4]-pawn quickly, not allowing us to get our ideal ...[a5] and ...[Ba6] setup.} c3 {We play dynamically and will try to preserve the pawn on [c3].} 14. bxc3 bxc3 15. Nb3 Ba6 16. Re1 Qb4 {The queen is well placed on [b4], defending the [c3]-pawn and attacking [d4]. Meanwhile, the white queen has no good squares to go to.} 17. Rb1 Qa4 18. Rc1 Qb4 $10 {[%cal Ga7c4,Ga7a5,Ga5a4] We would like to play ...[Bc4] next followed by...[a5]-[a4] on the queenside. It is probably best for White to repeat moves with [Rb1].} ({If we want to keep the game going, we can play} 18... Bb5 19. Nxc3 Nxc3 20. Rxc3 Qxa2 {with an equal position.}) *

