1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {We will now consider the sidelines on move 5. The Fianchetto system is a decent try against all openings after 1.d4. It can be tried on different moves. Here, the drawback is the knight on [c3]. It is usually better placed on [d2] to defend the [c4]-pawn.} dxc4 {We take up the challenge. Generally against the fianchetto bishop, I prefer to keep my pawn on [d5] as it restricts the bishop on [g2]. We have cemented it with both the pawns on [c6] and [e6]. At the same time, the knight is misplaced on [c3]. This gives us the chance to go ...[b5]-[b4] on the queenside after we win the pawn on [c4]. White, on the other hand, focuses on building up their centre.} 6. Bg2 Nbd7 7. O-O {This is the most common move, preparing to play [e4] next. White is not too bothered about the missing pawn and instead wants to advance in the centre. I think this is the more critical approach and we need to be careful.} b5 {We defend the pawn on [c4] and gain space on the queenside. The added benefit is that we can kick the knight from [c3] with ...[b4] at any moment.} 8. e4 {White's threat is [d5], opening up the position. The conventional wisdom is to put our bishop on [b7] to prevent this.} b4 $5 {Instead of the standard lines, we are looking to be more aggressive and pro-active on the queenside.} 9. e5 {This is the only critical move here, as White needs to get the knight to [e4]. White will then try to get the knight to [d6], especially after the trade of dark-squared bishops.} Nd5 10. Ne4 Be7 {We prepare to castle. The one drawback of this move is that White can trade the dark-squared bishops, but it was very difficult to stop this anyhow. We need to prioritise our king safety.} 11. Bg5 {This is a very logical move, exchanging the key defender of our dark squares.} O-O {This has never been played before. We are okay with White trading on [e7] and will look to initiate play on the queenside quickly.} (11... Bxg5 {is a significant error, as after} 12. Nfxg5 {⩲ White gets a dangerous initiative with the knights.}) 12. Re1 {White is trying to maintain the tension with the bishop on [g5], but this is not very effective.} Bxg5 {Now that there is no check on [d6], we can take on [g5] and follow it up with ...[h6], pushing White's knight back.} 13. Nfxg5 h6 14. Nf3 a5 {We have the luxury of time here, as White has not yet started going after our [c4]-pawn. We will do our best to hold on to this pawn, but if there is too much pressure we can always play ...[c3] and liquidate the pawns.} 15. Rc1 Ba6 16. Bf1 N7b6 17. Nfd2 c3 $1 {Once White has misplaced their pieces, we give the pawn back and trade some minor pieces.} 18. bxc3 Nxc3 19. Nxc3 bxc3 20. Ne4 {White needs to keep the [d4]-pawn protected. This pawn becomes weaker as more minor pieces are traded off. In the long run, we can double or even triple our major pieces along the d-file. With more minor pieces on the board, White would have better chances to create something with their pawn centre.} Bxf1 21. Rxf1 Nd5 $10 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Ge4c3,Gd5c3,Gd8d5] We trade the knights on [c3] and start putting pressure on [d4]. The position is likely to simplify soon with all the pawns on the queenside getting traded. White's [e5]-pawn is more of a liability than a strength.} *

