1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qb3 {In my opinion, this is less effective as the queen is not doing much on the queenside. The only use I see is to prevent ...[c5] for the moment, but even that won't be prevented forever.} a6 {We are ready to play ...[c5] next. We do not waste any time developing our minor pieces.} 8. g3 {This is too slow, especially when combined with bringing the queen out so early. Now we are easily in time to get our bishop to the long diagonal.} (8. a4 $2 {does not work with the queen on [b3] due to} b4 {∓ and there is no good square for White's [c3]-knight.}) 8... c5 9. dxc5 Bb7 10. Bg2 Bxc5 {There was also the option to take on [c5] with the knight, but I prefer this recapture as we are able to castle on the next move. We have the option to develop the [b8]-knight to either [d7] or [c6].} 11. O-O O-O 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. Rad1 Qb6 $10 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gh7h6,Gf6g4] We keep up the pressure on [f2]. We will bring our rooks to the centre next. At some point, we can consider sacrificing on [f2] followed by ...[Ng4]. White has to be very accurate not to get a worse position.} *

