1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qb3 {In my opinion, this is less effective as the queen is not doing much on the queenside. The only use I see is to prevent ...[c5] for the moment, but even that won't be prevented forever.} a6 {We are ready to play ...[c5] next. We do not waste any time developing our minor pieces.} 8. e4 {White gains space in the centre immediately. This is the top choice of the computer. It has not been played much, though.} c5 {There is no time to waste. We immediately fight back in the centre. We have not yet developed our minor pieces, but they will get out rapidly and will likely be better placed than our opponent's pieces. White's only trump is their space advantage in the centre.} 9. e5 {This has been played by Radjabov, albeit in a rapid game.} c4 $1 {We take the chance to gain space on the queenside with a tempo. This is a good structure for us, with a clear weakness on [d4] to target.} 10. Qc2 {This has been played the most, but the queen is better placed on [d1] as it will come under fire on [c2].} Nd5 11. a4 Bb7 {We are not going to break our structure on the queenside that easily. White cannot put more pressure on [b5] and we can trade on [c3] at any moment.} 12. axb5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 axb5 $15 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4][%cal Ga8f3] We have a fantastic pawn structure and a beautiful bishop along the long diagonal. Things have gone quite wrong for White.} 