1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qb3 {In my opinion, this is less effective as the queen is not doing much on the queenside. The only use I see is to prevent ...[c5] for the moment, but even that won't be prevented forever.} a6 {We are ready to play ...[c5] next. We do not waste any time developing our minor pieces.} 8. e4 {White gains space in the centre immediately. This is the top choice of the computer. It has not been played much, though.} c5 {There is no time to waste. We immediately fight back in the centre. We have not yet developed our minor pieces, but they will get out rapidly and will likely be better placed than our opponent's pieces. White's only trump is their space advantage in the centre.} 9. dxc5 ({This is better than} 9. e5 {, as it doesn't allow us to get a bind on the queenside. However, this of course allows us to develop our pieces more easily. There's just no easy game for White in this variation.}) 9... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Gb8d7] I like this unusual move as we remain flexible. White is hinting at the [e5] advance, and we will meet it with ...[Nfd7]xc5. Otherwise, our idea is to go ...[Nbd7]xc5 and the queen on [c7] would then prevent [e5].} 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7 $10 {We are getting our knight to [c5] next with a very comfortable position. Our king is still in the centre, but it's not in any danger anytime soon.} *

