1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qb3 {In my opinion, this is less effective as the queen is not doing much on the queenside. The only use I see is to prevent ...[c5] for the moment, but even that won't be prevented forever.} a6 {We are ready to play ...[c5] next. We do not waste any time developing our minor pieces.} 8. Bg5 {This is the most popular move in the position, preparing to play [e4] next. White has to justify the early queen moves somehow.} c5 {I like this approach, as it is consistent with all the lines we have seen so far. I do not mind doubling our pawns on the kingside, especially if White has to give up their dark-squared bishop to achieve it.} 9. dxc5 Bb7 10. a4 {This looks tempting, going after our queenside and targeting our [b7]-bishop.} Qa5 $1 {This reminds me of the meme: call the ambulance - but not for me! :- White has created some holes on the queenside which we can exploit.} 11. Rc1 {This is the only move for White to not be much worse.} b4 12. Bxf6 {Once again a necessary move, as otherwise our knight will head to [e4] and start creating chaos.} gxf6 13. Nb1 Bd5 $15 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7c5] We will continue with ...[Nd7] next and bring the knight to [c5]. The bishop can retreat to [c6] if White plays [e4]. Another option is to play ...[f5] and keep the bishop strong on [d5].} *

