1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qb3 {In my opinion, this is less effective as the queen is not doing much on the queenside. The only use I see is to prevent ...[c5] for the moment, but even that won't be prevented forever.} a6 {We are ready to play ...[c5] next. We do not waste any time developing our minor pieces.} 8. Bg5 {This is the most popular move in the position, preparing to play [e4] next. White has to justify the early queen moves somehow.} c5 {I like this approach, as it is consistent with all the lines we have seen so far. I do not mind doubling our pawns on the kingside, especially if White has to give up their dark-squared bishop to achieve it.} 9. Bxf6 (9. Bxf6 {White forces us to double our pawns on the kingside. This was the only opportunity for White, as currently we are unable to recapture} Qxf6 {due to the knight coming to [e4].}) 9... gxf6 10. dxc5 {White releases the tension in the centre because they do not want to allow us to play ...[c4], getting our ideal pawn structure. This move is not the best, though, as it allows us to develop our pieces much quicker.} Bb7 {As we have seen several times, we first develop the bishop and decide on how to recapture the [c5]-pawn a bit later.} 11. Rd1 Qa5 {The queen is very safe on [a5] and it creates problems for White along the [a5]-[e1] diagonal. Now White has to be precise in order not to be worse.} 12. Nd4 $1 {Only a strong player is likely to find this move over the board. Otherwise, we recapture the [c5]-pawn with a great position.} Bxc5 {We allow the sacrifice on [e6] as there is no immediate attack for White afterwards. It is a long-term sacrifice.} 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Qxe6+ Be7 15. e3 Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge8f8,Ge2h5,Gc7c4] We will continue with ...[Kf8] and I do not see a way for White to continue the initiative. We will soon take over with our extra piece. Keep in mind that the plan of [Be2]-[h5] can be well met with ...[Qc4].} *

