1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qb3 {In my opinion, this is less effective as the queen is not doing much on the queenside. The only use I see is to prevent ...[c5] for the moment, but even that won't be prevented forever.} a6 {We are ready to play ...[c5] next. We do not waste any time developing our minor pieces.} 8. Bg5 {This is the most popular move in the position, preparing to play [e4] next. White has to justify the early queen moves somehow.} c5 {I like this approach, as it is consistent with all the lines we have seen so far. I do not mind doubling our pawns on the kingside, especially if White has to give up their dark-squared bishop to achieve it.} 9. Bxf6 (9. Bxf6 {White forces us to double our pawns on the kingside. This was the only opportunity for White, as currently we are unable to recapture} Qxf6 {due to the knight coming to [e4].}) 9... gxf6 10. Rd1 ({This has been played only once, but it is better than} 10. dxc5 {as it delays our development.}) 10... Qb6 {We are not in a hurry to rush with the move ...[c4]. Our queen is well placed on [b6], covering the queenside and targeting the centre.} 11. d5 {This is the best try for White to pose problems, using the lead in development.} c4 {[%cal Gf8c5] This gives us the [c5]-square for the bishop and kicks White's queen to a worse square.} 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. g3 Bc5 {We want to force White to play [e3], which weakens the light-squares in their position. It is rarely a good idea to combine both [e3] and [g3].} 14. e3 Bb4 {[%csl Rd5,Rf3] Now we go after the [d5]-pawn. Thanks to our previous move, which forced White to weaken their position with [e3], the knight on [f3] is hanging if White takes on [e6].} 15. Bg2 (15. dxe6 {is still possible, but leads to equality after} Bxf3 16. Qf5 $1 Qc6 17. Qxf6 O-O {= . This can be analysed further if you are interested, but both sides have many options.}) 15... Bxd5 16. Rxd5 $1 {This is an important move for White, as otherwise we are a clean pawn up with a big advantage. White has some dynamic advantage.} exd5 17. Nd4 Nc6 $1 {We are giving back the exchange to finish our development.} 18. Bxd5 Nxd4 19. Qe4+ Ne6 20. Bxa8 O-O $10 {We reach an equal middlegame where I believe our knight is a better minor piece compared to White's light-squared bishop. However, our worse pawn structure on the kingside ensures that the position remains balanced.} *

