1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. g3 {The fianchetto is pretty slow for White, allowing us to break in the centre.} c5 9. Bg2 Bb7 {We effectively neutralise the bishop on [g2].} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bg5 {This has been played in a handful of games, but I never understood the appeal of giving up the bishop so easily. The usual logic is to get the bishop out before playing [e3]. It does not apply to positions with the pawn on [g3], however.} h6 {We invite White to trade on [f6], giving us the bishop pair.} 12. Bxf6 {There is no other option for White. Otherwise the inclusion of ...[h6] is beneficial for us.} Nxf6 13. Rfd1 {This happened in a game between Norowitz - Naroditsky, 2015. I hope by now you know exactly the move we will be going for.} c4 {Of course, we always meet the move [Rd1] with ...[c4], keeping the d-file closed.} 14. Qc2 Qb6 {We get our queen away from the d-file as White had some ideas involving a pawn sacrifice on [d5].} 15. a4 Bb4 $10 {[%csl Ge4] We stop White from going for the move [e4] in the centre. The bishop on [b4] also helps us on the queenside as it stops White’s play with the move [b3]. We will castle next and bring our rook to [c8]. We will not allow White to get the move [b4] easily. I think we are on the better side of equality here, with the semi-open e-file and active pieces. We will put our rook on [e8] and get the knight to [e4]. We can also play …a4 at the right moment to stop White’s play on the queenside.} *

