1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. a4 {This has not been played much, but it's one of the top choices of the computer. White is trying to provoke some weaknesses on the queenside. This was not possible with the queen on [b3], as White needs to be able to meet Black's ...[b4] with [Ne4].} Bb7 {We don't need to play ...[b4] yet. We have the option to either go for the ...[c5] break directly or start with the move ...[b4].} 9. Bg5 {This has been played by some strong players, including Ivanchuk. White wants to get the bishop out before playing [e3].} Nbd7 {This is a standard reaction after the move [Bg5], as we want to be able to recapture with the knight rather than the bishop or the queen, maintaining control over the centre.} 10. e3 b4 {I like this concrete option, going for the ...[c5] advance immediately afterwards.} 11. Ne4 c5 {We are okay with allowing White to double our pawns on the kingside if we can get the bishop pair in return.} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. dxc5 {This is essential, as we were threatening to play ...[c4]. The knight on [e4] is unstable.} Nxc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 $10 {[%csl Gb7,Gc5][%cal Ge8e7] We reach a pleasant endgame with the bishop pair compensating for our pawn structure. Our king will remain in the centre on [e7] and we can restrict the opponent's light-squared bishop with our pawns.} *

