1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. Bg5 {We have seen this several times already, and as usual this bishop move is not so effective.} c5 9. a4 {This has been tried by a few strong players.} cxd4 (9... c4 {is not great here due to} 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. e4 {↑ .}) 10. Nxd4 b4 {We keep the a-file closed. Although it looks like we are lagging behind in development, White cannot do much to exploit this.} 11. Ne4 Bb7 {We force White to give up the dark-squared bishop. White cannot waste time by retreating with the knight.} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%csl Gb7,Ge6,Gf6,Gf8][%cal Gf6f5,Gf8g7] I like this structure in conjunction with our bishop pair. In the future, we can play ...[f5] and wreak havoc with the bishops.} 13. Rd1 {You can take some time to try and find our next move.} b3 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4,Rb4e1] We want to get our bishop to [b4] and do not mind giving up a pawn to do so.} 14. Nxb3 {This has been played in both games that reached this position.} (14. e3 {can be met with} Bb4+ 15. Nc3 Nd7 {⩱ with a comfortable position for Black.}) 14... Qxd3 15. exd3 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Ra4,Rb2,Rd3][%cal Gf8b4,Ge8e7] We have a fantastic position in the endgame. We will give a check on [b4] and put our king on [e7]. The pawn on [d3] is a weakness, and so are White's queenside pawns due to the hole on [b4]. We also enjoy the bishop pair.} *

