1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. Bg5 {We have seen this several times already, and as usual this bishop move is not so effective.} c5 9. Bxf6 {This is the most common move in the position, doubling our pawns on the kingside at the cost of the bishop pair.} gxf6 10. d5 Bb7 {We are threatening to play ...[b4] after which we win the [d5]-pawn.} 11. e4 {This is the most played move in the position, but it is an inaccuracy.} (11. Rd1 {is a better option for White, but we equalise easily after} b4 {, intending ...[Qxd5] after the knight moves.}) 11... Nd7 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ge8c8,Gh8g8,Gg8g2] We will put our queen on [c7] next and castle queenside. The doubled pawns then become a strength for us, as we have the open g-file to attack White on the kingside.} 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Be2 O-O-O $17 {We have a large advantage already. We will put our king on [b8] next and start advancing with our h-pawn. Our king is very safe.} *

