1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. e4 {White goes for the direct move [e4], gaining space in the centre. However, White's control over the centre is very shaky, and we are well prepared to counter this move.} c5 {Our usual plan, breaking in the centre.} 9. e5 {This has been played by a few strong players.} c4 $1 {[%cal Gf6d5] Our standard response, gaining space on the queenside. Here we can make this move with a tempo.} 10. Qb1 {This is the superior square for the queen compared to [c2] because White is able to put pressure on [b5] after the trade on [c3].} (10. Qc2 {transposes to an earlier variation.}) 10... Nd5 11. a4 Bb7 {We go for the same move as in the line with the queen on [c2], but here this move is a pawn sacrifice. We give up the pawn on [b5] for quick development.} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 14. Nxb5 Bb4+ {We force White to allow the trade of dark-squared bishops. Even though our dark-squared bishop is an important piece in these structures, here we are playing dynamically, using our lead in development.} 15. Bd2 Bxd2+ 16. Nxd2 O-O {[%cal Gd5f4,Ga8g2] White is unable to take on [c4] with the bishop because then we would be able to jump to [f4] with the [d5]-knight. This is one of the benefits of exchanging the dark-squared bishops.} 17. Nxc4 Nc6 $36 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf7f6] We are going to play ...[f6] next and open the f-file. White should be careful with their king still stuck in the centre.} *

