1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. e4 {White goes for the direct move [e4], gaining space in the centre. However, White's control over the centre is very shaky, and we are well prepared to counter this move.} c5 {Our usual plan, breaking in the centre.} 9. dxc5 {This is the most common move in the position, exchanging the queens. White is happy to allow the trade of queens on [d3], as this would help develop their bishop.} Bxc5 {We do not mind keeping our king in the centre. We are not going to aid White in the development of their pieces, however.} 10. Qxd8+ {There was no other good option to keep the queens on the board.} Kxd8 11. e5 {White wants to get their [c3]-knight to [e4] and misplace our [f6]-knight. However, they are creating a big weakness on [e5].} Ng4 12. Bg5+ {This check seems strange because our king is exposed along the d-file. However, on the other hand, we can run over to the queenside from [d8]. Our play is similar in both of these situations.} Ke8 13. Ne4 (13. O-O-O $2 {was seen in a game between Navara and Kramnik, but Black is winning after} Nd7 {-+ .}) 13... Bb4+ 14. Bd2 Bxd2+ 15. Nexd2 Nc6 {[%csl Re5] It is very hard for White to defend the pawn on [e5]. White should instead try to do something on the queenside.} 16. a4 Rb8 $10 {White can win the [b5]-pawn in return for [e5] after [Rc1]-[c5], but we are faster in getting our pieces out. The endgame is very comfortable for us.} *

