1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. e4 {White goes for the direct move [e4], gaining space in the centre. However, White's control over the centre is very shaky, and we are well prepared to counter this move.} c5 {Our usual plan, breaking in the centre.} 9. dxc5 {This is the most common move in the position, exchanging the queens. White is happy to allow the trade of queens on [d3], as this would help develop their bishop.} Bxc5 {We do not mind keeping our king in the centre. We are not going to aid White in the development of their pieces, however.} 10. Qxd8+ {There was no other good option to keep the queens on the board.} Kxd8 11. Bd3 {White is ready to play [e5] followed by [Be4].} Nc6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5,Gf6g4,Gg4e5] We keep the [d7]-square available for the [f6]-knight. We would like to put a knight on [e5] in the future.} 12. Ke2 Ng4 13. Rf1 f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg7g5] I like this move, controlling the [e5]-square. It also helps us advance more pawns on the kingside in the future.} 14. Bf4 g5 15. Bg3 Nge5 $10 {The pawn on [g5] ensures that we do not run into [f4] anytime soon. Black is very comfortable with the knight restricting White's pieces.} *

