1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. g4 $5 {The most popular move in the position, and definitely the most dangerous one. I had not studied this line properly when I started playing the Semi-Slav, but I had to after I saw a game between Praggnanandhaa and Raja Rithvik back in 2021. It is similar to the [g4] line we saw earlier in one of the Anti-Meran chapters.} Nxg4 {This is the most principled move, taking up the challenge. White does not get an immediate initiative for the pawn but has long-term compensation with the centre and active pieces. We have to spend two moves to win the pawn and move the knight back.} ({I was considering recommending} 8... Bb7 {, primarily because it has hardly ever been played. However, the resulting positions are tricky and Black does not have a great score. It is better to grab the pawn and suffer than to not grab the pawn and get tricky positions regardless. :-}) 9. Bf4 {This is the best square for the bishop. White is preparing to castle queenside.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5]} (9... Bb7 {We are ready to play ...c5 to activate the b7-bishop. Now, all the games here continue with} 10. Rg1 {, which transposes to upcoming lines.}) 10. Bg2 (10. Rg1 Nf6 {will transpose.}) 10... c5 {I see no reason to deviate from our plan.} 11. d5 {White is trying to create quick play in the centre. They have to do something dynamic, as they risk being a pawn down for nothing.} c4 12. Qd4 Nd7 13. Rg1 e5 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gc5f2] We give the pawn back to simplify the position. We also block the diagonal, which means ...[Bc5] is a serious idea now.} 14. Bxe5 {[%cal Gd4g4] This is necessary to attack the knight on [g4].} Ngxe5 15. Nxe5 Bc5 16. Qf4 Qf6 $10 {We force the queens off the board, reaching an equal endgame. I like our position with the bishop pair. White has a pawn majority in the centre, but it is not as effective with so many pieces left on the board.} *

