 e4 {A very principled move, advancing in the centre.} c5 {We invite White to trade the queens, leading to an endgame that's comfortable for us.} 11. d5 {This was the point behind White's 10.e4. White's pieces are more active so they want to open the centre.} b4 12. Na4 exd5 13. exd5 Ra7 $1 {[%cal Gd8d5,Ga7e7] A creative way to bring the rook into the game. We also get out of the fork on [b6] and can take on [d5] next with the queen.} 14. Be3 Qxd5 15. Qe2 Bg4 {[%cal Ge3c5,Ga7e7] The discovered checks are not a big problem, as we can block them with our rook.} 16. Rxg4 (16. Bxc5+ Re7 {-+ .}) 16... Nxg4 17. Rd1 Qf5 18. Bxc5+ Re7 $10 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] We are forced to give back the exchange, but we remain a pawn up. White's king is much more exposed and we are one move away from castling kingside.} *

