1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. g4 $5 {The most popular move in the position, and definitely the most dangerous one. I had not studied this line properly when I started playing the Semi-Slav, but I had to after I saw a game between Praggnanandhaa and Raja Rithvik back in 2021. It is similar to the [g4] line we saw earlier in one of the Anti-Meran chapters.} Nxg4 {This is the most principled move, taking up the challenge. White does not get an immediate initiative for the pawn but has long-term compensation with the centre and active pieces. We have to spend two moves to win the pawn and move the knight back.} ({I was considering recommending} 8... Bb7 {, primarily because it has hardly ever been played. However, the resulting positions are tricky and Black does not have a great score. It is better to grab the pawn and suffer than to not grab the pawn and get tricky positions regardless. :-}) 9. Rg1 {White kicks our knight back and gets the rook to the open g-file.} Nf6 10. Bf4 {This is the most common move in the position, which can also arise from 9.Bf4 and then 10.Rg1. White will castle queenside in these lines and try to open the centre as quickly as possible.} Bb7 11. Ne5 {This does not achieve much as we are able to trade the knights easily. It was played by Grandmaster Le Tuan Minh against Vidit in the Asian Games 2023.} Nbd7 12. Bg2 Nd5 {This is a useful move, attacking the bishop on [f4]. The exchange of pieces is in our favour.} 13. Nxd5 cxd5 $15 {The centre is closed and now we can focus on the c-file. White lacks a good square for the king, which is in the way of their rooks.} *

