1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3 {(In this chapter, we will take a look at the early queen jump. Both the queen moves 5.Qb3 and 5.Qd3 lead to the same position. They are not principled, as White brings the queen out very early and gives us a couple of tempi to improve our position. White has to play actively using the centre to justify this.)} dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 {We take the chance to kick the queen back immediately. It can go to either [b3] or [d3], but our play is consistent with the main lines. We will try to get the ...[c5] break as soon as we can and develop our light-squared bishop on to the [a8]-[h1] diagonal.} 7. Qd3 ({This is slightly better than} 7. Qb3 {, as now White can get the knight to [e4] after a potential ...[b4]. At the same time, it does hinder the development of the light-squared bishop, and the queen is, generally, a bit awkwardly placed on [d3].}) 7... a6 {We play the same way as in the lines with the queen on [b3]. We are ready to continue with ...[c5]. This is the most flexible move for us.} 8. g4 $5 {The most popular move in the position, and definitely the most dangerous one. I had not studied this line properly when I started playing the Semi-Slav, but I had to after I saw a game between Praggnanandhaa and Raja Rithvik back in 2021. It is similar to the [g4] line we saw earlier in one of the Anti-Meran chapters.} Nxg4 {This is the most principled move, taking up the challenge. White does not get an immediate initiative for the pawn but has long-term compensation with the centre and active pieces. We have to spend two moves to win the pawn and move the knight back.} ({I was considering recommending} 8... Bb7 {, primarily because it has hardly ever been played. However, the resulting positions are tricky and Black does not have a great score. It is better to grab the pawn and suffer than to not grab the pawn and get tricky positions regardless. :-}) 9. Rg1 {White kicks our knight back and gets the rook to the open g-file.} Nf6 10. Bf4 {This is the most common move in the position, which can also arise from 9.Bf4 and then 10.Rg1. White will castle queenside in these lines and try to open the centre as quickly as possible.} Bb7 11. e4 {This is an important move to stop our ...[c5] break, as White will answer [d5] to open up the centre. This means we have to play more slowly here.} Nbd7 12. O-O-O g6 {[%cal Gf8e7] We defend the pawn on [g7] so that the [f8]-bishop can get into the game. Our king is reasonably safe on the kingside with White missing their g-pawn. White cannot checkmate us with only pieces.} 13. Kb1 {[%cal Ge4e5] This is the best try for White. They are threatening to play [e5] now, moving the king off of the c-file.} b4 $1 {We kick the knight away before White can get in the move [e5]. The knight is forced to go to the rim.} (13... Be7 {is bad due to} 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Ng5 {± and White's play on the kingside is much quicker.}) 14. Na4 Be7 {Knowing that we are one move away from castling is always reassuring.} 15. Bh6 {White immediately stops us from castling kingside. This was to be expected the moment we pushed the pawn to [g6].} Qa5 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] We change plans as we are going to castle queenside now. The king will be safer there, with so many of our pieces around.} 16. Qc2 c5 {We achieve our break in the centre, targeting White's central pawns.} 17. d5 exd5 18. exd5 O-O-O $10 {[%csl Rd5] We will go after the pawn on [d5] next. It is risky for White to push it further, as this would open up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop. It is a pretty fighting position with chances for both sides.} *

