[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2136127625761181"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. e3 {[%csl Rc1] This is a pretty dumb way of playing, shutting in the bishop on [c1]. The only realistic plan I see is to go for an IQP position with the [e4] break.} Bd6 {With the bishop stuck on [c1], we can put our dark-squared bishop on its most active square.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {We stop the move [e4] for now and also cover the [e5]-square. Often the plan of [Ne5] followed by [f4] can be pretty dangerous.} 9. Qc2 {This is typically the best square for the queen in this structure, and it also helps White prepare the move [e4].} Qe7 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6e4] We are sadistic and will not allow White to free their position that easily. Also, we are preparing to jump with the knight to [e4] at the right moment.} 10. Re1 Ne4 {This is the right moment to stop White from getting the [e4] break in the centre. In the long run, White is in serious trouble, as our play is much faster on the kingside.} 11. Ne5 $1 {This is a very important move for White in order to not be significantly worse. White needs to unbalance the game. It's a good lesson for us too, to understand how we should think in such positions. It's easy to just drift into a bad position, but strong players understand the dynamics very well.} Bxe5 {We are happy to win the central pawn.} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. f3 Nf6 $10 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f8,Gf8g6] White has decent compensation with the bishop pair, but at best it's enough for equality. We will play ...[Nbd7]-[f8]-[g6] and put our bishop on [d7], connecting the rooks. I highly doubt this variation will happen on the board, but is a pretty informative variation.} *

