1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. e3 {[%csl Rc1] This is a pretty dumb way of playing, shutting in the bishop on [c1]. The only realistic plan I see is to go for an IQP position with the [e4] break.} Bd6 {With the bishop stuck on [c1], we can put our dark-squared bishop on its most active square.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {We stop the move [e4] for now and also cover the [e5]-square. Often the plan of [Ne5] followed by [f4] can be pretty dangerous.} 9. Qc2 {This is typically the best square for the queen in this structure, and it also helps White prepare the move [e4].} Qe7 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6e4] We are sadistic and will not allow White to free their position that easily. Also, we are preparing to jump with the knight to [e4] at the right moment.} 10. Nd2 {This is the best plan for White, allowing them to get [e4] in.} Na6 {I like this manoeuvre with the knight, bringing it to [c7] and [e6] in the future.} 11. a3 Nc7 12. Re1 {With five! pieces covering [e4], White is finally ready to break in the centre. We have prepared for this by bringing the knight to [c7].} h6 {Making sure our h-pawn isn't hanging after some exchanges on [e4].} 13. h3 Be6 $10 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gd5e4,Gc7d5] We have a comfortable position, and an eventual [e4] will lead to a few exchanges followed by us planting the [c7]-knight on [d5]. There are several other plans too which you can go for in these structures. I just wanted to give you a sample line to show some possible plans.} *

