1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Bf4 {This has been played several times by top players like Magnus and Fabi. White is happy to trade off the dark-squared bishops as long as they are able to get the light-squared bishop to [d3].} Bf5 {We immediately put our bishop on the important [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We have to be careful about [Nh4] ideas, though, as White will try to kick the bishop away from this diagonal. The exchange of light-squared bishops is always in our favour. This is the typical pattern in this pawn structure. Our pawns are fixed on the light squares in the centre and it's hard to find a good square for the bishop other than [f5].} (6... Bd6 {is logical, but White answers} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Nh4 $1 {and we are unable to maintain the bishop along this diagonal.}) 7. e3 Nbd7 {We cover the [e5]-square as we are planning to go after White's dark-squared bishop with ...[Nh5] soon. We keep all the other options open.} 8. Be2 {[%cal Gf3h4] White understandably does not want to trade the light-squared bishops. They are preparing to play [Nh4], so they first cover the [g4]-square.} (8. Nh4 {is met with} Bg4 9. Qc2 Nh5 $1 {and we take over the position.}) 8... Qb6 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gf6e4] We can go after the [b2]-pawn now with the bishop on [f5]. White cannot just give this pawn up for compensation.} 9. Qc1 (9. Qd2 {runs into} Ne4 $1 {and White is forced to retreat, as} 10. Nxe4 $2 {fails to} dxe4 11. Ne5 Bb4 {-+ winning the queen.}) 9... h6 {We create a luft for the bishop on [h7].} 10. O-O Be7 {This is a good version of the London system with colours reversed. The queen is misplaced on [c1] and our bishop on [f5] is very active.} 11. h3 O-O 12. a3 a5 $10 {[%csl Rc1,Gf5][%cal Gf8e8] We will not allow White to get the move [b4] easily. I think we are on the better side of equality here, with the semi-open e-file and active pieces.} *

