1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Bf4 {This has been played several times by top players like Magnus and Fabi. White is happy to trade off the dark-squared bishops as long as they are able to get the light-squared bishop to [d3].} Bf5 {We immediately put our bishop on the important [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We have to be careful about [Nh4] ideas, though, as White will try to kick the bishop away from this diagonal. The exchange of light-squared bishops is always in our favour. This is the typical pattern in this pawn structure. Our pawns are fixed on the light squares in the centre and it's hard to find a good square for the bishop other than [f5].} (6... Bd6 {is logical, but White answers} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Nh4 $1 {and we are unable to maintain the bishop along this diagonal.}) 7. e3 Nbd7 {We cover the [e5]-square as we are planning to go after White's dark-squared bishop with ...[Nh5] soon. We keep all the other options open.} 8. h3 Qb6 ({Once again, we go after the pawn on b2.} 8... Be7 {is also a good positional option.}) 9. Bd3 {This is the extra option available to White here, not defending the pawn on [b2].} Qxb2 {We take on the challenge, giving up the light-squared bishop.} 10. Bxf5 Qxc3+ 11. Kf1 Qa3 {[%cal Gf8d6] We are preparing the move ...[Bd6]. Exchanging a few pieces would work very well for us.} 12. Rb1 Qxa2 13. Ra1 Qb2 $10 {We are forced to repeat, but I don't mind since this variation is pretty unlikely to happen anyway.} *

