1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Bf4 {This has been played several times by top players like Magnus and Fabi. White is happy to trade off the dark-squared bishops as long as they are able to get the light-squared bishop to [d3].} Bf5 {We immediately put our bishop on the important [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We have to be careful about [Nh4] ideas, though, as White will try to kick the bishop away from this diagonal. The exchange of light-squared bishops is always in our favour. This is the typical pattern in this pawn structure. Our pawns are fixed on the light squares in the centre and it's hard to find a good square for the bishop other than [f5].} (6... Bd6 {is logical, but White answers} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Nh4 $1 {and we are unable to maintain the bishop along this diagonal.}) 7. e3 Nbd7 {We cover the [e5]-square as we are planning to go after White's dark-squared bishop with ...[Nh5] soon. We keep all the other options open.} 8. Bd3 {This is the most played move in the position but it is pretty harmless as we get to trade our light-squared bishop.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 {[%cal Gf6h5] We create a potential threat of ...[Nh5], as we have the [g5]-square covered.} 10. h3 {White creates a square on [h2] for the bishop to retreat to in case of ...[Nh5]. We were not planning to go for this move immediately anyway.} O-O 11. O-O Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gf6e4] The rook definitely belongs on the e-file in these lines. We will try to get our knight to [e4] in the next few moves.} 12. Rab1 a5 {We have already seen this idea, delaying White's [b4] and intending to open the a-file.} 13. a3 a4 $10 {[%csl Ra3,Ga4,Rb2][%cal Ge7f8,Gf6e4] We stop White's queenside expansion once and for all. This is a luxury we usually don't get when the queen is on [d1] or [c2]. If White plays [b4] now it would give us a target on the queenside. We have our play with ...[Bf8] and ...[Ne4] in the centre.} *

