1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Qc2 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gc1g5,Ge2e3,Gf1d3] White tries to be clever by preventing the move ...[Bf5]. White would be better if they managed to get the [c1]-bishop out and follow it up with [e3] and [Bd3].} g6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] As we saw in the previous variations, we really want to get the bishop to [f5]. Now, this move will come with a tempo, attacking the queen on [c2]. The move ...[g6] does create some weaknesses on our kingside, but White is not in a position to exploit this.} 7. Bg5 Be7 ({Here} 7... Bf5 {runs into} 8. Qb3 {± .}) 8. e4 {This approach makes sense to try and do something quickly before we get the move ...[Bf5] in. The drawback is that White is left with an isolated pawn on [d4].} dxe4 9. Bxf6 {White has to give up the bishop, as otherwise they end up simplifying the position too much. We have the long-term advantage of playing against the isolated [d4]-pawn.} Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Qe7 {We get the queens off the board since we have the bishop pair.} 11. Bc4 Bf5 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. O-O-O Kf8 {I like this simple approach, bringing the king to [g7] where it is much safer. We can then decide where to develop the knights and rooks.} 14. h3 h5 $10 {[%csl Gf5,Gf6][%cal Gf8g7,Gd4d5] We stop the move [g4] and our position is pretty comfortable in the endgame. We can just ignore the move [d5] as White's pawn is not going anywhere soon.} *

