1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Qc2 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gc1g5,Ge2e3,Gf1d3] White tries to be clever by preventing the move ...[Bf5]. White would be better if they managed to get the [c1]-bishop out and follow it up with [e3] and [Bd3].} g6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] As we saw in the previous variations, we really want to get the bishop to [f5]. Now, this move will come with a tempo, attacking the queen on [c2]. The move ...[g6] does create some weaknesses on our kingside, but White is not in a position to exploit this.} 7. Bg5 Be7 ({Here} 7... Bf5 {runs into} 8. Qb3 {± .}) 8. e3 {This is the more traditional move, but it lets us execute our plan easily.} Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O {Black players usually delay castling a bit longer, but I see no real reason to do so. We only give White an extra option to play [Bh6], which would make our castling impossible.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. b4 {White gave up the bishop on [f6] to get this move in without allowing us to play ...[a5]. It makes some sense, but I do not think it is worth giving up the bishop for.} a6 13. O-O Nd7 14. a4 Nb6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] We are discouraging the [b5] break and encouraging White to close the queenside with the move [a5]. We can then focus on our play with ...[h5] or ...[Re8].} 15. b5 {This has been played the most, but it falls right into our plan.} cxb5 16. axb5 a5 $15 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ga8a1] Our a-pawn is now a dangerous passed pawn, and we have the [c4]-square for our knight in the future. White cannot put pressure on our isolated [d5]-pawn easily.} *

