1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Qc2 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gc1g5,Ge2e3,Gf1d3] White tries to be clever by preventing the move ...[Bf5]. White would be better if they managed to get the [c1]-bishop out and follow it up with [e3] and [Bd3].} g6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] As we saw in the previous variations, we really want to get the bishop to [f5]. Now, this move will come with a tempo, attacking the queen on [c2]. The move ...[g6] does create some weaknesses on our kingside, but White is not in a position to exploit this.} 7. Bg5 Be7 ({Here} 7... Bf5 {runs into} 8. Qb3 {± .}) 8. e3 {This is the more traditional move, but it lets us execute our plan easily.} Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O {Black players usually delay castling a bit longer, but I see no real reason to do so. We only give White an extra option to play [Bh6], which would make our castling impossible.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. h4 {This was played by Fabi in classical chess to beat Aryan Tari and should be taken seriously. White is trying to punish us for castling early.} Nd7 13. h5 Re8 {We are not too concerned about the h-file. Our king can always run to the centre.} 14. O-O-O Bg7 {We play a prophylactic move on the kingside. Next, we will start our play on the other side of the board.} 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Rh3 $6 {This was played by Bacrot, a strong French player back in 2001. White is on the wrong track, as it is extremely hard to create something on the h-file.} (16. Kb1 {is a better move. It can be met with} Rc8 {followed by ...[b5] and play on the queenside.}) 16... b5 17. Rdh1 Rc8 $17 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gc6c5] We are going to play ...[b4] and ...[c5] next. White is in big trouble on the queenside and the centre.} *

