1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Bg5 {This is the most common move here, and is typical for this structure. It is more effective with the pawn on [e3], though, as White would have had the chance to meet the move ...[Bf5] with [Qf3]. This is a crucial difference in the current position and makes life easy for us. I want to highlight the main difference between the critical exchange variation in the QGD and our version of the same: 2...e6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Bg5 c6 6.e3 Bf5 7.Qf3! This is the key move, which is possible with the inclusion of the move [e3] instead of [Nf3]. 7...Bg6 8.Bxf6 ⩲ (White manages to cripple our pawn structure on the kingside. You can check out the famous game Carlsen-Kramnik 2016 where White perfectly exploited the doubled pawns.)} h6 {It is always good to force White to make a decision early regarding their bishop. This also creates a luft for our own bishop on [h7].} 7. Bh4 Bf5 {This is an important move that we have seen several times already. We get our bishop to its most active square. If we can develop normally, we will end up taking over the position as we have the semi-open e-file.} 8. Qb3 {The concept is correct, trying to do something quick on the queenside, but it does not work out so well.} g5 {This is the main reason why we played the move ...[h6] earlier. We can force the bishop away from the diagonal with a single move.} 9. Bg3 (9. Qxb7 {is bad as the queen gets stuck after} gxh4 10. Qxa8 Qb6 {-+ .}) 9... Qb6 {We are happy to trade queens now. We have active well-placed pieces and a better pawn structure. We are definitely on the better side of equality.} 10. e3 Nbd7 11. Be2 Nh5 $15 {[%csl Gf5,Gf8,Rg3] We win the dark-squared bishop, getting the bishop pair advantage. We will trade queens shortly on [b3] and keep our king in the centre.} *

