1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. cxd5 {We come to the final chapter in the Semi-Slav complex. I kept this one for last, as it is more similar to the QGD structures compared to the Semi-Slav. However, it is also well known that an early exchange on [d5] combined with the move [Nf3] gives us the best possible version of this system. To fight for an advantage, White needs to get the bishop out to [g5] followed by [e3] and [Bd3] as soon as possible. If we manage to get our bishop to [f5] first, we equalise easily.} exd5 6. Bg5 {This is the most common move here, and is typical for this structure. It is more effective with the pawn on [e3], though, as White would have had the chance to meet the move ...[Bf5] with [Qf3]. This is a crucial difference in the current position and makes life easy for us. I want to highlight the main difference between the critical exchange variation in the QGD and our version of the same: 2...e6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Bg5 c6 6.e3 Bf5 7.Qf3! This is the key move, which is possible with the inclusion of the move [e3] instead of [Nf3]. 7...Bg6 8.Bxf6 ⩲ (White manages to cripple our pawn structure on the kingside. You can check out the famous game Carlsen-Kramnik 2016 where White perfectly exploited the doubled pawns.)} h6 {It is always good to force White to make a decision early regarding their bishop. This also creates a luft for our own bishop on [h7].} 7. Bh4 Bf5 {This is an important move that we have seen several times already. We get our bishop to its most active square. If we can develop normally, we will end up taking over the position as we have the semi-open e-file.} 8. e3 {This is the standard move, but it has much less bite as our bishop is already on [f5].} Nbd7 {We do not know yet the best square for our dark-squared bishop, so we play a more necessary move first.} 9. Bd3 {This is not the best exchange for White, but it would be even worse to let our bishop enjoy control over the [b1]-[h7] diagonal.} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 {Both bishop moves are possible, but I want to make sure that White does not get the move [e4] easily. We will follow our usual plan of getting the knight to [e4] in a couple of moves.} 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 a5 {Any attempt to go for the [b4] advance is delayed by our ...[a5].} 13. Qc2 Re8 14. Rab1 {We are following an online rapid game between Wojtascek and Praggnanandhaa.} Bd6 {Now that [e4] is no longer in the picture, I prefer to put the bishop on its most active square. This also gives us the [e7]-square for the queen.} 15. Rfc1 Qe7 $10 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf6e4,Gb2b4,Ga5b4,Gb7b5] We can continue with ...[g5] and ...[Ne4] next. We will focus more on the kingside and the centre. I am not sure what White is intending to do on the queenside. A future [b4] break will likely be met with a capture followed by ...[b5], fixing the pawn structure in our favour.} *

