1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 (3. cxd5 {The dreaded Exchange Slav. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game. Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to go for the more complex option, if it is objectively fine for Black. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines. 3...cxd5 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Bf4 Nc6 6.Nf3 a6 (I wanted to offer something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; and B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and [Ne2]. The pawn on [a6] covers the [b5]-square and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to go for the move [b5] in the future.)}) 3... Nf6 4. e3 ({(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These lines are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of them if you are going for the 2...e6 move order, but that has its own theory. I believe that)} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. It defends the pawn on [c4], but restricts the dark-squared bishop on [c1].}) (4. Qc2 {White defends the [c4]-pawn with their queen. We've seen this earlier, with the inclusion of the moves [Nc3] and ...[a6]. Here, White has not committed the knight to [c3] yet. This gives White more flexibility and they can get the knight to [d2] in some cases.} g6 $1 {We do not want to release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5] soon. These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was thinking about. I feel there are a lot of pluses to this approach to justify more work. The line is pretty easy to learn and we equalise without too much effort.}) (4. Qb3 {This is a slightly inferior version of the lines with [Qc2]. The queen is a bit worse placed here.} e6 $1 {We maintain the tension as the queen on [b3] is not doing much at the moment. We will continue developing our pieces for now.}) (4. g3 {We saw the Fianchetto system in the Semi-Slav already, but now we are seeing it a move earlier. This is more flexible, as the [b1]-knight does not need to go to [c3]. However, the drawback is that we are able to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} Bf5 {The bishop is well placed here along this diagonal. We will go ...[e6] next and get solid control over the centre. The bishop on [g2] is not a great piece when the centre remains closed.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop out of the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the knight to [c3] yet makes a big difference. This knight can go to [d2], which makes development easier for White. The move 4...e6 was recommended by Shankland for Black, but it was one of the very few lines in his course which I was not satisfied with.}) (4... Bg4 {is another option here, and was recommended by Sethuraman in his course. However, we often have to give up our bishop by taking on [f3], which I am not a big fan of.}) 5. Nc3 e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5].} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. Our bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. The game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble as the move [f3] is useful for White to control the centre and advance on the kingside.} *

