{We move on to another important system and will start with a game of the current World no.2.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 {This is the advantage we gain because White played 4.e3 instead of developing the knight to [c3]. At the same time, our queenside is a bit more exposed, and White will go after our bishop on [f5].} 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 {Black should provoke the move [f3].} 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 Be7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 ({Here} 10. Qb3 {is the main move.}) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O-O {White often castles queenside in this line. They feel more confident as they have the bishop pair advantage. However, we have the advantage of not having committed our king to either side yet. We can start our play on the queenside immediately.} a6 12. g4 dxc4 {We trade on [c4] to open up some of the files on the queenside.} 13. Bxc4 b5 14. Be2 c5 15. d5 {White keeps the c-file closed for now, but we get a dangerous majority on the queenside.} (15. Kb1 {gives us the open c-file:} cxd4 16. exd4 Rc8 {↑}) 15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. f4 b4 18. e4 d4 (18... c4 $1 {is my recommendation in the theory chapter.}) 19. e5 $2 (19. Kb1 {would have been better, to get the king out of the line of fire, but I still prefer Black after} Nb6 {↑}) 19... Nb6 $6 (19... c4 $1 {was very good for Black. We are happy to give up a pawn or two to open the position.} 20. Bxc4 Nb6 {∓}) 20. e6 $2 {White tries to attack, but it is harmless.} (20. Qe4 {was important to get some counterplay. Black has to trade queens now:} Qd5 21. Qxd5 Nxd5 22. h4 {⇆}) 20... Qd5 {Now Black takes full control over the position and the game is objectively over.} 21. exf7+ Kf8 22. h4 Qxa2 (22... c4 {-+ was stronger.}) 23. Qxg6 b3 24. Be1 c4 25. Rxd4 Na4 26. Qb1 Ba3 $1 {A nice finishing touch to the attack.} 27. Qxa2 bxa2 28. Kc2 Rb8 $1 {Black wants to give a check on [b2] and then queen the pawn.} 29. Rd8+ Rxd8 30. bxa3 c3 31. Bg3 Rd2+ 32. Kb3 Nc5+ {A nice miniature, which shows how dangerous our attack could be on the queenside.} 0-1

