{We've seen a game of the World Champion in the Botvinnik section, and now we will see a game of the World Championship Challenger.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 Qc7 9. Bd2 dxc4 (9... Be7 {is my recommended move in my course, but the game continuation 9...dxc4 will transpose back to our theory section later.}) 10. Bxc4 a6 11. Be2 (11. Rc1 {is an extra option for White via this move order.} b5 12. Be2 {⩲}) 11... Be7 12. O-O-O b5 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Kb1 c5 15. dxc5 Nbd7 16. h4 (16. g4 {is a better move, and we will see this in our theoretical chapter.}) 16... Nxc5 17. Qc2 Rc8 18. g4 Qb8 19. Rc1 (19. a3 {is necessary here. However, it feels very risky to allow Black to potentially open the b-file.} O-O {↑}) 19... O-O 20. h5 g5 $1 {We keep the h-file closed for now.} 21. h6 $6 {White's attack is not fast enough. These positions are pretty hard to evaluate over the board as it can change drastically every move.} g6 {This is not a bad move, and is very natural. However, it was even better to just ignore all the threats on the kingside.} (21... b4 {We can just ignore White's play on the kingside here.} 22. hxg7 Kxg7 23. Bc4 Rfd8 {-+}) 22. h7+ (22. a3 $1 {Now, it is not easy for Black to continue the attack on the queenside, but we can continue more slowly with a good edge.} Rfd8 {⩱}) 22... Kh8 23. a3 Rfd8 24. b4 Nb3 $1 {We win the important dark-squared bishop and get the rook to the 7th rank in one go.} 25. Qxb3 Rxd2 26. Rhd1 Rxd1 27. Nxd1 Rxc1+ 28. Kxc1 Kxh7 (28... Nd5 {-+ was even better to dominate White's pieces.}) 29. Kd2 Qa7 30. Qd3 Nd7 31. Nc3 Qc7 32. Ne4 f5 33. Qc3 Qb7 34. Nf2 Bf6 35. Qb3 Qc6 36. Qc2 Qd6+ 37. Qd3 Qe7 38. Ke1 Kg7 39. Qb3 Nb6 40. e4 Bd4 {We finally get to dominate the dark squares. Black was not playing the most precise moves, but it is very hard to play as White, defending such a position with opposite colour bishops on the board.} 41. Qd3 Qf6 42. Nh3 Na4 $2 {Black goes for the wrong plan, allowing White to equalise.} (42... fxe4 $1 43. Qxe4 Nd5 {-+}) 43. exf5 gxf5 44. Kf1 e5 45. gxf5 Qh6 46. f4 $2 {This was too creative. White had to consolidate by putting his king on [g2].} (46. Kg2) 46... gxf4 47. Qf3 e4 $1 48. f6+ Kxf6 49. Qxf4+ Qxf4+ 50. Nxf4 Nb6 51. Bd1 Bb2 52. Bc2 Ke5 53. Ng6+ Kd4 54. Ne7 Bxa3 55. Nc6+ Ke3 56. Nb8 Bxb4 57. Nxa6 Bd6 58. Ke1 Nd5 59. Bb3 Nc3 {It was not a smooth game by any means, but Black was in control throughout. He was never in any trouble and kept posing problems to White.} 0-1

