{Next up is a game of the current World no.4, Arjun Erigaisi. The advantage of recommending such a fundamentally strong opening is that we have a huge choice of top-level games to analyze.} 1. c4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 {This early queen move is a popular sideline. White wants to get good control over the centre. All the other authors recommend taking on [c4] here, as it reduces their workload. However, in this course I recommend a more principled move.} g6 {We want to exploit the queen on [c2] with the bishop coming to [f5] soon. Another point is that we want to open the centre and activate the bishop on [g7].} 5. Bf4 Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Nc3 c5 $1 {This is the best plan here, which allows Black to equalise and potentially take over the game. We are exploiting the fact that White's king is still in the centre.} 8. cxd5 {This is not a great idea, especially with the bishop on [f4].} (8. dxc5 {is a better try, but Black can equalise with} Qa5) 8... cxd4 9. exd4 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 {We are playing against the IQP on [d4] now.} 11. Bc4 Qf5 (11... Qa5+ {was maybe a bit better. We will see this in the theoretical chapter.}) 12. Qxf5 Bxf5 13. Bd5 Nc6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 {We reach a very comfortable endgame with the bishop pair. Also, we are planning to go ...[c5] next and open the long diagonal.} 15. Ne5 c5 16. dxc5 Rac8 17. c6 (17. b4 {is met with} Rfd8 {∓ with a big advantage, as we can go ...[Rd4] next.}) 17... f6 (17... g5 {was better to force the bishop back first.} 18. Bg3 f6 {-+ and we win the [c6] pawn next.}) 18. Nf3 $2 {White is playing too passively here.} (18. Nd7 $1 Rfe8 19. Rc1 e5 20. Be3 {This is the key difference here. Now, the rook on [c1] is defended by the bishop on [e3] and White is fine. Such details are easy to miss in a game.}) 18... e5 19. Be3 Rxc6 20. O-O a6 21. Rfc1 Rfc8 22. Rxc6 Rxc6 23. Rc1 Rxc1+ 24. Bxc1 {This is a terrible endgame for White. The two bishops are particularly strong in the endgame because they are able to play on both sides of the board and restrict the opponent's king effectively.} Kf7 25. Be3 Ke6 26. Nd2 Kd5 27. f3 Bd3 28. Kf2 f5 29. b4 Bc2 30. Bc5 Ba4 31. Nf1 Kc4 32. Ne3+ Kd3 33. Nd5 Bh6 34. f4 exf4 $2 (34... e4 $1 {was better. It is the more logical move but I guess Black was worried that White could blockade the [e4] pawn.} 35. g3 Bg7 36. Ne3 Bb2 37. Be7 Bc1 38. Bc5 Ba3 {-+ We can bring our bishop to [e6] next. Another plan is to go ...[a5] next.}) 35. Nc7 Bb5 36. Bd6 Ke4 37. a4 $1 {White manages to simplify the position by trading the a-pawns.} Bxa4 38. Nxa6 Kd5 39. Bb8 g5 40. Nc7+ Kc6 41. Ne6 Kd5 42. Nc7+ Ke5 43. h4 g4 44. Nb5+ Kf6 45. Nd4 f3 46. gxf3 Bf8 47. Kg3 h5 48. Kf4 Bh6+ 49. Kg3 Bf8 50. Kf4 Bh6+ 51. Kg3 Bd2 52. Bd6 (52. b5 {was a pretty easy draw:} Bc3 53. Ba7 Ke5 54. Nc6+) 52... Bc3 53. Bc5 Ke5 54. fxg4 $2 {A blunder in time trouble. This was not an easy decision, though.} (54. Ne2 $2 {loses to} Be1+ 55. Kg2 f4 {-+}) (54. f4+ $1 {It looks scary to put all these pawns on the dark-squares, but White is able to hold the pawns and the position.} Ke4 55. Ne2 {⩱}) 54... Bxd4 55. gxh5 f4+ 56. Kh2 Bxc5 57. bxc5 0-1

