1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 {We will see the move [g3] in many instances throughout the course. If White has played [c4] and also the move [Nc3], we take on [c4]. Otherwise, we typically bring the bishop out to [f5].} Bf5 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O h6 {This is the standard move in these positions, in order to create a luft for the bishop on [h7].} 6. c4 c6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. c5 {This is a prevalent theme across all levels. In most cases, Black is fine as the queenside is fully blocked. The only danger is if White gets to go [b4]-[b5] very quickly, creating play on the queenside.} Qxb3 10. axb3 O-O 11. b4 a6 {This is accurate, stopping White's play on the queenside.} (11... Nbd7 {might be a slight inaccuracy, as it allows} 12. b5 {↑}) 12. h3 (12. b5 cxb5 13. Nxb5 Nc6 14. Nc3 Nd7 {↑ Black is taking over here with ...[b6] to follow next.}) (12. Nd2 {was played in my game.} Bc2 $1 {(is an important move to stop the knight manoeuvre to [a5]. I got a huge advantage in my game- ½-½ Aravindh,C 2641-Arjun,K 2503 Riga Tech op-A 2021.)}) 12... Nbd7 13. g4 Bh7 14. Bf4 g5 $1 {With the pawn structure fixed on the queenside, Black needs to try to create something on the kingside or the centre.} 15. Bh2 h5 $1 {We are opening up the kingside immediately.} (15... Ne4 {is another plan, preparing to go ...[f5] next.}) 16. Nxg5 (16. gxh5 Nxh5 {⩱}) 16... hxg4 17. Nxh7 Kxh7 {White wins the bishop, but now we can bring our rooks over to the open files on the kingside.} 18. Rfd1 gxh3 19. Bxh3 Rg8+ 20. Kf1 Ng4 21. Bg1 Rg6 {We are bringing our rooks into the game along the g-file. White has to create his own play somewhere.} 22. e4 dxe4 23. Nxe4 Rag8 24. Ke2 Ndf6 (24... Rh6 {⩱ was better, forcing White to either take on [g4] or retreat.}) 25. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {[%csl Gd5] We have managed to get a beautiful square in the middle of the board for the knight. White's bishops are completely misplaced on the kingside. The attempt to open the position with [e4] has only backfired.} 26. Bh2 Nd5 (26... Rh6 {was again a better try, after which White has to find the only move} 27. Rh1 $3 Nd5 {⩱ (27...Rxh3 28.Bd6=)}) 27. Rd3 $2 (27. Bg3 {is important, followed by [Bg2xd5] next.}) 27... Bf6 28. Rad1 Rh6 {Now Black is winning material by force because of the bishops on the h-file.} 29. Bd6 Bxd4 30. Bf5+ exf5 31. Rxd4 Rg4 32. Rxg4 fxg4 33. b5 Re6+ 34. Kf1 axb5 {Black played very well to create quick play on the kingside. We need to play dynamic chess in this structure to compensate for White's space advantage on the queenside.} 0-1

