1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn, which is a target when we have developed our light-squared bishop on the kingside.} Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gb6b3,Ge4c2] We need to understand the difference in the move orders. In the main line with the inclusion of the moves [f3] and ...[Bg6], we put the queen on [c7]. Here, the main point is that we can meet [f3] with a capture on [b3] followed by ...[Bc2].} 8. Bd2 {This is a better try for White, maintaining the tension for now.} Na6 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3][%cal Gb6b3,Ga6b4] We anticipate a capture on [b3] in the future and are ready to jump to [b4] with the knight. This would create a lot of threats with White's king still on [e1].} 9. Be2 Qxb3 10. axb3 Nb4 11. O-O Bd3 $10 {[%cal Gf6e4] We trade White's best minor piece for our bad bishop. We can also play ...[Ne4] and trade off a few more pieces. Our king is well placed in the centre.} *

