1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. g3 {White defends the knight on [h4], hinting at maintaining the tension for a while. It also keeps White's kingside more secure.} Be7 9. Bd2 O-O $1 {Rarely do we castle so early, but White has played pretty slowly so far and is lagging in development. We want to start our play in the centre and on the queenside.} 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qb3 dxc4 $1 {We do not mind giving up the pawn on [b7] for the initiative.} 12. Qxb7 c5 $1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gd8d7,Gb8c6,Rb7a8] White cannot win the rook on [a8] without getting their queen trapped. Next, we will play ...[Nd7] followed by ...[Rb8], going after the [b2]-pawn.} 13. Bxc4 (13. Qxa8 {is met with} Qd7 {∓ , trapping the queen with ...[Nc6] to follow.}) 13... cxd4 (13... cxd4 {Now,} 14. Qxa8 {is met with} dxc3 $1 15. Bxc3 Qb6 {and the queen is in real danger of getting trapped.}) 14. exd4 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd4,Gd5,Re1][%cal Gd7b6] We will play ...[Nb6] next and play against the weak pawn on [d4]. The white king is stuck in the centre, which gives us more than enough compensation for the pawn.} *

