1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Bd2 {White prepares to get the king over to the queenside. This is the more aggressive plan in these positions: opposite-side castling.} Be7 {This is the standard square for our bishop, keeping an eye on the [h4]-knight.} 9. Nxg6 {The white queen is heading to [c2], so White needs to eliminate our bishop. This opens up the h-file for our rook, though.} hxg6 10. Qc2 {We should compare the queens on [b3] and [c2]. White's queen is more active on [b3], targeting the [b7]-pawn. We typically capture on [c4] and start playing on the queenside with ...[b5] and ...[c5]. The queen is generally more vulnerable in these lines along the c-file. However, the major advantage of the queen on [c2] is that the move ...[dxc4] will not come with a tempo. So compared to the main line, White can try some different ideas.} (10. Qb3 {will transpose after} Qc7 {to later variations.}) 10... Nbd7 {We usually do not move the knight from [b8] so early, since it might be able to go to [c6] directly. However, with the queen on [c2], the lines with [cxd5] are not as critical.} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Qb3 {White has wasted a full tempo moving the queen twice. This has been played by Gelfand and Praggnanandhaa as White.} O-O 13. Bd3 Nb6 {We want to get our knight to [c4] very soon. Once that happens, White will have to give up one of their bishops.} 14. O-O Qd7 $10 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gb6c4] We will continue with ...[Rfc8] next. White will probably trade off all the rooks on the c-file and reach an equal endgame.} *

