eir pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Bd2 {White prepares to get the king over to the queenside. This is the more aggressive plan in these positions: opposite-side castling.} Be7 {This is the standard square for our bishop, keeping an eye on the [h4]-knight.} 9. Nxg6 {The white queen is heading to [c2], so White needs to eliminate our bishop. This opens up the h-file for our rook, though.} hxg6 10. Qc2 {We should compare the queens on [b3] and [c2]. White's queen is more active on [b3], targeting the [b7]-pawn. We typically capture on [c4] and start playing on the queenside with ...[b5] and ...[c5]. The queen is generally more vulnerable in these lines along the c-file. However, the major advantage of the queen on [c2] is that the move ...[dxc4] will not come with a tempo. So compared to the main line, White can try some different ideas.} (10. Qb3 {will transpose after} Qc7 {to later variations.}) 10... Nbd7 {We usually do not move the knight from [b8] so early, since it might be able to go to [c6] directly. However, with the queen on [c2], the lines with [cxd5] are not as critical.} 11. O-O-O {This is the critical plan after both of White's queen moves.} dxc4 ({We release the tension, starting our play on the queenside. Our king is reasonably safe on e8 and we can castle anytime. I like this direct plan more compared to the more common move} 11... a6 {.}) 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 {The bishop is better off on [e2], away from our eventual ...[c4] advance.} a6 {We defend the [b5]-pawn to prepare the ...[c5] break. White has a few ways of reacting to this.} 14. e4 {This has been played by the World Champion in online chess. White is preparing to meet our break with the [d5] advance. Keep in mind that in the long run, White is better in these positions. They have the bishop pair and control over the centre.} c5 15. d5 {This is the critical reply. White opens the centre while keeping the queenside closed.} exd5 16. Nxd5 {White trades the knights off, which makes sense as we could play ...[b4] at any moment, kicking White's knight away.} (16. exd5 {is met with} Qc7 {followed by ...[Nb6] next.}) 16... Nxd5 17. exd5 Nb6 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gb6a4] I like the knight on [b6] compared to [f6], which is where the knight went in the game between Ding, L and Lei, T. We keep the [f6]-square for the bishop instead.} 18. Ba5 O-O 19. h4 Qd6 {It is important to blockade the [d5]-pawn. The queen is famously a bad blockader, but there is no other option in the current position. Our bishop needs to go to [f6] next to keep control over the kingside.} 20. h5 gxh5 21. g4 h4 {This is possible as we can start our play on the queenside pretty quickly. White cannot play [f4] yet.} 22. Kb1 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gg4g5] White is threatening to play [f4] and [g5] now. We have to be quick.} Nc4 $1 23. Bxc4 bxc4 24. Qxc4 Rab8 $10 {We give back the pawn and open the b-file in return. The position remains complex, but we are in no way worse.} *

