eir pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Bd2 {White prepares to get the king over to the queenside. This is the more aggressive plan in these positions: opposite-side castling.} Be7 {This is the standard square for our bishop, keeping an eye on the [h4]-knight.} 9. Nxg6 {The white queen is heading to [c2], so White needs to eliminate our bishop. This opens up the h-file for our rook, though.} hxg6 10. Qc2 {We should compare the queens on [b3] and [c2]. White's queen is more active on [b3], targeting the [b7]-pawn. We typically capture on [c4] and start playing on the queenside with ...[b5] and ...[c5]. The queen is generally more vulnerable in these lines along the c-file. However, the major advantage of the queen on [c2] is that the move ...[dxc4] will not come with a tempo. So compared to the main line, White can try some different ideas.} (10. Qb3 {will transpose after} Qc7 {to later variations.}) 10... Nbd7 {We usually do not move the knight from [b8] so early, since it might be able to go to [c6] directly. However, with the queen on [c2], the lines with [cxd5] are not as critical.} 11. O-O-O {This is the critical plan after both of White's queen moves.} dxc4 ({We release the tension, starting our play on the queenside. Our king is reasonably safe on e8 and we can castle anytime. I like this direct plan more compared to the more common move} 11... a6 {.}) 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 {The bishop is better off on [e2], away from our eventual ...[c4] advance.} a6 {We defend the [b5]-pawn to prepare the ...[c5] break. White has a few ways of reacting to this.} 14. g4 {This is in the spirit of the position. White is looking to create some play on the kingside. We have to be quick with our counterplay.} c5 15. g5 {White wants to force our knight to [d5], after which they can transform the structure. This was played in the game between Ghosh, D and Caruana, F, 2023.} cxd4 $1 {This is an important inclusion, opening up the c-file.} ({Fabi went wrong with} 15... Nd5 {as after} 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. h4 {± White's play on the kingside is much easier without the knight on [f6].}) 16. exd4 b4 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6d5] Another important move, kicking the knight on [c3]. We want to occupy the [d5]-square next, which would give us a big advantage. This is the usual reaction to the move [g5] in these lines.} 17. gxf6 {White cannot allow us to get the [d5]-square for free. Instead, the position is simplified forcefully.} bxc3 18. fxe7 cxd2+ 19. Qxd2 Qxe7 $36 {[%csl Rc1,Re2][%cal Gd4d5,Ge6d5,Gd2d5,Ge8g8] White has to liquidate their isolated d-pawn with [d5] next, after which we reach an equal position. I believe that practically we have much better chances, as White's king is quite exposed.} *

