eir pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Bd2 {White prepares to get the king over to the queenside. This is the more aggressive plan in these positions: opposite-side castling.} Be7 {This is the standard square for our bishop, keeping an eye on the [h4]-knight.} 9. Nxg6 {The white queen is heading to [c2], so White needs to eliminate our bishop. This opens up the h-file for our rook, though.} hxg6 10. Qc2 {We should compare the queens on [b3] and [c2]. White's queen is more active on [b3], targeting the [b7]-pawn. We typically capture on [c4] and start playing on the queenside with ...[b5] and ...[c5]. The queen is generally more vulnerable in these lines along the c-file. However, the major advantage of the queen on [c2] is that the move ...[dxc4] will not come with a tempo. So compared to the main line, White can try some different ideas.} (10. Qb3 {will transpose after} Qc7 {to later variations.}) 10... Nbd7 {We usually do not move the knight from [b8] so early, since it might be able to go to [c6] directly. However, with the queen on [c2], the lines with [cxd5] are not as critical.} 11. O-O-O {This is the critical plan after both of White's queen moves.} dxc4 ({We release the tension, starting our play on the queenside. Our king is reasonably safe on e8 and we can castle anytime. I like this direct plan more compared to the more common move} 11... a6 {.}) 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 {The bishop is better off on [e2], away from our eventual ...[c4] advance.} a6 {We defend the [b5]-pawn to prepare the ...[c5] break. White has a few ways of reacting to this.} 14. Kb1 {This is the most common move in the position. It makes sense, as you are generally supposed to go for the most necessary move first. In all the lines we've seen so far, White had to waste a move moving the king at some point or another.} c5 {Our play remains the same in all lines.} 15. dxc5 {A natural move, but not a critical one as it allows us to create play along the c-file.} Nxc5 16. e4 {White gets a good static position, but we have good attacking chances on the queenside.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gc5e4,Rc7c2] This is a clever move, stopping White from playing [f4].} 17. h4 ({Now} 17. f4 {fails to} Ncxe4 {∓ and we win a full pawn.}) 17... Rc8 18. g4 Nfd7 {We do not need to castle yet, although the engine is happy to do so. We should play the more necessary move first. White is going to play [g5] at some point, and our knight needs to head back.} 19. g5 Bd6 $10 {[%cal Gd6e5,Ge5f4] This bishop will be amazing on [e5] or [f4]. We have very good control over the dark squares. We can consider going ...[Qb8] followed by ...[b4], with play on the c-file.} *

