1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. Rc1 {White gives up the plan to castle queenside and instead prepares to play along the c-file.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re7h4,Rh4e1] This is the main move in the position, completing our development. We do not need to be worried about the [d5]-pawn. Our threat now is to play ...[Ne4], exploiting White's knight on [h4] which will fall with check.} 11. cxd5 (11. g3 {transposes to upcoming lines after} dxc4 12. Bxc4 O-O {.}) 11... Nxd5 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge7h4] We force White to open up the h-file for our rook.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. g3 {White defends the pawn on [h2], but this is pretty slow and creates some weaknesses on the kingside with the half-open h-file.} Nxc3 14. Bxc3 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6g3,Rh8h1] We are threatening to take on [g3] now. It is very hard for White to defend the pawn.} 15. f4 {This is a tempting move, blocking our bishop. However, it is pretty loose and it gives us more resources to attack White.} (15. Bg2 {still allows us to play} Rxh2 {and we win a pawn.}) (15. Kf2 {runs into} Bxg3+ $1 {.}) 15... g5 $1 16. Bg2 gxf4 17. exf4 Nf6 $36 {[%csl Re3,Rh2][%cal Gf6g4] This knight is heading to [g4] and will be eyeing the dark squares in White's camp. We also have the other g-pawn, which can be pushed to attack White's [f4]-pawn. Our king is pretty safe and we can castle queenside at any moment.} *

