1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. g3 {We have seen this idea in previous lines. White stops the immediate threat of ...[Ne4] and defends the [h4]-knight. It keeps the [h2]-pawn more secure.} O-O {As White is playing slowly, there is no need for us to delay castling. We will start our play on the queenside soon.} 11. g4 {White has wasted a tempo by going [g2]-[g3]-[g4], but they made us commit to castling kingside. I don't think this is worth a tempo, though, as the position is pretty dynamic.} dxc4 {We go for our standard plan in these positions.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Be2 {The advantage of the bishop on [e2] is that our move ...[c4] will not come with a tempo. However, the bishop is less active on [e2] compared to [d3].} (14. Bd3 {is met with the same plan:} b4 15. Na4 c5 {⇆ .}) 14... b4 15. Na4 Nbd7 16. Rc1 c5 $1 {We give up a pawn on the queenside, but we will get a few tempi in return for it.} 17. Qxb4 {Taking up the challenge. This is the only way for White to fight for an advantage.} Nd5 18. Qb3 a5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc7a7] We need the [a7]-square for the queen in order to put pressure on [d4]. The knight on [d5] does a good job in the middle of the board.} 19. O-O Qa7 20. e4 Rfb8 21. Qd1 Nb4 $10 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gb4a2] We are threatening to take on [d4] next. Also, the pawn on [a2] is hanging if White defends [d4]. We get good counterplay on the dark squares.} *

