eir pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. g3 {We have seen this idea in previous lines. White stops the immediate threat of ...[Ne4] and defends the [h4]-knight. It keeps the [h2]-pawn more secure.} O-O {As White is playing slowly, there is no need for us to delay castling. We will start our play on the queenside soon.} 11. Nxg6 {White trades on [g6] after we have castled kingside, which makes sense.} hxg6 12. Bg2 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2] This has been played in a few games, but the bishop is misplaced on [g2]. Putting the bishop on [g2] is rarely a good idea in the Slav, and here the bishop is further restricted by the [f3]-pawn.} dxc4 13. Qxc4 Nbd7 14. O-O e5 {This would have been dangerous with the bishop on [c4] or [d3], but in this case it works perfectly.} 15. Rfd1 Nb6 16. Qd3 Rad8 $10 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge5d4] We will take on [d4] soon leaving White with a weak IQP, and we get an amazing square on [d5] for the knight.} *

