reason why White played the early [e4]. They are able to get the pawn to [d5].} Nc5 {This is the ideal square for the knight. We can bring the other knight back to [d7].} 15. Qc2 b5 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Be2 cxd5 {Having forced the bishop back, we can go after the pawn on [d5]. This does weaken our [b5]-pawn, though.} 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 Rfc8 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc7d7,Gc7b7] We will move the queen to [d7] or [b7] next and then target the [d5]-pawn.} 20. Bxb5 {This is the only way to pose some problems for us.} Rab8 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gb8b2]} 21. Bc4 (21. Bc6 $2 {is not possible due to} Rxb2 {-+ with a fork on [d3].}) 21... Nb7 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb7d6,Gd6c4] We can get our knight to [d6] and eliminate White's light-squared bishop. White's king is more exposed, and we have enough compensation with our active pieces. It is hard for White to hold on to the d-pawn and keep their king safe at the same time.} *

