1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. Nxg6 {This trade can happen on several different moves, but we will look at those lines only via this move order.} hxg6 11. O-O-O {We already saw the plan of castling kingside in the previous lines. Instead, castling queenside is the most testing plan for White. If you recall, we saw similar lines with the queen on [c2] instead of [b3]. There we were not forced to go for the move ...[Qc7], though.} dxc4 {We trade immediately, not giving White any extra options. As I've mentioned earlier, with the queen on [b3] the plan of ...[c5]-[c4] will come with a tempo, and is what we are aiming for.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {We waste no time and immediately start preparing the move ...[c5]. Our king is safe on [e8] for now.} 14. Qc2 {This is a strange move, which was played by Topalov against Shirov in 2021. White wastes a tempo by going back to [c2].} c5 15. Ne4 {This is White's point. They want to get the queen to the centre.} Nxe4 16. Qxe4 cxd4+ (16... Qc6 {was an inaccurate response by Shirov in the aforementioned game.}) 17. Kb1 Nc6 {We want to force White to recapture on [d4] with the e-pawn, damaging the pawn structure.} 18. Rc1 Rc8 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf8d8] Our plan is to castle next and bring our rook to the d-file.} 19. f4 $5 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gf3c6,Gc1c6] White is preparing the move [Bf3], targeting the [c6]-knight.} Qd6 $10 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gf7f5,Ge8f7]} (19... Qd6 {This is an important move, as we not only move the queen away from the c-file but also prepare to meet} 20. Bf3 {with} f5 {followed by putting the king on [f7].}) *

