eir pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. Nxg6 {This trade can happen on several different moves, but we will look at those lines only via this move order.} hxg6 11. O-O-O {We already saw the plan of castling kingside in the previous lines. Instead, castling queenside is the most testing plan for White. If you recall, we saw similar lines with the queen on [c2] instead of [b3]. There we were not forced to go for the move ...[Qc7], though.} dxc4 {We trade immediately, not giving White any extra options. As I've mentioned earlier, with the queen on [b3] the plan of ...[c5]-[c4] will come with a tempo, and is what we are aiming for.} 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 a6 {We waste no time and immediately start preparing the move ...[c5]. Our king is safe on [e8] for now.} 14. Ne4 {This is the main move in the position, asking us to improve White's pawn structure in the centre. We do not have much of a choice, as otherwise it is harder to get the move ...[c5] in.} Nxe4 15. fxe4 {White's f-pawn has moved towards the centre. This also gives White the [f3]-square for the bishop.} c5 16. Kb1 (16. d5 {is not a good idea here due to} c4 {⩱ . We will close the centre with ...[e5] next, and then bring our knight to [c5]. The pawns on [e3] and [e4] become a weakness for White.}) 16... Nc6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd4d5] We want White to push the pawns in the centre, as that would create weaknesses for us to exploit. White's central formation is similar to hanging pawns, which we see in many [d4] middlegames. The pawns are strong when they are on the same rank in the middle of the board. But the very second that one of the pawns moves forward, a hole is created for the opponent to utilize.} 17. e5 {This is a better structure for White as they can use the backward e-pawn to control [d5]. Their d-pawn is still under fire, though.} Rc8 {We get the rook out of the long diagonal and threaten to take the pawn on [d4].} (17... cxd4 {is met with} 18. Bf3 {⩲ and there is pressure along the long diagonal, with [Rc1] to follow.}) 18. Bf3 O-O 19. Rc1 {White makes sure that we cannot go after the [d4]-pawn for now, but that is not our only plan.} Na5 {The knight is heading to [c4] from where it will create a lot of headache for White.} 20. Bxa5 Qxa5 $10 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gc5d4,Ga5d2] We've traded off one of the bishops and will now look to push our pawns on the queenside with ...[c4] and ...[b4]. We can also trade on [d4] now.} *

