1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {(We are moving on from the Semi-Slav to some of the sidelines in the Slav. These are pretty topical, as they avoid two major systems the Semi-Slav and the Classical Slav. You can avoid all of these sidelines for White if you are playing the ) 2...e6 move order, but that has its own set of theory.} ({I believe that} 4. e3 {is a critical test, and the most testing option other than the main lines in the Semi-Slav. This move defends the pawn on [c4] but restricts the dark-squared bishop.}) 4... Bf5 {We go for the principled option, exploiting the drawback of the move 4.e3. White is not putting pressure on [d5], which allows us to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} (4... e6 {is the natural response for a Semi-Slav player. However, the fact that White has not committed the queenside knight to [c3] makes a big difference. The knight can go to [d2] instead, which makes development easier for White.}) 5. Nc3 {White commits the knight to [c3] and prepares to take on [d5] followed by [Qb3], putting pressure on [d5]. We will look at the critical line in this chapter and then move on to the sidelines next.} e6 {We get our usual pawn structure, but with the bishop more active on [f5]. Now, if White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the e-pawn, transposing into the structures we saw in the previous theory chapter.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only way to fight for an advantage, going after our active bishop. This bishop is active but not very safe on [f5]. Now the game is getting dynamic.} Be4 {We force White to create some weaknesses if they want to win our light-squared bishop. However, at the same time, this is a risky gamble, as White's move [f3] is useful to control the centre and to advance on the kingside.} 7. f3 {A necessary but double-edged move. It helps White gain space but at the same time weakens their kingside.} Bg6 {White can win the bishop on [g6] anytime at their leisure. They have to choose how to develop their pieces and where their king is going.} 8. Qb3 {White goes after our [b7]-pawn now that the light-squared bishop is out of the picture.} Qc7 {We go for the principled move, keeping the queens on the board when White has created some weaknesses on their kingside.} (8... Qb6 {is the usual reaction to [Qb3] in most lines of the Slav. However, things are different here, as White is going to win our light-squared bishop on [g6]. I do not want to trade queens without the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {⩲ I feel these positions are unpleasant to play practically.}) 9. Bd2 {Now there are several different plans for White. They can castle queenside next and tuck the king away on [b1]. Another dangerous plan is to take on [d5] and then castle queenside. White can also keep the king in the centre for now and put the queenside rook on [c1]. There is also the question of the tension on the kingside with our bishop and White's knight.} Be7 {I want to keep the queenside knight on [b8] for now. If White takes on [d5], we will recapture with the c-pawn and get our knight to [c6].} 10. cxd5 {White decides to release the tension on the queenside, stopping our plan of taking on [c4] followed by ...[b5]. This is the reason why we have maintained our knight on [b8] until now.} cxd5 (10... exd5 $6 {is not good after} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. O-O-O {± .}) 11. Nxg6 {White will have to trade on [g6] at some point or the other. They want to tuck the king on [b1], where it is reasonably safe. This exchange does open the h-file for our rook, though.} hxg6 12. O-O-O {This is the only plan we need to check here. I got crushed comprehensively in this line back in 2017 when I was exclusively playing the Slav move order. The variation was published by Avrukh in one of his White repertoire books, and it got very popular pretty quickly. White's play is easy to understand while it is not as easy for Black. You need to examine the move order carefully.} Nc6 13. Kb1 a6 {We are preparing to play ...[b5] soon. Our king will remain on [e8] for the foreseeable future.} 14. Rc1 {[%cal Rc1c7,Rb8b5,Gc3b5] White stops our plan of ...[b5], as now there is a lot of pressure on the knight on [c6].} Rc8 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gb7b5,Gc6a5] We are again preparing to play ...[b5], this time by defending the knight on [c6]. We still need to prepare the move ...[b5] further with ...[Nd7] next, to counter the pin along the [a4]-[e8] diagonal.} ({The immediate} 14... b5 $2 {runs into} 15. Nxb5 {+- .}) 15. g4 {White is trying to be aggressive on the kingside, but this only pushes us to execute our plan on the queenside.} Nd7 {The other advantage of this move is that we can get our knight to [a5], kick White's queen back, and follow it up with ...[Nc4]. Earlier, White had the check on [a4].} 16. f4 Na5 17. Qd1 Nc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb2b3,Gc4d2,Ge7b4,Rb4d2] White is not able to kick the knight away as the [c3]-knight is loose.} 18. Bd3 (18. b3 $2 {loses a piece after} Nxd2+ 19. Qxd2 Bb4 {-+ .}) 18... b5 $10 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb5b4,Gf7f5] We have a few different plans. We can get our other knight to [b6] and try to get the move ...[b4] in. A more drastic plan is to go for ...[f5], halting White's play on the kingside.} *

