oon. Our king will remain on [e8] for the foreseeable future.} 14. Rc1 {[%cal Rc1c7,Rb8b5,Gc3b5] White stops our plan of ...[b5], as now there is a lot of pressure on the knight on [c6].} Rc8 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gb7b5,Gc6a5] We are again preparing to play ...[b5], this time by defending the knight on [c6]. We still need to prepare the move ...[b5] further with ...[Nd7] next, to counter the pin along the [a4]-[e8] diagonal.} ({The immediate} 14... b5 $2 {runs into} 15. Nxb5 {+- .}) 15. Be1 {This was played against me by the Dutch GM Max Warmerdam in Aeroflot 2019. Can you see what the drawback of White's move is?} Na5 $1 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc8c1] We no longer need to prepare this with the move ...[Nd7], as the rook on [c1] is hanging.} 16. Qd1 Qd7 {[%csl Ga4] We stop all ideas of Qa4+. I went for the move 16...[Nc4] allowing the queen check, although Warmerdam did not go for this.} 17. h4 Nc4 18. Bxc4 {Something similar happened in my game. I was confused as to how to recapture on [c4].} dxc4 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] This is the better and more ambitious option. I went for the other recapture, which led to a quick draw soon. Here, the play is double-edged with us going for ...[b5]-[b4] while White tries to create play on the kingside and the centre.} *

