1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 {Let us start the chapter with the main move in the position. This time we will look at some sidelines on move 6.} e6 {Keep in mind that we are doing very well in the long-term with our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. The lines where White plays [Nh4] are the only critical ones.} 6. Qb3 {This is an inferior version of the lines we've seen in the previous chapter. White is not close to winning our light-squared bishop, which makes the queen manoeuvre ineffective.} (6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 {will be checked via a different move order.}) 6... Qb6 {We do not mind trading queens currently, as we won't lose our light-squared bishop cheaply. However, keep in mind that we are not planning to take on [b3] in most of the cases.} 7. Nh4 {White goes for the same idea as in the previous chapter, but our bishop has more options now.} Be4 8. f3 $2 {Other moves either transpose or are just harmless.} Qxb3 $1 {We go for this exchange as we are winning a pawn on [b3].} 9. axb3 Bc2 $17 {[%csl Rb3,Rh4][%cal Gg7g5] The knight on [h4] is stuck and the threat is ...[g5], trapping the knight.} *

