1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 {Let us start the chapter with the main move in the position. This time we will look at some sidelines on move 6.} e6 {Keep in mind that we are doing very well in the long-term with our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. The lines where White plays [Nh4] are the only critical ones.} 6. Qb3 {This is an inferior version of the lines we've seen in the previous chapter. White is not close to winning our light-squared bishop, which makes the queen manoeuvre ineffective.} (6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 {will be checked via a different move order.}) 6... Qb6 {We do not mind trading queens currently, as we won't lose our light-squared bishop cheaply. However, keep in mind that we are not planning to take on [b3] in most of the cases.} 7. Be2 {White develops his pieces slowly giving us ample time to finish our development. We are doing well statically here with the bishop out of the pawn chain. White is the one with a passive bishop on [c1].} Nbd7 8. O-O Be7 9. Bd2 (9. Nh4 {is not an issue at all due to} Qxb3 10. axb3 Bc2 {⩱ , either winning the b-pawn or trading the bishops.}) 9... h6 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Gb3b6,Gf3h4] We finally take the time to create a luft for the bishop on [h7]. White was threatening to take on [b6] and follow up with [Nh4].} 10. Rfc1 O-O 11. Na4 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gb7b5,Ga7a6] We could have also traded on [b3], but I prefer keeping more pieces on the board if possible. We will take on [c4] next and go for our typical play with ...[a6] and ...[b5].} *

