1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 {Let us start the chapter with the main move in the position. This time we will look at some sidelines on move 6.} e6 {Keep in mind that we are doing very well in the long-term with our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. The lines where White plays [Nh4] are the only critical ones.} 6. Qb3 {This is an inferior version of the lines we've seen in the previous chapter. White is not close to winning our light-squared bishop, which makes the queen manoeuvre ineffective.} (6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 {will be checked via a different move order.}) 6... Qb6 {We do not mind trading queens currently, as we won't lose our light-squared bishop cheaply. However, keep in mind that we are not planning to take on [b3] in most of the cases.} 7. c5 {White tries to force a capture on [b3].} Qc7 $1 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gb7b6,Ge6e5,Gb8d7] No, thank you! The bishop is stuck on [c1] and our queen is perfect on [c7], preparing a future ...[b6] or ...[e5]. Given another move, we will play ...[h6] and follow up by opening the queenside. The bishop is very well placed on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal.} 8. Nh4 Be4 9. f3 Bg6 10. Bd2 b6 $15 {[%cal Ga7b6,Gc6c5] The pawn on [c5] is a big problem for White, as it's a hook for us to open the queenside very quickly. We will be able to fight for the centre better with ...[c5] ourselves next.} *

