1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 {Let us start the chapter with the main move in the position. This time we will look at some sidelines on move 6.} e6 {Keep in mind that we are doing very well in the long-term with our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. The lines where White plays [Nh4] are the only critical ones.} 6. Be2 {[%cal Gf3h4] White takes it slow, giving us a very comfortable position. Their only idea is to play [Nh4] next.} h6 {As usual, we create a square for the bishop on [h7]. Next, we can just continue developing our pieces normally.} 7. O-O Nbd7 8. b3 {The engine wants to play [Bd3] instead, which should highlight how ineffective this variation is for White. Letting our bishop chill on [f5] is not a great idea.} Bd6 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Rc1 Qe7 $10 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf8e8,Gd7f6,Ga8d8] White has run out of useful moves to play. We can put our rooks on [e8] and [d8] next. We can then play ...[Ne4] and get the other knight to [f6].} *

