1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nbd2 {Putting knight on [d2] is not an improvement for White over the lines we have seen so far. I faced this move in a classical game, and I still do not know what its purpose is.} e6 6. Be2 {This has been played the most, but such slow moves are completely harmless as usual. The only plan is [Nh4] to win our bishop, but we can easily parry this.} h6 {[%cal Gf5h7] We create a square for the bishop on [h7].} 7. O-O Nbd7 8. b3 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6h2,Gf6e4] I like our bishop on [d6] in these lines, particularly when White's g-pawn is not on [g3]. We are going to play ...[Ne4] soon and then we'll start playing on the kingside.} 9. Bb2 Ne4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Ne5 Qg5 $36 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gd6c7,Gh6h5] We will take on [e5] next with the knight and go after the [e5]-pawn. On the kingside, we can start pushing our h-pawn down the board.} *

