1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nbd2 {Putting knight on [d2] is not an improvement for White over the lines we have seen so far. I faced this move in a classical game, and I still do not know what its purpose is.} e6 6. Nh4 {White goes for the same plan as in the main line with the knight on [c3]. The issue is that with the knight on [d2], it is very hard for White to develop the queenside further.} Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 Qc7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5,Gb8c6] In these lines we are not going to take on [c4], but instead we'll go for the ...[c5] break, targeting the centre.} 9. g3 c5 $1 10. cxd5 exd5 $15 {[%csl Rd2,Gd5][%cal Gc5c4] Although we do get an IQP on [d5], this pawn restricts the knight on [d2] and by extension the white queenside. White has created a lot of weaknesses with the move [f3]. We can go for ...[c4] next.} *

