1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. cxd5 {White releases the tension in the centre, going for a symmetrical position. This is similar to the Exchange Slav which we will take a look at in a later chapter, but in this particular instance White's dark-squared bishop is stuck behind the pawn chain.} cxd5 6. Qb3 {This has been played a lot by GM Lysyj with pretty good results. White will bring the bishop directly to [b5] in these lines.} Qc7 7. Nc3 {I think this is not the best approach. Now play becomes very straight-forward and White is stuck with a bad bishop on [c1].} e6 8. Bd2 Nc6 9. Rc1 Be7 {We prioritise development over preserving our light-squared bishop. Now moves like [Ne5] are too slow as we can castle immediately.} ({Here} 9... h6 $6 {is an inaccuracy due to} 10. Ne5 {⩲ when White will take on [c6] next, creating weaknesses.}) 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Rfc8 $10 {[%csl Gf5] We get a very comfortable version of the Slav exchange with our bishop active on [f5]. The colours are basically reversed.} *

