1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. cxd5 {White releases the tension in the centre, going for a symmetrical position. This is similar to the Exchange Slav which we will take a look at in a later chapter, but in this particular instance White's dark-squared bishop is stuck behind the pawn chain.} cxd5 6. Qb3 {This has been played a lot by GM Lysyj with pretty good results. White will bring the bishop directly to [b5] in these lines.} Qc7 7. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2b4] This is clever. White wants to trade the dark-squared bishop on [b4] in the future.} e6 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Bb4 {White goes for the trade immediately. I think it is better for White to wait for us to move the dark-squared bishop first.} Bxb4+ 10. Qxb4 Nd7 {[%cal Gc6b4] We block the pin, attacking the queen on [b4].} 11. Qa3 {[%cal Ga3f8] White maintains control over the [a3]-[f8] diagonal, preventing us from castling kingside.} Nxd4 $1 {We give White a rude shock. We are going against the white king in the centre.} 12. exd4 Qc1+ 13. Ke2 Qxh1 14. Ne5 O-O-O $10 (14... O-O-O {White has to play precisely here in order to force a draw. The direct} 15. Qxa7 {loses after} Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qc1 {. White has to go 15.Bxd7 Rxd7 16.Qxa7 and he can make a draw.}) *

