1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. cxd5 {White releases the tension in the centre, going for a symmetrical position. This is similar to the Exchange Slav which we will take a look at in a later chapter, but in this particular instance White's dark-squared bishop is stuck behind the pawn chain.} cxd5 6. Qb3 {This has been played a lot by GM Lysyj with pretty good results. White will bring the bishop directly to [b5] in these lines.} Qc7 7. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2b4] This is clever. White wants to trade the dark-squared bishop on [b4] in the future.} e6 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. O-O {We now have to make a decision on how to develop the [f8]-bishop. Both options are quite similar, but there are some subtle differences.} Be7 {This has been played only two times so far. I like putting the bishop on [e7] as we can recapture back on [e7] with the knight. It is always good to go for the less explored option, if both moves are equally strong.} (9... Bd6 10. Bb4 {is a bit more annoying.}) 10. Bb4 O-O 11. Bxc6 {White eliminates the [c6]-knight first. This creates some imbalance in the pawn structure, which I like.} bxc6 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 $10 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gf8c8,Gf6d7,Gc6c5] We now have the semi-open b-file for our rook. We can slowly prepare the ...[c5] break with ...[Rfc8] and ...[Nd7].} *

