1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Bd3 {White trades off the light-squared bishops, simplifying the position. This is usually played by those who are happy to make a draw with White. There are a few different ways in which we can react.} Bxd3 {We go for the simplest option, trading the bishops without wasting a tempo. While this does bring White's queen to [d3] in one go, I do not think White has any plan other than the [e4] break. This, in turn, weakens the [d4]-pawn, and then we are going to play against this pawn.} 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Nc3 {White is rushing to play [e4].} Be7 {[%csl Gb8][%cal Gb8c6] I think this is the more flexible developing move, as our queenside knight can jump to [c6] in some rare cases. Also, we do not want to block the d-file for now. Our bishop will likely head to [f6] after some trades on [e4].} 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 c5 $1 {[%csl Rd3] We exploit the position of the queen on [d3] with a pin along the d-file. We are ready to play ...[Nc6] and ...[Nb4] next.} 10. d5 {White gets a passed pawn in the middle of the board, but I am not sure if it is really an asset for them. The pawn can be easily blockaded and might end up being a weakness.} Nxe4 11. Qxe4 exd5 12. cxd5 O-O $10 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f6,Gf8e8,Ge7d6] We will continue with ...[Nd7]-[f6] and our bishop can go to [d6] if required. The position is balanced, but there is still a lot of play left. Just be careful not to rush with the move ...[Bd6], allowing White to go for an attack on the kingside with [Ng5].} *

