1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Bd3 {White trades off the light-squared bishops, simplifying the position. This is usually played by those who are happy to make a draw with White. There are a few different ways in which we can react.} Bxd3 {We go for the simplest option, trading the bishops without wasting a tempo. While this does bring White's queen to [d3] in one go, I do not think White has any plan other than the [e4] break. This, in turn, weakens the [d4]-pawn, and then we are going to play against this pawn.} 6. Qxd3 e6 7. O-O Be7 {As we saw in the previous line, we are delaying the development of the [b8]-knight in order to be able to play ...[c5] and ...[Nc6].} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. b3 {We see the same plan again, but with the knight on [c3]. Although the knight blocks the bishop on [b2], it prevents our play on the queenside with ...[b5] which we saw earlier.} Nbd7 10. e4 {White goes for the move [e4] only after we've developed the knight to [d7]. This way White avoids the lines with ...[c5] which we just saw.} dxe4 11. Nxe4 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd3,Re4][%cal Gd4e5,Gd7e5] Once again, we make use of the undefended queen on [d3] to equalise in the centre.} 12. Ng3 Nc5 {We get the knight to [c5] with a tempo and force White's queen to a worse square.} 13. Qd1 exd4 14. Nxd4 Re8 $10 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gg7g6,Gh7h5,Gf8g7,Gh5h4] We will tuck away the bishop on [f8] with a comfortable position. We can play ...[g6] and regroup the bishop to [g7] in the future. With White's knight on [g3], ...[h5]-[h4] is always in the air.} *

