1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Bd3 {White trades off the light-squared bishops, simplifying the position. This is usually played by those who are happy to make a draw with White. There are a few different ways in which we can react.} Bxd3 {We go for the simplest option, trading the bishops without wasting a tempo. While this does bring White's queen to [d3] in one go, I do not think White has any plan other than the [e4] break. This, in turn, weakens the [d4]-pawn, and then we are going to play against this pawn.} 6. Qxd3 e6 7. O-O Be7 {As we saw in the previous line, we are delaying the development of the [b8]-knight in order to be able to play ...[c5] and ...[Nc6].} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. b3 {We see the same plan again, but with the knight on [c3]. Although the knight blocks the bishop on [b2], it prevents our play on the queenside with ...[b5] which we saw earlier.} Nbd7 10. Bb2 a5 11. a3 h6 {We go for a useful waiting move, asking White how they want to proceed. In such positions, we need to be aware of our typical plans and ideas. Precise move orders are not as important.} 12. h3 Re8 13. Rfd1 (13. e4 {can still be met with} dxe4 14. Nxe4 c5 {, with ...[Qb6] to follow next.}) 13... Qb6 $10 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga8d8,Gb6a6] We will get the other rook to [d8] next. The queen can go to [a6], putting pressure on the [c4]-pawn. The position is pretty balanced. The [e4] advance would only create more weaknesses for White.} (13... Qb6 {Just note that we cannot meet moves like} 14. Rac1 {with} Qxb3 $2 {due to} 15. Nxd5 $1 {. Instead we go 14...[Rad8] with a good position.}) *

