1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 {In this chapter, we will be focussing on a couple of early queen moves with which White can defend the [c4]-pawn. We saw this earlier with the inclusion of the moves [Nc3] and ...[e6]. Here, White has not committed the knight to [c3] yet. This gives White more flexibility, and they can instead develop the knight to [d2] in some cases.} e6 {We maintain the tension, as the queen on [b3] is not doing much at the moment. We will continue developing our pieces for now.} (4... dxc4 {is the usual reaction of many players, forcing White to recapture with the queen. This makes sense, also because we can do the same against the move 4.Qc2, cutting down the amount of theory to learn. However, I do feel we are releasing the tension too early, giving White easier play.}) 5. Bf4 {The bishop rarely stands well on [f4] in the Slav, and this is no exception. This move has been played by a few strong players, including Mamedyarov against Magnus.} (5. Nc3 {transposes to an earlier chapter.}) 5... c5 $1 {[%csl Rb3] Surprisingly, this has been played only twice so far. However, the ...[c5] push is a common reaction in these lines with the queen on [b3]. White's play in the centre has been unconvincing, and we can break immediately.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Rf4] This perfectly showcases the problem with the bishop on [f4]. White has to move the bishop again.} 7. Bg5 {This was played in the Grandmaster game Dreev - Kobalia in 2019.} Qb6 {We are very happy to trade the queens on either [b6] or [b3].} 8. e4 Qxb3 9. axb3 Nb4 $36 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3] The knight is well placed on [b4], eyeing the light squares. It cannot be pushed back anytime soon.} *

