1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 {In this chapter, we will be focussing on a couple of early queen moves with which White can defend the [c4]-pawn. We saw this earlier with the inclusion of the moves [Nc3] and ...[e6]. Here, White has not committed the knight to [c3] yet. This gives White more flexibility, and they can instead develop the knight to [d2] in some cases.} e6 {We maintain the tension, as the queen on [b3] is not doing much at the moment. We will continue developing our pieces for now.} (4... dxc4 {is the usual reaction of many players, forcing White to recapture with the queen. This makes sense, also because we can do the same against the move 4.Qc2, cutting down the amount of theory to learn. However, I do feel we are releasing the tension too early, giving White easier play.}) 5. Bg5 {White is mixing up several different plans. I am not a fan of these lines with [Bg5], as White will likely have to give the bishop up on [f6] at some point. Otherwise, I don't think this move achieves much.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd5c4,Ge6e5] We would like to recapture on [f6] with the knight. We are preparing to take on [c4] next and break in the centre with the move ...[e5].} 6. e3 {White is ready to recapture on [c4] with the bishop, but this move is too slow.} Qa5+ $1 {We are getting our knight to [e4] with a tempo. The bishop on [g5] is going to come under fire.} 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Bf4 g5 $1 {[%cal Gf3g5,Ge4g5,Gf4g5,Gd5c4,Ra5g5]} (8... g5 {We are going hard after the bishop on f4.} 9. Nxg5 {will be met with} dxc4 10. Qa4 Qxa4 11. Nxa4 Bb4+ {with a light edge.}) 9. Be5 f6 10. Bg3 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] We have gained a lot of space on the kingside and White is now forced to move the h-pawn. Then we can cripple White's kingside by capturing on [g3].} 11. h3 Bb4 {It's useful to develop our bishop with a tempo, attacking [c3].} 12. Nd2 Bxc3 {Once again, we wait a bit longer before taking on [g3]. We force White to recapture on [c3] with the pawn and keep the queens on the board.} 13. bxc3 Nxg3 14. fxg3 Qc7 (14... Qc7 {The pawn on g3 cannot be defended easily anymore.} 15. Kf2 {runs into} h4 {with great play on the kingside.}) 15. O-O-O {[%cal Ge3e4] White is willing to give up the pawn to get a pawn break in the centre.} f5 $10 {[%csl Rg3] We first stop White's [e4] break, followed by winning the pawn on [g3] next. White has some compensation with the lead in development, but it's not enough for an advantage.} *

