1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 {In this chapter, we will be focussing on a couple of early queen moves with which White can defend the [c4]-pawn. We saw this earlier with the inclusion of the moves [Nc3] and ...[e6]. Here, White has not committed the knight to [c3] yet. This gives White more flexibility, and they can instead develop the knight to [d2] in some cases.} e6 {We maintain the tension, as the queen on [b3] is not doing much at the moment. We will continue developing our pieces for now.} (4... dxc4 {is the usual reaction of many players, forcing White to recapture with the queen. This makes sense, also because we can do the same against the move 4.Qc2, cutting down the amount of theory to learn. However, I do feel we are releasing the tension too early, giving White easier play.}) 5. Bg5 {White is mixing up several different plans. I am not a fan of these lines with [Bg5], as White will likely have to give the bishop up on [f6] at some point. Otherwise, I don't think this move achieves much.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd5c4,Ge6e5] We would like to recapture on [f6] with the knight. We are preparing to take on [c4] next and break in the centre with the move ...[e5].} 6. Nc3 {White develops the knight, blocking the [a5]-[e1] diagonal.} h6 {We poke the bishop on [g5], inviting it to give itself up on [f6]. I like forcing White to clarify their intentions as early as possible.} 7. Bh4 dxc4 {It's time to go for our usual plan against the white queen. This is very similar to the earlier chapter, as White has played the move [Nc3].} 8. Qxc4 a6 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gb7b5] We cover the [b5]-square and are ready to play ...[c5] next. We will follow this up with ...[b5] later.} 9. e3 c5 10. Qa4 {White delays our ...[b5] move, but this is only a temporary delay.} Rb8 11. Bg3 {This was White's point: our rook is again attacked.} b5 12. Qc2 cxd4 $1 {This is a nice intermediate move, not allowing White to take on [c5]. White could then play [Ne4] and try to take control over the diagonal.} (12... Ra8 {looks natural, but} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. a4 $1 b4 15. Ne4 {is a bit annoying.}) 13. Nxd4 Ra8 14. Be2 Bb7 $10 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8c5] We have achieved our ideal setup on the queenside and will continue with ...[Rc8] and ...[Bc5]. We are on the better side of equality.} *

