1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 {In this chapter, we will be focussing on a couple of early queen moves with which White can defend the [c4]-pawn. We saw this earlier with the inclusion of the moves [Nc3] and ...[e6]. Here, White has not committed the knight to [c3] yet. This gives White more flexibility, and they can instead develop the knight to [d2] in some cases.} e6 {We maintain the tension, as the queen on [b3] is not doing much at the moment. We will continue developing our pieces for now.} (4... dxc4 {is the usual reaction of many players, forcing White to recapture with the queen. This makes sense, also because we can do the same against the move 4.Qc2, cutting down the amount of theory to learn. However, I do feel we are releasing the tension too early, giving White easier play.}) 5. g3 {This is the natural continuation after the move 4.Qb3. White is looking to go for a Catalan type of position where it is natural to bring the queen out to regain the [c4]-pawn once Black captures it.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rb3] As I mentioned earlier, the queen on [b3] gives us the chance to break in the centre. We are happy to get an IQP on [d5]. White is far away from getting control over the [d4]-square, and our pieces are much more active.} 6. Bg2 {White keeps the tension for a bit.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] We put more pressure on [d4], forcing White to release the tension.} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 {The bishop is developed to [c5] in one go, which is a great achievement for us. The [d4]-square is firmly in our control.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 {White does not want to open the diagonal for our light-squared bishop. Delaying the [cxd5] capture can easily backfire, though, as we already have an excellent hold over the centre.} d4 $1 {[%csl Rb1,Rc3] We gain more space by pushing the pawn to [d4], restricting the knight on [b1].} 10. Ne1 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nd3 Qe7 $10 {[%cal Ge6e5] We are looking to play ...[e5] next. The position is balanced, with our centre compensating for the active bishop on [g2].} *

