1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. Nc3 {I don't think this makes a lot of sense with the queen on [c2]. It is not great to get the move [e4] quickly with the king still in the centre.} Bg7 6. e4 {This is a pretty serious inaccuracy. We would love to open up the centre with the bishop on [g7]. It is much more annoying when White keeps the centre blocked.} (6. Bf4 {has been played more often, but we can continue with} dxc4 {and play ...[b5] next, holding on to the pawn. White cannot do much in the centre.}) 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Qxe4 c5 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2] We are forcing White to fully open up the diagonal for our bishop. It feels like a dream version of a Grunfeld.} 9. d5 O-O 10. Bd3 e5 $17 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ge5e4] I have never seen this idea before, but it is extremely effective here. We are going to play ...[f5] and ...[e4] next, kicking back White's pieces.} *

