1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. cxd5 {[%cal Gc6d5,Gb8c6,Gc8f5,Ga8c8] This is a favourite move of Andreikin, who has played it several times. It makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] will not be so effective staring at the [d4]-pawn with a static pawn structure. However, this does allow us to develop our knight to [c6] easily, and the queen on [c2] is misplaced on the c-file. Both the moves [Qc2] and ...[g6] are not a great inclusion in the Exchange Slav, so it balances out.} cxd5 6. Nc3 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ge2e3] The move order does not matter too much. White will play the moves [Nc3], [Bf4] and [e3] in any order.} Nc6 {We, too, can develop our pieces in any order.} 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. e3 O-O {[%cal Gf6h5,Gc8f5,Gf6e4] The first part of our plan is complete. We are almost done with our development. Next, there are a few different plans we can go for: ...[Nh5] going after the bishop on [f4], or ...[Ne4] or ...[Bf5], playing against the queen on [c2].} 9. h3 {White creates a luft on [h2] for the bishop. This is a not a developing move, though, and White is lagging behind.} Bf5 {We gain a tempo against the queen on [c2]. We are not done harassing the queen yet.} 10. Qb3 Na5 {Another tempo against the queen. This is less impressive as we move the same piece twice, but our knight is heading to the attractive [c4]-square.} 11. Qb4 Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge4c3] We intend to exchange the knight on [c3], which poses some annoying issues for White. They have to take with the b-pawn, creating a weakness on [c3].} 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Be2 Qb6 $1 {After forcing White to move their queen around, we trade the queens just before White is able to connect the rooks. We will take on [c3] on the next move and weaken White's pawn structure.} 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Nd2 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Bd7 $10 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb6b5,Ga5c4] We are preparing to play ...[b5] next, after which we can put our knight to [c4]. We have equalised completely and can take over the initiative if White is not precise.} *

