1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. cxd5 {[%cal Gc6d5,Gb8c6,Gc8f5,Ga8c8] This is a favourite move of Andreikin, who has played it several times. It makes sense, as the bishop on [g7] will not be so effective staring at the [d4]-pawn with a static pawn structure. However, this does allow us to develop our knight to [c6] easily, and the queen on [c2] is misplaced on the c-file. Both the moves [Qc2] and ...[g6] are not a great inclusion in the Exchange Slav, so it balances out.} cxd5 6. Nc3 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ge2e3] The move order does not matter too much. White will play the moves [Nc3], [Bf4] and [e3] in any order.} Nc6 {We, too, can develop our pieces in any order.} 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. e3 O-O {[%cal Gf6h5,Gc8f5,Gf6e4] The first part of our plan is complete. We are almost done with our development. Next, there are a few different plans we can go for: ...[Nh5] going after the bishop on [f4], or ...[Ne4] or ...[Bf5], playing against the queen on [c2].} 9. Be2 Nh5 {We go after White's dark-squared bishop. It is White's most active minor piece at the moment.} 10. Be5 {White forces the move ...[f6], blocking in the bishop on [g7].} f6 11. Bg3 Be6 {[%cal Ge6f7,Gh5g3,Ge7e6] This is a surprising move as we are developing our bishop to [f7] rather than the usual [f5]-square. We need to be more cautious with the pawn on [f6]. We are winning the bishop pair and can afford to play slowly.} 12. O-O Bf7 13. Rac1 e6 $10 {[%cal Gd8e7,Ga8c8] The rook will come to [c8] next, and we have opened the [e7]-square for the queen. This is a great version of the Exchange Slav for us.} *

