1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. g3 {This is rarely a good idea in the Slav with the pawn on [d5], and definitely not a good idea here. White has wasted a move with [Qc2]. We will soon attack the queen to gain a tempo.} Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nbd2 $6 {This was played in a game between Mamedyarov and Magnus, but it is an inaccuracy. I cannot see what the knight is doing on [d2].} a5 $1 {[%cal Rb2b3,Ga5a4] This is really clever, getting the pawn to [a4]. It restricts the knight on [d2] and also the bishop on [c1]. White's best plan to develop the bishop is with [b3] and [Bb2].} 8. O-O a4 9. Qd1 Bf5 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2] We are already slightly better. White's minor pieces are stuck due to the knight on [d2]. White cannot regroup the knight easily, as then the [c4]-pawn is hanging. They have to take on [d5], but that leaves us up several tempi in an Exchange Slav pawn structure.} *

