1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. g3 {This is rarely a good idea in the Slav with the pawn on [d5], and definitely not a good idea here. White has wasted a move with [Qc2]. We will soon attack the queen to gain a tempo.} Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {White will likely develop the knight to [c3] next, and try to get control over the centre.} Bf5 {As usual, we gain a tempo against the queen.} 8. Qb3 Qb6 {We are happy to trade the queens and simplify the position.} 9. Nc3 Rd8 {There is no need to release the tension as of now. We are waiting to see how White continues next.} 10. c5 {This has been played in a few games, but it is an inaccuracy to release the tension in the centre. White is not able to get quick play on the queenside while we are faster with the ...[e5] break.} Qxb3 11. axb3 Na6 $15 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf6d7,Ge7e5] We will continue with ...[Nd7] and ...[e5] next. White cannot get [b4] even with the rook on [a4], as we have the answer ...[Bc2].} *

