1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. e3 {White keeps his bishop on [c1] behind the pawn chain, intending to develop the kingside as quickly as possible.} Bg7 {We are not going to rush with the bishop to [f5] to trade the light-squared bishops. Instead, our idea is much simpler. We want to play ...[O-O] next and go for ...[c5]. We will open up the centre, making use of our lead in development.} 6. Be2 {The bishop is less active here compared to [d3], but it is more safe when Black's knight is coming to [b4] or [c5].} O-O 7. O-O c5 {This is the plan I was talking about. We get a Grunfeld-like position, which perfectly suits our bishop on [g7]. This is the 8th most common move here!} 8. cxd5 {This is usually harmless, allowing us to get our knight to [d5].} (8. dxc5 {can be met with} Bf5 {and we will follow up with ...[Nbd7]-[c5].}) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd5 10. Rd1 Qb6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gb8c6] We get the queen out of the d-file. Her majesty is well placed on [b6], keeping an eye on [d4]. We are going to continue with ...[Nc6] next.} 11. Nc3 {White wants to open the b-file for their rook. This would also help them develop the [c1]-bishop to [a3].} Nb4 $5 {We will avoid that if possible and try to develop our queenside. This complicates matters and makes the game more dynamic.} (11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 {followed by} Nc6 {is not bad either.}) 12. Qb3 N8c6 13. a3 {All of this happened in an online game between Van Foreest, J and Kollars, D on chess.com.} Bxd4 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb4c2] We have to play very concretely, making use of the queen on [b3]. We will meet both recaptures by attacking the queen on [b3] and trying to get the knight to [c2].} ({In the aforementioned game, Black went wrong with} 13... Nxd4 {⩲ , giving White good control over the centre.}) 14. axb4 Be6 15. Qa4 Bg7 16. b5 Ne5 $10 {[%csl Ge5,Ge6,Gg7]} (16... Ne5 {Our pieces are pretty active and we have equalised in spite of the weakness on a7. If White tries to bring the bishop out with} 17. e4 {, we have the move} Ng4 {, going after the [f2]-pawn.}) *

