1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. e3 {White keeps his bishop on [c1] behind the pawn chain, intending to develop the kingside as quickly as possible.} Bg7 {We are not going to rush with the bishop to [f5] to trade the light-squared bishops. Instead, our idea is much simpler. We want to play ...[O-O] next and go for ...[c5]. We will open up the centre, making use of our lead in development.} 6. Bd3 {This is the more active square for the bishop in general, but it is not as effective with our pawn on [g6] blocking the diagonal.} O-O 7. Nc3 {I don't think it is a great idea to develop the knight so early. It's better to wait until Black has commited to a plan.} c5 $1 {Our typical break is even stronger here, with our knight eyeing the [b4]-square next.} 8. dxc5 Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5,Ga6b4] We see yet another drawback of the queen on [c2]. In addition to attacking the pawn on [c5], we are also preparing to go for ...[Nb4], winning the light-squared bishop.} 9. Nxd5 Nxc5 $1 {We are in no rush to win the [d5]-pawn back.} 10. e4 {This is essential to not be much worse, hanging on to the [d5]-pawn.} Bg4 $36 {[%cal Gg4f3,Ga8c8] We want to bring the rook to [c8] quickly and the bishop is perfect on [g4], damaging White's pawn structure.} *

