1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. e3 {White keeps his bishop on [c1] behind the pawn chain, intending to develop the kingside as quickly as possible.} Bg7 {We are not going to rush with the bishop to [f5] to trade the light-squared bishops. Instead, our idea is much simpler. We want to play ...[O-O] next and go for ...[c5]. We will open up the centre, making use of our lead in development.} 6. Bd3 {This is the more active square for the bishop in general, but it is not as effective with our pawn on [g6] blocking the diagonal.} O-O 7. O-O c5 $1 {We continue with the same plan. It is very easy to play these types of positions once we know the ideas. It's a shock to me that this move is not more popular. It's the 6th most-played option in the position.} 8. cxd5 {This hands us control over the position, as the centre simplifies and our pieces are better placed. The bishop is perfect on [g7] for these situations.} cxd4 9. e4 {White tries to hold on to the centre, but it is not going to last long. White leaves us with a strong passed pawn in the middle of the board.} e6 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb8c6] We need to play this immediately before White gets any of their pieces out.} 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 {White has to give us the bishop to preserve their centre.} Qxf6 12. e5 Qf4 $10 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc8e6,Rb8c6] We will get out bishop to [e6] soon, and will then go after the [e5]-pawn. We are on the better side of equality with the bishop pair.} *

