1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. Bf4 {This is the most popular move, getting the bishop out of the pawn chain before playing [e3].} Bg7 {The best part of our repertoire is that we are going for the same plan as we saw in the previous lines. We will castle next and go for the ...[c5] break. It's a very effective plan to exploit the queen on [c2] and make use of our dark-squared bishop.} 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 {This is a big inaccuracy. We have already seen that the bishop on [d3] is going to come under fire along with the queen on [c2]. The bishop on [f4] only makes things worse for White, once our knight comes to [d5].} c5 $1 8. dxc5 Nc6 {We bring our knight in contact with the centre, hinting at jumping to [b4] at any moment.} 9. O-O Nd7 $15 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gc6b4,Gb4d3] We are threatening to win an exchange with ...[Nb4] now as the pawn on [b2] is hanging at the end. We can also regain the [c5]-pawn at any moment. The bishop on [g7] is a monster unleashed.} *

