1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 ({I think this is superior to} 4. Qb3 {. From [c2] the queen keeps an eye on the [e4]-square, and White will typically develop the [f1]-bishop to [g2].}) 4... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8g7] Similar to what we saw in the previous lines, we do not release the tension early in the centre. Instead, we are looking to play against the queen on [c2] with the move ...[Bf5].These positions are quite different from the usual Slav lines, and this was something I was contemplating. I feel there are a lot of merits to this approach to justify putting in a bit of extra effort. Also, as we've seen, the lines with [Qb3] are pretty easy to learn and Black equalizes without too much effort.} 5. Bf4 {This is the most popular move, getting the bishop out of the pawn chain before playing [e3].} Bg7 {The best part of our repertoire is that we are going for the same plan as we saw in the previous lines. We will castle next and go for the ...[c5] break. It's a very effective plan to exploit the queen on [c2] and make use of our dark-squared bishop.} 6. e3 O-O 7. Nc3 {White goes for the most natural move, keeping an eye on the [d5]-pawn.} c5 {Once again, this is the 3rd most popular move in the position, but this pawn break should be obvious to you after having seen it so many times previously in this chapter.} 8. dxc5 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] This is different from the lines we have seen so far. White has not yet developed his light-squared bishop. The bishop being on [f4] means that this pin is very annoying for White, and they cannot block it with [Bd2]. We will get our bishop to [f5] next.} 9. Be2 {This wastes a whole tempo once White has to recapture the pawn on [c4].} dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxc5 {Once again, White has to waste time defending the bishop.} 11. Bb3 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf6h5] We will play ...[Bf5] next, completing our development. Our pieces are better developed too, with the bishop on [g7]. We can go after the dark-squared bishop with ...[Nh5] later.} *

