o equal.}) 10. cxd5 {This is the more combative option for White, winning another pawn in the centre. However, it gives us a plethora of good options to choose from.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc8f5] I want to bring the other knight into the game. We will get this knight to [c5] and follow up with ...[Bf5]. We can always win back the [c3]-pawn.} 12. Be2 Nxc5 {White cannot allow us to get our bishop to [f5] next. The white queen would lack a good square.} 13. Nd4 Na4 {[%csl Rc3,Rd5] Now we go after the [c3]-pawn, forcing White to defend it. The [d5]-pawn is also under fire.} 14. Rc1 Nb6 $10 {[%csl Rc3,Rf4][%cal Gb6d5] We can take on [d5] with the knight next, attacking the bishop on [f4]. White has a weakness we can target on [c3]. The position is dynamically balanced due to White's slight lead in development, but we have the edge in the long run.} *

