1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {We saw the Fianchetto system in the Semi-Slav too, but now we are seeing it a move earlier. Playing g3 on move 4 is more flexible for White, as their queenside knight does not need to go to [c3]. However, the drawback for White is that we are able to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} Bf5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5,Rg2][%cal Ge7e6] The bishop is well placed along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We will play ...[e6] next and get solid control over the centre. The lines here are very different compared to earlier variations where White played [g3], as we are not going to go after the [c4]-pawn. The bishop on [g2] is not a great piece when the centre remains closed.} 5. Bg2 {This is the most common move in this position, but it is not the most critical one. White lets us consolidate the bishop on [f5]. As I mentioned before, this means we are doing very well positionally. White should try to create something quick and play dynamically.} (5. Qb3 {is a move we will see several times in this chapter, and our reaction is consistent across the different move orders:} Qb6 {. This will transpose into one of our other lines.}) 5... e6 6. Nbd2 {This has been played in many games, but the knight is useless on [d2]. The only logic is to develop the bishop to [b2], but both White's bishops are going to be staring at a blocked centre. In such positions, the bishop is better off in the middle of the board, where it has different options to choose from.} h6 {[%csl Gh7] This is a quiet but important move that we will see multiple times in this chapter. We need the [h7]-square for the bishop, as White is hinting at [Nh4]. Earlier we could go to [e4] with the bishop, but now White can trade our bishop off with [Nxe4] if we play that.} 7. O-O Nbd7 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gf8d6] We have still not made our decision about the dark-squared bishop. Meanwhile, the queenside knight definitely belongs on [d7] in these lines.} 8. Re1 {[%cal Gf3h4,Ge2e4] White wants to play [Nh4] and open up the centre with the move [e4]. This would justify putting the bishop on [g2].} Be7 {We stop White's plan with this simple move. If White puts the knight on [h4], it will come under pressure now.} 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 a5 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3][%cal Ga5a4] Another typical move in these lines, especially when White plays [b3]. We want to continue with ...[a4] and harass the white queenside.} 11. a3 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb3b4] White gets ready to meet ...[a4] with [b4], gaining space on the queenside. This is also a standard reaction to our previous move. The [a3]-pawn is weak in some lines once the rook moves away from the a-file.} Ne4 {Trades are good for us, as we have less space. I want to get a good bishop vs bad bishop situation with the dark-squared bishops.} 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 {We are not going to leave the [e4]-square unless we are allowed to trade the bishops.} 13. Nd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 b5 $10 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga5a4,Gd7b6,Gb6c4] We want to play ...[a4] next and fix the pawns on the dark squares. It is not easy for White to play with the bishop on [b2]. We are on the better side of equality.} *

