1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {We saw the Fianchetto system in the Semi-Slav too, but now we are seeing it a move earlier. Playing g3 on move 4 is more flexible for White, as their queenside knight does not need to go to [c3]. However, the drawback for White is that we are able to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} Bf5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5,Rg2][%cal Ge7e6] The bishop is well placed along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We will play ...[e6] next and get solid control over the centre. The lines here are very different compared to earlier variations where White played [g3], as we are not going to go after the [c4]-pawn. The bishop on [g2] is not a great piece when the centre remains closed.} 5. Bg2 {This is the most common move in this position, but it is not the most critical one. White lets us consolidate the bishop on [f5]. As I mentioned before, this means we are doing very well positionally. White should try to create something quick and play dynamically.} (5. Qb3 {is a move we will see several times in this chapter, and our reaction is consistent across the different move orders:} Qb6 {. This will transpose into one of our other lines.}) 5... e6 6. Nc3 {I think this is a better square for the knight. The [f3]-knight can head to [d2] if required.} h6 {Once again, we need to create a luft for the bishop on [h7].} 7. O-O {White is more flexible, keeping different options open. Next, they can go for the move [b3], the [e4] break or attack our queenside with [Qb3].} Be7 {This is clever, keeping the knight on [b8]. We have already seen in a few lines that sometimes our queenside knight can go directly to [c6]. This is particularly effective in the [Qb3] lines.} 8. b3 {We have seen similar lines earlier, but White has a few extra plans with the knight on [c3].} (8. Qb3 Qb6 9. c5 Qxb3 10. axb3 {transposes to lines we've seen earlier.}) 8... O-O 9. Bb2 Nbd7 {We no longer need to go to [c6] with the knight.} 10. Re1 {It seems like White is mixing up a lot of different plans. Now we have a clever idea to exploit the rook on [e1]. You can take some time to try and find it.} b5 $1 {[%csl Re1] An unusual idea, but it works due to the rook on [e1]. White is not able to win our pawn on [b5]. There were other good moves too but this is the most creative.} 11. Ne5 (11. cxb5 {does not work well due to} cxb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 {∓ . We will continue with ...[Rfc8], after which White's knight is in a lot of trouble.}) 11... Rc8 {We just defend the pawn on [c6], encouraging White to go after the [b5]-pawn.} 12. cxb5 cxb5 13. Nxb5 Qb6 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ga2a4,Ga7a6] Now the queen is better on [b6] than on [a5] because we cover the [a7]-square, preparing the move ...[a6]. Otherwise, with the knight on [e5], [Na7]-[c6] is very annoying.} ({The slight issue with} 13... Qa5 {is that after} 14. a4 {we cannot go} a6 $2 {due to} 15. Na7 $1 {+- .}) 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. Nc3 Bb4 $36 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge2e4,Gd5e4,Ge1e3] White is in trouble with the knight. They have to give the pawn back with [e4] to be able to defend the [c3]-knight with their rook on [e3].} *

