r trade or kick White's knight back.} 12. Be3 {The bishop is better placed on [e3] compared to [b2], as we saw earlier. However, even here our dark-squared bishop is superior to White's, and our goal remains the same: trade the other minor pieces.} Nf6 13. Nc3 {White should keep the knights on the board.} Ng4 $1 {We kick the bishop away. We are going for the [d4]-pawn.} 14. Bf4 e5 {We give up a pawn temporarily to break White's pawn structure in the centre. We will likely win the pawn back soon or win the bishop pair.} 15. dxe5 g5 {[%cal Gg4e5]} 16. h3 $1 {This is the best option for White, trapping our knight on [g4].} Qxd1 17. Raxd1 gxf4 18. gxf4 ({After} 18. hxg4 Bxg4 19. Rd4 Rad8 20. Rxf4 Be6 {we have very good compensation with the bishop pair and the open d-file.}) 18... Nxe5 {We give back the knight and are down a pawn. However, the pair of bishops give us enough compensation.} 19. fxe5 f6 {[%csl Rf2,Gf6,Rh3][%cal Ge7f6,Gf6b2] Our dark-squared bishop will be a monster on the long diagonal. White's pawn structure is too weak on the kingside for them to create anything there.} *

