1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {We saw the Fianchetto system in the Semi-Slav too, but now we are seeing it a move earlier. Playing g3 on move 4 is more flexible for White, as their queenside knight does not need to go to [c3]. However, the drawback for White is that we are able to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} Bf5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5,Rg2][%cal Ge7e6] The bishop is well placed along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We will play ...[e6] next and get solid control over the centre. The lines here are very different compared to earlier variations where White played [g3], as we are not going to go after the [c4]-pawn. The bishop on [g2] is not a great piece when the centre remains closed.} 5. Nc3 {This is the critical move, preparing to play [Nh4] very early. As I have mentioned, White needs to play dynamically in these lines.} e6 6. Qb3 {This is similar to the [Qb3] lines we have seen so far, but now the bishop is still on [f1]. It's not necessary for White to develop it to [g2] in these lines.} Qb6 7. c5 Qxb3 8. axb3 Be7 {[%csl Gb8][%cal Gb8c6] We always develop the bishop first in these lines, keeping the knight on [b8] so that it might jump to [c6] directly.} 9. b4 O-O 10. Nh4 {White tries going after our active bishop.} Bc2 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gc2h7] We will keep the bishop alive if possible. Next, we can push the h-pawn and bring the bishop back home.} 11. Kd2 Bb3 {[%cal Gf6e4] Although our light-squared bishop looks stuck, we have our ways to activate it.} 12. e3 Ne4+ $10 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gb3d5,Ge7h4] If White takes on [e4] we get the beautiful [d5] square for the bishop. Otherwise, we will take on [h4] and break White's pawn structure.} *

