1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {We saw the Fianchetto system in the Semi-Slav too, but now we are seeing it a move earlier. Playing g3 on move 4 is more flexible for White, as their queenside knight does not need to go to [c3]. However, the drawback for White is that we are able to develop our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} Bf5 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5,Rg2][%cal Ge7e6] The bishop is well placed along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. We will play ...[e6] next and get solid control over the centre. The lines here are very different compared to earlier variations where White played [g3], as we are not going to go after the [c4]-pawn. The bishop on [g2] is not a great piece when the centre remains closed.} 5. Nc3 {This is the critical move, preparing to play [Nh4] very early. As I have mentioned, White needs to play dynamically in these lines.} e6 6. Nh4 {We move on to White's critical try, going after the bishop on [f5]. This is similar to the lines we saw in the 4.e3 chapter, but the move 4.g3 is less useful in comparison. Still, we need to play precisely.} Be4 {[%cal Rf2f3] We go for the same plan as we saw in the 4.e3 chapter, forcing White to weaken the kingside with the move [f3]. This is a double-edged idea, however, as it helps White get control over the centre.} 7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc1f4] The major difference compared to the earlier chapter is that White can get the bishop to [f4] in one go. This makes it impossible for us to put our queen on [c7].} Qd7 {[%csl Re1] We keep the queens on the board, which is more principled as White has weakened their kingside. The advantage is also that it is much less common compared to the main line.} (8... Qb6 {is the main move by far, and one of the top choices of the engine, but I do not want to trade queens when White can win the bishop pair.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. c5 Qxb3 11. axb3 Na6 {You can definitely analyse this further. It should be a draw with precise play, but I think Black has no chances to play for a win.}) 9. Nxg6 {This trade has to happen at one point or another. There is no point for White to maintain the tension for too long. If they do keep the tension, we can take on [c4] at the right moment and follow up with ...[Bc2].} hxg6 10. Bg5 {Seeing that there are very few games with this position, I've decided to analyze the top 3 choices of the computer. After 10.Bg5 White wants to play [e4] next.} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] This is our standard development, preparing to castle at a moment's notice.} 11. Rd1 (11. e4 {does not work due to} Nxe4 {⩱ . After mass trades we can break White's structure with ...[c5] and ...[Nc6].}) 11... Qc7 {We create a cheeky trap for White.} 12. Bg2 {This is exactly what we wanted to see. Can you figure out how we are better now?} ({Meanwhile,} 12. Bf4 {is met with} dxc4 13. Qxc4 Qa5 {⇆ , when ...[b5]-[b4] is coming up next.}) 12... dxc4 13. Qxc4 Rxh2 $15 {[%cal Gc7g3,Gh2h1,Gb8d7,Ge8c8] We win a pawn on the kingside, giving us a big advantage. We will trade on [h1] and play ...[Nbd7] followed by ...[O-O-O].} *

