 9. Nxg6 {This trade has to happen at one point or another. There is no point for White to maintain the tension for too long. If they do keep the tension, we can take on [c4] at the right moment and follow up with ...[Bc2].} hxg6 10. Bg2 {White gets ready to castle kingside. One of the issues for White is the pawn on [d4].} Be7 (10... Be7 {We keep it simple and consistent with our usual approach. We give White the option to transpose back to the main lines with} 11. Be3 {, which are considered next.}) (10... dxc4 {is also an option, to go after the [d4]-pawn. After} 11. Qxc4 b5 {Black should be okay, but I do not think it's necessary for us to play like this.}) 11. O-O {White decides to castle first and strengthen the centre next.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rg1] Of course, we grab the chance to break in the centre. This is very effective with White's king on [g1].} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e4 $1 {This is the best try for White, counter-attacking in the centre. They want to get the d-pawn to [d5], from where it will restrict our knight on [b8]. We have to be precise.} cxd4 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 {White trades the queens as they have the bishop pair. Both the central pawns are weak now, but it is easier for us to go after White's [d5]-pawn.} Qxd5 16. exd5 Na6 $10 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge8c8,Ga6b4] We will continue with either ...[Nb4] or queenside castling. The weak pawn on [d5] compensates for the bishop pair.} *

