 9. Nxg6 {This trade has to happen at one point or another. There is no point for White to maintain the tension for too long. If they do keep the tension, we can take on [c4] at the right moment and follow up with ...[Bc2].} hxg6 10. Be3 {This is the main move, keeping an eye on [d4]. Now lines where we take on [c4] are much less effective.} Be7 11. Bg2 a5 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4][%cal Ga5a4] I came up with this move after letting the engine run for a long time. We have a concrete threat of ...[a4] on the queenside. It is not easy for White to stop this. They have to release the tension with the c-pawn.} 12. c5 {This move was a headache for me initially, as the engines kept giving White a small but nagging edge. Sometimes all you need is to have trust in the position and keep analysing further. I felt very strongly that this should be fine for us, since White is releasing the tension.} Qc8 $1 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gb8d7] This is a very important move. We need to get the knight to [d7] as quickly as possible. White was threatening to play [Na4]-[b6]. The queen cannot go to [c7] yet due to [Bf4].} 13. Na4 Nbd7 14. O-O O-O {White has to play quickly to fight for an advantage. Otherwise we will go for the ...[e5] break.} 15. Rad1 {It looks natural to bring the rook to the centre, but this is too slow and does not create any threat.} Re8 {[%cal Gc8c7,Ge7d8,Ge6e5] We need the rook on the e-file to prepare the ...[e5] break.} 16. Kh1 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd7e5] Our preparations are complete and we are going to play ...[e5] next. We needed to be able to recapture on [e5] with the knight without allowing a fork on [b6].} *

