 9. Nxg6 {This trade has to happen at one point or another. There is no point for White to maintain the tension for too long. If they do keep the tension, we can take on [c4] at the right moment and follow up with ...[Bc2].} hxg6 10. Be3 {This is the main move, keeping an eye on [d4]. Now lines where we take on [c4] are much less effective.} Be7 11. Bg2 a5 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4][%cal Ga5a4] I came up with this move after letting the engine run for a long time. We have a concrete threat of ...[a4] on the queenside. It is not easy for White to stop this. They have to release the tension with the c-pawn.} 12. c5 {This move was a headache for me initially, as the engines kept giving White a small but nagging edge. Sometimes all you need is to have trust in the position and keep analysing further. I felt very strongly that this should be fine for us, since White is releasing the tension.} Qc8 $1 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gb8d7] This is a very important move. We need to get the knight to [d7] as quickly as possible. White was threatening to play [Na4]-[b6]. The queen cannot go to [c7] yet due to [Bf4].} 13. Na4 Nbd7 14. O-O O-O {White has to play quickly to fight for an advantage. Otherwise we will go for the ...[e5] break.} 15. Bf4 {This is the critical test, stopping us from playing ...[Qc7]. Now we need to act quickly to get the ...[e5] break in. Otherwise, it's a very annoying position for Black.} (15. Bf4 Re8 {runs into} 16. e4 {± .}) 15... Nh5 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Rf4b8] We kick the bishop back immediately before White can play [e4]. White would then put their bishop on [d6] and follow up with [e5].} 16. Bd2 {White has slightly improved the position of their bishop, targeting [a5]. It is not so easy for us to play the ...[e5] break now, as White will take and then put the knight on [b6].} (16. Be5 {can be met with} Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qc7 18. f4 g5 {, and we will get the move ...[g6] in next with a good position.}) 16... Qc7 17. Rac1 Rfb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b6] We are changing plans, preparing the ...[b6] break instead. This is the other typical reaction to White's [c5] advance. It should be more than enough if you remember the moves until here, but there is one critical line I still want to show.} 18. e4 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Ge4e5,Gg3g4] White intends to play [e5] and trap the [h5]-knight.} b6 $1 {We go all out on the queenside.} 19. cxb6 Nxb6 20. e5 Nc4 {We go for counterplay on the queenside. It is already too late to save the [h5]-knight.} 21. Qd3 (21. Qc2 {is met with} Qa7 {⇆ .}) 21... Nxb2 22. Nxb2 Rxb2 23. g4 Nf4 $1 {We do not want to further weaken our kingside. It is not worth winning a pawn.} 24. Bxf4 Rxa2 $10 {[%csl Ga2,Ga5][%cal Ga8b8] This is a fascinating position. White is up a whole piece, and in return we only have two disconnected pawns on our side of the board. However, the activity of our rook and the passed a-pawn fully compensate for the piece. Engines give a 0.00 evaluation, and it's anybody's game.} (24... Rxa2 {The game could continue with} 25. Be3 {, preparing to push the f-pawn down the board. We can go} Rb8 26. Rc2 Rbb2 27. Rxb2 Rxb2 28. f4 Qb6 29. f5 {and we are in time to get counterplay with} Qb3) *

