1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Bg5 ({I have faced this move twice against very strong opponents. Someone who plays} 4. Bg5 {is likely looking for a fight, and this is exactly what we are hoping too. There are several much safer lines for White to try to make a draw.}) 4... f6 {A very unusual move, but we are getting a tempo against the bishop and it is useful to gain space in the centre. We are very ambitious and want to play ...[e5] soon.} 5. Bd2 {The last few moves have been pretty unorthodox. White has no better square than [d2] to retreat to with the bishop. They will now try to play [Nc3] and [e4], opening up the position, to try and exploit our weakening move ...[f6].} Nc6 6. Nc3 {The principled move, as White is ready to give up the [d4]-pawn for development.} (6. e3 {is met with} e5 {with a fantastic position for Black.}) 6... e5 $1 {We are the first to break in the centre.} 7. e4 {White is not far behind, though.} dxe4 8. dxe5 fxe5 {[%cal Gg8f6] Although it looks like we have created a weak pawn on [e5], this allows us to get our knight to [f6] next. We will easily compensate for this with our piece activity.} 9. Bc4 {White focuses on developing their pieces quickly and getting the king to safety. The bishop on [c4] ensures that we cannot castle kingside.} Nf6 10. Nge2 Na5 $1 {[%csl Rc4] We need to get the [c4]-bishop out of the way as quickly as possible.} 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb5c7] This is clever as it ensures that, after an exchange on [b5], we cannot kick the knight away from [b5] that easily.} (12. O-O {is met with} Bxb5 13. Nxb5 a6 {, kicking the knight back.}) 12... e3 $1 {We give back the pawn, but we will be able to either trade the queens or develop our pieces with tempo.} 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Bxe3 Qxd1+ 15. Rxd1 Nc4 $10 {[%csl Gc4,Re3,Ge8] Our king will be perfect in the middle of the board in the endgame. The endgame is pretty even.} *

