1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4] This has been played quite a few times by Aditya, M a few years ago. It can be unpleasant to face over the board if we do not know what we are doing.} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Gb8c6] We are going to put pressure on the [d4]-pawn with ...[Nc6] next. The [b2]-pawn is also under attack, which makes it harder for White to defend his centre.} 6. e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 e5 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4] An important move, preventing White from playing [e5] themselves. We also open up the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop with a tempo.} 8. Bb5+ {This is the critical test. Now we need to be precise.} Nc6 $1 9. d5 Bb4 $1 {[%csl Rb5] White will not be able to maintain the pin for much longer, as we are going after the bishop on [b5].} 10. Qd3 a6 11. Ba4 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb4e1] Once again, the bishop is under attack. White either has to retreat or take on [c6], giving up the bishop.} 12. Bd1 Nd4 $36 {[%csl Re1,Re5][%cal Gc8d7,Gd7b5] There have been quite a few correspondence games which have reached this position. We are preparing ...[Bd7]-[b5] next. White's king is more exposed and their centre is under fire.} *

