1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. Ne5 {This has been played by Vidit a few times. I think a general pattern here is that if a move has been played less, it is likely to be an attempt to play for a win. Why would they not just go for the main lines, if they want to make a draw?} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4] The queen does a good job attacking two pawns. We want to see White release the tension with the knight on [e5].} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5]} 9. Qd2 {White keeps both pawns defended, but the queen is vulnerable on [d2], especially if we are able to trade off the [c3]-knight.} Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Rb4e1] First, we bring the bishop out of the pawn chain. We are now threatening to play ...[Ne4].} 10. f3 Qb7 $10 {[%csl Gc5,Rf3][%cal Gc3a4,Ge7e6] A clever prophylactic move, anticipating the plan of [Na4]-[c5]. The queen is still active on the b-file and our priority is to play ...[e6] and finish our development. White has weakened their position with the move [f3], which is exactly what we wanted.} *

