1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. Rc1 {White delays the move [e3], making it harder for us to develop our bishop to [g4]. The rook is generally pretty useful on the c-file.} Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6] We stick to our guns and are not too worried about the knight coming to [e5]. Otherwise, we are pretty happy to play ...[e6] and ...[Bd6] next. A big advantage of this move is that it has been played very few times compared to other moves.} (7... Bf5 {is certainly possible, but is much more common and likely to lead to a draw, as after} 8. e3 {we get an almost symmetrical position.}) 8. e3 {If White continues slowly, we would rather have the bishop on [g4] than on [f5].} e6 9. Qb3 {White tries to justify the move [Rc1] by going for concrete play on the queenside.} Bxf3 $1 {[%cal Rf3e5] We cannot allow the knight to [e5]. Also, this creates an imbalance, weakening White's kingside at the cost of the bishop pair.} 10. gxf3 Na5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga5c4,Gb7b5] It's time to kick White's queen back. Our knight will then get to the [c4]-square.} 11. Qa4+ {[%csl Re8][%cal Rb7b5,Gc3b5]} Nc6 {We unfortunately have to retreat. Our plan is to play ...[Bd6] and trade the dark-squared bishops.} 12. Qb3 {I feel this is very unlikely, as we have come quite a few moves into a rare line. But I will give you an option to deviate from White's repetition here just in case.} Bb4 {We can give up our dark-squared bishop to stop the knight from getting to [a4].} (12... Qd7 {would be ideal, but is met with} 13. Na4 {⩲ . Both [b6] and [c5] are weaknesses.}) 13. a3 Bxc3+ 14. Rxc3 Qd7 $10 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf6h5] White does have some pressure on the queenside, but objectively the position is close to equal. We can play ...[Nh5] in the future to trade the bishop on [f4].} *

