1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. Rc1 {White delays the move [e3], making it harder for us to develop our bishop to [g4]. The rook is generally pretty useful on the c-file.} Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6] We stick to our guns and are not too worried about the knight coming to [e5]. Otherwise, we are pretty happy to play ...[e6] and ...[Bd6] next. A big advantage of this move is that it has been played very few times compared to other moves.} (7... Bf5 {is certainly possible, but is much more common and likely to lead to a draw, as after} 8. e3 {we get an almost symmetrical position.}) 8. Ne5 {[%csl Rg4] This is definitely the critical move, targeting the bishop on [g4].} Nxe5 9. dxe5 {This is the scarier option at first sight, as it looks like we are losing the [d5]-pawn. However, White has not moved their [e2]-pawn yet, which is in our favour.} d4 $1 10. Na4 {This forces us to play some precise moves as the knight still lacks a good square to go to.} ({After} 10. exf6 dxc3 {the queens have to be traded one way or the other, and we reach an equal endgame.}) 10... g5 $1 {An important move to remember. We give up a pawn to get a tempo for our knight.} 11. Bxg5 Ne4 12. Bd2 Rc8 $10 {[%cal Ge4d2,Gc8c1,Gd8a5,Gb7b5] We are threatening to take on [d2] and go after the [a4]-knight. I am ending the line here because I feel it is very unlikely that we will get this in a practical game, and our play becomes easier from now on.} *

