compared to other moves.} (7... Bf5 {is certainly possible, but is much more common and likely to lead to a draw, as after} 8. e3 {we get an almost symmetrical position.}) 8. Ne5 {[%csl Rg4] This is definitely the critical move, targeting the bishop on [g4].} Nxe5 9. Bxe5 {White keeps their pawn structure intact and is threatening to take on [f6] next.} e6 {[%cal Gg4d1] We have achieved the first stage of our plan: getting the bishop out of the pawn chain. This [g4]-bishop ensures that White cannot play [e3] yet.} 10. Bxf6 {White takes the opportunity to damage our pawn structure on the kingside.} gxf6 ({We are unable to go} 10... Qxf6 $6 {due to} 11. Qa4+ b5 $2 12. Nxb5 $1 {.}) 11. Qd2 {[%cal Ge2e3] White needed to get the queen out of the way in order to be able to play [e3].} Bd6 12. e3 Bf5 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gf5g6] Our bishop belongs on [g6] in this structure, holding the kingside together. We anticipate White putting their bishop on [d3].} 13. Bd3 Bg6 14. O-O Rc8 {I want to keep the king on [e8] for the moment. We are waiting to see which plan White is going to go for.} 15. f4 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 f5 $10 {[%cal Ge8e7,Ge8d7,Gh8g8,Gg8g1] We stop White's play on the kingside. Next, we will put our king on either [e7] or [d7], where it is pretty safe.} *

