1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. Rc1 {White delays the move [e3], making it harder for us to develop our bishop to [g4]. The rook is generally pretty useful on the c-file.} Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6] We stick to our guns and are not too worried about the knight coming to [e5]. Otherwise, we are pretty happy to play ...[e6] and ...[Bd6] next. A big advantage of this move is that it has been played very few times compared to other moves.} (7... Bf5 {is certainly possible, but is much more common and likely to lead to a draw, as after} 8. e3 {we get an almost symmetrical position.}) 8. Ne5 {[%csl Rg4] This is definitely the critical move, targeting the bishop on [g4].} Nxe5 9. Bxe5 {White keeps his pawn structure intact and is threatening to take on [f6] next.} e6 {We have achieved the first stage of our plan: getting the bishop out of the pawn chain. This [g4]-bishop ensures that White cannot play [e3] yet.} 10. h4 {This is a clever move recommended by Alonso in his Catalan course on Chessable. There are a few different ways to play here.} h5 {We stop any potential play on the kingside. We will just be better here if White continues slowly.} (10... h6 {is an option but it gives White the chance to play on the kingside after} 11. f3 Bh5 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. e3 {∞}) 11. Bxf6 gxf6 {As we saw earlier, we are okay with doubling our pawn structure on the kingside in return for winning the bishop pair.} (11... Qxf6 $6 {runs into} 12. f3 {and White starts advancing in the centre next. Complicating the game with} Bd6 13. fxg4 Bg3+ 14. Kd2 Bf4+ 15. Kd3 {⩲ is still not fully enough for equality.}) 12. Qd2 {White prepares to go [e3] next and put the bishop on [d3].} Bd6 13. e3 Bf5 {This is a very important move to cover the diagonal before White can do the same. Our bishop is stuck on [g4] otherwise.} 14. g3 {White keeps the option of putting the bishop on either [g2] or trading them on [d3].} (14. Bd3 {is a bit premature.} Bxd3 15. Qxd3 f5 $1 {We have a nice plan of going ...[Ke7] followed by ...[Qg8]-[g4].}) 14... Kf8 {I like the simple plan of putting the king on [g7]. It is not going to be easy for White to create any attack on the kingside.} (14... Ke7 15. Bg2 {is annoying.}) 15. Bd3 {White has to trade the bishops to pose any problems.} Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Rc8 17. O-O Kg7 {The king can defend the pawn on [h5] in the endgame and we will likely put the pawn on [f5] in the future.} 18. Kg2 Qd7 $10 {[%cal Gb7b5] We will continue with ...[b5] on the queenside and double up on the c-file. The bishop on [d6] is very well placed and covers the important squares.} *

