1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. Rc1 {White delays the move [e3], making it harder for us to develop our bishop to [g4]. The rook is generally pretty useful on the c-file.} Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6] We stick to our guns and are not too worried about the knight coming to [e5]. Otherwise, we are pretty happy to play ...[e6] and ...[Bd6] next. A big advantage of this move is that it has been played very few times compared to other moves.} (7... Bf5 {is certainly possible, but is much more common and likely to lead to a draw, as after} 8. e3 {we get an almost symmetrical position.}) 8. Ne5 {[%csl Rg4] This is definitely the critical move, targeting the bishop on [g4].} Nxe5 9. Bxe5 {White keeps their pawn structure intact and is threatening to take on [f6] next.} e6 {[%cal Gg4d1] We have achieved the first stage of our plan: getting the bishop out of the pawn chain. This [g4]-bishop ensures that White cannot play [e3] yet.} 10. Qb3 {This has been played in most of the games which reached this position. White goes after the [b7]-pawn and also gets ready to play [e3].} Bd6 {We give up the [b7]-pawn in return for quick development.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. e3 {White plays more conservatively, looking to develop the kingside.} Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gd3] We stop the bishop from getting to [d3], its most active square.} 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O b5 $10 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf8b8,Ga6a5,Gb5b4] We will bring our [f8]-rook to [b8] next and then start pushing our pawns on the queenside. The bishop is well placed on [f5] and White has to trade it off at some point.} *

