1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. e3 {This is the most common move, preparing to develop the kingside.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1] The drawback of White's approach is that we can pin the knight on [f3]. In this system, we do not mind giving up our light-squared bishop. We will trade the dark-squared bishops on [d6] and likely get a knight vs bishop middlegame. With the centre blocked, I like our knight more than White's bishop.} 8. Qb3 {White can play [Qb3] on several different moves. Our reaction is going to be similar everywhere.} Bxf3 {We first create some weaknesses on the kingside for White.} 9. gxf3 Na5 {[%csl Rb3] We have seen this plan earlier too, kicking the queen away from [b3].} 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. Qb3 {Once again, I feel this is pretty unlikely to happen, but in case it does, you can always deviate here and continue playing for the win.} Ra7 {An ugly move, but it is sufficient to defend the [b7]-pawn.} (11... Na5 {leads to a repetition.}) 12. Bd3 e6 13. O-O Be7 $10 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf6h5] We will castle next and go after the dark-squared bishop with ...[Nh5] soon. White does have some pressure on the queenside, but it is close to equal.} *

