te's bishop.} 8. h3 {This makes more sense, but it is unclear if White's queen is an asset or a liability on the kingside.} Bxf3 {We cannot retreat as then White would start pushing pawns on the kingside. We have to keep in mind that our move ...[a6] was a non-developing move, and we cannot afford to play very slowly.} (8... Bh5 $2 {is bad due to} 9. g4 Bg6 10. Qb3 {± , after which White will follow up with [h4]-[h5].}) 9. Qxf3 e6 10. Bd3 Bd6 {As mentioned, we want to trade off the dark-squared bishops. White has a few options now.} 11. O-O {White goes for an approach similar to the one in the previous line.} Bxf4 {We immediately trade the bishops before White has the option to play [Bg5]. Also, the queen is not doing much on [f4].} 12. Qxf4 Rc8 (12... Qb6 {is not possible here due to} 13. Na4 {⩲ and there is no check on [a5].}) 13. Rac1 O-O {If this position seems familiar, we are back to the game between Abasov and Hikaru, but this move order meant that we were not able to get our queen to [b6].} 14. a3 Na5 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2,Gc4] The move [a3] makes it easier for us to plant our knight on [c4]. White is unable to play [b3] without losing the [a3]-pawn.} 15. Na4 Rxc1 16. Rxc1 Nc4 $10 {[%csl Rb2,Rf4][%cal Gb7b5] We are ready to play ...[b5] next, after which the [b2]-pawn is in trouble. White would prefer to have the queen on [e2], holding the queenside together.} *

