1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. e3 {This is the most common move, preparing to develop the kingside.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1] The drawback of White's approach is that we can pin the knight on [f3]. In this system, we do not mind giving up our light-squared bishop. We will trade the dark-squared bishops on [d6] and likely get a knight vs bishop middlegame. With the centre blocked, I like our knight more than White's bishop.} 8. h3 {This makes more sense, but it is unclear if White's queen is an asset or a liability on the kingside.} Bxf3 {We cannot retreat as then White would start pushing pawns on the kingside. We have to keep in mind that our move ...[a6] was a non-developing move, and we cannot afford to play very slowly.} (8... Bh5 $2 {is bad due to} 9. g4 Bg6 10. Qb3 {± , after which White will follow up with [h4]-[h5].}) 9. Qxf3 e6 10. Bd3 Bd6 {As mentioned, we want to trade off the dark-squared bishops. White has a few options now.} 11. Bg5 {White keeps the bishop on the board and we will have to contend with the pin on the [f6]-knight.} h6 12. Bh4 Nb4 {[%csl Rd3] This is a clever move, forcing the bishop to [b1]. This ensures that White will have to play [a3] at some point, which is not a move they're happy to make. We saw earlier that this pawn being on [a3] makes our plan of [Na5]-[c4] easier to achieve.} 13. Bb1 Rc8 14. O-O O-O {The move order is not very important in these positions. We want to play ...[Be7] and regroup the queenside knight later.} 15. a3 Nc6 16. Bd3 Be7 $10 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2][%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Gb7b5] We can play ...[Na5] next, now that White has played the move [a3]. We will follow it up with ...[b5].} *

