1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. Nf3 {Let us start with the most played move in the position, even though I feel that this is slightly less precise. It makes more sense to keep the knight flexible for at least one more move.} a6 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gc8f5] I wanted to go for something which A is non-symmetrical and has some imbalance; B is consistent with both the knight moves Nf3 and Ne2.On [a6] the pawn covers the [b5]-square, and we can bring our bishop out to either [g4] or [f5] next. Another point is that it makes it easier for us to play ...[b5] in the future.} 7. e3 {This is the most common move, preparing to develop the kingside.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1] The drawback of White's approach is that we can pin the knight on [f3]. In this system, we do not mind giving up our light-squared bishop. We will trade the dark-squared bishops on [d6] and likely get a knight vs bishop middlegame. With the centre blocked, I like our knight more than White's bishop.} 8. Be2 {This is the most played move in the position, defending the [f3]-knight with the bishop. Even then, the bishop is not doing much there on [f3].} e6 9. Ne5 {White trades off two minor pieces, simplifying the position. It is a pain playing such opponents, but we cannot do much more. Just keep the game going for as long as possible. That is why these days most professional players have multiple openings in their repertoire to choose from. However, we always need a solid main option which we can play anytime. I feel only after learning a solid line should you start experimenting with alternatives.} Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c6] We want to take on [c6] with the rook, fighting for the c-file.} 11. O-O Bb4 $5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb4c3] This has been played in very few games so far. Our intention is to take on [c3] and imbalance the pawn structure.} 12. Rfc1 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 O-O $10 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gf6d7,Gd7b6] We are ready to take on [c3] now. We had to castle first because our idea is to take and immediately follow up with ...[Nd7], bringing the knight to the queenside.} *

