1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Be2 {White forces us to abandon the idea of getting our bishop to [g4]. However, White's bishop is also slightly more passive on [e2] than on its usual square [d3].} Bf5 {The bishop looks good on [f5], but is it doing something useful there? We have to be careful, since compared to the previous lines it is harder for us to get the ...[e5] break in. All the pieces are still on the board.} 8. g4 {This is an aggressive approach by White to justify the bishop on [e2]. I do not think it is so effective, as the knight on [g1] lacks a good square.} Be4 {[%csl Rg1] We force White to further restrict their own knight with the move [f3]. We would be happy to trade our bishop for the [c3]-night with White having made a lot of weaknesses on the kingside. They have to try and go after our bishop.} 9. f3 Bg6 10. h4 h6 {Our bishop is safe on [g6]. We will not castle kingside immediately but keep the option open. White also lacks a safe square for the king.} 11. Nh3 e6 12. Kf2 Be7 $10 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7b6] We will play ...[Nd7] next, attacking [h4] and bringing the knight over to the queenside. Our king is fine on [e8] for now.} *

