1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Be2 {White forces us to abandon the idea of getting our bishop to [g4]. However, White's bishop is also slightly more passive on [e2] than on its usual square [d3].} Bf5 {The bishop looks good on [f5], but is it doing something useful there? We have to be careful, since compared to the previous lines it is harder for us to get the ...[e5] break in. All the pieces are still on the board.} 8. Nf3 e6 9. Qb3 {White targets the [b7]-pawn. This makes a lot of sense, as we are unable to push White back with ...[Na5] and ...[b5]. Earlier, we were able to take on [f3] whenever White brought the queen over to the queenside.} Nh5 $1 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gd8c7] An important move, going after the dark-squared bishop. We need to be able to put our queen on [c7], covering the queenside.} (9... Na5 {is bad due to} 10. Qa4+ b5 11. Nxb5 axb5 12. Bxb5+ {± . Here 10...Nc6 also fails due to 11.Ne5! +- .}) 10. Be5 {This is clever. White wants to force us to weaken our kingside with the move ...[f6]. This also traps our knight on [h5], and White can target it with their bishop on [e2].} Na5 11. Qa4+ Nc6 {[%csl Re5] We have seen this idea before. We are unable to play the move ...[b5], but we have managed to kick White's queen away from [b3]. It is not doing too much on [a4]. The reason this works here is because of the bishop on [e5]: White is unable to answer [Ne5] as in earlier positions.} 12. h3 {[%cal Ge5h2] White creates a square on [h2] for the bishop. It will take us a while, though, to actually threaten to win the bishop on [e5], due to the pin and the position of our [h5]-knight.} (12. Qb3 {is another ugly attempt to make a draw as White. We need to make some concessions if we want to keep the game going:} f6 13. Nh4 Bg6 {The position is a bit unpleasant for Black, but objectively close to equal. You can check this out in more detail if needed.}) 12... Nf6 13. O-O Be7 14. Rfc1 O-O 15. Bg3 {White manages to keep their bishop on the board, but I do not see a clear plan for them to continue.} Rc8 $10 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gc6a5,Ga5c4] We want to play ...[Qb6] next and start playing on the queenside. White cannot meet this move with [Qb3], as that would really weaken their pawn structure. We can also go ...[Na5]-[c4] when White tries to get in [a3] and [b4].} *

