1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Bd3 {White gets their bishop to [d3], but keeps options open regarding the [g1]-knight.} Bg4 {Of course, we develop the bishop to [g4] before going for the move ...[e6].} 8. Qb3 {This is not very effective here, with the [c8]-[h3] diagonal still open for our bishop.} Na5 9. Qa4+ b5 {[%cal Gg4d7] Unlike the previous variations where we had already played ...[e6], we can move the bishop back to [d7] at any point now.} 10. Qc2 (10. Nxb5 $2 {does not work here:} axb5 11. Bxb5+ Bd7 {-+ .}) 10... Rc8 11. h3 Bh5 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gh5g6] At least now the bishop cannot come back to [d7], but instead, it can go to [g6] and trade off White's light-squared bishop.} 12. Nge2 e6 $10 {[%cal Gh5g6,Ga5c4] We will follow up with ...[Bg6]. The knight will come to [c4] and we have very good play on the queenside.} *

