1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Bd3 {White gets their bishop to [d3], but keeps options open regarding the [g1]-knight.} Bg4 {Of course, we develop the bishop to [g4] before going for the move ...[e6].} 8. f3 {White wants to start pushing pawns on the kingside. This is a risky strategy, as we have not yet committed our king anywhere. I do not think it is going to lead to much, as we can just bring our bishop to [g6] and trade off the bishops.} Bh5 9. Nge2 (9. Qb3 {is met with} Na5 10. Qa4+ Nc6 {.}) 9... e6 10. O-O Bg6 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gf6h5] We force the trade of the light-squared bishops and also vacate the [h5]-square for the knight.} 11. Rc1 Be7 12. Na4 Nh5 {We go after White's dark-squared bishop now, making sure that it cannot retreat.} 13. Be5 Rc8 {[%csl Gc5] We are not in a hurry to win the bishop immediately. It is always an option to capture, and mainly we stop White's knight from coming to [c5].} 14. h3 $2 {I thought this move makes sense as White wants to retreat to [h2], but it is a serious mistake. It weakens the kingside a lot.} Nxe5 15. dxe5 Rxc1 16. Nxc1 {The knight is misplaced on [c1] and White has given up control over the [g3]-square.} b5 17. Nc3 Bc5 $17 {[%csl Re3,Rg1][%cal Gd8g5] We are ready to play ...[Qg5]. The knight on [h5] can jump to both [f4] and [g3] and our attack is very quick on the kingside.} *

