1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Bd3 {White gets their bishop to [d3], but keeps options open regarding the [g1]-knight.} Bg4 {Of course, we develop the bishop to [g4] before going for the move ...[e6].} 8. Nge2 e6 9. Rc1 Bd6 {We've developed our light-squared bishop to [g4], and now we offer the trade of dark-squared bishops.} 10. f3 Bh5 11. O-O Bg6 {[%csl Gd3] This is a common theme in these lines where White goes for the move [f3]. We trade the bishops and will try to exploit some of the weaknesses in White's pawn structure in the centre.} 12. Na4 O-O 13. Nc5 {The knight lands on [c5], but this does not achieve much.} Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Bxf4 15. Nxf4 Qe7 $10 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c7,Gf8c8,Ge6e5] We will bring our rook to the c-file next and try to regroup our knights. We can also go for the ...[e5] break at the right moment.} *

