1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {Finally we come to the dreaded Slav Exchange. This was one of the reasons why I started playing the Nimzo move order to reach the Semi-Slav. 3.cxd5 is a common move across all levels, and in many cases, White is happy to make a draw. This is a challenge, as we would need to take undue risks to get a complicated game.Instead, my approach is simple: as much as possible I will try to give the more complex option if it is objectively fine for us. Our focus should be to play a long game and try to outplay our opponent. At the same time, it is very much possible that White will try to fight for an advantage in these lines.} cxd5 {White has three different ways to reach the main lines. They can start with either [Bf4], [Nc3] or [Nf3]. It is better to delay the development of the [g1] knight as it can come to [e2] in some lines.} 4. Nc3 {This is the most flexible option and can also be reached via 3.Nc3 Nf6 and then 4.cxd5 .} Nf6 5. Bf4 {Once again, the bishop almost always lands on [f4] in these lines, which makes it the more flexible move.} Nc6 6. e3 ({This move gives White a few additional options compared to the lines with} 6. Nf3 {. I think 6.e3 is more likely to be played by players who want to play for the win.}) 6... a6 {We stick to the same approach. We are waiting for White to decide on their plan first.} 7. Bd3 {White gets their bishop to [d3], but keeps options open regarding the [g1]-knight.} Bg4 {Of course, we develop the bishop to [g4] before going for the move ...[e6].} 8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 {[%cal Gd6f4,Gg4d1] We are threatening to take on [f4], as White cannot recapture with the knight currently.} 10. f3 Bh5 11. Na4 {[%cal Ga4c5] White gets the knight to [c5] one move earlier in this line, which changes the situation a bit.} Bg6 12. Nc5 Bxc5 {We change the pawn structure in the centre, creating a potential target on [c5]. At the same time, we give up our important dark-squared bishop. Its absence will not be felt too much, as we will trade the light-squared bishops, not giving White the bishop pair.} 13. dxc5 O-O 14. Rc1 Re8 $10 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge6e5,Gg6d3,Gd5d4,Gb7b6] We are ready to play ...[e5] next. We can also take on [d3] and go for the move ...[d4] first and then follow it up with ...[e5]. We can always play ...[b6] and get rid of the pawn on [c5].} *

