1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Bf4 {I think putting the bishop on [f4] so soon is a bit premature. I did not know this before I started preparing the material for this course, but it is better to start with the move 2.Nf3 first. We can try to exploit the move order 2.Bf4 now. 2...c5 3.e3 cxd4 I had not come across this move properly earlier. If you examine the position closely, you will realise that this can also appear via the Exchange Caro-kann where the move [Bf4] is not the critical test of Black's position. Of course, if you want to avoid this structure, you can check out the alternative lines which will likely transpose to the main lines.}) (2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White manages to get the move [e4] in quickly. Otherwise, the knight is just misplaced and hampers White's queenside play.} c5 {We go for an early surprise, as this is only the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the positioning of the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c4], which is one of White's main ways of playing against Black's center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and White then cannot play [c3].}) 2... Nf6 3. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade : This has been played by almost all top players once in a while. I think the London is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, as it is pretty easy to learn. It can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses for Black which allow us to equalize.} (3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids going for the move [c4] and instead will look to keep the centre intact. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we will take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but we often have to deviate in order to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.}) (3. Bg5 {This is the best version of the Trompowsky we can face via our move order, as we start with 1...d5. The Trompowsky in general is much more effective against the 1...Nf6 move order.} Ne4 {We get our knight to the centre with a tempo, attacking the [g5]-bishop. This helps us get the move ...[c5] on the queenside.}) 3... e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will go ...[c5] a bit later as we do not want White to get their bishop to [b5] easily.} 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bg3 (5. Ne5 {was recommended by Srinath and Sahaj in their LTR on the London on Chessable. It is a serious attempt to play for a win as White, but it also gives us the chance to take over in the complications.}) 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gb8d7] This is an important moment, which we need to remember clearly. Our plan is to get the knight to [d7] to control the [e5] square. We can then either go for the ...[e5] break or, more frequently, ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], finishing our development. We keep the diagonal open for the bishop and keep the [c5]-pawn defended.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Arjun's Semi-Slav"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The London System & Early Sidelines: Overview"]
[Black "Navara, David vs. Bok"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "D02"]
[PlyCount "58"]
[GameId "2136127627698728"]

{We come to the final model game for this course, and what better opening to look at than the dreaded London System? Almost every Tom, Dick, and Harry has this system in their opening repertoire.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 (3... d5 {I prefer this move order. We will go ...[Bd6] next and castle first before going ...[c5].} 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bg3 O-O 6. c3 c5 {transposes to the game.}) 4. e3 d5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 O-O 7. Nbd2 Qc7 $1 {As we saw in the section overview, this is an important idea to know, as we want to fight for the [e5]-square. The knight will go to [d7] rather than [c6], which is a big improvement.} 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bxg3 10. hxg3 b6 (10... e5 {is another plan, but it simplifies the position too much for my liking.}) 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bb7 {This is a good structure to play for a win. We have an imbalance, and the bishop on [b7] is very active. It is also a very common structure in this line.} 13. Qe2 cxd4 ({In the theory section I recommend the move} 13... Qc6 {.}) 14. Nxd4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nc5 17. Qc6 Rac8 {White is clearly okay with a draw here. He wants to trade as many pieces as possible. This happens very frequently at lower levels, where people who are lower-rated try to simplify the game as much as possible.} 18. Qxc7 Rxc7 19. Rad1 Na4 20. Rd2 Rd8 {Even though objectively the position is close to equal, Black is clearly pressing here. Right now, Black is threatening to go ...[e5], when the [b2]-pawn is hanging at the end of the line.} 21. f4 g6 (21... h5 {↑ could be a better move here, in order to stop White's kingside expansion. It would fix some of White's weaknesses on the kingside.}) 22. g4 b5 (22... g5 $5 {is another option to keep the game complex.} 23. g3 Rd5) 23. Rff2 b4 24. Nb5 Rxd2 25. Rxd2 bxc3 $1 {Black forces some weaknesses in White's position.} 26. Rd8+ (26. bxc3 Rc5 27. Rd8+ Kg7 28. Nd6 {White manages to get enough counterplay here.}) 26... Kg7 27. Nxc7 {White thought that he was simplifying into a knight endgame, but it ends up being a whole lot worse.} (27. bxc3 {was necessary:} Rc6 28. Nxa7 Rxc3 29. Nb5) 27... cxb2 28. Rd1 (28. Rb8 Nb6 {-+}) 28... Nc3 29. Re1 Ne2+ $1 {The knight is heading to [c1] next, and then Black will queen the b-pawn. A short end to the game, but it shows some of the typical ideas for Black to put pressure on White's position in this structure.} 0-1

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Arjun's Semi-Slav"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The London System & Early Sidelines: Overview"]
[Black "Richter, Michael vs. Lupulescu"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "D05"]
[PlyCount "116"]
[GameId "2136127627715113"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 e6 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. Qe2 Ne4 {This is my main recommendation in the course. Black would love to go ...[Bd6] next and maybe ...[f5] to consolidate control over the centre.} 9. Ne5 (9. c4 {is the best move, which is analysed here.}) 9... Bd6 (9... Nxe5 {is another decent option forcing White to recapture with the d-pawn.} 10. dxe5 a6 {We stop a check on [b5]. We can go ...[Qc7] next and castle queenside.} 11. f4 Qc7) 10. f4 O-O 11. Bxe4 $6 {White gives up his best minor piece very easily. He leaves Black with the bishop pair. In addition, the bishop on [c1] is completely stuck.} (11. Nxe4 {was a better option.} dxe4 12. Bb5 Nf6 {Black will go ...[a6] and ...[b5] next.}) 11... dxe4 12. Ndc4 Ba6 $1 {This pin is a big frustration for White. We can take on [c4] at the right moment to force a weakness on the queenside.} 13. b3 f6 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. a4 Qc6 16. Ba3 Rfd8 {Black has played a perfect game so far. Now, he will retreat with the bishop back to [f8] next, and White is just stuck.} 17. Rfd1 Bf8 18. dxc5 $6 {This is a bad exchange, opening up the d-file.} (18. Qg4 Rac8 {∓}) 18... bxc5 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Rd1 Bxc4 $1 {We transform our advantage by forcing clear weaknesses for us to exploit on the queenside.} 21. bxc4 Rd3 {This gives White more chances than necessary in the endgame. However, it is a very practical decision to simplify the position.} (21... Rb8 {-+ is slightly more precise.}) 22. Rxd3 exd3 23. Qxd3 Qxa4 24. Bc1 Qa1 (24... a5 {-+ is more precise, keeping options open.}) 25. Qc2 a5 26. Kf2 $6 {This is a natural move but is objectively a decisive mistake.} (26. e4 $1 {I analysed the endgame quite a bit, and it is fascinating. The pawn structure on the kingside matters a lot, and the value of a tempo is very high. The main point now is that White remains flexible, and the king can go to [h3] in some lines, as we will see.} a4 27. Qb2 Qxb2 28. Bxb2 Kf7 29. g3 Kg6 30. Kg2 Kh5 31. Kh3 {This is the key point. White is able to go [g4] next.}) 26... a4 27. Qb2 {This is White's best try.} Qxb2+ 28. Bxb2 Kf7 29. e4 Kg6 $1 {This is the key idea here. We are bringing the king to [h5]. White had to get the king to [h3] in time to be able to hold. We have to prepare the ...[g5] break at the right moment.} 30. Kf3 (30. g4 {does not work due to} h6 $1 {This is a very important move to stop the move [g5]. We are going to break with ...[f5] next. (( 30...f5 31.exf5+ exf5 32.g5= ))} 31. Kf3 f5 $1 32. h3 Be7 33. Ba3 fxg4+ 34. hxg4 Kf7 $1 {Black will go ...[g5] next with the decisive breakthrough.} 35. Bb2 g5 36. fxg5 Bxg5 {-+}) 30... f5 $2 ({This is the wrong plan here.} 30... Kh5 $1 {was essential to stop the move [g4]. Now, we can meet it with ...[Kh4].} 31. g3 g5 $1 {and now} 32. fxg5 {opens up the diagonal for the bishop.} fxg5 33. h3 Bg7 {-+ . Better is 32.f5 g4+ 33.Ke3 and now not 33...Bh6+ 34.Kd3= but 33...Kg5! A very important move. We want to open up the centre. 34.fxe6 f5! 35.e5 f4+! 36.gxf4+ Kf5 -+}) 31. g4 $2 {White blunders in return. This allows Black to imbalance the pawn structure and eventually break through.} (31. exf5+ $1 {Now, the position becomes too symmetrical.} Kxf5 32. g4+ Kf6 33. Bc1 g6 34. Ke4 {. Or 31...exf5 32.h3 Kh5 33.g3 Be7 34.Ba3 Bd6 35.Bb2 h6 36.Bc1 g5 37.Kg2 gxf4 38.gxf4 Kh4 39.Kh2 Bc7 40.Kg2 Ba5 41.Bb2=}) 31... fxg4+ $1 32. Kxg4 Be7 33. Ba3 Kf7 $2 ({Black gives White another chance to hold.} 33... h5+ {is the easiest winning plan.} 34. Kf3 Kf6 35. Ke2 g6 36. Kf3 e5 37. fxe5+ Kxe5 {-+}) 34. Kf3 $2 {This is the wrong plan. White sticks to waiting around, and Black eventually finds the right plan.} (34. h4 $1 {White is able to get the pawn to [h5] in time.} g6 35. h5 $1 gxh5+ 36. Kxh5 {It looks like White is able to hold the fortress although more analysis is needed here.}) 34... Bf6 (34... g5 {-+ is much faster.}) 35. Bb2 Ke8 36. Ke2 Kf7 37. Kf3 g5 38. fxg5 Bxg5 39. Kg4 Kg6 40. Kf3 Kh5 41. Ba3 Be7 42. h3 Bd6 43. Kg2 Kh4 44. Bc1 Be5 45. Ba3 Bxc3 46. Bxc5 Kg5 47. Bd6 Kf6 48. Ba3 Ke5 49. Kf3 Kd4 50. c5 Ba5 51. h4 Kc4 52. Kf4 Bc7+ 53. Kg5 Bd8+ 54. Kf4 Kd4 55. c6 Bc7+ 56. Kf3 h5 57. Be7 Kc4 58. Ke3 Kb5 0-1

