[Black "London: 2.Bf4 with 3.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2136127627731498"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... c5 {We waste no time in fighting for the centre.} 3. e3 cxd4 {I had not come across this move properly earlier. If you examine the position closely, you will realise that this can also appear via the Exchange Caro-Kann where the move [Bf4] is not a critical test. Of course, if you want to avoid this structure, you can check out the alternate lines which will likely transpose to the London main lines.} 4. exd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5g4,Ge7e6] We have seen similar structures in the previous chapter. We want to develop the bishop either to [f5] or [g4] before playing ...[e6].} 5. Nf3 {This is a natural move, but it gives us the additional option of pinning the knight on [f3].} (5. Nc3 {will transpose to the next chapter after} Bf5 {.}) 5... Bf5 {We keep the lines consistent, as White could have forced us to develop the bishop to [f5] anyway. It is in no way worse on [f5] compared to [g4].} 6. c4 {This is the only independent option I can see here, as other moves transpose to upcoming lines.} e6 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gd5c4] We are waiting for White to develop the light-squared bishop, after which we will take on [c4]. We can also put our bishop on [b4] if White develops the knight to [c3].} 7. c5 Nge7 {[%cal Gf7f6,Ge7c6] This is important as we will often need to play ...[f6] in these lines. The knight defends the other knight on [c6], anticipating the move [Bb5].} 8. Qb3 Qd7 9. Bb5 f6 {[%cal Gg7g5,Ge8f7] We are ready to play ...[g5] next, and our king has a great square on [f7].} 10. h4 a6 11. Ba4 g6 $10 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg6g5,Gf8g7,Ge8f7] This is a clever move. We are preparing to play ...[h6] next, followed by ...[g5]. Before that we will put our king on [f7] and the bishop on [g7]. There is no rush. White cannot play [h5] on any move as this allows us to push our g-pawn to [g5] immediately.} *

