1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... c5 {We waste no time in fighting for the centre.} 3. e3 cxd4 {I had not come across this move properly earlier. If you examine the position closely, you will realise that this can also appear via the Exchange Caro-Kann where the move [Bf4] is not a critical test. Of course, if you want to avoid this structure, you can check out the alternate lines which will likely transpose to the London main lines.} 4. exd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5g4,Ge7e6] We have seen similar structures in the previous chapter. We want to develop the bishop either to [f5] or [g4] before playing ...[e6].} 5. c3 {White delays the development of the knight on [f3] to discourage us from playing ...[Bg4].} Bf5 {I am pretty happy with the [f5]-square as it means we will either trade the bishops on [d3] or force White's light-squared bishop to a more passive square.} 6. Nf3 e6 7. Bd3 {Trading the bishops is not very ambitious for White.} Nge7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Ge7g6,Gh7h5] We would love to recapture on [f5] with the knight. Another idea is to get the knight to [g6] and go after White's dark-squared bishop. I quite like these ideas to delay castling.} (7... Bxd3 {followed by ...[Bd6] is perfectly fine too.}) 8. O-O Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Ng6 10. Bg3 h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] This was the point of playing ...[Ne7]-[g6] so early. We want to get our pawn to [h4].} 11. h3 h4 12. Bh2 Bd6 $10 {[%csl Gf4,Gh4] We do end up trading the bishops, but getting the pawn to [h4] is a big achievement, especially in the endgame.} *

