1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... c5 {We waste no time in fighting for the centre.} 3. e3 cxd4 {I had not come across this move properly earlier. If you examine the position closely, you will realise that this can also appear via the Exchange Caro-Kann where the move [Bf4] is not a critical test. Of course, if you want to avoid this structure, you can check out the alternate lines which will likely transpose to the London main lines.} 4. exd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5g4,Ge7e6] We have seen similar structures in the previous chapter. We want to develop the bishop either to [f5] or [g4] before playing ...[e6].} 5. c3 {White delays the development of the knight on [f3] to discourage us from playing ...[Bg4].} Bf5 {I am pretty happy with the [f5]-square as it means we will either trade the bishops on [d3] or force White's light-squared bishop to a more passive square.} 6. Nf3 e6 7. Nbd2 {This is more flexible, keeping the options open.} h6 {[%csl Gh7] We do the same and create a luft for the bishop on [h7]. We can decide on how to develop our pieces based on White's next move.} 8. Qb3 Qd7 {[%cal Gf8d6] We now defend the [b7]-pawn first before playing ...[Bd6] next. We can also consider starting an attack on the kingside with the moves ...[f6] and ...[g5].} 9. Bb5 f6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg7g5] This prepares the move ...[g5] and also stops the threat of [Ne5].} 10. h4 Nge7 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gg7g5,Gh4g5,Ge7g6] We are ready to play ...[g5] now, as we have the intermediate move ...[Ng6] attacking the bishop on [f4].} 11. h5 g5 12. hxg6 Nxg6 13. Bg3 h5 $10 {[%cal Gf8h6,Ge8c8] White is not able to castle kingside anymore. We will put our bishop on [h6] next. We can castle queenside at the right moment.} *

