1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... c5 {We waste no time in fighting for the centre.} 3. e3 cxd4 {I had not come across this move properly earlier. If you examine the position closely, you will realise that this can also appear via the Exchange Caro-Kann where the move [Bf4] is not a critical test. Of course, if you want to avoid this structure, you can check out the alternate lines which will likely transpose to the London main lines.} 4. exd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5g4,Ge7e6] We have seen similar structures in the previous chapter. We want to develop the bishop either to [f5] or [g4] before playing ...[e6].} 5. c3 {White delays the development of the knight on [f3] to discourage us from playing ...[Bg4].} Bf5 {I am pretty happy with the [f5]-square as it means we will either trade the bishops on [d3] or force White's light-squared bishop to a more passive square.} 6. Nf3 e6 7. Qb3 {This is a very tempting move, as the absence of our light-squared bishop weakens the [b7]-pawn.} Bd6 $1 {It would be great if you could memorize this idea, as it is not very intuitive. We are willing to give up the [b7]-pawn in return for White's bishop.} 8. Qxb7 Bxf4 {[%csl Gf4,Gf5]} 9. Qxc6+ Kf8 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ga8b8] The king is doing pretty well on [f8] while White is lagging behind in development. We will get the knight out with a tempo against the queen on [c6]. The queenside is a target for us as we have two open files.} 10. Nbd2 Rb8 11. Nb3 g6 $10 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf8g7] We create a square on [g7] for the king. I encourage you to play around with this position. You will realise that we have long-term compensation for the pawn. The white queen will take a long time to get back to safety.} *

