1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... e6 {This is a good alternative if you just want to transpose back to our main lines in the London. We will see the independent options here for White.} 3. Nc3 {Usually, this would transpose to the next chapter based on 2.Nc3. However, I am recommending the move ...[c5] there instead of ...[e6], so we need to cover this alternative.} Bd6 {This is clever as we avoid a lot of theory. We immediately trade off the dark-squared bishops before White is able to get the knight to [b5].} 4. e3 {White maintains the tension, keeping the bishop on [f4] for now.} (4. Bxd6 {is harmless after} Qxd6 {.}) 4... Bxf4 {We take immediately, not giving White the option to defend the bishop with [Qf3].} 5. exf4 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gc7c5] The knight is better here compared to [f6], keeping an eye on [f5]. Next, we are going to prepare the move ...[c5] on the queenside.} 6. Nf3 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gc7c5] This is a multipurpose move, preparing to play both ....[Ba6] and the ...[c5] break.} 7. Qd2 {White is preparing to castle queenside.} (7. Bd3 {can be met with} c5 8. O-O c4 {. We will focus on the queenside next and start pushing the b-pawn.}) 7... c5 8. O-O-O c4 {[%csl Rc1,Gc4][%cal Gb6b5,Gb5b4] There is a similar idea in the Classical French. White is supposed to take on [c5] before they castle, as the move ...[c4] allows Black to attack freely on the queenside. White has no counterplay in the centre. We are going to play ...[b5]-[b4] soon.} 9. b3 Ba6 10. bxc4 O-O $36 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gd8d6] We are not in a rush to take on [c4]. Instead, we will continue with the move ...[Qd6] next. White will have to take on [d5] at some point, further exposing the queenside.} *

