1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... e6 {This is a good alternative if you just want to transpose back to our main lines in the London. We will see the independent options here for White.} 3. e3 (3. Nf3 {is a direct transposition after} Nf6 {.}) 3... Nf6 {Our plan is simple: we play ...[Bd6] next, followed by ...[O-O]. We will then continue with ...[c5]. Whenever White goes for the move [Nf3], it transposes to the main line.} 4. c4 {This has been played a few times by Melkumyan.} Bb4+ {We exploit the move [c4], which has weakened the [a5]-[e1] diagonal.} 5. Nd2 {Melkumyan has played this as White 5 times. It looks pretty bad at first sight, but White has some resources.} Ne4 6. Ngf3 g5 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg5g4] We have seen these ideas several times already. Here, in addition to going after the bishop on [f4], we are also hinting at an attack on the [f3]-knight which is defending [d2].} 7. Bg3 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} (7... g4 {can be answered by} 8. a3 {± .}) 8. Qc2 $1 {The only move for White not to get a worse position.} Nc6 {We are preparing to play ...[h4] next, as we have covered the [e5]-square.} (8... h4 {does not work immediately:} 9. Be5 f6 10. cxd5 {⩲ .}) 9. O-O-O Nxd2 10. Nxd2 h4 11. Be5 Nxe5 {Unfortunately, we could not trap the bishop with the move ...[f6] due to the queen on [c2], but we do win the dark-squared bishop.} 12. dxe5 Bd7 $10 {[%csl Gb4,Gd7][%cal Gc7c6,Gd8a5] The position is pretty unusual. We will play ...[c6] next followed by ...[Qa5], and try to create play on the queenside. I like the fact that we have the bishop pair. The position is dynamically balanced.} *

