1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... e6 {This is a good alternative if you just want to transpose back to our main lines in the London. We will see the independent options here for White.} 3. e3 (3. Nf3 {is a direct transposition after} Nf6 {.}) 3... Nf6 {Our plan is simple: we play ...[Bd6] next, followed by ...[O-O]. We will then continue with ...[c5]. Whenever White goes for the move [Nf3], it transposes to the main line.} 4. c4 {This has been played a few times by Melkumyan.} Bb4+ {We exploit the move [c4], which has weakened the [a5]-[e1] diagonal.} 5. Nc3 {This looks more natural and safe.} c5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd8a5] We have a lead in development right now and we want to utilise this. White has to be careful, as we are threatening to play ...[Ne4] and ...[Qa5] very quickly. They cannot release the tension in the centre.} 6. Nf3 cxd4 7. exd4 O-O {Now the pawn structure is in our favour. We will wait for the [f1]-bishop to move before taking on [c4].} 8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd5 10. Bd2 {We have a tactical opportunity here if we are alert.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qc7 $10 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] We are going after the [c3]-pawn. White has to be careful not to lose the light-squared bishop very easily, with the king still in the centre.} *

