[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2136127627838002"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {Welcome to one of the most talked about openings of the last decade :-. The London System has been played by almost all players once in a while. I think it is a good opening to start playing 1.d4 with, and is pretty easy to learn. The London can be a decent surprise weapon, and White typically gets a very solid position. At the same time, there are several good responses to equalise as Black.} ({Coming back to this particular position, I think putting the bishop on f4 on move 2 already is a bit premature. I did not know this before preparing the course material, but it is a better move order to start with the move} 2. Nf3 {first. We can try to exploit White's 2.Bf4 .}) 2... e6 {This is a good alternative if you just want to transpose back to our main lines in the London. We will see the independent options here for White.} 3. e3 (3. Nf3 {is a direct transposition after} Nf6 {.}) 3... Nf6 {Our plan is simple: we play ...[Bd6] next, followed by ...[O-O]. We will then continue with ...[c5]. Whenever White goes for the move [Nf3], it transposes to the main line.} 4. Nc3 {This position has been seen quite a few times via the 2.Nc3 move order. However, I think here this move is an inaccuracy.} Bb4 5. Nge2 {An ugly move to make with the bishop still on [f1], but this is the only move to get rid of the pin quickly.} ({With} 5. Bd3 {White wants to develop the knight to [e2] after having developed the bishop first, but after} c5 {they have to release the tension as ...[c4] is a threat.}) 5... O-O 6. a3 Be7 {We just retreat. Now White will struggle to develop the kingside.} 7. Ng1 {This was played by Magnus in a rapid online, but it is too slow.} c5 8. Nf3 Nh5 9. dxc5 Nxf4 10. exf4 Bxc5 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gd8f6] All of this happened in the aforementioned game, and Black already had a slight edge. Although Magnus managed to outplay his opponent later on, it was a great position out of the opening for Jeffrey Xiong.} *

