[Result "*"]
[ECO "D03"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2136127627846195"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. Nbd2 $5 {This is an interesting idea I came across for White, which is aimed against our specific plan.} Bd6 5. Bg5 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ge4e5] White wants to play [e4] next and get control over the centre.} Be7 {We do not mind wasting a tempo to get rid of the pin. However, this does mean that White is able to keep the dark-squared bishops on the board.} 6. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop to get the [e4] break in.} Bxf6 7. e4 c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We immediately want to open up the centre for our pieces. It was not the best decision for White to give up the bishop pair so easily.} 8. e5 Be7 9. c3 {This is the most popular move, keeping the centre closed, but it is not the right approach.} (9. dxc5 {is probably best, but we are very comfortable after} Bxc5 {with ...[Nc6] to follow.}) 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Qb6 {[%cal Gb8c6] We are ready to pressurize the [d4]-pawn with ...[Nc6] next. White is in big trouble as they are unable to defend this pawn with the [d2]-knight due to the check on [b4].} 11. Qb3 g5 $17 {[%cal Gg5g4] I really like this idea of pushing the g-pawn down the board. We will develop our knight to [c6] soon.} *

