1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. Nbd2 $5 {This is an interesting idea I came across for White, which is aimed against our specific plan.} Bd6 5. Bg5 {[%cal Ge2e4,Ge4e5] White wants to play [e4] next and get control over the centre.} Be7 {We do not mind wasting a tempo to get rid of the pin. However, this does mean that White is able to keep the dark-squared bishops on the board.} 6. e3 c5 $1 {We are in a rush to get control over the [e5]-square. This move is possible now because the [h2]-[b8] diagonal is vacant and we can get our queen to [c7].} 7. c3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Ge5] We stop the move [Ne5], which is a crucial detail. 8...Qc7 has not been played much compared to other moves. Now we can continue by slowly finishing our development. White's plan of [e4] is not as critical anymore, as White ends up trading too many pieces.} (8... b6 {is the most played move, but it becomes unpleasant for Black after} 9. Ne5 {⩲ .}) 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 b6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8b7] This is our standard development. We do not want to rush with the ...[e5] break. We will wait for White to break into the centre.} 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bb7 $10 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gf6e4] We are going to see this structure several times in this chapter. I like it, as it keeps some imbalance in the position. We will likely play ...[Rfe8] next and then trade on [e4].} *

