1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bxd6 {Let's start with this harmless trade, which allows us to develop the queen with a tempo.} Qxd6 6. c4 {This is the only justification for White's previous move, as otherwise we get great control over the centre.} O-O 7. Nc3 b6 {We are waiting for White to develop the [f1]-bishop before we take on [c4]. We also prevent White from pushing [c5].} 8. cxd5 {This is a standard reaction to the move ...[b6], as White does not want to allow us to activate our bishop along the diagonal.} Nxd5 $1 {Of course, we recapture with the knight. The knight on [c3] does a much better job on the queenside.} 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 c5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gc8e6] We are threatening to play ...[c4] now on the queenside. Another point to keep in mind is that our bishop will develop to the [c8]-[h3] diagonal.} 11. O-O $6 {This is a pretty careless move.} c4 $1 12. Bc2 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gb6b5,Gc8e6] We stop White from playing [Ne5]. Now our play is very simple on the queenside. We will put our bishop on [e6] and get our rooks to the queenside.} *

