1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bxd6 {Let's start with this harmless trade, which allows us to develop the queen with a tempo.} Qxd6 6. c4 {This is the only justification for White's previous move, as otherwise we get great control over the centre.} O-O 7. Nc3 dxc4 {This is the simplest move to equalise, but the drawback is that the play becomes too simple. We have almost no winning chances now, so I will give this as an alternative. It also breaks our general principles as we take on [c4] before White moves the bishop.} 8. Bxc4 c5 9. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gc5d4] We want to take on [d4] next move and saddle White with an IQP.} 10. Nb5 {This is clever, as White gains a tempo against our queen.} Qe7 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Rc1 Rd8 {We force White's queen away from the d-file before retreating with our queen.} 13. Qe2 Qe7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gc8d7,Gd7e8] We will play ...[a6] and ...[b5] next, and the game is likely to lead to a draw very soon. There are not enough pieces left to play for either side.} *

