1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bd3 {White maintains the tension with the bishop on [f4]. They claim that it would only improve their pawn structure if we traded on [f4].} Bxf4 {We trade immediately, but it is important to remember the follow up.} 6. exf4 Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6f4,Gd6b4] This is the reason we traded on [f4] happily. We create two threats: taking on [f4] and the check on [b4], winning the [b2]-pawn.} 7. Qd2 {[%csl Gb1,Rd2] This is the best reply, but it takes away the [d2]-square from White's knight, which is in our favour.} (7. Qc1 {can also be played, but we answer} b6 {as well. White still cannot get the knight to [d2].}) 7... b6 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc8a6] We are preparing to play ...[c5] next and can trade the bishops on [a6] soon.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Ba6 {We trade off our bad bishop for White's best minor piece. There was no easy way for White to prevent this trade.} 10. Ne5 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nc6 $10 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gc7c5] We will play ...[Ne7] next and get in the ...[c5] break. I do not think the change in pawn structure has helped White, and we can target the pawn on [d4].} *

