1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Nbd2 {[%csl Gf4] This is a popular try these days, similar to the previous variation. White maintains the tension with the bishop on [f4], but we do not have the same idea as in the previous line.} O-O 6. Bd3 Bxf4 {We continue in the same manner as in the previous 5.Bd3 lines, with the difference that White has managed to get their knight rather than queen to [d2]. So, it is a slightly better version for White.} (6... c5 {is the main move and is perfectly fine for Black. However, I think White's position after} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Nc6 9. c4 {is too solid for us to get any winning chances.}) 7. exf4 b6 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc8a6] We have seen this already, preparing both ...[c5] and ...[Ba6].} 8. Ne5 {Now, if we play too slowly, White can play [g4] next and start play on the kingside.} c5 9. c3 Ba6 {We are in time to trade the bishops before White can do something on the kingside.} 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. O-O Nb8 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gb8c6] This is another very typical idea in these positions, bringing the knight back to [c6].} 12. Ndf3 Qc7 13. Qc2 Nc6 $10 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc6e7,Gf6e4,Gf7f6] We are ready to play ...[Ne7] next if given the chance. We can always kick White's knight away from [e5] with the move ...[f6].} *

