1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Nbd2 {[%csl Gf4] This is a popular try these days, similar to the previous variation. White maintains the tension with the bishop on [f4], but we do not have the same idea as in the previous line.} O-O 6. Bd3 Bxf4 {We continue in the same manner as in the previous 5.Bd3 lines, with the difference that White has managed to get their knight rather than queen to [d2]. So, it is a slightly better version for White.} (6... c5 {is the main move and is perfectly fine for Black. However, I think White's position after} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Nc6 9. c4 {is too solid for us to get any winning chances.}) 7. exf4 b6 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc8a6] We have seen this already, preparing both ...[c5] and ...[Ba6].} 8. Qe2 {White stops the move ...[Ba6] for now, but this is only temporary.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] We renew the threat of ...[Ba6]. Now White cannot do anything to stop it.} 9. O-O c5 {We always play ...[c5] first, threatening to trap White's bishop with ...[c4]. We want to force White to play [c3].} 10. c3 Ba6 {Finally, we trade the bishops and equalise.} 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 {This recapture feels more natural and gives us more options. We can even bring the knight to [c7] in some cases.} 12. Ne5 (12. Rfe1 {is met with} Nb8 {with ...[Nc6] to follow.}) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 $10 {[%cal Gb4c2,Ga8c8,Gb4c6] The threat is to play ...[Nc2]. Next, we will bring our rook to the c-file and then the knight can retreat to [c6].} *

