1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Ne5 {This was recommended by Srinath and Sahaj in their LTR on the London on Chessable. It is a serious attempt to play for a win for White, but it also gives us the chance to take over in the complications.} O-O 6. Nd2 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf1d3,Gd2f3] The move order does not matter too muche. White will put their bishop on [d3] next and will be ready to reinforce the knight on [e5] with [Ndf3]. They will always meet ...[c5] with [c3] in these lines.} c5 7. c3 Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6] This is the same development plan we go for in the main line too. We want to put the queen on [c7] first, as the [b8]-knight could go to either [d7] or [c6].} 8. Bd3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7] With White's knight on [e5], we want to put the [b8]-knight on [c6] as it will head to [e7] next. White will bring their other knight to [f3] and we want to slowly prepare the move ...[f6].} 9. Ndf3 (9. Nxc6 {is harmless after} Bxf4 10. exf4 bxc6 {, with ...[c4] and ...[c5] to follow.}) 9... Ne7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf6e4,Gf7f6] We should aim to get the [f6]-knight to [e4] and then play ...[f6], as the knight on [e5] lacks a good square to retreat to. White, on the other hand, will try to create something on the kingside, making use of their active pieces.} 10. g4 {White decides to immediately start pushing the pawns down the board on the kingside. I faced this myself in a classical game against a strong Indian GM. It was annoying, as he had simply mixed up his move order, but this is still a decent move. It would have been better if he remembered his theory as I was much better prepared against his main line. :-} cxd4 {I decided to try and open up the open up the position with the white king still in the centre.} 11. cxd4 Ne4 $1 {This is a typical idea to prepare the move ...[f6].} 12. g5 {White stops our intended ...[f6], but creates a big weakness on [f5]. Playing ...[f6] now is not advisable, as it would allow White to open the g-file.} Bd7 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gd7b5,Gd3b5,Gc7a5,Ga5b5] This is an improvement over my game, in which I played my knight to [f5]. Instead, we are now preparing to play ...[Bb5] next and trade off the light-squared bishops.} 13. O-O {White stops our plan as we cannot give a check on [a5] anymore.} Be8 $10 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Gf7f6] We change plans, preparing to play ...[f6]. This is much safer now with White's king on [g1], and we have managed to bring our bishop to [e8], from where it is ready to jump to the kingside.} *

