1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Ne5 {This was recommended by Srinath and Sahaj in their LTR on the London on Chessable. It is a serious attempt to play for a win for White, but it also gives us the chance to take over in the complications.} O-O 6. Nd2 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf1d3,Gd2f3] The move order does not matter too muche. White will put their bishop on [d3] next and will be ready to reinforce the knight on [e5] with [Ndf3]. They will always meet ...[c5] with [c3] in these lines.} c5 7. c3 Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6] This is the same development plan we go for in the main line too. We want to put the queen on [c7] first, as the [b8]-knight could go to either [d7] or [c6].} 8. Bd3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7] With White's knight on [e5], we want to put the [b8]-knight on [c6] as it will head to [e7] next. White will bring their other knight to [f3] and we want to slowly prepare the move ...[f6].} 9. Ndf3 (9. Nxc6 {is harmless after} Bxf4 10. exf4 bxc6 {, with ...[c4] and ...[c5] to follow.}) 9... Ne7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf6e4,Gf7f6] We should aim to get the [f6]-knight to [e4] and then play ...[f6], as the knight on [e5] lacks a good square to retreat to. White, on the other hand, will try to create something on the kingside, making use of their active pieces.} 10. O-O ({This is the natural human move, but it is a bit slow when you compare it to the move} 10. h4 {which we will analyze next.}) 10... c4 $1 {This has been played in only one random online blitz game. We want to start our play on the queenside.} 11. Bc2 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] We prepare to play ...[b5]-[b4] next.} ({The immediate} 11... b5 {would be premature due to} 12. a4 {⩲ , when we cannot push the pawn further due to the bishop on [f4].}) 12. Ng5 {This is an interesting try to create an attack on the kingside.} h6 13. h4 {White is able to maintain the knight on [g5], and it does look pretty threatening. However, I am not sure exactly what White intends to do on the kingside if we just do nothing.} b5 (13... hxg5 $2 14. hxg5 Ne4 15. Qh5 {is dangerous for Black.}) 14. a3 a5 {We just proceed with our play on the queenside.} 15. Qf3 b4 16. axb4 axb4 17. Nh3 {[%cal Gf4h6] Now there are real threats on the kingside. White wants to take on [h6].} Rb6 $10 {[%cal Gd6e5,Gf6d7] This is clever, getting out of the [h2]-[b8] diagonal. We can now meet [Bxh6] by winning a pawn on [e5]. We can continue with ...[Nd7] next.} *

