1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Ne5 {This was recommended by Srinath and Sahaj in their LTR on the London on Chessable. It is a serious attempt to play for a win for White, but it also gives us the chance to take over in the complications.} O-O 6. Nd2 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf1d3,Gd2f3] The move order does not matter too muche. White will put their bishop on [d3] next and will be ready to reinforce the knight on [e5] with [Ndf3]. They will always meet ...[c5] with [c3] in these lines.} c5 7. c3 Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6] This is the same development plan we go for in the main line too. We want to put the queen on [c7] first, as the [b8]-knight could go to either [d7] or [c6].} 8. Bd3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7] With White's knight on [e5], we want to put the [b8]-knight on [c6] as it will head to [e7] next. White will bring their other knight to [f3] and we want to slowly prepare the move ...[f6].} 9. Ndf3 (9. Nxc6 {is harmless after} Bxf4 10. exf4 bxc6 {, with ...[c4] and ...[c5] to follow.}) 9... Ne7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf6e4,Gf7f6] We should aim to get the [f6]-knight to [e4] and then play ...[f6], as the knight on [e5] lacks a good square to retreat to. White, on the other hand, will try to create something on the kingside, making use of their active pieces.} 10. O-O ({This is the natural human move, but it is a bit slow when you compare it to the move} 10. h4 {which we will analyze next.}) 10... c4 $1 {This has been played in only one random online blitz game. We want to start our play on the queenside.} 11. Bb1 {We need to check this move too, as now White can put the queen on [c2] to target [h7].} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gg7g6,Gd8g7] We prepare the move ...[f6] and also get ready to play ...[g6] and ...[Ng7]. It helps that the bishop on [b1] is much worse than on [c2] in these lines.} 12. Ng5 g6 13. h4 Ng7 {[%csl Gh5]} 14. Ng4 $5 {White gives up a pawn to go after the dark squares. We have to be precise now.} (14. Qg4 {can be met with} h5 15. Qg3 Ngf5 {with ...[f6] to follow soon.}) 14... Bxf4 15. exf4 Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6] We need to play ...[f6] soon, in order to kick the knight away from [g5].} 16. Nf6 h6 $1 {[%cal Gh6g5,Ge6e5,Gc8h3] We are threatening to take on [g5] and continue with ...[e5], bringing our bishop into the game.} 17. Qf3 Ng8 $10 {The [f6]-knight is forced to go back and we have managed to consolidate our position on the kingside. It remains complex but is dynamically balanced. This is us being very careful, as the new move came quite a few moves earlier.} *

