ed before. We will continue a bit deeper, though.} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6d8,Ge7d5] This is the easiest response, bringing the queen back to [d8] to hold the position together. I would not want to be White here, as I feel it is not going to be easy practically to prove the compensation for two pawns.} (18... Nd5 {is also good and transposes to the previous variation, but it gives White a few extra options.}) 19. Nc4 Qd8 20. Nd6 Nd5 {The knight gets to its ideal square. We are ready to play ...[f5] next.} ({The immediate} 20... f5 {runs into} 21. d5 $1 {+- .}) 21. Nxe4 Nxf4 22. exf4 b6 $10 {[%cal Gc8b7] White is the one who has to be careful here to equalise. We are ready to play ...[Bb7] next and are up a pawn.} *

