1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. Bd3 {This is another move order to reach the main line, but we will only check an independent option here.} c5 7. c3 Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb7b6,Ge6e5] This is a very important detail to remember. We will put our knight on [d7] rather than [c6] in these lines. I will explain this in more detail in the main line.} 8. Ne5 {This has been played a few times via this move order. I think this is an inaccuracy, as White is unable to reinforce the knight on [e5] with their other knight.} Nbd7 {We immediately try to trade off the [e5]-knight.} 9. f4 {[%csl Re4]} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rb1] We utilise yet another drawback of the knight still being on [b1]: the [e4]-square is not fully covered.} 10. Nd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 Nf6 $10 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc5c4,Gb7b5] We can bring our other knight to [e4] next. Another plan is to play ...[c4] and ...[b5] next, before getting the knight to [e4]. We are already on the better side of equality.} *

