[Black "London 2.Nf3 with 5.Bg3 #3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D02"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[GameId "2136127628030531"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. c4 {This does not fit in with the London, but it is still something which should be checked briefly. It has been tried by some strong players.} c5 $1 {We immediately fight back in the centre. We have a slight lead in development and White's king is still on [e1].} 7. cxd5 exd5 $1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Gc5c4] We are happy to get an IQP structure due to our lead in development. White is not in time to get full control over the [d4]-square.} 8. Bxd6 (8. Nc3 {can be met with} c4 $1 {and the light-squared bishop is pretty restricted.}) 8... Qxd6 9. dxc5 Qxc5 {This position has been reached thrice by Kamsky from the white side. He is a well-known expert in the London, but I do not think this position has anything meaningful for White. They are too underdeveloped to fight for an advantage.} 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Be2 d4 {This is the easiest way to equalise. We are able to liquidate the central pawns.} 12. exd4 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Ga8d8] We are going to play ...[Bg4] next, and then bring the rook to [d8]. White cannot hold on to the pawn for much longer. In addition to this, we are threatening to take the pawn on [b2].} 13. Qb3 Qxb3 14. axb3 Be6 15. Bc4 Bg4 $10 {Allowing us to take on [f3] will leave White with too many weaknesses. They should probably play [Ne5] and give back the pawn, reaching an equal endgame.} *

