1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. Nbd2 {The knight always belongs on [d2] in these positions as White will play [c3] next, strengthening their control over [d4].} c5 7. Bd3 {This has been played by a few strong players including Pragg, but only in online blitz.} c4 {We do not need an invitation to gain more space on the queenside. This is always a potential idea for us, especially if White's light-squared bishop is unable to stay on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal.} 8. Be2 {[%csl Re2]} b5 9. c3 Nc6 10. Qc2 {White is preparing to play [e4] in the centre. This is the best way for White to create play in the position.} Bb7 11. e4 (11. O-O {allows us to play} Ne7 {, stopping [e4].}) 11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 h6 $10 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gc6e7,Gc6a5,Gb7d5] We can continue with ...[Rb8] and ...[Ne7] next, or go ...[Na5] followed by ...[Bd5]. We have the beautiful [d5]-square for the bishop and can continue with ...[b4] on the queenside.} *

