[Result "*"]
[ECO "D02"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2136127628051013"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. Nbd2 {The knight always belongs on [d2] in these positions as White will play [c3] next, strengthening their control over [d4].} c5 7. c3 {This is an almost automatic reaction from White. They keep good control over [d4].} Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gb7b6] This is an important moment, which we need to remember clearly. Our plan is to get the [b8]-knight to [d7] to control the [e5]-square. We can then either go for the ...[e5] break, or more frequently for ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], finishing our development. We keep the diagonal open for the bishop and keep the [c5]-pawn defended.} (7... Nc6 {is the main move in the position, but the drawback is that we cannot get control over [e5] as easily. Then our queen cannot go to [c7], as the [c5]-pawn will hang.} 8. Bd3 Qe7 9. Ne5 {White gets the knight to [e5] in time. There is a very famous trap here which you must know:} Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 {This looks like the most natural recapture by far, but it is actually a serious mistake.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 {+- and White gets the knight to [g5] on the next move.}) 8. Ne5 {We have seen this move several times already, but this is good version for us.} c4 $1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] We are able to restrict White's light-squared bishop and not allow it to reach its ideal [b1]-[h7] diagonal.} 9. f4 {This has been played the most, but it is a huge concession as White weakens the [e4]-square.} (9. Be2 {is met with the move} Nbd7 {, after which White either has to retreat the knight or play} 10. f4 {, which will transpose to this line.}) 9... b5 {We advance freely on the queenside and also prepare to get the bishop to [b7] to control [e4].} 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O Nb6 {[%csl Ga4] The knight is well placed here on the queenside, stopping the move [a4]. We will continue with ...[a5] and ...[b4] soon.} 12. Bf3 a5 13. e4 $6 {This is the only way to create play in the centre. However, White is not fully ready yet and we can immediately go after [e4].} Bb7 $17 {[%csl Re4] We will trade all our pieces on [e4] next and then play ...[f5]. We have the beautiful [d5]-square for the knight. White's dark-squared bishop is completely restricted.} *

