1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. Nbd2 {The knight always belongs on [d2] in these positions as White will play [c3] next, strengthening their control over [d4].} c5 7. c3 {This is an almost automatic reaction from White. They keep good control over [d4].} Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gb7b6] This is an important moment, which we need to remember clearly. Our plan is to get the [b8]-knight to [d7] to control the [e5]-square. We can then either go for the ...[e5] break, or more frequently for ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], finishing our development. We keep the diagonal open for the bishop and keep the [c5]-pawn defended.} (7... Nc6 {is the main move in the position, but the drawback is that we cannot get control over [e5] as easily. Then our queen cannot go to [c7], as the [c5]-pawn will hang.} 8. Bd3 Qe7 9. Ne5 {White gets the knight to [e5] in time. There is a very famous trap here which you must know:} Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 {This looks like the most natural recapture by far, but it is actually a serious mistake.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 {+- and White gets the knight to [g5] on the next move.}) 8. Bd3 {This is the most played move in the position. White puts the bishop on its ideal diagonal and is hinting at the [e4] advance in the near future. The problem is that this move allows us to get control over [e5] very easily.} Nbd7 {[%csl Ge5]} 9. e4 $6 {White tries to get in the move [e4] very quickly, but this is premature and they will be left with an IQP.} cxd4 10. cxd4 (10. Nxd4 {runs into} Bxg3 11. hxg3 Nc5 {∓ and the [e4]-pawn is in trouble.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 {This looks natural and has been played by Wesley So against Magnus. However, we are able to keep White's king stuck in the centre.} (11. Bxe4 {is the better move, but the position is still better for us after} Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Qa5+ {⩱ followed by ...[Bb4] next.}) 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Nf6 13. Bd3 Qa5+ $1 {[%cal Ge1f1,Ge1e2] White's best reply now is to move the king. We have a good edge in the resulting position.} 14. Nd2 {It seems more natural to block the check with the knight.} Qd5 $17 {[%cal Rd2f3,Gd6b4] We attack both [d4] and the [g2]-pawn. We can also give a check on [b4] if the knight moves.} *

