r, but it is actually a serious mistake.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 {+- and White gets the knight to [g5] on the next move.}) 8. Bd3 {This is the most played move in the position. White puts the bishop on its ideal diagonal and is hinting at the [e4] advance in the near future. The problem is that this move allows us to get control over [e5] very easily.} Nbd7 {[%csl Ge5]} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4] White is ready to play [e4] next and bring their queen to the centre.} e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] We are just in time to break in the centre before White could do so. We are taking over the initiative.} 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Nf3 {This has been played the most, but as often is the case, the most played move is not the best. White wants to open the h-file for the rook, but this pawn structure is in our favour on the kingside. White cannot do much with just the h-file.} (12. Bxe5 {leads to a comfortable position for Black after} Qxe5 {.}) 12... Bxg3 13. hxg3 Re8 14. O-O Bg4 $15 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gg7g6,Gg8g7,Ge8h8,Gh5h4] We will continue with ...[h5] next followed by ...[g6] and ...[Kg7]. We can try to open up the h-file for our rook, which would be much more dangerous for White.} *

