1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. Nbd2 {The knight always belongs on [d2] in these positions as White will play [c3] next, strengthening their control over [d4].} c5 7. c3 {This is an almost automatic reaction from White. They keep good control over [d4].} Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gb7b6] This is an important moment, which we need to remember clearly. Our plan is to get the [b8]-knight to [d7] to control the [e5]-square. We can then either go for the ...[e5] break, or more frequently for ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], finishing our development. We keep the diagonal open for the bishop and keep the [c5]-pawn defended.} (7... Nc6 {is the main move in the position, but the drawback is that we cannot get control over [e5] as easily. Then our queen cannot go to [c7], as the [c5]-pawn will hang.} 8. Bd3 Qe7 9. Ne5 {White gets the knight to [e5] in time. There is a very famous trap here which you must know:} Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 {This looks like the most natural recapture by far, but it is actually a serious mistake.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 {+- and White gets the knight to [g5] on the next move.}) 8. dxc5 {This is the best way for White to pose problems for us and keep the game complex. White does not give us the chance to recapture on [c5] with the knight.} Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 {We want to take on [g3] next and then play ...[e5]. It is also possible to play more slowly with ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], as we saw earlier.} 10. Qe2 {White is very ambitious and wants to castle queenside. They also prepare to play [e4] next.} Bxg3 $1 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Rh2g3] Of course, we first damage White's pawn structure on the kingside.} 11. hxg3 e5 {[%cal Ge5e4] Now the game is getting heated up and both sides have to be careful. We want to play ...[e4] next.} 12. g4 {White ignores the threat as they want to start play on the kingside.} e4 13. g5 exd3 14. Qxd3 Ne4 {We are up a piece for a couple of pawns. White has some compensation, though, due to our undeveloped queenside.} 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 g6 17. O-O-O h5 $1 {[%cal Gg5h6,Gd7f6] This is a clever move. We want White to take on [h6] with the g-pawn, which would allow us to get our knight to [f6].} 18. g4 $1 {This is the only move to maintain the balance.} Qc6 $36 {We force the queens off the board. White gets three pawns for the piece, but I think it is much easier to play this a piece up in the endgame.} *

