1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {This is the best move order to reach the London, keeping more options open.} Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 {Our next two moves are simple: we will get our bishop to [d6] and castle kingside. We will play ...[c5] a bit later, as we do not want to allow White to develop the bishop to [b5] easily.} (3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 {is not the same as the lines we saw earlier, as after} 5. exd4 {we have developed a knight to [f6] compared to a knight on [c6] earlier. We saw several lines where we wanted to put our knight on [e7], which is not possible here. It is still playable for Black, but not as simple.}) 4. e3 Bd6 {We have reached a critical position. There are a few different plans which White has, all of which we need to check carefully. Try to clearly understand the logic behind White's various options.} 5. Bg3 {This is the most common move, but not the most testing in my opinion. We have a fairly simple plan to fight back in the centre.} O-O {[%cal Gc7c5] As usual, we castle first before going for the ...[c5] break, in order to avoid a check on [b5].} 6. Nbd2 {The knight always belongs on [d2] in these positions as White will play [c3] next, strengthening their control over [d4].} c5 7. c3 {This is an almost automatic reaction from White. They keep good control over [d4].} Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gb7b6] This is an important moment, which we need to remember clearly. Our plan is to get the [b8]-knight to [d7] to control the [e5]-square. We can then either go for the ...[e5] break, or more frequently for ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], finishing our development. We keep the diagonal open for the bishop and keep the [c5]-pawn defended.} (7... Nc6 {is the main move in the position, but the drawback is that we cannot get control over [e5] as easily. Then our queen cannot go to [c7], as the [c5]-pawn will hang.} 8. Bd3 Qe7 9. Ne5 {White gets the knight to [e5] in time. There is a very famous trap here which you must know:} Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 {This looks like the most natural recapture by far, but it is actually a serious mistake.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 {+- and White gets the knight to [g5] on the next move.}) 8. dxc5 {This is the best way for White to pose problems for us and keep the game complex. White does not give us the chance to recapture on [c5] with the knight.} Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 {We want to take on [g3] next and then play ...[e5]. It is also possible to play more slowly with ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], as we saw earlier.} 10. Qe2 {White is very ambitious and wants to castle queenside. They also prepare to play [e4] next.} Bxg3 $1 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Rh2g3] Of course, we first damage White's pawn structure on the kingside.} 11. hxg3 e5 {[%cal Ge5e4] Now the game is getting heated up and both sides have to be careful. We want to play ...[e4] next.} 12. e4 {White stops our threat of [e4], but is opening up the centre with their king still on [e1].} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd7c5] An important move to remember, going after the white queenside. We also vacate the [c5]-square for the knight, which would finally allow us to get our [c8]-bishop out.} 13. O-O-O {White gets the king over to the queenside, defending [b2] in the process. We need to play some only moves now.} (13. exd5 {is not great for White after} Qxb2 {↑ . White has to castle kingside, giving up another pawn.}) 13... Re8 14. Rh4 $1 {This is the only move for White too, and is definitely not an easy move to find on the board. They need to get more control over [e4]. I think if White is coming up with moves over the board, there is a very good chance they go wrong in some way or the other.} Nc5 {[%cal Gb8g4] We are looking to get the bishop out to [g4] next.} 15. exd5 $1 {This is necessary, even though it gives up a piece.} e4 16. Nxe4 {There are a few different ways of playing for us now, and invariably all lines lead to a repetition in one way or the other.} Nfxe4 {We go for the most direct line, winning a piece. This forces White to make a few more precise moves.} 17. Bxe4 f5 18. d6 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ge2c4,Gc4g8] A very important move, cutting our queen off from the kingside and opening up the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. This is findable in this position, but it's a move that's extremely difficult to anticipate from afar. This is why I am really excited to face the London. I am always hoping they will go for this line. It has been recommended for White by Le Quang in his London course on Chessable, but he just says that there is nothing much White can do other than take a draw.} Rxe4 19. Rxe4 fxe4 20. Ng5 h6 21. Qc4+ {You can see why the pawn on [d6] is so useful for White. We are unable to block the check.} Kh8 22. Nf7+ Kh7 23. b4 $1 {The final precise move that White needs to find. Now, it leads to a forced repetition.} Nd3+ 24. Rxd3 exd3 (24... exd3 {Now after} 25. Qe4+ Kg8 {there are a couple of different ways in which White can repeat, but he cannot prolong the game any longer. This is a pretty satisfying end to our chapter on the London and is personally something I really hope to face on the board.}) *

