r, but it is actually a serious mistake.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 {+- and White gets the knight to [g5] on the next move.}) 8. dxc5 {This is the best way for White to pose problems for us and keep the game complex. White does not give us the chance to recapture on [c5] with the knight.} Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 {We want to take on [g3] next and then play ...[e5]. It is also possible to play more slowly with ...[b6] and ...[Bb7], as we saw earlier.} 10. Qe2 {White is very ambitious and wants to castle queenside. They also prepare to play [e4] next.} Bxg3 $1 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Rh2g3] Of course, we first damage White's pawn structure on the kingside.} 11. hxg3 e5 {[%cal Ge5e4] Now the game is getting heated up and both sides have to be careful. We want to play ...[e4] next.} 12. e4 {White stops our threat of [e4], but is opening up the centre with their king still on [e1].} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd7c5] An important move to remember, going after the white queenside. We also vacate the [c5]-square for the knight, which would finally allow us to get our [c8]-bishop out.} 13. O-O-O {White gets the king over to the queenside, defending [b2] in the process. We need to play some only moves now.} (13. exd5 {is not great for White after} Qxb2 {↑ . White has to castle kingside, giving up another pawn.}) 13... Re8 14. Rh4 $1 {This is the only move for White too, and is definitely not an easy move to find on the board. They need to get more control over [e4]. I think if White is coming up with moves over the board, there is a very good chance they go wrong in some way or the other.} Nc5 {[%cal Gb8g4] We are looking to get the bishop out to [g4] next.} 15. exd5 $1 {This is necessary, even though it gives up a piece.} e4 16. Nxe4 {There are a few different ways of playing for us now, and invariably all lines lead to a repetition in one way or the other.} Bf5 ({I will give you an alternate variation just in case. With} 16... Bf5 {we activate the bishop first and connect the rooks before going after the piece.}) 17. Nfd2 Bxe4 18. Nxe4 Nfxe4 19. Bxe4 f5 {White loses a piece, but they have enough play to make a draw.} 20. Qh5 Nxe4 21. Qxh7+ Kf7 22. Qxf5+ Qf6 $10 {[%cal Gf5d7,Gf6e7,Gd7f5,Ge7f6] The position is complex but dynamically balanced. White has 4 pawns for the piece, but our king is safe and the pawns are not too threatening. I would probably still not go for this, as White has the option to keep the game going.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Arjun's Semi-Slav"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) 1.d4 Sidelines: 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Veresov 3.dxc5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D00"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[GameId "2136127628173902"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. dxc5 Nf6 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] We defend [d5] and also prevent the move [e4]. Already we are more comfortable with better control over the centre.} 4. e4 $5 {This was played by one of the most creative players in the world Baadur Jabova and is in the spirit of the position. White has to try something out of the box to justify their first couple of moves.} ({After} 4. e3 e6 {we will take on [c5] next with a very comfortable position.}) 4... d4 $1 {[%csl Rc3] Another drawback of the knight on [c3]. We get to kick it around, gaining space and time.} 5. Bc4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c3,Gc4f7] This was White's cunning idea, but more often than not these creative ideas have pretty simple solutions. The only rule is not to blunder any pieces, especially the queen. :-} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gd4c3] Now we are threatening to take the knight, as [d8] is protected. We also get the [e5]-square under our control.} ({Please do not go for} 5... dxc3 $4 6. Bxf7+ $1 {+- .}) 6. Nd5 Nxe4 $1 {One of my coaches made me read the entire book My System by Nimzovich a decent book, but slightly archaic for modern times. There are some important ideas but I feel it could be explained much better these days. One of my major takeaways from that book was how to play with and against the centre. A basic rule is to take any pawn in the centre if it can be done without too much danger. Let White prove their compensation.} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Qe2 Bf5 {[%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gd4,Gd5,Ge4,Ge5,Gf4,Gf5] I like how 8 squares in the middle of the board are fully occupied by pieces and pawns. :- It may look a bit messy, but it is much more dangerous for our opponent as their pieces are the loose ones.} 9. f3 {The only move to keep the balance. Here Jobava managed to confuse his opponent enough to force an inaccuracy.} Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Let's get rid of the knight on [d5]. It is a good sign that we have a few decent options, while our opponent's moves are forced.} (9... exf4 {(gave White decent chances in the game 1-0 45 Jobava, B -Lupulescu, C Baku 2016.)}) 10. Bxe5 Nxd5 11. Bc7+ Qe7 {There's nothing to worry about here. The queens will likely get traded soon.} 12. Bxd5 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2] We are not satisfied by the messiness we have seen so far. We complicate the position even further, but this makes a lot of sense as we are slightly ahead in development.} 13. Bxb7 Nxc2+ 14. Kd2 Kd7 $1 {Both the kings join the party. However, I think our king is definitely safer.} 15. Bf4 Qxc5 16. Bxa8 Nxa1 {[%csl Rd2,Gd7] The position remains complex but we are on the better side of equality. White has to find a lot of only moves to maintain the balance.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Arjun's Semi-Slav"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) 1.d4 Sidelines: 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Veresov 3.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D00"]
[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2136127628202575"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. Nf3 {This is also too slow and lets us take over the position. White needs to be able to play the move [e4] to fight for an advantage.} Nc6 {We will keep bringing our pieces in contact with the centre.} 4. e3 {This is a very passive way of playing, allowing the bishop to get stuck on [c1].} Nf6 5. Bb5 {This is the most played move, but I am really not sure what the bishop achieves on [b5]. White is still not close to achieving their ideal plan of [e4].} e6 {With the bishop on [b5] we can develop our pieces normally and kick it back with ...[a6] at the right moment. We do not need to get the bishop out of the pawn chain now.} 6. O-O (6. Ne5 {just leads to a worse position for White after} Qc7 {⩱ .}) 6... Qc7 {We hold off on developing the [f8]-bishop for a couple of moves. We do not want to waste a tempo if White takes on [c5]. It is also not clear what our opponent is planning to do.} 7. Re1 (7. Bxc6+ {just gives up the bishop for free. We can recapture both ways. My personal preference is} bxc6 {, keeping the queen on [c7].}) 7... Bd7 8. h3 a6 9. Bf1 cxd4 {[%cal Ge3e4] We take on [d4] since White was prepared to play [e4].} 10. exd4 Bd6 $10 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ge8g8] We can see that we have prepared well to get our bishop to [d6]. Also, keep in mind that [Bg5]-[f6] will not really bother us. We will focus on castling kingside and getting our rooks into the game.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Arjun's Semi-Slav"]
