[PlyCount "20"]
[GameId "2136127628214864"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. Nf3 {This is also too slow and lets us take over the position. White needs to be able to play the move [e4] to fight for an advantage.} Nc6 {We will keep bringing our pieces in contact with the centre.} 4. dxc5 Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8c5] With the knight on [c3], it is not easy for White to stop our simple plan of ...[e6] and ...[Bxc5]. White should focus on making sure that they do not get a worse position.} 5. e4 {This is the right spirit from our opponent, but we can exploit the knight on [c3].} d4 {[%csl Rc3]} 6. e5 {This is the only way to not be worse for White. We now reach an endgame by force.} dxc3 7. Qxd8+ Nxd8 8. exf6 cxb2 {It is always a question in such positions whether to take on [b2] or not. On the one hand, we win a pawn, but we also help develop White's bishop to [b2].} ({We could also play} 8... exf6 {and force our opponent to double their pawns. Here, I like 8...cxb2 more as I do not want to give White a supporting square on d4 after} 9. bxc3 Bxc5 10. Nd4 {.}) 9. Bxb2 exf6 10. O-O-O Bd7 $10 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gd8e6,Ge6c5,Ge8c8] We stop the move [Bb5] and prepare to take on [c5] next. We can also play ...[Ne6] and take with the knight. We are likely to castle queenside.} *

