1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. Nf3 {This is also too slow and lets us take over the position. White needs to be able to play the move [e4] to fight for an advantage.} Nc6 {We will keep bringing our pieces in contact with the centre.} 4. dxc5 Nf6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8c5] With the knight on [c3], it is not easy for White to stop our simple plan of ...[e6] and ...[Bxc5]. White should focus on making sure that they do not get a worse position.} 5. e3 e6 6. Bd3 {[%cal Ge3e4] White prepares to play [e4], making use of the knight on [c3]. However, as we will see, we often just answer ...[d4], gaining space in the centre.} Bxc5 7. O-O e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] I think this is the most precise move order since it forces our opponent to play [e4]. We should be flexible when it comes to our move order, but the other way around when it is our opponent's move order. :-} 8. e4 d4 {I like this structure in the centre. It really restricts White's bishop on [d3]. We would like to hold on to our [d4]-pawn for as long as possible.} 9. Ne2 O-O 10. h3 h6 {We will play slow useful moves, improving our position. We have more space and the more comfortable position. We want to see how White is planning to fight back.} 11. a3 a5 {A very typical move, stopping [b4]. The weakness of the [b5]-square is not that significant as White cannot really exploit it.} 12. Ng3 Be6 13. Nh2 {This happened in the game Steinberg, N 2542-Cunha, L 2309 2022. We will improve upon the game.} Bd6 $15 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gf8e8,Ga5a4] We stop White's plan of [f4]. I do not see any other meaningful idea for White. We have a very pleasant position.} *

