1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. Nf3 {This is also too slow and lets us take over the position. White needs to be able to play the move [e4] to fight for an advantage.} Nc6 {We will keep bringing our pieces in contact with the centre.} 4. Bf4 {This seems to be a mix of so many different systems :-. We can continue developing our pieces. We are always happy to see White take on [c5], as this allows us to get our bishop out in one go.} Nf6 5. e3 {Surprisingly this position has been played by many strong players. Mostly by transposition, but I feel that we already have a more pleasant position.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg4d1] It is always a nice achievement to get the bishop out before playing ...[e6]. We put even more pressure on White's center.} 6. Bb5 {This has been played a few times, but it does not help White much. The pin along the [d1]-[h5] diagonal is an issue for our opponent.} (6. dxc5 {leads to a worse position for White after the simple} e6 {⩱ .}) 6... e6 7. h3 Bxf3 {[%csl Rd4] There are usually a few reasons to trade pieces. A common one, applicable here, is to simply not lose a tempo. We also want to weaken our opponent's control over the [d4]-pawn.} 8. Qxf3 cxd4 {We go for this trade usually before developing our dark-squared bishop.} 9. exd4 Qb6 {[%csl Rd4]} 10. O-O {White gives up the [d4]-pawn in order to finish development quickly.} Qxd4 {Of course, we take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger. Let our opponent prove compensation.} 11. Rfe1 Be7 12. Na4 {This is the only move to maintain the balance, preparing [c3] to trap our queen in the middle of the board.} Qb4 13. c4 Qa5 $10 {[%cal Ge8h8] Next we will castle kingside. It is not going to be easy for White to prove compensation.} *

