1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. Nf3 {This is also too slow and lets us take over the position. White needs to be able to play the move [e4] to fight for an advantage.} Nc6 {We will keep bringing our pieces in contact with the centre.} 4. Bf4 {This seems to be a mix of so many different systems :-. We can continue developing our pieces. We are always happy to see White take on [c5], as this allows us to get our bishop out in one go.} Nf6 5. e3 {Surprisingly this position has been played by many strong players. Mostly by transposition, but I feel that we already have a more pleasant position.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg4d1] It is always a nice achievement to get the bishop out before playing ...[e6]. We put even more pressure on White's center.} 6. Be2 {We will see a similar position in a different line after the trade on [d4]. Now White can also recapture on [d4] with the knight, but we are happy to maintain the tension for the time being.} e6 7. O-O Rc8 {We still maintain the tension as White does not have many useful moves left. We are waiting for them to commit to a plan.} 8. Ne5 {White trades the light-squared bishops and also regroups the knight that's stuck on [c3].} Bxe2 9. Nxe2 Be7 10. c3 O-O $10 {[%cal Gd8b6] We can continue with ...[Qb6] next. It seems like the colours are reversed - usually White is the one who has the pawn on [c4] in such positions. We have the power to release the tension in the centre at any point in time.} *

