1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. Bf4 {We encounter a very stubborn London player :-. This is not a bad move, though, and we need to make sure we do not transpose back to the Jobava London main line.} Nc6 (3... Nc6 {We would of course love to see} 4. dxc5 {now, as it helps us to play} e5 {with tempo. We usually want to get our [c8]-bishop out quickly before playing ...[e6].}) 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Bf5 {Throughout our repertoire, there are many cases where we put our bishop on [f5]. This is one of the easiest versions for us due to the knight on [c3].} 6. Nf3 {This is the most common move in the position, but I feel it is slightly inaccurate. We will see the reason soon.} e6 7. Bd3 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] This option would not have been available for us if White had played [Bd3] a move earlier. Now the pin is quite annoying for our opponent.} 8. Be2 {A pretty sad move to play, as the bishop is not doing much on [e2]. It also takes away a square from the [c3]-knight.} Bd6 {[%csl Rc3] I like this trade, getting good control over the [e5]-square. We get a very good version of this structure as White needs more time to regroup the knight on [c3].} 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. O-O Nf6 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gd6b4] We will take on [f3] if provoked, and we have the idea to play ...[Qb4], attacking two pawns.} 11. Re1 O-O $10 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gg4f3,Gc6a5,Ga5c4] White has to waste a move with [a3] to stop our plan before they can play [Ne5]. We can then try to play on the queenside with ...[Na5]-[c4].} *

