1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. Bf4 {We encounter a very stubborn London player :-. This is not a bad move, though, and we need to make sure we do not transpose back to the Jobava London main line.} Nc6 (3... Nc6 {We would of course love to see} 4. dxc5 {now, as it helps us to play} e5 {with tempo. We usually want to get our [c8]-bishop out quickly before playing ...[e6].}) 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Bf5 {Throughout our repertoire, there are many cases where we put our bishop on [f5]. This is one of the easiest versions for us due to the knight on [c3].} 6. Bd3 {This is the most precise move order. White offers the trade of bishops, and we do not have the option of answering with ...[Bg4]. However, we are fine with the trade, and will continue to develop normally. White has to regroup the [c3]-knight at some point.} Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nf3 Nf6 {The other option that we have is to play ...[Bd6] followed by ...[Ne7], which is also pretty good. I like to keep more pieces on the board if possible, though, and we have ideas of playing ...[Qb6] on the queenside.} 9. O-O Be7 10. Ne2 O-O $10 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gd8b6,Ga8c8] Our next move is likely to be either ...[Ne4] or ...[Qb6]. We can also play ...[Rc8] and put more pressure on the queenside. The position is balanced.} *

