1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. e4 {This is the most critical test of 2...c5. White makes use of the [c3]-knight to immediately break in the centre.} dxe4 4. Bb5+ {I am often reminded of the quote: patzer sees check, patzer plays check! :- I do not think this move makes sense for White, as it only trades the light-squared bishops on [d7].} Bd7 5. dxc5 Nf6 {[%csl Ge4] We keep control over [e4] a central pawn!.} 6. Bg5 a6 {The [b5]-bishop now looks stupid. Taking on [d7] helps us get our [b8]-knight to its ideal square.} 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. Qd4 Rc8 {We go after the [c5]-pawn in return for [e4]. White cannot defend the pawn.} 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nxc5 11. Qe2 Qd5 $1 {We are not happy with simple equality. We want to get full control over the centre.} 12. Nf3 f6 $10 {[%cal Ge7e5] We will play ...[e5] next and build a nice centre. The queen on [d5] also stops White from castling queenside.} *

