1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. e4 {This is the most critical test of 2...c5. White makes use of the [c3]-knight to immediately break in the centre.} dxe4 4. d5 {This is the principled move, getting control over the centre and restricting our pieces. We have two plans now: to play ...[e6] or to fianchetto the bishop with ...[g6].} (4. Nxe4 {is just better for Black after} cxd4 {⩱ .}) 4... Nf6 {We first need to defend our [e4]-pawn.} 5. Bf4 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] London players and their obsession with the [f4]-square! :- This is pretty ambitious, as White wants to play [Qd2] and [O-O-O] quickly. Let us see who is faster! Being a pawn up does help us here.} g6 6. Qd2 Bg7 {If you give this position to a Sicilian Dragon player, I am sure they would be overjoyed. We have the centre under control and it is going to be a while before White's play on the kingside becomes dangerous.} 7. O-O-O O-O 8. Bh6 {This is the critical plan, but it's also the only way for White to keep equality.} e3 $1 {A very nice idea, giving up our extra pawn to win a tempo. We force White's bishop back and we are also going to try and win their dark-squared bishop.} 9. Bxe3 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gd8a5] Where is the bishop going? If it stays on the [c1]-[h6] diagonal we can answer ...[Qa5] and start our play on the queenside. The white queen is kind of overloaded.} 10. Bxc5 Qc7 {We gain a tempo on the bishop. Now White has a difficult choice to make.} 11. h3 {This is best, trying to open up the h-file for the [h1]-rook.} Qxc5 {We allow White to open the h-file, but we win back the pawn. White cannot achieve much along the h-file without the dark-squared bishop.} 12. hxg4 Bxg4 13. f3 Bc8 $10 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f6,Gf8d8] We have the bishop pair and can continue developing our queenside pieces.} *

