1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. e4 {This is the most critical test of 2...c5. White makes use of the [c3]-knight to immediately break in the centre.} dxe4 4. d5 {This is the principled move, getting control over the centre and restricting our pieces. We have two plans now: to play ...[e6] or to fianchetto the bishop with ...[g6].} (4. Nxe4 {is just better for Black after} cxd4 {⩱ .}) 4... Nf6 {We first need to defend our [e4]-pawn.} 5. Bg5 {This is the most common move for White, but it is an inaccuracy. The bishop does not achieve anything on [g5] and can be kicked away with ...[h6] soon.} Nbd7 6. Qe2 ({After} 6. Qd2 a6 {we can play ...[b5] next and start playing on the queenside.}) 6... g6 7. Nxe4 Bg7 {We improve upon the game between 0-1 Fernandez Estremera, F 2279-Puranik, A 2605 Benasque 2023.} 8. d6 {This may look a bit scary at first sight, but we have a simple refutation.} Qa5+ $1 9. Bd2 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 10. dxe7 {The pawn on [e7] is one of our best defenders! We will win the pawn on [b2] by force and trade queens.} Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Qxb2 $17 {[%cal Gb2e5] Our next move is ...[Qe5]. We are a clean pawn up in the endgame.} *

