1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. e4 {This is the most critical test of 2...c5. White makes use of the [c3]-knight to immediately break in the centre.} dxe4 4. d5 {This is the principled move, getting control over the centre and restricting our pieces. We have two plans now: to play ...[e6] or to fianchetto the bishop with ...[g6].} (4. Nxe4 {is just better for Black after} cxd4 {⩱ .}) 4... Nf6 {We first need to defend our [e4]-pawn.} 5. f3 {This is a creative pawn sacrifice, but not a very sound one. White is not ahead of us in development and we will look to fianchetto the bishop and get our king to safety quickly.} exf3 6. Nxf3 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Give us two more moves and we will just be better. White has to play dynamically to try and prove compensation.} 7. Bb5+ $1 {This has been played very few times. White wants to misplace our bishop, making us put it on [d7], blocking our own pieces. Other moves are worse for White.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gd7b6] Once again White has to act quickly since we plan to play ...[Bg7], ...[O-O] and then ...[Nb6].} 8. d6 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {The first part of our plan is complete. Our play has been very simple: be greedy and then focus on finishing our development. :-} 10. dxe7 Qxe7 11. Re1 Qd8 $10 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gd7b6,Gc8e6] Engines claim that White has some compensation, but it is not easy to understand why. We will play ...[a6] followed by ...[Nb6] and ...[Be6].} *

