1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 {Typically, in 1.d4 lines, the knight goes to [c3] only after White has already played the move [c4]. Here, White gets the knight out early. This only makes sense if White is able to play the [e4] advance quickly. Otherwise the knight is just misplaced on [c3] and hampers their queenside play.} ({Let us see a sample variation to understand the drawback of the knight on c3:} 2. Nf3 c5 {and now the move} 3. c4 $1 {is the key move to fight for the advantage against 2...c5. Another plan is to take on [c5] and continue with either [c4] or hold it with [b4] and [c3].}) 2... c5 $5 {[%csl Rc3] We go for an early surprise, as this is the 6th most popular move in the position! We want to exploit the knight on [c3] immediately. White lacks the move [c2]-[c4] which is one of the main ideas to play against our center. Also, White cannot take on [c5] and hold on to the pawn, as we will meet [b4] with ...[a5] and they cannot answer with [c3].} (2... Nf6 {is the main move by far, and certainly fine for us. However, I feel there are other options which take our opponent more out of the comfort zone.}) 3. e4 {This is the most critical test of 2...c5. White makes use of the [c3]-knight to immediately break in the centre.} dxe4 4. d5 {This is the principled move, getting control over the centre and restricting our pieces. We have two plans now: to play ...[e6] or to fianchetto the bishop with ...[g6].} (4. Nxe4 {is just better for Black after} cxd4 {⩱ .}) 4... Nf6 {We first need to defend our [e4]-pawn.} 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gg3e4,Ge7e6,Ge2f4]} (5. Nge2 {This is by far the best move in the position, but as usual it has been played very rarely. The move contains two ideas: to go after the e4-pawn with Ng3, and secondly to meet} e6 {with} 6. Nf4 {. We could play our usual plan with ...[g6], but then White would regain the [e4]-pawn quickly. The other plan is 5...e6, to eliminate the annoying pawn on [d5].}) 5... e6 {I think this is the simplest way to equalise.} (5... g6 {is slightly unpleasant for us after} 6. Ng3 {↑ , winning [e4].}) 6. Nf4 (6. Bg5 Be7 {is very comfortable for us.}) 6... exd5 7. Nfxd5 (7. Bb5+ {does not do much after} Nc6 {.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Qxd5 {White exchanges the queens and gets their remaining knight to [d5]. We are a pawn up for now, but we need to neutralise White's initiative properly.} Qxd5 9. Nxd5 Bd6 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb8c6,Gc8e6,Ge6f5,Ge8c8] Next, our development is going to be ...[Nc6], ...[Be6]/[f5] followed by ...[O-O-O]. Once we achieve that we should be better. However, our [d6]-bishop will come under pressure along the d-file. White has a slight lead in development.} 10. Bg5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ge1c1,Gd5f6,Rg7f6] The drawback of the bishop on [g5] is that if White plays [Nf6]+ after [O-O-O] we can take on [f6], attacking the bishop on [g5].} Nc6 11. O-O-O Bg4 {This would not have been wise with the bishop on [e3], since White had [Nf6]+ followed by winning our most important minor piece on [d6].} 12. Re1 O-O 13. Rxe4 Be6 $10 {[%csl Gc6,Gd6,Ge6][%cal Gb7b6,Gg7g6,Gg8g7] The position is equal, but our pieces have more harmony and we could easily take over. We will slowly improve our position with moves like ...[b6] and ...[g6] next.} *

