{is slightly unpleasant for us after} 6. Ng3 {↑ , winning [e4].}) 6. Nf4 (6. Bg5 Be7 {is very comfortable for us.}) 6... exd5 7. Nfxd5 (7. Bb5+ {does not do much after} Nc6 {.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Qxd5 {White exchanges the queens and gets their remaining knight to [d5]. We are a pawn up for now, but we need to neutralise White's initiative properly.} Qxd5 9. Nxd5 Bd6 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb8c6,Gc8e6,Ge6f5,Ge8c8] Next, our development is going to be ...[Nc6], ...[Be6]/[f5] followed by ...[O-O-O]. Once we achieve that we should be better. However, our [d6]-bishop will come under pressure along the d-file. White has a slight lead in development.} 10. Be3 Bf5 11. O-O-O {[%cal Gd5f6] White's threat is to play [Nf6]+ next, and we cannot really do much about it. We will plan to meet it with ...[Ke7], keeping our dark-squared bishop alive.} ({After} 11. Bb5+ Nc6 {we will play ...[O-O-O] next with a great position.}) 11... Nc6 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 12. Nf6+ {Any other move will be met with ...[O-O-O] and then we will start playing for the advantage.} Ke7 13. Nd5+ {All of this so far happened in only one game between two very strong players: 0-1 Niemann, H 2637 -Shevchenko, K 2652 2022. We can just follow their play, but I like another option for Black here which is a bit safer.} Kf8 {The king is tucked away and we will bring our rook to [d8] next.} (13... Ke6 14. Nc3 Ne5 {happened in the aforementioned game. Black eventually even took over, although White can certainly improve upon the game.}) 14. Bc4 {This is a good square for the bishop. They want to bring their other rook into the game.} Ne5 15. Be2 Nc6 {Our plan is to go back to [d4] next, and we will be very happy to win our opponent's dark-squared bishop.} 16. h3 Nd4 $1 17. Bg4 Bg6 $10 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gc2c3,Gh7h5] We will play either ...[f5] or ...[h5] next, attacking the bishop on [g4] which lacks a good square to go to.} *

