1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2 {In this chapter, we will look at a bunch of rare 3rd and 4th moves which do not fit in any of the other chapters. I could have split these different moves up into a couple of separate chapters, but I feel putting them all together in one chapter is more effective, as a lot of these variations are quite similar.} Bf5 {We saw these structures in detail in the 4.e3 chapters, but here we will see all the lines other than the move 4.e3.} 5. Nh4 {This is the main move, in the same position with 4.e3 not allowing our [f5]-bishop to stay on the board.} Be4 6. Qb3 Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] We are preparing the ...[e5] break very soon. White lacks proper development and we are going to exploit this factor.} 7. f3 {This looks serious as we lack a good square for the bishop. Our play here is very instructive, however.} (7. Qxb7 {is met with} e5 {↑ , opening up the position for our pieces.}) 7... dxc4 8. Qxb7 Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6c5] We get the bishop to the middle of the board. However, White is ready to kick it back.} 9. e4 e6 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Re1,Rf3,Rh4][%cal Gc6d5] We give up a whole piece but fix our pawn structure. White is struggling with development and our pawns really restrict White's pieces.} 10. exd5 cxd5 11. g3 Rb8 12. Qa6 Bb4 $36 {[%csl Ra1,Ra6,Rc1][%cal Gc4c3] We are preparing to play ...[c3] next, going after White's queenside. The queen is stuck on [a6] away from all the play.} *

