1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nbd2 {In this chapter, we will look at a bunch of rare 3rd and 4th moves which do not fit in any of the other chapters. I could have split these different moves up into a couple of separate chapters, but I feel putting them all together in one chapter is more effective, as a lot of these variations are quite similar.} Bf5 {We saw these structures in detail in the 4.e3 chapters, but here we will see all the lines other than the move 4.e3.} 5. Nh4 {This is the main move, in the same position with 4.e3 not allowing our [f5]-bishop to stay on the board.} Be4 6. f3 Bg6 7. Qb3 {Once again, White tries to go after our queenside.} Qc7 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2] We can play more slowly in this case. Compared to the previous line, White cannot take on [e4] immediately. It will take time for White to get their pieces out as both the bishop on [c1] and the knight on [d2] are misplaced.} 8. g4 {White wants to play [g5] and kick the knight back.} e6 9. e4 {This has been played by the Turkish GM Emre Can in classical chess. It seems like a one-game bluff to scare Black.} Be7 10. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gb8c6] This is an improvement over Can's game. It seems a bit counter-intuitive to block the development of the [b8]-knight, but we will be able to play the move ...[c5] pretty soon.} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. e5 Nfd7 $36 {[%cal Gc6c5,Ge7h4] We will play ...[c5] next. We can also give a check on [h4] when needed. White's position is overextended.} *

