1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 {We have not seen this move order yet. It will likely transpose back to the Semi-Slav main lines, but in this chapter we will be looking at some independent options.} Nf6 4. Bg5 {This has been seen in a few games, but White is pushing their luck too much. White is a move down in the lines we saw in the Botvinnik variation. White's [Nf3] is much more important compared to our move ...[e6]. It probably is better for us with the pawn on [e7], as White cannot make use of [e4]-[e5] as our knight is not pinned.} dxc4 {[%cal Gb7b5] Of course, we are greedy and take the pawn.} 5. a4 {White needs to stop the move ...[b5].} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4] We attack [b2] and keep an eye on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Qd2 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ra5a1] This may look strange, but the point is that now we can play ...[b5] next. The [a1]-rook is undefended as White's queen has left the first rank.} 7. Nf3 b5 8. Qc1 {White finally defends the rook, but it is too late now.} b4 9. Nb1 Nbd7 10. Qxc4 Ba6 $36 {[%cal Ga6f1,Gf6e4,Gc6c5] We are already ahead in development and White cannot play [e3] without allowing us to trade on [f1], leaving their king stuck in the centre. We will play ...[Ne4] and ...[c5] pretty quickly.} *

