1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 {We have not seen this move order yet. It will likely transpose back to the Semi-Slav main lines, but in this chapter we will be looking at some independent options.} Nf6 4. e3 {This move order can be annoying for those who play the Classical Slav. However, it does not make a huge difference for us as we will transpose back to the main lines.} e6 (4... e6 {Unlike the lines we saw with 3.Nf3 and 4.e3, here White cannot play anything other than} 5. Nf3 {really, transposing to the Meran chapters. The knight on [c3] is the one that could have gone to [d2] in some lines.}) 5. Bd3 Nbd7 {We could have taken on [c4] here, but there is no reason to do this when we can just transpose to the lines we have seen earlier.} 6. b3 {This has been played by a few strong players to try and delay the development of the [g1] knight. It has a clear drawback, though.} e5 $1 {[%csl Rg1] Without the knight we can immediately break in the centre.} 7. Nge2 e4 {[%csl Rc1,Rc3,Rd3,Re2] This is a great pawn structure for us, as all of White's pieces are restricted on the queenside. Our bishop on [d6] will be very strong along the diagonal.} 8. Bc2 Bd6 9. f3 {This is the only justification for White's earlier play.} exf3 10. gxf3 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8g6] We want to regroup our knight to the kingside via [f8] and [g6]. If we are able to keep control over the centre, we are just better.} 12. e4 dxe4 13. fxe4 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Rg1,Rh2] We immediately go after White's exposed kingside. The game is getting pretty concrete.} 14. e5 Ndxe5 $1 15. dxe5 Qb6+ 16. Kg2 Bxe5 $36 {[%csl Ge5,Rg2,Gg4] We have tremendous compensation for the piece with very active pieces, playing against an exposed king on [g2].} *

