1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 {We have not seen this move order yet. It will likely transpose back to the Semi-Slav main lines, but in this chapter we will be looking at some independent options.} Nf6 4. e3 {This move order can be annoying for those who play the Classical Slav. However, it does not make a huge difference for us as we will transpose back to the main lines.} e6 (4... e6 {Unlike the lines we saw with 3.Nf3 and 4.e3, here White cannot play anything other than} 5. Nf3 {really, transposing to the Meran chapters. The knight on [c3] is the one that could have gone to [d2] in some lines.}) 5. b3 {This has been played by strong players including Magnus. It is an improvement for White over the previous line, as we are not able to play ...[e5] immediately.} Bb4 {[%cal Rb4e1] We want to exploit White's early fianchetto and lack of development.} 6. Bd2 {[%csl Gb2,Rd2] This is already a concession as the bishop is misplaced here, the b-pawn being on [b3]. We can now play slowly, improving our pieces.} O-O 7. Nf3 b6 {[%cal Gc6c5] We will delay the development of the [b8]-knight for now. We want to play the ...[c5] break as quickly as we can.} 8. Bd3 (8. Be2 {is too slow. We can answer} Bb7 9. O-O Bd6 {with the usual development.}) 8... Bb7 9. O-O dxc4 {It is time to break in the centre.} 10. bxc4 c5 {[%cal Gd8d3] This is very effective as the [d3]-bishop is exposed. White cannot release the tension in the centre.} 11. Qe2 cxd4 12. exd4 Nc6 $10 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6e7,Ge7f5,Ge7g6] White has trouble keeping control over the hanging pawns in the centre. We will keep our dark-squared bishop along the [a5]-[e1] diagonal and trade on [d2] whenever White moves the knight. We can regroup the [c6]-knight via [e7] to either [f5] or [g6].} *

