1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 {We have not seen this move order yet. It will likely transpose back to the Semi-Slav main lines, but in this chapter we will be looking at some independent options.} Nf6 4. e3 {This move order can be annoying for those who play the Classical Slav. However, it does not make a huge difference for us as we will transpose back to the main lines.} e6 (4... e6 {Unlike the lines we saw with 3.Nf3 and 4.e3, here White cannot play anything other than} 5. Nf3 {really, transposing to the Meran chapters. The knight on [c3] is the one that could have gone to [d2] in some lines.}) 5. b3 {This has been played by strong players including Magnus. It is an improvement for White over the previous line, as we are not able to play ...[e5] immediately.} Bb4 {[%cal Rb4e1] We want to exploit White's early fianchetto and lack of development.} 6. Bb2 {The more principled move, but this leaves the pin on the [c3]-knight intact, which is dangerous.} Ne4 {We put more pressure on [c3], forcing White to misplace their pieces.} 7. Nge2 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ga2a3] White would be better if we were forced to trade our active pieces. Instead, we need to do something dynamic.} dxc4 8. bxc4 e5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We break in the centre just in time.} 9. f3 (9. dxe5 {is met with} Nd7 10. Qc2 Ndc5 {with the initiative.}) 9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 11. Nxc3 exd4 {After a bunch of trades we force White to weaken their pawn structure one way or the other.} 12. exd4 O-O $10 {[%csl Rb4,Rd4][%cal Gc8f5,Gb8d7] The hanging pawns are a clear target for us. Typically they are good dynamically when there are more pieces on the board. Currently, however, there are only two sets of minor pieces left. We will put our bishop on [f5] next, followed by ...[Nd7].} *

