1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 {We have not seen this move order yet. It will likely transpose back to the Semi-Slav main lines, but in this chapter we will be looking at some independent options.} Nf6 4. e3 {This move order can be annoying for those who play the Classical Slav. However, it does not make a huge difference for us as we will transpose back to the main lines.} e6 (4... e6 {Unlike the lines we saw with 3.Nf3 and 4.e3, here White cannot play anything other than} 5. Nf3 {really, transposing to the Meran chapters. The knight on [c3] is the one that could have gone to [d2] in some lines.}) 5. b3 {This has been played by strong players including Magnus. It is an improvement for White over the previous line, as we are not able to play ...[e5] immediately.} Bb4 {[%cal Rb4e1] We want to exploit White's early fianchetto and lack of development.} 6. Bb2 {The more principled move, but this leaves the pin on the [c3]-knight intact, which is dangerous.} Ne4 {We put more pressure on [c3], forcing White to misplace their pieces.} 7. Qc2 {What is the drawback of the queen on [c2]?} e5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We go after the centre, namely the [d4]-pawn. We can also get our bishop to [f5] next with a tempo, targeting the queen on [c2].} 8. a3 {White wants to trade off the minor pieces to consolidate their centre.} (8. dxe5 {is met with} d4 $1 {⩱ , gaining full control over the centre.}) 8... exd4 $1 {We first want to open the e-file before we give up the bishop on [c3]. Otherwise, White has the option to recapture with the bishop on [d4].} 9. axb4 (9. exd4 {is not great after} Bxc3+ 10. Bxc3 Qe7 {⩱ , with ...[Bf5] to follow.}) 9... dxc3 10. Bxc3 O-O {[%cal Gd8e7,Gd5d4] We have brought our king to safety. Next, we will play ...[Qe7] and try to get ...[d4] in. Taking on [d5] would open the c-file for our rook and give us the [c6]-square for the knight.} 11. Bd3 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qe7 $10 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb7b5,Gb8a6] Our sights are set on the [b4]-pawn. We are threatening to play ...[b5] followed by ...[Na6], winning the pawn. White can win [c6] in return, but this would open the queenside for our pieces.} *

