1. d4 d5 2. e3 {Now, we move on to lines which do not involve the move [c4], which we have been looking at so far.} Nf6 {We will always play ....[Nf6] in these rare lines, as it is the most flexible option. White can transpose with [c4] to more common lines at any moment.} 3. f4 $6 {[%csl Re4] Let's take one look at the stonewall structure. This is a serious inaccuracy by White, as we are still able to get our light-squared bishop out of the pawn chain.} Bf5 {This bishop is supposed to be our bad bishop, but now it is very active on [f5]. White will likely have to trade it for their best minor piece. The [e4]-square is going to be a big headache for White in the long run.} 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bd3 Be7 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge6f5] We are happy to get our pawn to [f5] as it opens up the e-file for us to target the [e3]-pawn. The [e5]-square is not a big deal as we can always cover it with ...[f6] in the future.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Ne5 c5 $15 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gb8c6] We will play ...[Nc6] next with a fantastic position. It is hard to see what White is going to do with the passive bishop on [c1]. We can always take on [d4] if White tries to go for the move [b3].} *

