1. d4 d5 2. e3 {Now, we move on to lines which do not involve the move [c4], which we have been looking at so far.} Nf6 {We will always play ....[Nf6] in these rare lines, as it is the most flexible option. White can transpose with [c4] to more common lines at any moment.} 3. Bd3 {This has been played in quite a few games. It is similar to the usual Colle lines, which we will check next.} c5 {In all the positions where White delays the move [c4], we take charge immediately by going ....[c5].} 4. c3 {White goes for some kind of a reverse Semi-Slav, but of course, this is not enough for more than equality.} Nc6 {We are ready to play ...[e5] next.} 5. f4 $2 {This is yet another bad Stonewall from White, and I hope you know what we are going to play next.} Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6] Of course, the bishop gets out before we play ...[e6]. After that we can always drop back with the bishop to [f5].} 6. Nf3 e6 7. O-O Bd6 {[%cal Gc6e7] We want to keep the [e7]-square for the knight.} 8. Qe1 O-O 9. Ne5 Bf5 $17 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4] We trade White's best minor piece and enjoy a big advantage. We can regroup our knight to [e7] and [f5] next.} *

