1. d4 d5 2. e3 {Now, we move on to lines which do not involve the move [c4], which we have been looking at so far.} Nf6 {We will always play ....[Nf6] in these rare lines, as it is the most flexible option. White can transpose with [c4] to more common lines at any moment.} 3. Bd3 {This has been played in quite a few games. It is similar to the usual Colle lines, which we will check next.} c5 {In all the positions where White delays the move [c4], we take charge immediately by going ....[c5].} 4. c3 {White goes for some kind of a reverse Semi-Slav, but of course, this is not enough for more than equality.} Nc6 {We are ready to play ...[e5] next.} 5. Nf3 Bg4 {The play is similar to what we saw in the previous line. We are able to get our bishop out before developing our kingside. With the bishop on [d3], the pin on the [f3]-knight is another issue for White.} 6. Nbd2 e6 7. O-O Bd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. e4 {The most common move in the position, but this opens up the diagonal for the [c5]-bishop, which targets the [f2]-pawn.} O-O 10. Qc2 {[%cal Ra8c8,Rc8c2] We are continuing with the most popular move, but this is an inaccuracy. The queen is misplaced on the c-file. It should rather be on [e2].} (10. exd5 {would have been better, but we get a comfortable position after} Qxd5 {followed by ...[Rfd8].}) 10... h6 11. h3 Bh5 12. exd5 Nxd5 $17 {[%csl Rd2,Rf3][%cal Gd5f4,Ga8c8,Gc6b4] The knight is heading to [f4] next. We will play ...[Rc8], preparing to continue with ...[Nb4]. White cannot develop their queenside easily as the knight on [d2] has to defend the one on [f3].} *

