1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. g3 {Although this is a popular move, it usually transposes into the Slav [g3] lines we saw previously.} (3. Nc3 {is answered by} c5 {, which will likely transpose to the upcoming 2.Nc3 chapter.}) 3... Bf5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ge7e6] I think an early [g3] is not principled as we can get our bishop out very easily.} 4. Bg2 (4. Nh4 {is met with} Be4 $1 5. f3 Bg6 {, a theme we have seen earlier.}) 4... e6 5. Nh4 {This is the only independent option I could think of which is at least worth considering.} ({After} 5. O-O {we create a luft for the bishop on [h7] with} h6 {. Anytime White plays the move [c4], it will transpose into Slav [g3] lines which we have already checked.}) 5... Be4 6. f3 Bg6 {[%cal Gc7c5] White is able to win the bishop, but we have not played the move ...[c6] yet and there is no reason to play it anymore.} 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. e4 c5 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6] We will increase the pressure on White's centre with ...[Nc6] next. There is no reason to take on [e4] and activate White's light-squared bishop.} *

