1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. c3 {This has been played by Praggnanandhaa and other strong players when they just want to get a game going. This is a standard approach these days, as many people get fed up with the huge amount of theory in the main lines. Instead, if you can land the first surprise and get a fighting game, it is an achievement already.} e6 {This fits best with our repertoire against the London, which we'll take a look at in the next chapter. We want to meet [Bf4] with the move ...[Bd6] without playing ...[c5] yet.} 4. Bg5 {White gets a strange version of the Trompowsky with the inclusion of the move [c3].} h6 {We give White a choice between giving up the bishop or risk getting stuck on the kingside.} 5. Bxf6 $1 {White gives up the bishop and will now focus on getting the [e4] break in.} Qxf6 6. Nbd2 c5 {[%csl Gd4] We need to get our play going on against White's centre.} 7. e4 cxd4 {We want to force White to get an IQP with ...[dxe4] next.} 8. exd5 {This is best, trading off the pawns on [d5] and leaving us with an IQP.} exd5 9. Nxd4 Nc6 $10 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8] We do not mind, though, as the bishop pair compensates for the IQP. The position is balanced but has a lot of life left.} *

