1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. c3 {This has been played by Praggnanandhaa and other strong players when they just want to get a game going. This is a standard approach these days, as many people get fed up with the huge amount of theory in the main lines. Instead, if you can land the first surprise and get a fighting game, it is an achievement already.} e6 {This fits best with our repertoire against the London, which we'll take a look at in the next chapter. We want to meet [Bf4] with the move ...[Bd6] without playing ...[c5] yet.} 4. Bg5 {White gets a strange version of the Trompowsky with the inclusion of the move [c3].} h6 {We give White a choice between giving up the bishop or risk getting stuck on the kingside.} 5. Bh4 {This is the most played move in the position, but it is an inaccuracy as it allows us to start our play on the kingside.} g5 6. Bg3 Ne4 {[%cal Gh6h5,Gh5h4] We create a strong threat of ...[h5]-[h4] on the kingside.} 7. Nfd2 $1 {This is the only way for White to not be significantly worse.} Nxg3 8. hxg3 Bg7 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7] We have won the bishop pair and our king is pretty safe on the dark squares. We will look to open up the centre soon for our bishops.} 9. e4 O-O 10. Bd3 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nd7 $10 {[%cal Gc7c5,Ge6e5] Next, we can go for either of the two pawn breaks in the centre. We can also play ...[f5] to kick the white knight back.} *

