1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. Bg5 {This is the best version of the Trompowsky we can face via our move order, as we start with 1...d5. The Trompowsky in general is much more effective against the 1...Nf6 move order.} Ne4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge4g5,Gc7c5] We get our knight to the centre with a tempo, attacking the [g5]-bishop. It helps us play ...[c5] on the queenside.} 4. Bh4 h5 $5 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gf7f6,Gg7g5,Gh5h4] This is one of the most unusual moves I have seen, but the threat is ...[f6] and ...[g5]. Surprisingly, this is not so easy to stop.} 5. h3 {This is the most logical move, creating a luft for the bishop on [h2]. Overall I do like the inclusion of these two moves on the kingside.} (5. e3 {is met with} f6 {↑ , preparing to play ...[g5] next.}) 5... c5 6. e3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2] We now shift our attention to the queenside. White has to be very precise to not get a significantly worse position.} 7. Nc3 $1 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Qa5 9. Qd2 c4 $10 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Gc8f5,Gb8d7] We will continue with ...[Bf5] next, followed by ...[Nd7]. The pawn structure on the queenside is clearly in our favour as White's queen is tied to the [c3]-pawn and their light-squared bishop is restricted.} *

