1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. Bg5 {This is the best version of the Trompowsky we can face via our move order, as we start with 1...d5. The Trompowsky in general is much more effective against the 1...Nf6 move order.} Ne4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge4g5,Gc7c5] We get our knight to the centre with a tempo, attacking the [g5]-bishop. It helps us play ...[c5] on the queenside.} 4. Bf4 ({This is better than} 4. Bh4 {, as on [f4] the bishop keeps contact with the centre. We will not be able to use ideas of trapping the bishop as we saw in the previous line.}) 4... c5 5. e3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rf4] Once again we see the same plan. With the bishop away from the queenside, the [b2]-pawn is our big target.} 6. Qc1 {The most played move in the position, but the queen loses control over the centre, namely the [d4]-pawn.} Nc6 {[%csl Gd4] We develop the knight with a tempo, targeting [d4].} 7. c3 f6 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Gc5d4,Ge7e5] We play in the spirit of the position threatening to go ...[g5] and ....[h5] next. We are also preparing to take on [d4] and go for the ...[e5] break. White cannot stop both threats.} 8. h3 {White creates a luft for the bishop on [h2] in case we play ...[g5].} cxd4 {We go for the other plan, making use of the queen on [b6] and the knight on [e4] which are both targeting the [f2]-pawn.} 9. exd4 e5 {[%cal Gb6f2]} 10. Be3 exd4 11. Nxd4 Bc5 $15 {[%csl Rd4] White cannot defend [d4] adequately and the queen is stuck on [c1], defending [b2]. White has to be very resourceful to survive this position.} *

