1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. Bg5 {This is the best version of the Trompowsky we can face via our move order, as we start with 1...d5. The Trompowsky in general is much more effective against the 1...Nf6 move order.} Ne4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge4g5,Gc7c5] We get our knight to the centre with a tempo, attacking the [g5]-bishop. It helps us play ...[c5] on the queenside.} 4. Bf4 ({This is better than} 4. Bh4 {, as on [f4] the bishop keeps contact with the centre. We will not be able to use ideas of trapping the bishop as we saw in the previous line.}) 4... c5 5. e3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rf4] Once again we see the same plan. With the bishop away from the queenside, the [b2]-pawn is our big target.} 6. Nc3 {This is the best move, attacking the [d5]-pawn. White wants us to exchange off our active knight on [e4], but at the same time this does weaken their pawn structure on the queenside.} Qa5 {We go after the [c3]-knight immediately and will win a pawn on [c3]. However, we need to be careful with the king still in the centre.} 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. O-O Nxc3 9. Bxc6+ {White creates a weakness on [c6], which they will try to exploit with the knight coming to [e5] next.} bxc6 10. bxc3 Qxc3 11. Ne5 cxd4 12. exd4 Bf5 $10 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gf7f6] We are ready to play ...[f6] next. We can always take on [c2] and trade the queens if necessary.} *

