1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. Be2 {Let's start with this timid-looking move, which has been played by a few strong players.} Nc6 5. O-O Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6] As we have seen several times, we develop the bishop out of the pawn chain. We maintain the tension in the centre, not allowing White to develop the dark-squared bishop easily.} (5... cxd4 {is also possible, but I do not want to open the diagonal for the c1-bishop unless it is necessary.}) 6. Nbd2 {White develops the queenside slowly, giving us ample time to finish our development. In such positions, the value of a tempo is not very high and we are essentially playing the White side of a QGD.} e6 7. b3 cxd4 {[%csl Rb3,Rd4][%cal Rc1b2] A well-known rule in these positions is to take on [d4] immediately after White plays [b3]. Now the bishop has to go to [b2] and we can open the [c1]-[h6] diagonal. We stop White from taking on [c5] themselves.} 8. exd4 Bd6 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Ne5 Bf5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5c2] It is better to preserve the bishops in this structure. Our bishop is more active on [f5] along the diagonal.} 11. c4 h6 $10 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Gf6e4] We create a luft for the bishop on [h7]. We have the better pawn structure as we can always take on [c4], leaving White with hanging pawns. We can play ...[Ne4] next as the exchange of pieces should be in our favour.} *

