1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. Be2 {Let's start with this timid-looking move, which has been played by a few strong players.} Nc6 5. O-O Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6] As we have seen several times, we develop the bishop out of the pawn chain. We maintain the tension in the centre, not allowing White to develop the dark-squared bishop easily.} (5... cxd4 {is also possible, but I do not want to open the diagonal for the c1-bishop unless it is necessary.}) 6. h3 {This is more testing, asking us to clarify our intentions.} (6. dxc5 {is not as effective without the inclusion of the move [h3]. After} e6 7. a3 Bxc5 8. b4 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Bd6 {we are ready to play ...[Ne5] next with a great position.}) 6... Bxf3 {This is pretty rare, giving up the bishop so easily, but we do misplace the white bishop. It would be much better on [d3] in the resulting structure.} (6... Bh5 {is the usual response, but the lines after} 7. dxc5 e6 8. a3 Bxc5 9. b4 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 {are annoying for us. If we compare it to the previous move, the pawn being on [h3] makes a huge difference. We are not able to play ...[Qc7] with a tempo.}) 7. Bxf3 cxd4 {[%csl Gd6,Gf8][%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6] We release the tension as we do not want to open up the centre, having given up the bishop pair. Our dark-squared bishop is the most important minor piece in this middlegame and it will be well placed on [d6].} 8. exd4 e6 9. c3 Bd6 10. Nd2 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Gf3e2,Ge8c8,Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Gg5g4]} (10... Qc7 {Until the previous move, we were following a game of Anish Giri. I like this move simply because we can meet the natural} 11. Be2 {with} O-O-O {followed by ...[h6] and ...[g5]. We can also start with the move ...[h6], keeping our options open.}) *

