1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. Nbd2 {White develops the knight first, keeping the options open for the light-squared bishop. We need to understand the drawbacks of this move.} cxd4 $1 {Now that the diagonal is blocked by the [d2]-knight do we release the tension in the centre.} (4... Nc6 {gives White the extra option of} 5. Bb5 {.}) 5. exd4 Qc7 {[%cal Gb8c6,Rf1b5] Once again, this is clever as we wait for a move before developing the knight to [c6]. We do not want White to move the bishop to [b5] and then follow up with [c4].} 6. c3 (6. Bb5+ {is not effective now due to} Bd7 {.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bd3 {White stops the bishop from coming to [f5], but this is not our only option.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge7e6] This is very important, as otherwise White could play [h3] and our bishop would be left stuck on [c8].} 8. Nf1 {This has not been played as much, but it was tried by a couple of strong players. White wants to get the knight to [g3] as quickly as possible. If White castles first, they would need to move the rook first and only then go for this manoeuvre.} e6 9. Ng3 Nh5 $1 {[%csl Rg3] A very typical idea to deal with the knight on [g3]. We trade off the knights, which creates more space for our light-squared bishop.} 10. O-O Bd6 11. Re1 Nxg3 12. hxg3 {All of this happened in the game between Aronian and Anand in 2018.} O-O-O $36 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] This is our improvement, planning to go ...[h5]-[h4] next. Our king will be pretty safe on [b8]. The pawn on [g3] is a nice hook for us to open the h-file.} *

