1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. dxc5 {This is always something to be considered, as White is essentially playing a Queens Gambit Accepted reversed with an extra tempo. However, this is still a big concession from White in case we can recapture the pawn easily on [c5].} e6 5. c4 {This has been played by Hikaru a couple of times, but it is not very principled. We are able to develop our pieces faster and get a very comfortable middlegame.} Bxc5 6. a3 {White wants to gain space on the queenside with [b4].} O-O {There is no need to stop White's plan as it gives us a target to play against on the queenside.} 7. b4 Bd6 {The bishop is slightly better on [d6], as we would like to play ...[e5] at the right moment.} 8. Bb2 a5 {[%csl Rb4] We first create some weaknesses on the queenside.} 9. b5 {Now the queenside is under our control, as the pawn on [b5] is not doing much. White cannot play [c5] anymore and has to take on [d5] at some point.} Nbd7 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd7b6]} 10. Be2 Re8 11. O-O Nb6 {We try to force White to release the tension in the centre. This also opens up the diagonal for the bishop, as we will play ...[e5] next.} 12. Nbd2 e5 $10 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gd6c5,Gb2e5,Ge5e4,Gd8e7] We are threatening to play ...[e4] and ...[Qe7]. White has to give up their c-pawn for our [e5]-pawn with the move [c5]. Our pieces are very active and the position is balanced.} *

