1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. dxc5 {This is always something to be considered, as White is essentially playing a Queens Gambit Accepted reversed with an extra tempo. However, this is still a big concession from White in case we can recapture the pawn easily on [c5].} e6 5. b4 {This makes more sense, holding on to the pawn. This is the most played move in the position.} a5 {We will immediately go after White's queenside pawns which are overextended.} 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5] White is unable to hold on to the pawn. They cannot take on [b6] as then [b4] falls with a check. White has to decide on a good way to give back the pawn.} 8. a4 {White decides to give up [c5] but gets connected passed pawns on the queenside. These are very strong in the endgame, but not as impressive with many pieces on the board. The central pawns are more valuable in the middlegame.} bxc5 9. b5 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] We would like to play ...[e5] as well. The more space we get in the centre, the better it is. At the same time, we should not be in a rush, as this central advance can backfire if White is able to blockade our pawns.} 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Be2 O-O {[%cal Re6e5,Ge3e4] Let us first finish our development before trying to play ...[e5]. White will always try to meet it with the move [e4].} (11... e5 {is too early due to} 12. e4 $1 d4 13. Nfd2 {⩲ . The [c4]-square is a big issue for us.}) 12. O-O Bb7 13. Nbd2 Bc7 $10 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gc7a5] We change our plans, as White keeps threatening to counter our ...[e5] with [e3]-[e4]. The bishop is well placed on [c7] to stop White's queenside expansion. We will play ...[c4] next and move and put the bishop on [a5].} *

