1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. dxc5 {This is always something to be considered, as White is essentially playing a Queens Gambit Accepted reversed with an extra tempo. However, this is still a big concession from White in case we can recapture the pawn easily on [c5].} e6 5. b4 {This makes more sense, holding on to the pawn. This is the most played move in the position.} a5 {We will immediately go after White's queenside pawns which are overextended.} 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5] White is unable to hold on to the pawn. They cannot take on [b6] as then [b4] falls with a check. White has to decide on a good way to give back the pawn.} 8. Bb5+ {White will go for the same structure as in the previous line, but first they trade the light-squared bishops. This makes sense as our bishop was much more active on [b7] in those lines.} Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4 bxc5 11. b5 {The same plan as in the last line would be less effective currently. However, we have a clever idea in mind. You can take some time to try and find our next move.} g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4] It is time to start playing on the kingside. Having very good control over the centre, it makes sense to start playing on the flank. White is likely going to castle kingside.} 12. Bb2 Bd6 13. Qe2 {White keeps the king in the centre for now, which makes a lot of sense.} g4 14. Nfd2 Qc7 $10 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gh7h5,Gh5h4] We want to play ...[c4] next. Another plan is to go ...[h5]-[h4] on the kingside. White has to be very precise to maintain the balance. We can castle kingside if necessary, as White finds it hard to create any play with their pieces stuck on the queenside.} *

