1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. c4 {It is rare for White to play [c4] in the Colle, and it does not make much sense in conjunction with the move [e3].} cxd4 5. exd4 g6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] With the centre open and a nice target on [d4], this is the perfect scenario for us to fianchetto the bishop. It is somewhat similar to the 4.Qc2 Slav lines we saw in an earlier chapter.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Qb3 (7. cxd5 Nxd5 {is very comfortable for us.}) 7... O-O {We will win back the [d5]-pawn very soon. White will be left with an IQP on [d4].} 8. cxd5 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd7b6]} 9. Bg5 Nb6 10. Bxf6 {White desperately wants to hold on to the [d5]-pawn, but gives up the valuable dark-squared bishop in the process. It is only a matter of time before [d5] falls anyway.} exf6 11. Be2 a5 $10 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gd8d6,Gf8d8] We want to play ...[a4] to kick the queen back. If White stops it with their pawn, we get the juicy [b4]-square for our pieces. We will likely play ...[Qd6] and ...[Rd8] to regain the [d5]-pawn.} *

