1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. c3 {White plays it in the style of the Semi-Slav with colours reversed. If you think logically you will know which setup we will be going for.} e6 {If you recall, we put our bishop on [f5] against the 4.e3 system. Here White is unable to do that since they have already shut the bishop on [c1] with the move 3.e3. We discussed in the 4.e3 chapters that it is a better version for White when they have not yet committed the knight to [c3]. So we'll stick to that approach here, with colours reversed.} 5. Bd3 Nbd7 {We put our knight on [d7], leaving the [a8]-[h1] diagonal open for the bishop which we will develop to [b7].} 6. Nbd2 b6 {The first priority is to get the bishop to [b7], keeping good control over the [e4]-square.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White prepares to play [e4]. Now, there are two broad approaches for Black. I will show and explain both of them and then you can choose based on your style.} Ne4 {[%csl Ge4] This is the more aggressive option, which I personally would play in a game. We physically stop the move [e4] and restrict White's pieces.} 9. Qc2 {This is the most-played move in the position, but it's a significant error.} f5 $1 {We further strengthen our control over [e4]. The [e5]-square is not a big weakness with White's pieces stuck on the queenside. It is too late now to create any play.} 10. c4 Bd6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. dxc5 bxc5 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5][%cal Ge8g8] We have amazing control over the centre. We can castle next and start playing on either flank next. White's pieces lack space and are too passive.} *

