1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. c3 {White plays it in the style of the Semi-Slav with colours reversed. If you think logically you will know which setup we will be going for.} e6 {If you recall, we put our bishop on [f5] against the 4.e3 system. Here White is unable to do that since they have already shut the bishop on [c1] with the move 3.e3. We discussed in the 4.e3 chapters that it is a better version for White when they have not yet committed the knight to [c3]. So we'll stick to that approach here, with colours reversed.} 5. Bd3 Nbd7 {We put our knight on [d7], leaving the [a8]-[h1] diagonal open for the bishop which we will develop to [b7].} 6. Nbd2 b6 {The first priority is to get the bishop to [b7], keeping good control over the [e4]-square.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White prepares to play [e4]. Now, there are two broad approaches for Black. I will show and explain both of them and then you can choose based on your style.} Be7 {This is the alternate approach, where we castle first allowing White to achieve the [e4] break. It is equally strong, but the only drawback is that the position might simplify too much.} 9. e4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {White makes sure that they do not end up with an IQP.} dxe4 11. Nxe4 O-O {This is a typical structure which we will also see in the next chapter. It does have its imbalances, but overall it is pretty solid for both sides. I would probably go for this if I was happy to make a draw.} 12. Qe2 Nc5 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 $10 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb7g2] The position is balanced, but I do like our bishop along the long diagonal. You can choose based on your preference on the day.} *

