1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {We move on to the more common lines with the knight on [f3]. We will see all of White's different options here except for the London System, which we explore in a separate chapter.} Nf6 3. e3 {This is called the Colle system. White avoids playing [c4] and instead will look to keep a solid central formation. There are a number of different options for White on the next move, and we take a look at all the possible setups. I will try to keep our play consistent, but often we have to try to exploit the drawback of our opponent's move order in a specific way.} c5 {Our general approach to these quiet systems is to gain more space on the queenside. We will place our pieces as actively as possible and try to fight for the advantage.} 4. c3 {White plays it in the style of the Semi-Slav with colours reversed. If you think logically you will know which setup we will be going for.} e6 {If you recall, we put our bishop on [f5] against the 4.e3 system. Here White is unable to do that since they have already shut the bishop on [c1] with the move 3.e3. We discussed in the 4.e3 chapters that it is a better version for White when they have not yet committed the knight to [c3]. So we'll stick to that approach here, with colours reversed.} 5. Bd3 Nbd7 {We put our knight on [d7], leaving the [a8]-[h1] diagonal open for the bishop which we will develop to [b7].} 6. Nbd2 b6 {The first priority is to get the bishop to [b7], keeping good control over the [e4]-square.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Qe2 {This is pretty similar to the previous two lines. We have the same choice here as well.} Be7 {You can also go for the simpler plan of just castling kingside.} 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 O-O {We get a very similar position to the previous line, with the only difference that White's rook is likely to go to [d1] directly.} 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Bg5 Rfe8 $10 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gc5c4,Gc5d4] We defend the bishop on [e7] and now have a few ideas. We can go for the move ...[c4], exploiting the knight on [e4]. We are also threatening to take on [d4] next. White likely has to simplify by exchanging on [f6] a few times, which would lead to an equal endgame.} *

