1. d4 d5 2. a3 {Welcome to the final theoretical chapter in our journey through the 1.d4 jungle! Here, we will look at some odd first moves which you will likely never face in a tournament game. But for the sake of completeness and because Hikaru likes to mix it up in Titled Tuesday, we will briefly look at all of White's rare 2nd move tries.} ({The move} 2. a3 {, for example, has been played by both Hikaru and Magnus.}) 2... Nf6 {We will meet all of these moves with ...[Nf6] as it is the most flexible answer, keeping our options open.} 3. Nf3 c5 {We go for our standard plan against these quiet moves. If I had to come up with a plan over the board, I probably would not play like this, as it feels like the move [a3] is specifically aimed against this plan. But, with the help of the computer, there is no reason to hesitate.} 4. dxc5 e6 5. b4 {This is the only plan which makes any sense for White, attempting to hold onto the pawn.} a5 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5] We will immediately strike on the queenside, before White is able to consolidate.} 6. Bb2 axb4 7. axb4 Rxa1 8. Bxa1 b6 {[%csl Rb4] White can neither defend the [c5]-pawn nor take on [b6], as the [b4]-pawn then falls with check.} 9. c4 bxc5 10. b5 Bb7 $10 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] We will continue with ...[Nbd7] and ...[Be7]. I like our control over the centre much more than White's passed pawn on [b5], which can become a weakness in the future.} *

