1. d4 d5 2. c3 {White goes for the reverse Slav, which is aimed against the move ...[c5].} Nf6 3. Bg5 {This has been played by Magnus a couple of times. I guess White really wants to play the Trompowsky, and decided to wait for the move ...[Nf6].} (3. Nf3 {transposes to an earlier chapter.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] This is a very unusual recommendation, but I could not resist it as it is extremely creative. We want to play ...[e5] next.} 4. Nf3 {White stops our plan and we will look very silly unless we do something quick to justify our previous move.} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rg5] This is the point of our play. We want to play against White's dark-squared bishop.} 5. Bf4 {This looks natural, keeping an eye on [e5].} (5. Be3 {can be met with} e6 {↑ followed by ...[Bd6], and we can even go ...[f5] later.}) 5... f6 $1 {[%cal Gg7g5] We follow up in the spirit of the position, preparing to play ...[g5] next. We want to kick White's bishop back to where it came from.} 6. Nbd2 g5 7. Be3 Nd6 $15 {[%cal Gd6f5,Gh7h5] This knight is heading to [f5] next and we will win the dark-squared bishop. We can then continue playing on the kingside with ...[h5]-[h4].} *

