1. d4 d5 2. e4 {This has been played way more than all of the previous moves of this chapter combined, but is an inaccuracy. It is called the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit.} dxe4 {Of course, we take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger.} 3. Nc3 (3. f3 {is met very strongly with} e5 {∓ .}) 3... Nf6 4. Bg5 ({This has been played less often than the main move} 4. f3 {, but we will still take a brief look at it. White wants to take on [f6] and win the [e4]-pawn.}) 4... Bf5 {We defend the [e4]-pawn by developing our bishop to a good square.} 5. f3 {Now White wants to get the queen to [f3] next, targeting our queenside.} Nbd7 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Of course, there is no reason to help White develop their pieces.} 6. Bc4 exf3 {We trade on [f3] now because we are able to grab the pawn on [c2] if White takes on [f3] with the queen.} 7. Qxf3 Bxc2 8. Rc1 Bg6 $17 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6,Ge8h8] We will continue with ...[e6] and ...[Bd6]. White has no compensation for the missing pawn even after they grab [b7].} *

