1. d4 d5 2. e4 {This has been played way more than all of the previous moves of this chapter combined, but is an inaccuracy. It is called the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit.} dxe4 {Of course, we take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger.} 3. Nc3 (3. f3 {is met very strongly with} e5 {∓ .}) 3... Nf6 4. f3 {This is White's main point. They are willing to sacrifice a pawn to develop their pieces quickly. White will castle kingside next and try to make use of the half-open f-file. However, this is nowhere close to having enough compensation for the pawn.} exf3 5. Nxf3 g6 {With the centre open, our bishop is perfect on [g7]. This also keeps the king more secure on the kingside.} 6. Bc4 Bg7 7. O-O O-O {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gb8c6] We want to play ...[Bg4] next and target the [d4]-pawn. Ourknight will come to [c6] next to do the same.} 8. h3 {This has not been played much, but it is the best option for White to cover the [g4]-square.} Nc6 9. Be3 Na5 {We kick the bishop away from its ideal square.} 10. Be2 b6 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7e6,Gf6d5] We will put our bishop on [b7] next to get control over the long diagonal. We can also play ...[e6] followed by ...[Nd5].} *

