1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {We move on to the Pseudo-Trompowsky, which is again not a well-reputed opening. It is much better to play 2.Bg5 when Black alread has a knight on [f6].} f6 {We have already seen something similar in this chapter, and if you recall, also in the Slav Exchange chapter. This move is very useful to prepare the ...[e5] advance in the centre.} 3. Bh4 {This is not the best reply, as the bishop gets stuck on the kingside.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gh6f5] The knight will head to [f5] next, going after White's dark-squared bishop.} 4. f3 {This is the best move, creating a square on [f2] for the bishop. However, it also weakens White's kingside.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5] We stick to our plan of preparing the move ...[e5] as quickly as possible.} 5. e3 e5 6. Nc3 Be6 {[%csl Gd5] We maintain the tension in the centre, defending the pawn on [d5].} 7. Bb5 Qd6 8. Nge2 O-O-O $15 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Gh6f5,Gh7h5] Our king is safe on the queenside. We have very good control over the centre. We can continue with ...[Nf5] and ...[h5] on the kingside. In opposite-side castling middlegames, the side with an advantage in the centre has the edge.} *

