1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {We move on to the Pseudo-Trompowsky, which is again not a well-reputed opening. It is much better to play 2.Bg5 when Black alread has a knight on [f6].} f6 {We have already seen something similar in this chapter, and if you recall, also in the Slav Exchange chapter. This move is very useful to prepare the ...[e5] advance in the centre.} 3. Bf4 {White tries to delay our ...[e5] plan for as long as possible.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] We target [d4] and prepare the move ...[e5].} 4. Nf3 (4. e3 {gives us a great position after} e5 {⩱ .}) 4... g5 $1 {There should be no hesitation once we have played ...[f6]. We have to be very concrete in these positions and play dynamically.} 5. Bg3 g4 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] We kick the knight away from the centre.} 6. Nh4 {The knight has to go to the rim. Otherwise we push our h-pawn down the board.} e5 7. dxe5 (7. e3 $2 {is bad due to} f5 $1 {∓ with ...[Be7] to follow.}) 7... f5 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gf5f4,Gf8e7] Once again, we are threatening to win the piece on [h4] with ...[Be7], or even with ...[f4]. Now White has to find some only moves.} 8. e4 $1 {White fights back in the centre.} fxe4 9. Nc3 Be6 {The centre is firmly under our control now.} 10. h3 Qd7 {We are ready to castle next with a big advantage. White has to do something quickly.} 11. hxg4 O-O-O 12. Ng6 $1 {White wins the exchange on the kingside and gets rid of their knight on the edge of the board. However, they are lagging behind in development.} hxg6 13. Rxh8 Bb4 $36 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gd5d4] We have a huge initiative with ...[d4] coming up. White has to keep coming up with only moves to survive, while our play is pretty easy. A lot of these moves are very hard to find practically. I think we cannot end the theoretical part with a better line than this one, as it perfectly showcases the kind of chess we aim to play: principled chess, looking to fight for the initiative.} *

