1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {We move on to the Pseudo-Trompowsky which is again not a well-reputed opening. It is much better with the knight on [f6].} f6 {We have already seen something similar in this chapter and if you recall also in the Slav Exchange. This is very useful to get the move ...[e5] in the centre.} 3. Bd2 {This has been played by a few strong players and recommended in a Chessable course - The Trompowsky: Simplified. It is good to know how to deal with it.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] We immediately target the [d4] pawn which is undefended.} 4. e3 (4. c4 {can be met with} Nxd4 5. Bc3 e5 {and we will win the dark-squared bishop next.}) 4... e5 5. Bb5 {This is White's main try here to try and exploit the pawn on [f6] with concrete moves.} (5. Nf3 {runs into} e4 6. Ng1 Be6 {and we get a good version of the French with reversed colours. The bishop is misplaced on [d2].}) 5... Qd6 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ga7a6,Gd6c6] I like this option to maintain the tension in the centre. We also do not let White damage our pawn structure. White has to do something here as otherwise we are just better with the move ...[a6].} (5... exd4 {is the main move and perfectly fine too.}) 6. a3 {[%cal Gd2b4]} Bd7 7. Bxc6 Qxc6 {White has to go for the complications now.} 8. dxe5 fxe5 9. Qh5+ Kd8 {Our king is stuck in the centre but we have the bishop pair and more active pieces.} 10. Qxe5 Qxc2 11. Ne2 Nf6 $36 {[%cal Gf8d6] We will get our bishop to [d6] next and the queen can retreat along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. White has to be careful not to get worse.} *

